# Threads & Processes — Overview

> [!info] This is an overview. For the full content, see: [[01 — Processes & Threads]], [[02 — The OS Scheduler]], [[03 — SMT, Affinity & Thread Pools]].


### The `std::thread::hardware_concurrency()` Trap

```cpp
// THE TRAP: spawning hardware_concurrency() threads and expecting linear scaling
unsigned int n = std::thread::hardware_concurrency();  // 16 on 8-core HT
std::vector<std::thread> threads(n);

auto start = now();
for (unsigned int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
    threads[i] = std::thread([i]() {
        HeavyCompute(i);  // CPU-bound, uses FPU intensively
    });
}
for (auto& t : threads) t.join();
auto elapsed = now() - start;

// Expected speedup: 16×
// Reality: ~8-12× because SMT threads compete for FPU and memory bandwidth
// Meanwhile: the OS has 200 other threads that also want CPU time
// Your 16 threads aren't the only ones on the 16 logical cores
```

### The Lock Contention Trap — Threads Waiting Are Wasted

```cpp
// THE TRAP: fine-grained locking with many threads
std::mutex m;
int counter = 0;

void Worker() {
    for (int i = 0; i < 1'000'000; i++) {
        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m);
        counter++;  // 1 nanosecond of work inside the lock
    }
    // Lock held for ~20 ns (mutex overhead + increment)
    // If 8 threads contend: 7 threads are BLOCKED at any moment
    // 7 context switches per lock handoff
    // Actual throughput: maybe 20% of single-thread performance!
    // You'd be FASTER with ONE thread doing all the work.
}

// THE BETTER WAY: batch work, minimize critical sections
// Or use atomics for simple counters, or partition the data so threads don't contend
```

> [!note] Learning Path Note
> Atomic is explained in detail in [[04 — Data Races & Mutexes]]. This note only covers what is necessary for the current topic.


### The False Sharing Trap

```cpp
// THE TRAP: two threads updating adjacent variables
struct alignas(64) Counters {  // Even with alignment...
    int counterA;  // Thread A increments this
    int counterB;  // Thread B increments this
};
Counters c;

// Thread A: c.counterA++  (core 0's L1 cache)
// Thread B: c.counterB++  (core 1's L1 cache)
// 
// PROBLEM: counterA and counterB are on the SAME 64-byte cache line!
// Thread A writes → core 0's cache line is Modified
// Thread B writes → core 1 must invalidate core 0's cache line, fetch it
// Thread A writes again → core 0 must invalidate core 1's cache line
// Every write triggers a cache coherence ping-pong
// Performance: ~50-100× slower than using separate cache lines!

// THE FIX: pad to ensure different cache lines
struct alignas(64) PaddedCounters {
    alignas(64) int counterA;  // On its own cache line
    alignas(64) int counterB;  // On a DIFFERENT cache line
};
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

A process is like a restaurant — it has its own building, kitchen, and supplies. Threads are the chefs. Each chef works on their own dish at their own station (stack), but they all share the same pantry and fridge (heap and globals). The OS scheduler is the head chef who walks around every few milliseconds saying \"Switch stations!\" — the chef at the stove moves to prep, the chef at prep moves to plating. Each chef notes exactly where they left off (program counter) and cleans up their tools (save registers). This switching costs time, especially if the chef at the new station needs to re-gather ingredients (cache warmup). Hyperthreading is like one chef with two cutting boards — they can work on two dishes at once, but only one can use the stove at a time. A thread pool is a catering company that keeps chefs on staff permanently instead of hiring and firing for every order. User-space threads (fibers/green threads) are chefs who organize their own work shifts without the head chef knowing — faster to switch, but if one chef takes a long call to a supplier (blocking I/O), ALL the chefs in that kitchen are stuck waiting.

### Technical

A process is a kernel abstraction consisting of a virtual address space (MMU page tables rooted at CR3), a set of file descriptors (per-process `files_struct`), credentials (UID/GID), and one or more threads. A thread is a schedulable execution context: it has its own user stack (1-8 MB virtual, COW-backed), kernel stack (~16 KB), and a `task_struct` (Linux) or `ETHREAD` (Windows) containing saved register context (GPRs, RIP, RSP, RFLAGS, FS/GS base, potentially FPU/SIMD state tracked via CR0.TS). The OS scheduler implements preemptive multitasking via per-core timer interrupts (LAPIC timer, typically 1-10 ms granularity). Linux CFS uses a vruntime-weighted red-black tree with target latency of 6 ms period and minimum granularity of 0.75 ms; the Windows scheduler uses 32 priority levels with round-robin within each level and dynamic priority boosts for I/O completion. Context switching involves: hardware interrupt saves RIP/RFLAGS/CS/RSP → kernel interrupt handler saves remaining GPRs and optionally FPU state (XSAVE) → scheduler selects next thread → if cross-process, CR3 reload flushes TLBs (mitigated by PCID on modern CPUs) → restore next thread's register state → IRETQ. Direct cost: 1-5 µs (same process), 3-10 µs (cross-process). Indirect cost: cache warmup latency of 5-100 µs as the new thread's working set is reloaded from L3/DRAM. SMT duplicates architectural state (register files, APIC IDs) but shares execution units and caches, yielding 15-30% throughput improvement for typical workloads. CPU affinity (`sched_setaffinity`/`SetThreadAffinityMask`) constrains thread-to-core mapping to preserve cache warmth in latency-critical threads. Thread pools amortize creation costs (stack allocation, TCB initialization, scheduler registration: ~10-50 µs) by reusing long-lived workers, with work-stealing deques (lock-free Chase-Lev or bounded MPMC) distributing tasks without central contention. Green threads (user-space threads) multiplex onto OS threads via cooperative context switching (stack pointer swap + callee-saved register save/restore: ~10-30 ns) but require non-blocking I/O to prevent head-of-line blocking. C++20 coroutines are stackless, compiler-generated state machines with heap-allocated activation frames, enabling synchronous-style async code via `co_await` suspension points.

---

Real-time threads have **fixed priorities** and **immediately preempt** lower-priority threads:

| OS | Real-Time Policies |
|---|---|
| Linux | `SCHED_FIFO` (run until blocked or higher priority arrives), `SCHED_RR` (round-robin within same priority) |
| Windows | `THREAD_PRIORITY_TIME_CRITICAL` (15 levels above normal, never boosted or decayed) |

**Game engine use:** Audio threads and render threads often run at real-time priority — an audio buffer underrun causes an audible glitch. The main game thread typically runs at high (but not real-time) priority to prevent starving the OS.

> [!warning] Danger: A real-time thread that never yields can freeze the entire system. The scheduler cannot preempt it for lower-priority threads — including the desktop, mouse cursor, and terminal.

## Exercises

1. **Conceptual:** The note says SMT yields 15-30% throughput improvement. Why not 100%? What specific hardware resources do the two logical threads share that prevent linear scaling?

2. **Code:** Write two programs — one spawning `std::thread::hardware_concurrency()` threads doing FPU-intensive work, another spawning the same number doing integer-only work. Which scales closer to linear? Explain using the "shared execution units" point from the Technical section.

3. **Analysis:** Context switching cross-process costs 3-10 µs and flushes the TLB. If your game thread is context-switched out 100 times per second, how much frame budget (in percentage of a 16.67 ms frame) is lost? What would CPU affinity do to change this?

4. **Real-world:** The audio thread runs at real-time priority. If it holds a mutex that a normal-priority thread also acquires, what happens? Trace the priority inversion using the scheduler rules in this note.

5. **Design:** Green threads multiplex onto OS threads cooperatively. Design a fiber system where each fiber gets its own 4 KB stack carved from a pre-allocated block. How do you detect stack overflow without hardware guard pages?



## std::jthread & stop_token — Cooperative Cancellation (C++20)

`std::thread` has no cancellation mechanism. If you want to stop a thread, you must roll your own: an atomic flag, a condition variable, or a promise/future pair. `std::jthread` (C++20) fixes this:

```cpp
#include <thread>

void worker(std::stop_token token) {
    while (!token.stop_requested()) {
        // Do work. Check token periodically.
    }
    // Clean shutdown — flush buffers, release resources
}

std::jthread t(worker);  // j = "joining" — auto-joins in destructor
// ... later ...
t.request_stop();  // Signals the stop_token
// t's destructor joins — no detached threads, no leaks
```

`std::stop_token` can be passed through the call stack — any function can check `token.stop_requested()` to cooperatively shut down. `std::stop_callback` lets you register cleanup actions that run when stop is requested. Together they eliminate the "how do I cleanly shut down this background thread" problem that plagued C++ for decades.
## See Also

- [[04 — Data Races & Mutexes]] — Mutexes, atomics, memory ordering, and avoiding data races between threads
- [[../C++/Stack vs Heap]] — Each thread gets its own stack; the heap is shared
- [[../C++/Object Memory Layout]] — Cache lines, false sharing, and alignment for multi-threaded code
- [[00 — RAM & Virtual Memory Overview|RAM & Virtual Memory]] — The address spaces, TLBs, and page tables that context switches manipulate
- [[00 — Storage Overview|Storage]] — Async I/O patterns and the page cache that blocking threads wait on

15 \u2014 Kernel Modules & Drivers.content:
# Kernel Modules & Drivers

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[13 — Interrupts & Exceptions]], [[../System Software/04 — Syscalls & Kernel]]

---

## Why

The kernel manages CPU, memory, and processes. But it doesn't know how to talk to every GPU, Wi-Fi card, and NVMe drive ever made. Drivers bridge this gap — they're kernel modules that teach the kernel how to communicate with specific hardware. Without drivers, your $2000 GPU is a paperweight. Game engines interact with drivers constantly: GPU drivers (D3D12/Vulkan shader compilation), audio drivers (WASAPI/DirectSound), input drivers (XInput/RawInput).

---

## The Split — Kernel Space vs User Space

```
User Space:    Game/Application
                  ↓ syscall
Kernel Space:   ┌─────────────┐
                │  VFS Layer  │ ← "I want to read a file"
                │  Driver     │ ← "NVMe drive, read sector 42"
                │  Hardware   │ ← Physical NAND chips
                └─────────────┘
```

Drivers run in KERNEL SPACE with full hardware access. A buggy driver crashes the ENTIRE system (BSOD/kernel panic). User-space drivers (D3D12/Vulkan UMD — User Mode Driver) run in user space for safety at the cost of syscall overhead per GPU command.

---

## Linux Kernel Module — Structure

```c
#include <linux/module.h>
#include <linux/kernel.h>

static int __init mydriver_init(void) {
    printk(KERN_INFO "MyDriver: loaded\n");
    // Register with kernel subsystem (PCI, USB, etc.)
    // Allocate device numbers
    // Map hardware registers (ioremap)
    return 0;
}

static void __exit mydriver_exit(void) {
    printk(KERN_INFO "MyDriver: unloaded\n");
    // Unmap registers (iounmap)
    // Free device numbers
}

module_init(mydriver_init);
module_exit(mydriver_exit);
MODULE_LICENSE("GPL");
```

**Loading:** `insmod mydriver.ko` or `modprobe mydriver`. The kernel calls `init`, the module registers itself with a subsystem (e.g., `pci_register_driver()`), and from then on the kernel routes I/O to it.

---

## Memory-Mapped I/O (MMIO)

Drivers don't talk to hardware via special instructions (mostly) — they read/write to memory addresses that are mapped to device registers:

```c
// Map PCIe device BAR0 (Base Address Register) into kernel virtual memory
void __iomem *regs = ioremap(pci_resource_start(dev, 0), 
                              pci_resource_len(dev, 0));

// Write a command to the device's command register
writel(CMD_START_DMA, regs + REG_COMMAND);

// Read device status
uint32_t status = readl(regs + REG_STATUS);

// Unmap when done
iounmap(regs);
```

The CPU's MMU routes these memory accesses over PCIe to the device instead of to RAM. The device's PCIe endpoint decodes the address and acts on the write.

---

## DMA — The Driver's Workhorse

Drivers set up DMA transfers so the device can read/write system RAM directly:

```c
dma_addr_t dma_handle;
void *cpu_addr = dma_alloc_coherent(dev, size, &dma_handle, GFP_KERNEL);
// cpu_addr: kernel virtual address (CPU can read/write)
// dma_handle: bus address (give this to the device)

// Tell the device: "DMA from dma_handle, size bytes"
writel(dma_handle, regs + REG_DMA_ADDR);
writel(size, regs + REG_DMA_SIZE);
writel(CMD_DMA_START, regs + REG_COMMAND);

// Wait for interrupt signaling completion
```

---

## Interrupt Handling — Top Half vs Bottom Half

When hardware needs attention, it fires an interrupt. The ISR (Interrupt Service Routine) must be FAST — it runs with interrupts disabled:

```c
// Top Half (ISR) — do the minimum:
static irqreturn_t mydrv_isr(int irq, void *dev_id) {
    // Read and acknowledge the interrupt
    uint32_t status = readl(regs + REG_INT_STATUS);
    writel(status, regs + REG_INT_CLEAR);

    // Schedule the real work (Bottom Half)
    schedule_work(&mydev->work_struct);

    return IRQ_HANDLED;
}

// Bottom Half (workqueue) — do the heavy lifting:
static void mydrv_work(struct work_struct *work) {
    // Process completed DMA transfer
    // Copy data to user buffer
    // Wake up waiting user-space process
}
```

---

## Windows Driver — KMDF Framework

Windows drivers use the Kernel-Mode Driver Framework (KMDF):

```c
NTSTATUS MyDriverEvtDeviceAdd(WDFDRIVER Driver, PWDFDEVICE_INIT DeviceInit) {
    WDFDEVICE device;
    WdfDeviceCreate(&DeviceInit, &attributes, &device);

    // Create IO queue for user requests
    WDF_IO_QUEUE_CONFIG queueConfig;
    WDF_IO_QUEUE_CONFIG_INIT_DEFAULT_QUEUE(&queueConfig, WdfIoQueueDispatchParallel);
    queueConfig.EvtIoDeviceControl = MyDriverEvtIoDeviceControl;
    WdfIoQueueCreate(device, &queueConfig, WDF_NO_OBJECT_ATTRIBUTES, &queue);
}

// Handle user-space DeviceIoControl calls:
VOID MyDriverEvtIoDeviceControl(WDFQUEUE Queue, WDFREQUEST Request, ...) {
    // Process the IOCTL, read/write hardware, complete the request
}
```

---

## GPU Drivers — A Special Beast

GPU drivers are split into kernel-mode (KMD) and user-mode (UMD) components:
- **KMD:** Memory management (VRAM allocation), command buffer submission, interrupt handling, power management. Crashes = TDR (Timeout Detection & Recovery) — GPU reset.
- **UMD:** Shader compilation (HLSL/GLSL → ISA), state translation, draw call validation. Runs in user space — crash = app crash, not system crash.

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE:** GPU drivers (D3D12/Vulkan) are the single biggest source of crashes in shipped games. `FPlatformMisc::GPUDriverInfo()` queries driver version. RHI abstracts driver differences.
- **Audio:** UE's `IAudioDevice` talks to platform audio APIs which talk to audio drivers which talk to hardware via DMA + interrupts.
- **Input:** RawInput (Windows) / evdev (Linux) — drivers forward USB HID reports to user space.

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
A driver is a translator between the kernel and a specific piece of hardware. The kernel says "write this data to storage" in a generic language. The NVMe driver translates that to NVMe commands the SSD understands. Drivers live in kernel space (dangerous — a bug crashes the whole system) or user space (safe but slower). GPU drivers split the difference: memory management in kernel space, shader compilation in user space. Memory-mapped I/O means the driver reads/writes to special memory addresses that are physically connected to the device's registers — not RAM.

### Technical
Linux driver model: `struct device_driver` → probe/remove callbacks, device tree or ACPI matching. MMIO: `ioremap()` creates a kernel virtual mapping of PCIe BAR space. DMA: `dma_alloc_coherent()` for consistent (no cache flush needed) or `dma_map_single()` for streaming (manual cache sync). Interrupts: `request_irq()` registers handler, top-half/bottom-half split via tasklets or workqueues. Windows: WDF framework abstracts PnP, power, and I/O. GPU: KMD in `dxgkrnl.sys`, UMD in `dxgi.dll` + vendor UMD (nvlddmkm, amdxc64). UE's RHI wraps D3D12/Vulkan which talk to UMD which talks to KMD.

---

## Exercises

1. **Conceptual:** A kernel-mode driver crash causes a system-wide BSOD/kernel panic, while a user-mode driver crash only kills the application. Why? What specific CPU protection mechanism (rings) prevents a user-mode process from crashing the kernel, and why must kernel-mode drivers run in ring 0 despite this risk?

2. **Code:** Write a minimal Linux kernel module that registers a character device at `/dev/hello`. The `read()` handler should return "Hello from kernel!\\n". Insert the module with `insmod`, test it with `cat /dev/hello`, then remove with `rmmod`. Check `dmesg` output for your `printk` messages.

3. **Analysis:** The note says `ioremap()` maps a PCIe BAR physical address to a kernel virtual address. A PCIe device has BAR0 at physical address 0xF8000000, 256 MB. The kernel uses 4 KB pages. How many page table entries must be created for `ioremap()` of this BAR? Why can't the driver just dereference the physical address directly?

4. **Real-world:** UE's RHI delegates draw calls to a UMD (user-mode driver) which forwards command buffers to the KMD (kernel-mode driver). If the UMD crashes, TDR resets the GPU. If the KMD crashes, the system BSODs. Why does Microsoft split the driver this way? What specific operations MUST stay in kernel mode and what can safely run in user mode?

5. **Design:** The note describes top-half (ISR) and bottom-half (tasklet/workqueue) interrupt handling. Design a network driver's ISR: the NIC signals an interrupt when a packet arrives. The ISR must do minimal work. What does it do in 3-4 lines of pseudocode? What work is deferred to the bottom-half, and why must it not be done in the ISR?

## See Also

- [[13 — Interrupts & Exceptions]] — How drivers get notified by hardware
- [[09 — DMA & Bus Mastering]] — How drivers transfer data without CPU involvement
- [[../System Software/04 — Syscalls & Kernel]] — How user space talks to kernel space

16 \u2014 Hardware Security.content:
# Hardware Security — Side Channels & Speculative Execution

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[04 — CPU Architecture]], [[RAM & Virtual Memory/02 — Page Tables & TLB]]

---

## Why

The fastest code is code that runs correctly. The most dangerous code is code that runs correctly but leaks secrets through physics. Spectre and Meltdown (2018) showed that modern CPU optimizations — the same ones that make your game run at 144fps — can be weaponized to read kernel memory from user space. Understanding these attacks means understanding why CPUs are both brilliant and terrifying.

---

## Speculative Execution — The Vulnerability

Modern CPUs don't wait. When they hit a branch, they GUESS which way it goes and execute ahead speculatively. If the guess is wrong, they discard the results — but NOT the side effects on the microarchitecture:

```cpp
// Spectre v1 — bounds check bypass:
if (index < array_size) {              // Branch: likely TRUE
    value = lookup_table[data[index]]; // Executed SPECULATIVELY before branch resolves
}
// Attacker: make index = malicious_value
// CPU speculates index < size (trained branch predictor)
// lookup_table[data[malicious_value]] is accessed — loads secret into cache
// Even though the branch was WRONG, the cache state was modified
// Attacker measures cache timing to extract the loaded value
```

---

## Cache Timing — The Measurement Tool

```cpp
// Flush+Reload: measure whether address X is cached
uint64_t before = __rdtsc();
volatile int tmp = probe_array[X * 64];  // 64-byte stride avoids prefetcher
uint64_t after = __rdtsc();
uint64_t time = after - before;

if (time < THRESHOLD) {
    // X was CACHED — the secret accessed this index
    printf("Secret byte = %d\n", X);
}
```

L1 cache hit: ~4 cycles. L3 hit: ~12 cycles. DRAM: ~100 cycles. The 25× difference is trivially measurable.

---

## Meltdown — Reading Kernel Memory

Meltdown exploits that Intel CPUs (pre-Cascade Lake) check page table permissions AFTER the speculative load:

```c
// Kernel maps all physical memory in its address space (for efficiency)
// User-space code:
uint8_t secret = *(uint8_t*)kernel_address;  // #PF — page fault
// BUT: speculative execution already loaded the value into a register
// BEFORE the page fault was raised
probe_array[secret * 64] = 1;  // Access probe array at index = secret
// The page fault fires, the instruction is discarded...
// ...but probe_array[secret * 64] is NOW IN CACHE

// Attacker: Flush+Reload every index of probe_array
// The cached one is the secret value
```

**Fix:** KPTI (Kernel Page Table Isolation) — kernel pages are unmapped in user-space page tables. The kernel has its own separate page table. Context switch between them on every syscall — ~5-30% performance hit.

---

## Spectre v1 — Bounds Check Bypass

Train the branch predictor to predict "in bounds." Then provide an out-of-bounds index. The speculative execution accesses the secret via `data[index]`, loads it, and leaks it through the cache:

```c
// Mitigation: LFENCE (Load Fence) or conditional move:
if (index < size) {
    _mm_lfence();  // Stall pipeline until branch resolved
    value = lookup_table[data[index]];
}

// Or compiler-level: -mindirect-branch=thunk (retpoline)
```

---

## Spectre v2 — Branch Target Injection

Poison the indirect branch predictor (BTB — Branch Target Buffer) to make the CPU speculatively jump to an attacker-chosen gadget:

```c
// Victim code at address VICTIM_ADDR:
void victim(size_t index) {
    if (index < size) gadget(data[index]);
}

// Attacker: train BTB to predict that an indirect call at ATTACKER_ADDR
// will jump to VICTIM_ADDR
// Then issue the indirect call with attacker-controlled index
// CPU speculatively jumps to victim, executes gadget with attacker data
```

**Fix:** Retpoline — replace indirect calls/jumps with a `return` trampoline that can't be speculatively redirected. Available as compiler flag `-mindirect-branch=thunk`.

---

## Rowhammer — Flipping Bits in Someone Else's Memory

Repeatedly activate the same DRAM row (hammer it). Capacitive coupling causes charge to leak from adjacent rows — BIT FLIPS in memory you don't even own:

```c
// Pseudocode:
while (1) {
    *row_A = 1;  // Activate row A
    *row_B = 1;  // Activate row B (adjacent to A)
    // After ~100,000 activations, bits in adjacent rows flip
    // Including rows in OTHER processes' memory
    // Including kernel memory if the attacker knows the physical layout
}
```

**Fix:** ECC memory (detects and corrects single-bit errors). DRAM refresh rate increase (from 64ms to 32ms). Target Row Refresh (TRR) in DDR4+ — the memory controller tracks highly-accessed rows and refreshes their neighbors.

---

## Engine Connection

- **Web browsers:** First to deploy Spectre mitigations (site isolation, reduced timer precision)
- **Cloud providers:** Meltdown meant VMs could read the HYPERVISOR'S memory — major security crisis
- **Game consoles:** Fixed hardware = known microarchitecture = can audit for these vulnerabilities. Console devkits often have debug registers to detect side-channel attacks
- **Anti-cheat:** Cheat engines use read/write process memory — similar to Meltdown in concept (accessing another process's memory). Hardware-enforced stack protection (CET — Control-flow Enforcement Technology) blocks ROP attacks

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Your CPU is so impatient that it starts executing instructions BEFORE checking if it's allowed to. It guesses which way a branch goes and races ahead. If the guess was wrong, it throws away the work — but it can't un-ring the bell. The speculative execution touched memory, and that memory is now in cache. A clever attacker measures which addresses are cached (fast to access) vs uncached (slow) and reconstructs the secret one bit at a time. It's like the CPU whispered the secret before the security guard could stop it, and you can tell what it whispered by how fast it is to repeat certain words.

### Technical
Spectre v1: train branch predictor, then provide OOB index. CPU speculates past bounds check, loads secret via array[index], caches probe_array[secret]. Flush+Reload reveals secret. Mitigation: LFENCE serializes execution, retpolines for indirect branches. Meltdown: Intel's permission check happens in parallel with speculative load — KPTI unmaps kernel pages in user page tables to prevent the load entirely. Rowhammer: repeated DRAM row activation (tRAS) causes capacitive coupling to adjacent rows, flipping bits. ECC/TRR mitigations. Cache side channel: Prime+Probe, Flush+Reload, Evict+Time — all exploit cache timing differential (~4 cycles L1 vs ~100 cycles DRAM) or the 25× ratio.

---

## Exercises

1. **Conceptual:** Spectre uses the branch predictor to speculatively execute code that loads a secret into cache. Meltdown exploits the fact that Intel CPUs don't check page-table permission bits until after the load retires. Why does Meltdown NOT affect AMD CPUs? What specific implementation difference in the permission check pipeline protects AMD?

2. **Code:** Implement a Flush+Reload covert channel between two processes: Process A (sender) either accesses or doesn't access a shared memory page. Process B (receiver) uses `clflush` + timed reload to detect whether the page is in cache. Measure the timing difference. How many bits per second can this channel transmit?

3. **Analysis:** KPTI unmaps kernel pages from user-space page tables. Before KPTI, a user process's page table contained both user and kernel mappings (the top half of the address space). With KPTI, every syscall requires switching page tables. How many CR3 writes does this add per syscall? If your game makes 100,000 syscalls per second (a high number), how much overhead does KPTI add in cycles?

4. **Real-world:** A cloud provider hosts VMs from different customers on the same physical machine. Customer A's VM uses a Rowhammer attack to flip bits in Customer B's VM. How is this possible — don't VMs have separate physical memory? What specific hardware feature (hint: DRAM rows are shared within a DIMM) enables this, and what mitigation does DDR5's on-die ECC provide?

5. **Design:** Anti-cheat engines must detect when a cheat program reads/writes the game's process memory. Design a detection scheme: if you place a "canary" value at a known memory address and periodically check it, can you detect the cheat? How does the cheat evade this by only reading memory (not writing)? What hardware feature could the anti-cheat use instead — hint: performance counters that count cache misses?

## See Also

- [[04 — CPU Architecture]] — The speculative execution engine being exploited
- [[RAM & Virtual Memory/01 — DRAM Cells & Memory Physics]] — Why rowhammer works (capacitive coupling)
- [[../Concurrency/04 — Data Races & Mutexes]] — Timing side channels are a form of race condition

00 \u2014 RAM & Virtual Memory Overview.content:
# RAM & Virtual Memory Overview
> [!info] Part of the [[../../Learning Path|RAM & Virtual Memory]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> Unknown acronym? Check the [[../../Glossary]].
> You should understand the memory hierarchy — why RAM is slow relative to cache. See [[../05 — Memory Hierarchy|Memory Hierarchy]].

> [!info] Memory Map Reference
> For where this region lives in the process address space, see the **Memory Map diagram** in [[../04 — CPU Architecture|CPU Architecture]]. It shows the full layout: stack, heap, data, code — and how they connect to page tables and caches.

## Why This Matters — The Numbers That Should Terrify You

A modern CPU core runs at 5 GHz — that's one clock cycle every **0.2 nanoseconds**. Light, the fastest thing in the universe, travels about **6 centimeters** in that time. Your RAM DIMM sits roughly 10-15 centimeters from the CPU socket on the motherboard. That means just getting an electrical signal from the CPU to the RAM and back takes a bare minimum of ~1 nanosecond, or **5 clock cycles** — assuming the signal traveled at light speed down a straight wire, which it doesn't.

In reality, a DDR5 RAM access takes **80-100 nanoseconds**. That's **400-500 clock cycles** at 5 GHz. The CPU, which can dispatch 4-8 instructions per cycle, could have executed **1,600-4,000 instructions** in the time it took to read one value from RAM.

This gap — the **memory wall** — is the single most important performance fact in computing. Every cache, every prefetcher, every clever memory layout trick exists to hide this brutal reality. And we're going to understand exactly why it exists, starting from the physical hardware.

---


## Part 3: The Memory Hierarchy — Why We Have Caches

Now you understand the problem. The solution is the **memory hierarchy**:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  CPU Registers       │ ~0.2 ns  │ ~1 KB   │ 1 cycle             │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  L1 Cache (SRAM)     │ ~1 ns     │ 32-64 KB │ 4-5 cycles         │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  L2 Cache (SRAM)     │ ~3-7 ns   │ 256 KB-2 MB │ 12-20 cycles   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  L3 Cache (SRAM)     │ ~10-40 ns │ 8-128 MB │ 40-120 cycles     │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  DRAM (DDR5)         │ ~80-100 ns│ 16-256 GB│ 400-500 cycles    │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  NVMe SSD (swap)     │ ~50-100 µs│ 1-8 TB   │ 250,000-500,000   │
├─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┤
│  HDD (swap, worst)   │ ~5-10 ms  │ 1-20 TB  │ 25-50 MILLION     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

Every level is a compromise: smaller = faster, larger = slower. SRAM (used in caches) is fast because it uses 6 transistors per bit — no capacitors, no refresh, just a stable flip-flop. But those 6 transistors take up ~100× more silicon area than a DRAM cell. That's why your CPU has 64 KB of L1 cache but your motherboard has 64 GB of RAM: you can't afford 64 GB of SRAM.

The key insight: **caches work because programs exhibit locality**. If your program accesses address X, it's likely to access X+4 (spatial locality) and to access X again soon (temporal locality). Caches exploit both patterns to keep the frequently-used data in fast SRAM and the rarely-used data in slow DRAM.

But caches have their own addressing problem: they sit between the CPU and the MMU. Before a cache can even look up a memory address, that address must be translated from virtual to physical. Which brings us to...

---


## Hardware → Code: Putting It All Together

### The Trap: Virtual Allocation ≠ Physical Cost

```cpp
// THE TRAP: spawning 10,000 actors and thinking you've used 10,000 × ActorSize bytes
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    AMyActor* Actor = GetWorld()->SpawnActor<AMyActor>();
    // Virtual address space: reserved for the actor's UObject + components
    // Physical RAM: only the UObject header and small members — maybe 200 bytes per actor
    // Total physical cost after spawning: ~2 MB, not 50 MB
}

// THEN, later, when you actually FILL the actor's data arrays:
Actor->LargeVertexBuffer.AddUninitialized(100000);
// NOW: 100,000 × sizeof(FVector) → ~1.2 MB of physical pages allocated via minor faults
// The RAM bill arrives LATE
```

### The TLB Trap: Scattered Allocations Kill Performance

```cpp
// THE TRAP: allocating 100,000 small objects scattered across the heap
MyObject* objects[100000];
for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) {
    objects[i] = new MyObject();  // Each in a different 4 KB page, potentially
}

// Iterating: every 4-8 objects requires a new TLB entry
// With 64-entry L1 D-TLB, you're thrashing after touching ~256 KB of objects
// Performance: 50-80 ns per access due to TLB misses

// THE RIGHT WAY: allocate a contiguous array
MyObject* contiguous = new MyObject[100000];  // One allocation, fewer pages, TLB-friendly
// Or use a pool allocator that carves from large pre-allocated blocks
```

### The mmap Trap: Random Access vs Sequential

```cpp
// THE TRAP: mmap a 10 GB file, then randomly access it
char* data = (char*)mmap(NULL, 10_GB, PROT_READ, MAP_PRIVATE, fd, 0);
for (int r : random_indices) {
    process(data + r * block_size);  
    // Each random access → page fault if page not in RAM
    // HDD: 10 ms per fault → your loop runs at 100 iterations/second
}

// THE RIGHT WAY: access sequentially, let OS read-ahead work
for (size_t i = 0; i < 10_GB; i += 4096) {
    process(data + i);
    // OS detects sequential pattern → pre-loads next pages before you ask
    // Effective throughput: near full disk bandwidth
}
```

---


## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

Think of RAM as your work desk. The desk has limited space — that's physical RAM. Each program thinks it has the entire desk to itself — that's virtual memory. The OS is a personal assistant who silently swaps papers between your desk and a filing cabinet (your hard drive) so it looks like everyone has infinite desk space. The TLB is a sticky note on your monitor listing where the 64 most-used papers currently are on the desk. When you reach for a paper not on the sticky note, the assistant checks the full filing system (page table walk) — slow. A page fault is when the paper isn't on the desk at all — the assistant must go to the filing cabinet to fetch it. Swap is when the desk is completely full and papers must be moved back to the cabinet to make room. Huge pages are like taping 512 small papers into one big poster — fewer things to track on the sticky note, but wasteful if you only need one corner. On a multi-socket server (NUMA), it's like having two desks with a narrow bridge between them — papers on the other desk take longer to reach.

### Technical

DRAM stores bits as charge in trench capacitors (1T1C cells), organized into rows and columns. Charge leaks due to subthreshold transistor leakage across the storage node junction, requiring periodic refresh via sense-amplifier-rewrite cycles at tREFI intervals (7.8 µs per row, 64 ms per full array at ≤85°C per JEDEC JESD79-5). The MMU translates 48-bit virtual addresses through a 4-level hierarchical page table (PML4→PDPT→PD→PT, 9 bits per level, 4 KB pages) to physical frame numbers, with access control bits (NX, R/W, U/S, Present, Accessed, Dirty) per PTE. The TLB caches these VA→PA translations in content-addressable memory: L1 D-TLB (64 entries, fully associative, 1-cycle lookup) and L2 STLB (1,536 entries Intel / 3,072 entries AMD Zen 4, 8-12 cycle lookup). A TLB miss triggers a hardware page walk (4 dependent memory references, ~50-400 ns). Page faults are classified by `vm_fault` return: minor (PTE not present but page in page cache, ~1 µs to wire up PTE), major (page must be fetched from backing store: file I/O or swap, ~50 µs NVMe to ~10 ms HDD), and invalid (SIGSEGV). `mmap` creates a VMA (`vm_area_struct`) in the process's `mm_struct`, establishing a file-backed or anonymous virtual mapping; physical allocation is deferred to the first page fault via the fault-around optimization (reads ~16 pages in a batch to amortize I/O). Swap implements a two-level eviction policy via the LRU lists (`lruvec`), writing dirty anonymous pages to swap slots tracked by `swap_info_struct`, with the PTEs marked as swap entries encoding the swap device and offset. Huge pages (2 MB using `PMD_SIZE`, 1 GB using `PUD_SIZE`) use the same page table hierarchy with larger leaf entries, reducing TLB miss rate at the cost of internal fragmentation and compaction overhead (`khugepaged` for THP). NUMA domains are specified in the ACPI SRAT/SLIT tables, with the kernel's `mempolicy` (`MPOL_BIND`, `MPOL_PREFERRED`, `MPOL_INTERLEAVE`) controlling page allocation across nodes; the `numactl` tool and `libnuma` (`numa_alloc_onnode`, `mbind`) provide userspace control.

---



## Exercises

1. **Conceptual:** The Memory Numbers table shows L2 cache at ~4 ns, RAM at ~100 ns, NVMe at ~50,000 ns. Why does RAM latency (~100 ns) NOT improve at the same rate as CPU clock speeds? What fundamental physical constant limits DRAM access time regardless of manufacturing process?

2. **Code:** Write a benchmark that allocates a 500 MB array and randomly accesses 10 million elements. Use two strategies: (a) `new MyObject[500000]` with 1 KB objects (contiguous), and (b) `new MyObject*[500000]` with individually `new`'d objects (fragmented). Measure wall-clock time. Which is faster and by what factor? Explain using TLB miss rate.

3. **Analysis:** The note says a minor page fault costs ~1 us while a major page fault costs ~10 ms (HDD). If your game's mmap'd level data file is 8 GB and you access pages in a random order, with 16 GB of RAM available and a cold cache, how many page faults are minor vs major? What's the total fault overhead?

4. **Real-world:** The "Pointer Maze Trap" shows why arrays of pointers cause TLB thrashing. You're reviewing code that does `std::vector<unique_ptr<Enemy>> enemies` with 10,000 enemies. Rewrite using a contiguous allocation and explain how many page table entries the original vs your version touches when iterating all enemies.

5. **Design:** The Simple Two-Way says "TLB is a sticky note with the 64 most-used papers." Design a cache-aware data structure for a particle system with 1,000,000 particles (position: 12 bytes, velocity: 12 bytes, lifetime: 4 bytes). How do you lay these out to minimize TLB misses when (a) updating physics on all particles, and (b) rendering only alive particles?


