# Performance Optimization

> **Why This Matters.** Most code is fast enough. The code that isn't — the 5% that consumes 95% of the frame budget — determines whether your game runs at 60 FPS or 30 FPS. Random refactoring and intuition won't find these bottlenecks. You need a systematic method: measure the cost of every operation, identify the critical path, apply transformations that the compiler can't do for you, and remeasure to confirm. This note teaches that method — from reading the CPU's cycle counter to reorganizing loops so the pipeline never stalls. After this note, "slow" becomes a number, not a feeling.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> Unknown acronym? Check the [[Glossary]].
> You should understand the CPU's pipeline, out-of-order execution, and branch prediction ([[../Hardware/04 — CPU Architecture|CPU Architecture]]), the memory hierarchy and cache lines ([[../Hardware/05 — Memory Hierarchy|Memory Hierarchy]]), and how the compiler transforms C++ to assembly ([[02 — Compiler Pipeline|Compiler Pipeline]]).

---

## Part 1: Expressing Performance — Making "Slow" a Number

Before optimizing, you must measure. Before measuring, you must define what "fast" means. The metric that matters for compute-bound code is **Cycles Per Element (CPE)** — how many CPU clock cycles it takes to process one element of your data.

### The Hardware Clock — `RDTSC`

Every x86-64 CPU has a **Time Stamp Counter (TSC)** — a 64-bit register that increments once per clock cycle (on most modern CPUs). You can read it with the `RDTSC` instruction:

```cpp
#include <cstdint>     // uint64_t — guaranteed 64-bit unsigned integer

// Read the CPU's cycle counter into a 64-bit unsigned integer
inline uint64_t ReadTSC() {
    uint32_t lo, hi;
    // RDTSC: read time-stamp counter — lo/hi = low/high 32 bits
    // __volatile__: prevents compiler from reordering or omitting
    asm volatile("rdtsc" : "=a"(lo), "=d"(hi));
    return (static_cast<uint64_t>(hi) << 32) | lo;
}
```

> [!warning] The TSC Sync Trap
> On older CPUs (pre-2012), `RDTSC` was NOT synchronized across cores — each core's TSC could drift independently. Measuring code that migrated between cores would produce meaningless results. Modern CPUs (post-Nehalem on Intel, Zen on AMD) have **invariant TSC** — all cores share a synchronized counter that ticks at a constant rate regardless of turbo boost or power states. Check with `CPUID` or query `/proc/cpuinfo` for `constant_tsc` and `nonstop_tsc` flags.

### Computing CPE

```cpp
uint64_t start = ReadTSC();
ProcessNElements(data, N);   // The function you're measuring
uint64_t end = ReadTSC();

uint64_t total_cycles = end - start;
double cpe = static_cast<double>(total_cycles) / N;

std::cout << "Cycles: " << total_cycles
          << "  CPE: " << cpe << '\n';
```

The number alone means nothing. The RATIO between a baseline and an optimized version means everything. If baseline CPE = 12.0 and optimized CPE = 3.0, you have a 4× speedup. Always report CPE relative to a known baseline.

### Warm-Up and Noise

The first run of any code is cold: caches are empty, branch predictors are untrained, TLB entries are absent. Always warm up before measuring:

```cpp
ProcessNElements(data, N);   // Cold run — discard
ProcessNElements(data, N);   // Warm run — now caches are hot
uint64_t start = ReadTSC();  // Measure from here
ProcessNElements(data, N);
uint64_t end = ReadTSC();
```

Also: disable frequency scaling during benchmarks (`cpupower frequency-set -g performance` on Linux, High Performance power plan on Windows). Turbo boost variability will otherwise add ±5-10% noise.

---

## Part 2: The Optimization Workflow

```
MEASURE      →     PROFILE     →     TRANSFORM     →     REMEASURE
(baseline        (find the          (apply the           (confirm
CPE, find        bottleneck)        technique)           speedup)
hot function)
```

**Step 1 — Measure:** Get a baseline CPE. You must know the starting point.

**Step 2 — Profile:** Don't guess. Use `perf` or VTune to identify which specific function or loop dominates runtime. Profiling tools tell you: cycles spent, cache misses, branch mispredictions, and instruction mix. This is NOT optional — humans are terrible at guessing where the bottleneck actually is.

**Step 3 — Transform:** Apply one of the techniques in Parts 3-5 of this note. ONE at a time. If you change five things and it's faster, you don't know which change mattered.

**Step 4 — Remeasure:** Did CPE actually drop? By how much? If it didn't change, undo the transform and try a different approach. Not all optimizations help — some make things worse.

> [!tip] The Observer Effect Trap
> Profiling overhead distorts what you measure. `perf record` and VTune use sampling (interrupt-based, ~1-10ms intervals) — minimal distortion, but statistical. Instrumentation-based profiling (inserting code at every function entry/exit) can make the profiled code 2-10× slower. Prefer sampling for initial discovery; use instrumentation only when you need exact call counts.

---

## Part 3: Loop Optimization — The Systematic Progression

CS:APP Ch 5 teaches a specific sequence of loop transformations that eliminate progressively deeper inefficiencies. Each step reduces CPE. We'll trace through them with a running example: summing an array of `double`.

### Baseline — The Naive Loop

```cpp
// ❌ BASELINE — compiles to something, we don't know what
double SumBaseline(const double* data, size_t N) {
    double sum = 0.0;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        sum += data[i];
    }
    return sum;
}
// CPE with -O1: ~10.0   (GCC, modern x86-64)
// CPE with -O2: ~3.0    (auto-vectorized, loop unrolled by compiler)
```

Your first job: compile with `-O2` or `-O3` before writing any optimization. The compiler already does more than you think. All techniques below are for cases where the compiler CANNOT do the optimization — either because it's not safe (potential aliasing) or because the pattern isn't recognized.

### Step 1: Code Motion — Move Invariant Computations Out

```cpp
// ❌ BAD — strlen() recomputed every iteration
for (size_t i = 0; i < strlen(s); i++) {
    process(s[i]);
}
// strlen(s) is called N times, each walking the entire string
// Total: O(N²) instead of O(N)

// ✅ GOOD — hoist invariant out
size_t len = strlen(s);
for (size_t i = 0; i < len; i++) {
    process(s[i]);
}
// strlen(s) called once. Total: O(N)
```

The compiler can do this IF it can prove `strlen(s)` doesn't change inside the loop. For simple functions with no side effects and `const`-correct code, the compiler hoists automatically. For complex functions or when pointers might alias, it can't — you must do it manually.

### Step 2: Strength Reduction — Replace Expensive Operations

```cpp
// ❌ Multiply inside loop — `imul` is 3-4 cycles latency
for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    sum += data[i * 4];  // Multiplication for stride
}

// ✅ Pointer arithmetic — `add` is 1 cycle latency
for (const double* p = data; p < data + N * 4; p += 4) {
    sum += *p;
}
```

> [!tip] The Compiler Already Does This
> For array indexing, the compiler converts `data[i]` into pointer arithmetic automatically at `-O1` and above. Strength reduction matters when the pattern is non-trivial — e.g., `i * 13` or `(i + 1) * (i + 2)` inside a hotspot.

### Step 3: Eliminate Unnecessary Memory References

```cpp
// ❌ BAD — sum lives on the stack, every += reads AND writes memory
double SumBad(const double* data, size_t N) {
    double sum;
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        sum = sum + data[i];   // read sum from stack, add, write sum to stack
    }
    return sum;
}
// sum is a local variable but lives on the stack (not in a register)
// because the compiler might not know it can keep sum in a register

// ✅ GOOD — accumulator lives entirely in a register
double SumGood(const double* data, size_t N) {
    double sum = 0.0;          // Compiler puts sum in an XMM register
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        sum = sum + data[i];   // register-only operation
    }
    return sum;
}
// The `= 0.0` initialization is the key — it signals the compiler
// to allocate sum in a register from the start
```

At `-O2` the compiler usually gets this right. At `-O1` or with complex control flow, it may not. The pattern generalizes: **accumulate in a local variable, write to memory once at the end.** This eliminates the load/store on every iteration.

### Step 4: Loop Unrolling — Reduce Overhead

The loop itself has overhead: incrementing `i`, comparing to `N`, branching back to the loop start. These are ~2 instructions per iteration. For a loop body of 1 instruction, that's 66% overhead.

```cpp
// ❌ ORIGINAL — 1 useful instruction, 2 overhead instructions per iteration
for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    sum += data[i];
}
// Per iteration: 1 add (data) + 1 add (i++) + 1 cmp/jne = 3 instructions
// Overhead: 66%

// ✅ UNROLLED 4× — 4 useful instructions, 2 overhead per 4 elements
size_t i;
for (i = 0; i < N - 3; i += 4) {
    sum += data[i];
    sum += data[i + 1];
    sum += data[i + 2];
    sum += data[i + 3];
}
for (; i < N; i++) sum += data[i];  // Cleanup tail
// Per 4 elements: 4 adds + 1 add (i+=4) + 1 cmp/jne = 6 instructions
// Overhead: 33%
```

The downside: more code = more I-cache pressure. Unrolling 4-8× is the sweet spot on x86-64. Unrolling 32× bloats the instruction cache and the prefetcher can't keep up with the stride.

> [!warning] The Compiler Already Unrolls at `-O2`
> With `-O2` and above, GCC and Clang auto-unroll loops when profitable. Manual unrolling is only useful when: (a) you're at `-O1` for debug-cycle speed, (b) the compiler's unroll heuristic is wrong for your data size, or (c) you need to combine unrolling with the next technique.

### Step 5: Multiple Accumulators — Break the Dependency Chain

This is the most important optimization in the progression. It exploits the CPU's out-of-order execution and superscalar capabilities.

```cpp
// ❌ SINGLE ACCUMULATOR — chain of dependencies
double sum = 0.0;
for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
    sum += data[i];
}
// CPU data-flow:
//   sum += data[0]  →  wait 3-5 cycles (FP add latency)
//   sum += data[1]  →  must wait for previous sum
//   sum += data[2]  →  must wait for previous sum
//   ...
// The ALU sits idle waiting for the previous add to complete
// CPE = FP add latency (~3-5 for double on modern CPUs)

// ✅ MULTIPLE ACCUMULATORS — independent chains, parallel execution
double sum1 = 0.0, sum2 = 0.0, sum3 = 0.0, sum4 = 0.0;
size_t i;
for (i = 0; i < N - 3; i += 4) {
    sum1 += data[i];        // Chain 1: independent
    sum2 += data[i + 1];    // Chain 2: independent
    sum3 += data[i + 2];    // Chain 3: independent
    sum4 += data[i + 3];    // Chain 4: independent
}
double sum = (sum1 + sum2) + (sum3 + sum4);
// Four independent chains → the CPU can execute 2-4 FP adds
// in parallel if it has enough execution units
// CPE ~= FP add latency / num_accumulators
```

**How many accumulators?** The sweet spot = `throughput × latency`. If the CPU can start 2 FP adds per cycle (throughput = 0.5 cycles/add) and each add takes 4 cycles (latency = 4), you need at least `4 / 0.5 = 8` accumulators to completely hide the latency and saturate the execution units. In practice, 4-8 accumulators is the range to test; register pressure limits how many you can use.

### Step 6: Reassociation — Change How Operations Combine

```cpp
// ❌ SEQUENTIAL — each addition depends on the previous
sum = ((((data[0] + data[1]) + data[2]) + data[3]) + data[4]);

// ✅ TREE — independent additions, then combine
// sum = (data[0] + data[1]) + (data[2] + data[3]) + data[4];
//       └─── independent ──┘  └─── independent ──┘
```

> [!warning] The `-ffast-math` Trap
> Floating-point addition is NOT associative. `(a + b) + c ≠ a + (b + c)` due to rounding. The compiler CANNOT reassociate floating-point operations unless you explicitly tell it to with `-ffast-math` (GCC/Clang) or `/fp:fast` (MSVC). This flag also enables: treating subnormals as zero, ignoring NaN/Inf, and assuming no signed zeros. In game physics, `-ffast-math` is standard — the ~1-2 ULP precision loss is acceptable for the 2-5× speedup. But NEVER use it in financial code, scientific reproducibility contexts, or deterministic multiplayer with lockstep simulation unless you've verified bit-identical results.

---

### Worked Example — Tracing CPE Through All Six Transformations

This is CS:APP Ch 5's signature pedagogy: one function, six transformations, CPE measured after each. We'll trace a **combining function** that multiplies all elements of an integer array into `*dest`. All measurements assume a modern x86-64 CPU (~3 GHz), GCC `-O2`, data fits in L1 cache (N=1024).

**The function:**
```cpp
// Multiply all elements of data[] into dest
void Combine(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        *dest = *dest * data[i];
    }
}
```

| Step | Transformation | CPE | Speedup | What Changed |
|:----:|--------------|----:|--------:|-------------|
| 0 | Baseline (vanilla `-O2`) | 10.00 | — | Compiler does basic optimization but reads/writes `*dest` every iteration |
| 1 | Code motion — hoist `*dest` into local | 5.00 | 2.0× | Eliminated repeated memory load/store of `*dest` |
| 2 | Strength reduction — none needed | 5.00 | — | Multiplication is already the cheapest op for this loop |
| 3 | Eliminate memory refs — accumulate in register | 5.00 | — | Already done in step 1 (local = register) |
| 4 | Loop unrolling 2× | 3.00 | 1.67× | Reduced loop overhead from ~50% to ~33% of instructions |
| 5 | 2 accumulators + 2× unroll | 1.50 | 2.0× | Two independent multiply chains → CPU issues 2 per cycle |
| 6 | Reassociation | 1.01 | 1.49× | Tree reduction lets the CPU schedule multiplies across all 3 execution ports |

**Step-by-step code with measurements:**

```cpp
// ===== BASELINE (CPE = 10.0) =====
void Combine1(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        *dest = *dest * data[i];   // Read *dest, multiply, write *dest — every iteration
    }
}
// Problem: *dest lives in memory. Every *= reads, modifies, writes back.
// Memory alias: compiler can't prove data[i] != *dest, so it reloads every time.
// Result: 10 cycles per element — limited by store-forwarding latency.

// ===== CODE MOTION (CPE = 5.0) =====
void Combine2(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    long acc = *dest;              // Hoist: read dest once into local (register)
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++) {
        acc = acc * data[i];       // Register-only multiply — 5 cycle latency for IMUL
    }
    *dest = acc;                   // Write back once
}
// Improvement: 2.0× faster. But CPE is still limited by integer multiply latency.
// Each IMUL depends on the previous result → 5-cycle chain.

// ===== LOOP UNROLLING 2× (CPE = 3.0) =====
void Combine4(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    long acc = *dest;
    size_t i;
    size_t limit = N - 1;
    for (i = 0; i < limit; i += 2) {
        acc = acc * data[i];       // Still dependent on acc from previous iteration
        acc = acc * data[i + 1];   // NOT independent — still chained through acc!
    }
    for (; i < N; i++) acc = acc * data[i];
    *dest = acc;
}
// Improvement: 1.67×. Loop overhead reduced, but the critical path (acc→acc→acc)
// is still a single chain of dependent multiplies. Unrolling alone doesn't help
// data-dependent code.

// ===== 2 ACCUMULATORS + 2× UNROLL (CPE = 1.50) =====
void Combine5(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    long acc1 = *dest;             // Independent accumulator 1
    long acc2 = *dest;             // Independent accumulator 2
    size_t i;
    size_t limit = N - 1;
    for (i = 0; i < limit; i += 2) {
        acc1 = acc1 * data[i];     // Chain A: acc1 → acc1 → acc1 ...
        acc2 = acc2 * data[i + 1]; // Chain B: acc2 → acc2 → acc2 ...
        // Chains A and B are INDEPENDENT — CPU can execute both in parallel
    }
    for (; i < N; i++) acc1 = acc1 * data[i];
    *dest = acc1 * acc2;           // Combine at the end
}
// Breakthrough: 3.33× over previous. Two independent chains let the CPU
// overlap execution. CPE = latency / num_accumulators = 5 / 2 = 2.5... 
// but we get 1.50 because the CPU actually issues 3 integer multiplies 
// per cycle on modern hardware (3 execution ports with IMUL capability).

// ===== REASSOCIATION (CPE = 1.01) =====
void Combine6(long* data, size_t N, long* dest) {
    long acc = *dest;
    size_t i;
    size_t limit = N - 1;
    for (i = 0; i < limit; i += 2) {
        acc = acc * (data[i] * data[i + 1]);  // Reassociated!
        // Step 1: data[i] * data[i+1] — independent, can run NOW
        // Step 2: acc * (result)          — depends on step 1
        // This creates a 2-stage tree instead of a linear chain,
        // allowing more instruction-level parallelism
    }
    for (; i < N; i++) acc = acc * data[i];
    *dest = acc;
}
// Near the throughput bound: CPE ≈ 1.01. The CPU's three integer execution
// ports are saturated — you've hit the hardware limit. You CANNOT go faster 
// on this CPU without changing the algorithm or data layout.
```

> [!tip] The Key Insight
> The critical path (longest chain of dependent operations) determines CPE. Code motion, unrolling, and eliminating memory references shorten the path by removing overhead. Multiple accumulators and reassociation **break** the chain into parallel sub-chains, letting the CPU's out-of-order execution overlap work. When CPE approaches `1 / execution_ports`, you're at the throughput bound — the hardware literally cannot do more arithmetic per cycle.

**What this means for real code:**

1. **Profile first** — you don't know you have a CPE=10 function until you measure
2. **Single-accumulator loops are almost always latency-bound** — 2-4 accumulators fix this
3. **Memory aliasing kills optimization** — the compiler loaded `*dest` every iteration because it thought `data[i]` might point to `*dest`. `__restrict` or local variables fix this
4. **The transformation order matters** — code motion enables unrolling, unrolling enables accumulators, accumulators enable reassociation
5. **Stop when you hit the throughput bound** — more transformations after CPE=1.01 are wasted effort

---

## Part 4: Understanding CPU Limits

Every loop has a floor — the fastest it can possibly run given the hardware. CS:APP teaches how to compute this floor so you know when to stop optimizing.

### Latency vs Throughput Bounds

- **Latency bound:** The minimum CPE imposed by the longest chain of dependent operations. If each FP add takes 4 cycles and every add depends on the previous, CPE ≥ 4.0 no matter what.
- **Throughput bound:** The minimum CPE imposed by the number of execution units. If the CPU has 2 FP adders, it can complete at most 2 adds per cycle → CPE ≥ 0.5.

The **actual** CPE = `max(latency_bound, throughput_bound)`. If your measured CPE is close to the throughput bound, you're done — the hardware can't go faster. If it's close to the latency bound, use more accumulators (Step 5) to break the dependency chain.

### The Data-Flow Graph

For a loop body, draw the dependency graph:

```
sum += data[i]:

  data[i] ──┐
             ├──► [+] ──► sum'
     sum  ──┘       ↑
                    │
              3-5 cycle chain (FP add latency)
              Every iteration waits on this edge
```

The critical path is the longest chain of dependent operations. Your target: make the critical path shorter than the throughput limit. Reassociation and multiple accumulators both shorten the critical path by introducing parallel work.

---

## Part 5: Profiling Tools

### Linux: `perf`

```bash
# Statistical sampling — find hot functions
perf record ./myprogram          # Record samples (~4 kHz default)
perf report                      # Interactive flame graph / call tree

# Count hardware events for a specific function
perf stat -e cycles,instructions,cache-references,cache-misses,\
branches,branch-misses ./myprogram

# Per-function breakdown
perf stat -e cycles:u -- ./myprogram 2>&1
```

Key metrics from `perf stat`:
| Metric | What It Tells You |
|--------|-------------------|
| IPC < 1.0 | Pipeline stalls — cache misses, branch mispredictions, data dependencies |
| IPC > 2.5 | Code is well-optimized, executing multiple instructions per cycle |
| Branch miss rate > 2% | Branch predictor is suffering — sort your data or restructure conditionals |
| L1 D$ miss rate > 5% | Cache-hostile access pattern — check AoS vs SoA, loop order |
| LLC miss rate > 1% | Working set doesn't fit in L3 — blocking/tiling needed |

### Intel VTune / AMD uProf

GUI-based profilers showing microarchitecture bottlenecks:
- **Front-End Bound:** Decoder can't supply enough instructions (I-cache misses, branch mispredictions).
- **Back-End Bound (Memory):** Execution units waiting on cache/memory.
- **Back-End Bound (Core):** Execution units saturated — you're at the throughput bound.
- **Bad Speculation:** Wasted work from branch mispredictions.
- **Retiring:** Actually useful work. Higher = better. Aim for >70%.

### UE5 Profiling

```
stat unit         — Frame breakdown: Game, Draw, GPU
stat fps           — Frame rate
Unreal Insights    — Per-thread timeline, memory tracing, asset loading
Trace::ToggleChannel() — In-code markers for custom profiling
```

---

## Part 6: Amdahl's Law — Why the "Small" Serial Parts Matter

> [!info] Analogy — The Single-Cashier Supermarket
> You have 20 checkout lanes (20 CPU cores), but only ONE cashier handles payments. Even if you add 100 more lanes, the payment step is serial — every customer waits for the one cashier. The maximum speedup is limited by the serial fraction, not the parallel fraction.

Amdahl's Law states:

```
                1
Speedup ≤ ─────────────
           S + (1-S)/P

Where: S  = fraction of work that is SERIAL (cannot be parallelized)
       P  = number of processors
```

| Serial Fraction (S) | P=4 | P=8 | P=16 | P=∞ (max) |
|---------------------|-----|-----|------|-----------|
| 1% | 3.88× | 7.48× | 13.9× | **100×** |
| 5% | 3.48× | 5.93× | 9.14× | **20×** |
| 10% | 3.08× | 4.71× | 6.40× | **10×** |
| 20% | 2.50× | 3.33× | 3.90× | **5×** |
| 50% | 1.60× | 1.78× | 1.88× | **2×** |

> [!warning] The Game Engine Implication
> If your frame has 10% serial work (game thread logic that can't be parallelized), you can NEVER exceed 10× speedup — even with infinite cores. At 8 cores, you're capped at 4.71×. This is why game engines invest heavily in keeping the main thread lean: every cycle spent in serial code is a cycle that limits the whole frame.

**Corollary — optimize the serial part first.** If your profiler shows 80% of time in a single-threaded loop, fix that loop before adding threads. Parallelizing already-fast code is wasted effort; speeding up the serial bottleneck benefits everything.

---

## Part 7: Cache-Friendly Code Patterns

Cross-reference [[../Hardware/05 — Memory Hierarchy|Memory Hierarchy]] for the theory. Here are the patterns that matter for performance:

### Loop Interchange

```cpp
// ❌ BAD — column-major access on row-major data
for (size_t j = 0; j < N; j++)         // Outer: columns
    for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++)     // Inner: rows
        sum += matrix[i][j];           // Stride-N access — every access misses cache

// ✅ GOOD — row-major access
for (size_t i = 0; i < N; i++)         // Outer: rows
    for (size_t j = 0; j < N; j++)     // Inner: columns
        sum += matrix[i][j];           // Stride-1 access — one miss per cache line
```

### Loop Blocking (Tiling)

When your data exceeds cache size, restructure the computation to work on cache-sized tiles:

```cpp
// ❌ BAD — entire matrix doesn't fit in cache, constant evictions
for (i...) for (j...) for (k...) C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];

// ✅ GOOD — block the loops to work on tiles that fit in L1
// BLOCK = 32 for 32 KB L1 cache (32×32×8 bytes per double = 8 KB per tile × 3 = 24 KB)
for (ii = 0; ii < N; ii += BLOCK)
    for (jj = 0; jj < N; jj += BLOCK)
        for (kk = 0; kk < N; kk += BLOCK)
            for (i = ii; i < min(ii+BLOCK, N); i++)
                for (j = jj; j < min(jj+BLOCK, N); j++)
                    for (k = kk; k < min(kk+BLOCK, N); k++)
                        C[i][j] += A[i][k] * B[k][j];
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Performance optimization is a four-step loop: measure how slow your code actually is (CPE), profile to find which function or loop is the bottleneck, apply ONE transformation at a time, then remeasure to confirm it helped. The most powerful transformations for loops are: hoist invariant calculations out, use pointer arithmetic instead of multiplication, keep your accumulator in a register, unroll the loop 4-8× to reduce overhead, and use multiple accumulators to keep all CPU execution units busy. Amdahl's Law is the brutal reality check: if 10% of your code must run serially, you can never get more than 10× speedup no matter how many cores you add. Fix the serial bottleneck first.

### Technical
Performance optimization targets the gap between measured CPE and the hardware's latency/throughput bounds. The data-flow graph reveals the critical path — the longest chain of dependent operations dictating the latency bound. Multiple accumulators and reassociation transform the critical path from a single long chain into multiple short chains that execute in parallel on the CPU's superscalar execution units. The throughput bound (CPE = 1 / (#execution_units × operations_per_cycle)) is the absolute hardware limit. Profiling tools (`perf`, VTune, uProf) classify pipeline stalls into front-end bound (I-cache, decoders), back-end bound (data cache, execution port saturation), and bad speculation (branch mispredictions). Amdahl's Law formalizes the diminishing returns of parallelism: Speedup = 1 / (S + (1-S)/P). Loop blocking (tiling) restructures computation to fit working sets into each cache level, trading increased instruction count for dramatically reduced cache misses.

---

## Exercises

1. **CPE measurement:** Write `SumBaseline` from Part 3. Instrument it with `RDTSC`. Run on arrays of size 1K, 10K, 100K, 1M, 10M. Plot CPE vs N. Why does CPE change with N? (Hint: what cache level does each N fit in?)

2. **Accumulator scaling:** Implement the sum function with 1, 2, 4, 8, and 16 accumulators. Plot CPE vs accumulator count. Find the sweet spot. At what count does CPE stop improving? Why? Compare against the FP add latency and throughput for your CPU (look up at `https://uops.info`).

3. **Amdahl's Law in practice:** Your frame budget is 16.7 ms (60 FPS). Profiling shows: 6 ms in parallelizable physics, 4 ms in parallelizable AI, 3 ms in serial game thread logic, 3.7 ms in GPU (separate pipeline). How many cores do you need to hit 60 FPS? If you optimize the serial logic by 50%, what's the new core requirement?

4. **Loop interchange benchmark:** Write a 2048×2048 matrix row-sum (row-major outer loop) vs column-sum (column-major outer loop). Time both. What's the ratio? Why? Now vary the inner loop size from 16 to 2048 — plot the performance cliff when the inner loop exceeds L1 D$ size.

5. **Compiler autovectorization:** Write a float array dot product. Compile with `-O2` and `-O2 -fno-tree-vectorize`. Compare assembly output (`objdump -d`) — find the `addps`/`vaddps` instructions. What's the CPE difference? Now add `__restrict` to the pointer parameters — why does this sometimes enable vectorization that was previously blocked?

---

