03 \u2014 static in C++.content:
# static in C++

> [!note] Why This Matters
> Static variables share data across all instances, create lazy-initialized singletons, and hide symbols from other .cpp files. Misunderstanding them leads to linker errors, thread-safety bugs, and crashes before `main()` even runs.

---

## One Keyword, Four Meanings

| Context | What `static` Does |
|---|---|
| **Member variable** | Shared across ALL instances of the class — one copy total |
| **Member function** | Callable without an object — no `this` pointer |
| **Local variable** | Persists across function calls — initialized only once |
| **Global variable/function** | Internal linkage — visible only in this .cpp file |

---

## Static Member Variables — One Copy, Shared By All

```cpp
class Soldier {
public:
    static int AliveCount;  // One variable shared by ALL Soldier objects
    int Health;             // Each Soldier has their OWN Health
};

int Soldier::AliveCount = 0;  // Must define outside the class (in .cpp)

Soldier a, b, c;
a.AliveCount = 3;  b.AliveCount = 5;
// c.AliveCount is also 5 — SAME variable
```

> [!tip] C++17 `inline static` — No Out-of-Class Definition Needed
> ```cpp
> class Soldier {
>     inline static int AliveCount = 0;  // Definition AND declaration in one place!
>     // No .cpp definition required. C++17 feature.
> };
> ``

### constexpr Static Data Members (C++17)

```cpp
class Config {
public:
    static constexpr int MaxPlayers = 64;     // Compile-time constant, inline by default
    static constexpr float Gravity = 9.81f;   // No .cpp definition needed
};
// Can be used as template arguments and array sizes without odr-use issues
std::array<int, Config::MaxPlayers> scores;  // OK
```

---

## Static Member Functions — No Object Needed

```cpp
class FMath {
public:
    static float Lerp(float A, float B, float Alpha);  // Called on class, not instance
};

float result = FMath::Lerp(0.0f, 100.0f, 0.5f);  // No FMath object exists
// Static methods have NO `this` pointer — cannot access non-static members
```

---

## Static Local Variables — Persist, Init Once, Thread-Safe

```cpp
int GetNextID() {
    static int nextID = 1000;  // Init ONCE on first call
    return nextID++;
}
```

### The Guard Variable — How Thread-Safe Init Works

Since C++11, static local initialization is thread-safe. The compiler generates a hidden **guard variable**:

```cpp
// What the compiler generates for: static int x = InitOnce();
static bool __guard = false;  // Hidden guard variable (1 byte, but padded to alignment)
static int x;                 // The actual static local

int GetNextID() {
    if (!__guard) {                    // Fast path: already initialized?
        LockGuard lock(__mutex);       // Slow path: acquire thread-safety lock
        if (!__guard) {                // Double-check under lock
            x = 1000;                  // Initialize
            __guard = true;            // Mark as done
        }
    }
    return x++;
}
```

The fast path (already initialized) costs one branch. The slow path (first call) costs a lock acquire. This is why `static constinit` (C++20) is faster — no guard variable needed:

```cpp
void Foo() {
    static constinit int counter = 0;  // Compile-time init — ZERO guard variable
    counter++;
}
```

---

## Static Global Variables/Functions — Internal Linkage

```cpp
// In MyFile.cpp:
static int counter = 0;     // Only visible inside MyFile.cpp
// In OtherFile.cpp:
// counter — ERROR: not visible here
```

Modern C++ prefers anonymous namespaces, but `static` is still common in UE:

```cpp
namespace { int counter; }  // Preferred modern way
static int debugCount;      // UE source style
```

---

## The Static Initialization Order Fiasco — Deep Dive

Global `static` objects across multiple `.cpp` files have **unspecified** construction order. This is the root of crashes before `main()`:

```cpp
// File: Logger.cpp
std::string globalLogPath = "/var/log/app.log";  // Constructed sometime before main()

// File: Database.cpp
extern std::string globalLogPath;
std::string dbPath = globalLogPath + "/database";  // Might read garbage!

// File: Network.cpp
extern std::string globalLogPath;
extern std::string dbPath;
// Which of these is initialized? No guarantee. No compiler warning. No runtime error until crash.
```

With 3+ translation units, the problem compounds combinatorially. There is **no** portable fix using global constructors — the only safe pattern is Meyer's Singleton:

```cpp
// The Fix for ALL translation units:
std::string& GetLogPath() {
    static std::string path = "/var/log/app.log";  // C++11: thread-safe, lazy
    return path;
}

std::string& GetDbPath() {
    static std::string path = GetLogPath() + "/database";  // Safe: GetLogPath() already initialized
    return path;
}
```

`constinit` (C++20) solves the fiasco for compile-time-constructible values:

```cpp
constinit int MAX = 64;  // Compile error if init requires runtime code — guaranteed safe
```

---

## thread_local vs static

`thread_local` gives each thread its OWN copy of a variable, with per-thread lazy initialization:

```cpp
thread_local int tlsCounter = 0;  // Each thread gets its own counter, starting at 0

void ThreadWork() {
    tlsCounter++;  // Thread-safe by design — no mutex needed
}
```

| Storage | One copy per | Lifetime | Init |
|---------|-------------|----------|------|
| `static` | Program | Program duration | Once (first call) |
| `thread_local` | Thread | Thread duration | Once per thread (first use) |
| `static thread_local` | Thread (same as thread_local) | Thread | Once per thread |

Game engine use: per-thread allocator caches (`thread_local MemoryArena`), per-thread random number generators, per-thread profiler counters.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
`static` is the shape-shifter of C++. Inside a class: "shared by everyone — one whiteboard, many readers." Inside a function: "remember this between calls — a notepad that survives the meeting." At file scope: "keep this private — don't tell the other .cpp files about it." The static init fiasco is the dinner party problem: guests (global objects) arrive in an unpredictable order. If Chef Bob needs wine from Sommelier Alice but Bob arrives first — disaster. Meyer's singleton fixes this by making guests arrive only when first called. `thread_local` gives each thread its own private copy — like each dinner guest having their own notepad. C++17 `inline static` lets you define class statics right in the header. C++20 `constinit` enforces compile-time init, eliminating guard variables.

### Technical
`static` has four distinct meanings: (1) static member variables — static storage duration, shared across all instances, defined out-of-class (or `inline static` in C++17 for in-header definition); (2) static member functions — no `this`, only static member access; (3) static local variables — initialized once on first execution with compiler-generated guard variable for thread safety (C++11+); (4) static at file/namespace scope — internal linkage. The static init order fiasco: global static objects across translation units are constructed in unspecified order before `main()`. Meyer's singleton (function-local static) defers to first call. `constexpr static` data members (C++17) are implicitly inline and compile-time. `constinit` (C++20) enforces compile-time initialization. `thread_local` provides per-thread instances with per-thread lazy initialization — useful for allocator caches and RNG state.

## See Also

- [[07 — const Correctness]] — The other major member modifier alongside static
- [[../05 — Modern C++/02 — constexpr, consteval & constinit|constexpr & constinit]] — constinit solves the fiasco for compile-time values

## Exercises

1. **Translation unit isolation:** Create two `.cpp` files. In file A, define a `static int counter = 0` at global scope and a function that increments it. In file B, declare `extern int counter` and try to access it. What linker error do you get? Fix it by removing `static`. What does this tell you about `static` at namespace scope?

2. **Static local initialization cost:** Write a function with a `static std::vector<int>` that is populated with 1M elements on first call. Call it 10,000 times from a loop. Measure the total time. Now change the static local to a function parameter (allocate outside the loop). Compare the times. How many cycles does the hidden guard variable check cost per call?

3. **Static member ordering:** Create two classes A and B where A's constructor calls a function in B and B's constructor calls a function in A. Both functions read a `static` member of the other class. Does this work? What's the static initialization order fiasco? How would `constinit` (C++20) help?

4. **Class static vs global:** You need a counter shared across all instances of `Entity`. Should you use a global `int g_entityCount` or `static int s_entityCount` inside the class? What's the practical difference? Which is more maintainable in a large codebase?

5. **Design:** Your game has a `Log` class where `Log::Write()` is called from 16 threads simultaneously. The log file handle should be opened exactly once. Design the `static` members: should the file handle be a static local, a static member, or a global? Should the open-once logic use the thread-safe static local guarantee, or `std::call_once`? Justify your choice.

04 \u2014 Structured Bindings.content:
# Structured Bindings (C++17)

## Destructuring Made Simple

```cpp
std::pair<int, std::string> p{42, "hello"};
auto [num, text] = p;      // num = 42, text = "hello" — no more .first / .second!

std::tuple<int, float, std::string> t{1, 3.14f, "world"};
auto [a, b, c] = t;        // a = 1, b = 3.14, c = "world"
```

**Structured bindings work with:** pairs, tuples, arrays, and structs with all public members.

---

## With Structs

```cpp
struct Point { float x, y, z; };
Point p{1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f};
auto [x, y, z] = p;  // Direct field access by name — x = p.x, etc.

// Works with const and references:
const auto& [cx, cy, cz] = p;  // const references — no copy
```

---

## With Maps

```cpp
std::map<int, std::string> m{{1, "one"}, {2, "two"}};
for (const auto& [key, value] : m) {
    // key is int, value is string — no .first / .second!
}
```

---

## With C++17 if-initializers

```cpp
if (auto [it, inserted] = mySet.insert(42); inserted) {
    // it points to the element, inserted is true — it was actually inserted
}
```

### C++20: Init-Statement Extensions

C++20 extended structured bindings to more contexts:

```cpp
// C++20: range-for with init-statement
for (auto& map = GetMap(); const auto& [key, value] : map) {
    // map lives for the loop duration; bindings are const references
}

// C++20: lambda capture of structured bindings
auto [a, b] = GetTuple();
auto lambda = [=] { return a + b; };  // Captures a and b by value

// C++20: structured binding in switch init
switch (auto [code, msg] = GetResult(); code) {
    case 0:   /* success */ break;
    case 404: /* msg is the error message */ break;
}
```

---

## The Compiler's View — What Structured Bindings Generate

Structured bindings are syntactic sugar. The compiler generates a hidden variable and the bindings are aliases into it:

```cpp
auto [x, y] = GetPair();  // User writes this

// Compiler generates (conceptual):
auto __hidden = GetPair();           // The source object (copy or reference)
std::tuple_element_t<0, decltype(__hidden)>& x = std::get<0>(__hidden);
std::tuple_element_t<1, decltype(__hidden)>& y = std::get<1>(__hidden);
```

The key insight: `auto [x, y]` — the `auto` applies to the HIDDEN object, not to x and y. x and y are always references into the hidden object. `const auto& [x, y]` makes the hidden object a const reference.

For structs with public members, the compiler uses direct member access instead of `get`<>`:

```cpp
struct Point { float x, y; };
auto [a, b] = Point{1, 2};

// Compiler generates:
Point __hidden{1, 2};
float& a = __hidden.x;  // Direct member reference — declaration order, NOT alphabetical
float& b = __hidden.y;
```

---

## Customizing — The Tuple Protocol

Make your own types unpackable via three specializations:

```cpp
class Vec3 {
    float data[3];
public:
    float& operator[](int i) { return data[i]; }
};

// 1. How many bindings?
template<> struct std::tuple_size<Vec3> : std::integral_constant<size_t, 3> {};

// 2. What type is binding N?
template<size_t I> struct std::tuple_element<I, Vec3> { using type = float; };

// 3. Provide get<I>() found via ADL
template<size_t I> float& get(Vec3& v) { return v[I]; }

auto [x, y, z] = Vec3{};  // Now works!
```

### The Aggregate Protocol — Automatic

If your type has only public members and no user-declared constructors, structured bindings work automatically — the compiler reflects on the members in declaration order. The number of bindings must match exactly.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Structured bindings unpack a box of values into separate names in one line. `auto [first, second] = pair;` replaces `first = pair.first; second = pair.second;`. For maps, `for (auto [key, value] : map)` replaces `.first`/`.second`. The names match member order (first member = first binding). You can customize your own types by telling the compiler how many slots and how to access each. The compiler creates a hidden copy; the binding names are aliases into that copy. `const auto& [x, y]` avoids copying entirely.

### Technical
Structured bindings (C++17) introduce an unnamed hidden variable `__e` initialized from the RHS. The binding identifiers are references into `__e` — for tuples via `std::tuple_element_t<I, E>, for aggregates via decltype of the member. The `auto` specifier applies to `__e`, not the bindings. Custom types opt in via `std::tuple_size`<T>`, `std::tuple_element``<I,T>``, and ADL-found `get`<I>`(T)`. C++20 extends bindings to lambda captures, range-for init-statements, and switch init-statements.

## See Also

- [[05 — Type Deduction]] — `auto` in structured bindings and the hidden variable's type deduction
- [[../05 — Modern C++/01 — Move Semantics & Perfect Forwarding|Move Semantics]] — Structured binding with `auto&&` for perfect forwarding
- [[../05 — Modern C++/07 — C++23 Overview|C++23 Overview]] — Deducing `this` and future directions

## Exercises

1. **Map iteration:** Iterate a `std::map<std::string, std::vector<int>>` using structured bindings: `for (const auto& [name, scores] : grades)`. Print each student's average. How would you write this WITHOUT structured bindings? Count the lines saved.

2. **Return value decomposition:** Write a function `DivideMod(int a, int b)` that returns a `std::pair<int, int>` (quotient, remainder). Use structured bindings to call it: `auto [q, r] = DivideMod(17, 5)`. Verify q=3, r=2. Now write the same thing with `std::tie`. Which is clearer?

3. **Custom type binding:** Implement the tuple-like protocol for a `struct Point3D { float x, y, z; }` by specializing `std::tuple_size`, `std::tuple_element`, and writing a `get<N>()` free function. Use `auto [px, py, pz] = point;` and verify it compiles.

4. **Reference semantics:** Declare `auto [a, b] = std::make_tuple(1, 2);` and modify `a`. Does the original tuple change? Now use `auto& [a, b] = tuple;` — does the tuple change now? Explain the difference between value and reference bindings.

5. **Design:** Your game's `GetEntityComponents()` returns a `std::tuple<Transform&, Mesh&, Health&>`. Should callers use structured bindings? What are the risks if the entity is destroyed while bindings are alive?

07 \u2014 const Correctness.content:
# const Correctness

## What `const` Actually Means

`const` is a promise: "I will not modify this." It's the most important keyword in C++ for preventing bugs, but its meaning changes depending on where you put it.

```cpp
const int* p;       // Pointer to const int — can't modify the int through p
int* const p;       // Const pointer to int — can't change where p points
const int* const p; // Both — can't modify the int, can't change the pointer
```

Read right-to-left: `const int* p` = "p is a pointer to an int that is const." `int* const p` = "p is a const pointer to an int."

---

## Const on Member Functions

```cpp
class Widget
{
    int value;
    int accessCount;  // Mutable — can change even in const methods

public:
    int GetValue() const
    {
        accessCount++;  // ✅ OK — marked mutable
        return value;    // ✅ OK — reading is allowed
        // value++;      // ❌ ERROR — can't modify in const method
    }

    void SetValue(int v)
    {
        value = v;  // ✅ OK — non-const method
    }
};
```

**`const` on a member function means:** "This method does not modify the object's observable state." The compiler enforces this — you cannot modify any member variable (except those marked `mutable`) inside a `const` method.

> [!tip] The const Contract Is Shallow
> `const` only protects the TOP-LEVEL members. If your class has a pointer member, `const` prevents you from changing the pointer — but it does NOT prevent you from modifying what the pointer points to. The `const` applies to the pointer itself (`int* const` implicitly), not to the pointed-to value.
> ```cpp
> class Container { int* data; };
> void Container::ModifyData() const { *data = 5; }  // ✅ Compiles! const doesn't propagate through pointers.
> ``

---

## Const References — The Backbone of C++

```cpp
void Process(const std::string& name);       // Pass by const ref — no copy, no modification
void Process(const std::vector<int>& data);  // Same for any type
```

**The rule:** Pass by `const&` when you need to read data without copying it. This is the default for function parameters in modern C++ — pass by value only when you need a copy.

**Lifetime extension:** A const reference extends the lifetime of a temporary:
```cpp
const std::string& ref = GetTemporaryString();  // Temporary lives as long as ref does
```

---

## `const` and Pointers — The Complete Matrix

| Declaration | Meaning | Can modify pointed-to value? | Can change pointer? |
|---|---|---|---|
| `T*` | Mutable pointer to mutable T | ✅ | ✅ |
| `const T*` | Mutable pointer to const T | ❌ | ✅ |
| `T* const` | Const pointer to mutable T | ✅ | ❌ |
| `const T* const` | Const pointer to const T | ❌ | ❌ |

---

## `const` with Iterators

```cpp
std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};

// const_iterator — can't modify elements
for (std::vector<int>::const_iterator it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); ++it)
{
    // *it = 5;  // ❌ ERROR — const_iterator
}

// const iterator — can't advance
const auto it = v.begin();
// it++;         // ❌ ERROR — iterator itself is const

// C++11 range-for with const
for (const auto& elem : v)  // Read-only access to each element
{
    // elem = 5;  // ❌ ERROR — const reference
}
```

**The rule:** Use `const_iterator` when you don't modify elements. Use `cbegin()/cend()` (C++14) to get const iterators explicitly.

---

## `const` and Return Types

```cpp
// ❌ Returning const by value is pointless — the caller gets a copy anyway
const int GetValue() { return value; }

// ✅ Returning const reference — caller can read but not modify
const std::string& GetName() const { return name; }

// ❌ Returning non-const reference to a member from a const method
std::string& GetName() const { return name; }  // ERROR — const method, non-const return
```

---

## Logical vs Physical constness

```cpp
class Cache
{
    std::vector<int> data;
    mutable std::optional<size_t> cachedSize;  // mutable: can change in const methods

public:
    size_t GetSize() const
    {
        if (!cachedSize)
        {
            // Compute and cache — logically const (observable state unchanged)
            cachedSize = data.size();
        }
        return *cachedSize;
    }
};
```

**`mutable` exists for this pattern:** The object's logical state (what the user cares about) doesn't change, but internal bookkeeping does. Use `mutable` sparingly — it's a tool for caching, mutexes, and debug counters, not for circumventing const correctness.

---

## Top-Level vs Low-Level const

```cpp
int x = 5;
const int cx = 10;

int* p1 = &x;           // Low-level: none. Top-level: none.
const int* p2 = &cx;    // Low-level: const int. Top-level: none.
int* const p3 = &x;     // Low-level: none. Top-level: const pointer.

// Top-level const is ignored when copying:
int* p4 = p3;  // ✅ OK — p3's top-level const is stripped

// Low-level const must match:
const int* p5 = p1;     // ✅ OK — adding low-level const
// int* p6 = p2;        // ❌ ERROR — can't remove low-level const
```

**The rule:** You can ADD const (non-const → const conversion), but you cannot REMOVE it (except with `const_cast`, which is almost always wrong).

---

## `constexpr` and `const` — Not the Same

```cpp
const int x = GetRuntimeValue();    // Value fixed at runtime
constexpr int y = 42;               // Value fixed at COMPILE TIME

constexpr int z = GetCompileTimeValue();  // Only works if function is constexpr
```

`const` = "won't change after initialization." `constexpr` = "known at compile time." All `constexpr` variables are implicitly `const`, but not all `const` variables are `constexpr`.

---

## `consteval` and `constinit` (C++20)

```cpp
consteval int CompileOnly(int x) { return x * 2; }  // MUST be evaluated at compile time
// int y = CompileOnly(rand());  // ❌ ERROR — rand() is runtime

constinit int global = 42;  // Initialized at compile time, but mutable at runtime
// constinit int bad = rand();  // ❌ ERROR — rand() not constexpr
```

- `consteval`: The function MUST be called at compile time. Stronger than `constexpr`.
- `constinit`: The variable MUST be initialized at compile time, but can change afterward. Prevents static initialization order fiasco.

---

## Common Mistakes

### 1. Forgetting `const` on "getter" methods

```cpp
// ❌ Getter isn't const — can't be called on const objects
int GetValue() { return value; }

// ✅
int GetValue() const { return value; }
```

If a method doesn't modify the object, mark it `const`. Not doing so prevents calling it from `const` references, which breaks composition.

### 2. Returning non-const references from const methods

```cpp
class Owner { std::string name; public:
    // ❌ Doesn't compile — const method returning non-const ref
    // std::string& GetName() const { return name; }

    // ✅ Return const ref from const method
    const std::string& GetName() const { return name; }

    // ✅ Return by value — caller gets their own copy
    std::string GetNameCopy() const { return name; }
};
```

### 3. Overusing `const_cast`

```cpp
const int x = 42;
int& ref = const_cast<int&>(x);  // Compiles
ref = 100;  // UNDEFINED BEHAVIOR — x was declared const
```

`const_cast` is for interop with legacy APIs that take non-const pointers but don't actually modify. Never use it to modify something that was genuinely declared `const`.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

`const` is a lock. When you mark something `const`, you lock it — nobody can change it. A `const` method is a method that promises not to change anything inside the object. A `const` reference is a window — you can look through it, but you can't touch.

### Technical

`const` modifies the type system to prevent modification through a given access path. Top-level const (`int* const`) applies to the variable itself and is ignored during copy initialization. Low-level const (`const int*`) applies to the pointed-to object and must be preserved across assignments. `const` member functions have an implicit `const T* this` parameter, preventing modification of non-mutable members. The compiler enforces const correctness at compile time with zero runtime overhead. `mutable` allows specific members to bypass const restrictions for caching and synchronization. `constexpr` extends const to compile-time evaluation, while `consteval` (C++20) enforces compile-time-only execution and `constinit` (C++20) prevents static initialization order issues.

---

## Exercises

1. **const propagation:** Class with `const` method returning non-const pointer to internal data. Compiles? Add `mutable`. When is mutable right?

2. **Four combos:** `const int*`, `int* const`, `const int* const`, `int*`. Try modifying pointer and pointee. Read right-to-left.

3. **const reference benchmark:** `void Foo(const FVector&)` vs `void Foo(FVector)`. 1M iterations. At what size does const& win?

4. **const_iterator:** `begin()` and `begin() const`. Call `begin()` on const object. Return type?

5. **UE const patterns:** `GetName()` returns `const FName&`. Why not `FName`? What would break if by value?


## See Also

- [[../03 — static in C++|static in C++]] — Static const members and initialization order
- [[../../03 — Memory/03 — Smart Pointers & Ownership|Smart Pointers]] — const with unique_ptr and shared_ptr
- [[../../04 — OOP & Generics/01 — Inheritance & Virtual Functions|Inheritance]] — const virtual functions and covariance
- [[../../../Computer Systems/Hardware/01 — Bits, Bytes & Number Systems|Bits & Bytes]] — Why const enables compiler optimizations at the hardware level

