# std::format (C++20)

> [!note] Why This Matters
> `printf` has been the formatting workhorse since 1972. It's also the #1 source of type-safety bugs in C and C++: pass `%d` with a `float`, and the runtime silently reads garbage from the stack. `std::cout <<` is type-safe but verbose — formatting a table requires a forest of `<< std::setw()` manipulators. `std::format` (C++20, based on the `{fmt}` library) combines Python-like format strings with C++ type safety and zero-overhead compilation. Errors in your format string are caught at **compile time** — not at 3 AM when a player triggers a rare dialogue path. This note covers the format mini-language, compile-time validation, positional arguments, and custom formatters.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[../../Primer/01 — Variables, Types & Memory|Variables & Types]] — type safety, strings.
> [[../String Types & string_view|String Types]] — `std::string`, `std::string_view`.

---

## The Problem — printf Is Unsafe, cout Is Verbose

```cpp
// printf: type-unsafe, no compile-time checking
printf("Player %s has %d health (%.2f%%)\n", name.c_str(), health, percent);
//                                                  ↑ forgot .c_str()? UB.
//                                                           ↑ health is float not int? UB.

// iostream: type-safe but painfully verbose
std::cout << "Player " << name << " has " << health << " health ("
          << std::fixed << std::setprecision(2) << percent << "%)\n";

// std::format: type-safe AND concise
std::string msg = std::format("Player {} has {} health ({:.2f}%)\n", name, health, percent);
```

`printf` passes arguments through `...` (C variadic) — all type information is lost. The format string is parsed at **runtime**; mismatches are undefined behavior. `std::cout` preserves types but scatters format logic across interleaved `<<` operators. `std::format` keeps the format string readable and validates types at compile time.

---

## Basic Usage

```cpp
#include <format>
#include <string>

// Positional arguments: {} consumes next argument in order
std::string s1 = std::format("{} + {} = {}", 2, 3, 5);  // "2 + 3 = 5"

// Indexed arguments: {N} refers to the Nth argument (0-based)
std::string s2 = std::format("{1} + {0} = {2}", 3, 2, 5);  // "2 + 3 = 5"

// Named arguments (C++20 via fmt, C++23 standardized — use positional in C++20)
// std::format("{a} + {b} = {c}", fmt::arg("a", 2), ...); // fmt library only

// Repeated arguments
std::string s3 = std::format("{0} {0} {0}", "Go");  // "Go Go Go"

// Output to iterator/stream
std::format_to(std::ostream_iterator<char>(std::cout), "FPS: {:.1f}\n", 59.94f);
```

---

## Format Specifiers — The Mini-Language

The full syntax: `{ [index] : [fill][align][sign][#][0][width][.precision][type] }`

```cpp
// Alignment and fill
std::format("{:*>10}", "hi");    // "********hi"   (right-align, * fill, width 10)
std::format("{:<10}",  "hi");    // "hi        "   (left-align)
std::format("{:^10}",  "hi");    // "    hi    "   (center)

// Integer types
std::format("{}",   255);        // "255"     (decimal)
std::format("{:x}", 255);        // "ff"      (hex lowercase)
std::format("{:X}", 255);        // "FF"      (hex uppercase)
std::format("{:#x}", 255);       // "0xff"    (hex with prefix)
std::format("{:b}", 255);        // "11111111"(binary)
std::format("{:o}", 255);        // "377"     (octal)

// Floating point
std::format("{}",    3.14159);   // "3.14159" (default)
std::format("{:.2f}", 3.14159);  // "3.14"    (fixed, 2 decimal places)
std::format("{:.2e}", 3.14159);  // "3.14e+00"(scientific)
std::format("{:.2g}", 3.14159);  // "3.1"     (general — auto-choose)
std::format("{:010.2f}", 3.14);  // "000003.14"(zero-padded width 10)

// Sign control
std::format("{:+}", 42);         // "+42"
std::format("{:+}", -42);        // "-42"
std::format("{: }", 42);         // " 42"     (leading space for positive)
```

---

## Compile-Time Format String Checking

This is `std::format`'s killer feature. The format string is validated at compile time:

```cpp
// ❌ Compile ERROR — caught before the binary exists
// std::format("Player {} has {:d} health", name, 3.14f);
//                                        ^^^^ type mismatch: :d expects integer, got float

// ❌ Compile ERROR — caught at compile time
// std::format("{} {} {}", a, b);
//                         ^ too few arguments

// printf equivalent — compiles fine, crashes at runtime
printf("Player %s has %d health", name, 3.14f);  // %d with float — UB, no warning!
```

How it works: `std::format_string<Args...> (a C++20 addition) uses `consteval` to enforce that the format string is valid for the given argument types. The compiler evaluates a consteval function at compile time that parses the format string and checks each `{}` replacement field against the corresponding argument type. If there's a mismatch → compile error with a descriptive message pointing to the exact position of the error.

This is a **zero-runtime-cost abstraction** — the check happens during compilation and adds nothing to the binary.

---

## Custom Formatters

To make your own types work with `std::format`, specialize `std::formatter`:

```cpp
struct FVector { float x, y, z; };

template<>
struct std::formatter<FVector> {
    // Parse format specifiers (e.g., {:vec} vs {:default})
    constexpr auto parse(std::format_parse_context& ctx) {
        auto it = ctx.begin();
        if (it != ctx.end() && *it == '}') return it;
        // Could parse custom specifiers like precision here
        return it;
    }

    // Format the value
    auto format(const FVector& v, std::format_context& ctx) const {
        return std::format_to(ctx.out(), "({:.1f}, {:.1f}, {:.1f})", v.x, v.y, v.z);
    }
};

std::string s = std::format("Position: {}", FVector{1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f});
// "Position: (1.0, 2.0, 3.0)"
```

The `parse` method is `constexpr` — called at compile time to validate any custom format specifiers. The `format` method does the actual output at runtime.

---

## Comparison to printf and cout

| Aspect | `printf` | `std::cout` | `std::format` |
|--------|----------|-------------|---------------|
| Type safety | ❌ No (variadic) | ✅ Yes (overloaded <<) | ✅ Yes (compile-time checked) |
| Format string errors | ❌ Runtime (UB) | N/A (no format string) | ✅ Compile-time error |
| Readability | ✓ Concise | ❌ Verbose (manipulators) | ✅ Concise |
| Performance | ✓ Fast | ⚠️ Slower (locale, sync) | ✅ Fast (comparable to printf) |
| Custom types | ❌ No | ✅ via `operator<<` | ✅ via `std::formatter<T>` |
| Locale support | ✓ (`%'d`) | ✅ (imbued locale) | ⚠️ Limited (C++20; C++23 improves) |
| Positional args | ✓ (`%1$s`) | N/A | ✅ (`{0}`, `{1}`) |
| Extensible format spec | ❌ No | ❌ No | ✅ Custom formatters parse specs |

---

## Performance — How format Beats iostream

`std::format` produces a `std::string` by writing into a pre-allocated buffer. Unlike `std::cout` which:

1. Checks locale on every `<<` call.
2. Synchronizes with `stdin` by default (`std::ios_base::sync_with_stdio`).
3. Performs virtual dispatch via `std::streambuf`.
4. Flushes on `std::endl` (common beginner mistake).

`std::format` does none of these. It computes the output size (via `std::formatted_size`), allocates once, and writes directly. For non-trivial formatting, `std::format` is typically **2-10× faster** than equivalent `std::ostringstream` code.

---

## `std::format_to` — Write to Any Output Iterator

```cpp
// Format directly into a pre-allocated buffer (no allocation)
char buffer[256];
auto result = std::format_to_n(buffer, sizeof(buffer), "FPS: {:.1f}", 59.94f);
// result.out points one past the last character written
// result.size is the number of characters that WOULD have been written

// Format into a std::string (grows automatically)
std::string s;
std::format_to(std::back_inserter(s), "{} {}", "Hello", "World");

// Format directly to stdout (no intermediate string)
std::format_to(std::ostreambuf_iterator(std::cout), "{}\n", 42);
```

---

## UE Connection — FString::Printf vs std::format

```cpp
// UE's printf-style formatting (still widely used)
FString msg = FString::Printf(TEXT("Health: %d"), Health);

// std::format equivalent (type-safe, compile-time checked)
std::string msg = std::format("Health: {}", Health);
// For UE FString: convert — UE doesn't have a native std::format equivalent yet
```

UE's `FString::Printf` uses the same unsafe `...` variadic mechanism as `printf`. `std::format` is the long-term replacement — type-safe, faster, and with compile-time validation. The `{fmt}` library (which `std::format` is based on) is already used internally by several UE plugins and tools.

---

## Exercises

1. **Format string error comparison:** Write equivalent formatting for a player stat display using: (a) `printf`, (b) `std::cout` with manipulators, (c) `std::format`. Introduce a deliberate type mismatch in each (wrong specifier/type). Which version catches the error? At what stage (compile, run, or silently produces wrong output)?

2. **Custom FVector3 formatter:** Implement `std::formatter<FVector3> that supports precision specifiers: `{:vec}` prints `(x, y, z)`, `{:.2vec}` prints with 2 decimal places. Parse the precision in `parse()` and apply it in `format()`. Test that `{:.2vec}` with `FVector3{1.2345f, 2.3456f, 3.4567f}` produces `"(1.23, 2.35, 3.46)"`.

3. **Performance benchmark:** Generate 100,000 formatted strings like `"Frame 12345: 59.94 FPS, 1423 draw calls"` using (a) `sprintf` into a buffer, (b) `std::ostringstream`, (c) `std::format`, (d) `std::format_to` into a pre-allocated buffer. Measure wall-clock time. Which is fastest? How many allocations does each perform?

4. **Compile-time format validation trace:** Write a program with a format string error: `std::format("{:d}", 3.14f)`. Compile and examine the error message. Where does it point? Now create a function template that chains `std::format` calls — how deep does the error trace go? Compare to what happens with the equivalent `printf` error at runtime.

5. **Design a game log formatter:** Design a `LogEntry` struct with timestamp, severity (enum), subsystem (string), and message (string). Implement `std::formatter<LogEntry> that formats entries as: `[2025-07-03 14:32:01] [ERROR] [Physics] Collision mesh overflow`. Support severity colorization via format specs (`{:color}` wraps in ANSI codes). How would you handle the case where ANSI codes aren't desired (e.g., file output)?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
`printf` is the old family recipe — "add %d, a pinch of %s, and %f to taste." But if you accidentally swap the sugar and salt (pass a float where an int is expected), nobody notices until the dish is served. `std::cout` is the kitchen scale — every ingredient individually measured and verified, but the recipe takes a paragraph to write. `std::format` is the modern recipe card: concise like printf, but the card reader (compiler) checks all ingredients against the recipe BEFORE you start cooking. A `{:d}` with a `float` gets caught when you're still holding the recipe, not when the guests are at the table.

### Technical
`std::format` (C++20, `<format>`) uses a format string with `{}` replacement fields and a Python-like mini-language. `std::format_string<Args...>` is a `consteval` wrapper that parses and validates the format string against argument types at compile time — type errors become compilation errors with precise location reporting. Format specifiers follow `{[index]:[fill][align][sign][#][0][width][.precision][type]}`. Custom types integrate via template specialization of `std::formatter<T>` with a `constexpr parse()` method and a `format()` method receiving `std::format_context`. `std::format_to` writes to arbitrary output iterators; `std::formatted_size` computes output size without allocating. Performance is comparable to `printf` (2-10× faster than `std::ostringstream`) because format avoids per-character locale checks, `sync_with_stdio` overhead, and virtual dispatch through `std::streambuf`. Based on the `{fmt}` library by Victor Zverovich, now part of the C++20 standard.

## See Also

- [[../../Primer/01 — Variables, Types & Memory|Variables & Types]] — Type safety and why compile-time checking matters
- [[09 — String Types & string_view|String Types]] — `std::string` and SSO — where format output lives
- [[../../04 — OOP & Generics/05 — Templates & Concepts|Templates & Concepts]] — How `std::format_string` uses variadic templates and concepts
- [[../../../Computer Systems/Hardware/Storage/04 — Filesystems & Page Cache|Filesystems & Page Cache]] — Where formatted logs actually land on disk

12 \u2014 I-O Streams.content:
# I/O Streams — Reading and Writing

## Why This Matters

```cpp
#include <fstream>
#include <sstream>

std::ifstream file("data.txt");
std::string line;
while (std::getline(file, line)) {
    std::istringstream iss(line);
    int x; float y;
    if (iss >> x >> y) {
        std::cout << "Read: " << x << ", " << y << '\n';
    }
}
```

Every program reads input and writes output. C++ does it with streams — a unified abstraction over files, strings, and the console. The syntax is operator-based (`>>` for input, `<<` for output), type-safe (no format strings to mismatch), and extensible (your types can plug right in). This note covers everything from `std::cout << "hello"` to binary file I/O with error handling.

---

## The Stream Hierarchy

```
std::ios_base              ← Format flags, state, locale
  └── std::ios             ← Base class for all streams
        ├── std::istream   ← Input (cin, ifstream, istringstream)
        │     └── std::iostream  ← Both input and output (fstream, stringstream)
        └── std::ostream   ← Output (cout, cerr, ofstream, ostringstream)
```

Pre-built stream objects: `std::cin` (standard input), `std::cout` (standard output), `std::cerr` (unbuffered error output), `std::clog` (buffered log output).

---

## Console I/O

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int age;
std::cout << "Enter your age: ";
std::cin >> age;  // Reads an integer. Stops at whitespace. Leaves newline in buffer.

std::string name;
std::getline(std::cin, name);  // Reads entire line including spaces
```

The trap: mixing `>>` and `getline`. After `cin >> age`, the newline is still in the buffer. The next `getline` reads an empty line:

```cpp
std::cin >> age;
std::getline(std::cin, name);  // Reads the leftover newline → empty string!

// Fix: consume the newline
std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n');
```

---

## File I/O

```cpp
#include <fstream>

// Write to file
std::ofstream out("output.txt");
out << "Hello, " << 42 << " worlds!\n";
out.close();  // Optional — destructor closes it

// Read from file
std::ifstream in("input.txt");
if (!in) {  // Check if file opened successfully
    std::cerr << "Failed to open file\n";
    return 1;
}
std::string word;
while (in >> word) {  // Reads whitespace-delimited words
    std::cout << word << '\n';
}
```

Open modes:

```cpp
std::ofstream out("file.bin", std::ios::binary);        // Binary mode (no text translation)
std::ofstream out("file.txt", std::ios::app);            // Append
std::ofstream out("file.txt", std::ios::trunc);          // Truncate (default for ofstream)
std::fstream  io("file.txt", std::ios::in | std::ios::out);  // Read + write
```

Binary mode does NOT change the format of what you write — it disables platform-specific text transformations (e.g., `\n` → `\r\n` on Windows).

---

## String Streams — In-Memory I/O

```cpp
#include <sstream>

// Formatting: build a string from pieces
std::ostringstream oss;
oss << "Score: " << 100 << ", Health: " << 75.5f;
std::string result = oss.str();  // "Score: 100, Health: 75.5"

// Parsing: extract values from a string
std::string data = "1920 1080 60";
std::istringstream iss(data);
int width, height, fps;
iss >> width >> height >> fps;  // width=1920, height=1080, fps=60
```

String streams are the C++ equivalent of `sprintf`/`sscanf` — type-safe and buffer-overflow-proof.

---

## Error Handling

Streams track their state with bit flags:

```cpp
std::ifstream file("nonexistent.txt");
if (file.fail()) { }    // Logical error (e.g., failed to open, format mismatch)
if (file.bad())  { }    // Irrecoverable stream error (e.g., disk failure)
if (file.eof())  { }    // End of file reached
if (file.good()) { }    // None of the above — everything is fine

// Boolean conversion
if (file) { }  // Equivalent to !file.fail()
if (!file) { } // Equivalent to file.fail()

// Clear errors and retry
file.clear();            // Reset error flags
file.ignore(1000, '\n'); // Skip bad input
```

The pattern for robust input reading:

```cpp
int value;
while (std::cout << "Enter a number: " && !(std::cin >> value)) {
    std::cin.clear();  // Reset error flag
    std::cin.ignore(std::numeric_limits<std::streamsize>::max(), '\n');
    std::cout << "Invalid input. Try again.\n";
}
```

---

## Buffering

Streams are buffered for performance. `std::cout` is line-buffered (flushes on `\n` when connected to a terminal). `std::cerr` is unbuffered. Files are fully buffered.

```cpp
std::cout << "Processing... ";
std::cout.flush();            // Force output now
std::cout << std::endl;       // Writes '\n' AND flushes (expensive — use '\n' unless you need flush)
```

`std::endl` is a performance trap in loops — it flushes every time. Use `'\n'` instead unless you specifically need the buffer flushed.

---

## Custom Type Integration

Overload `<<` and `>>` for your types:

```cpp
struct Vec3 { float x, y, z; };

std::ostream& operator<<(std::ostream& os, const Vec3& v) {
    return os << v.x << ' ' << v.y << ' ' << v.z;
}

std::istream& operator>>(std::istream& is, Vec3& v) {
    return is >> v.x >> v.y >> v.z;
}

Vec3 pos{1, 2, 3};
std::cout << "Position: " << pos << '\n';  // "Position: 1 2 3"
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

Input and output in C++ work like a pipeline. `std::cout` is a pipe to the console — you push data in with `<<` and it appears on screen. `std::cin` is a pipe FROM the keyboard — you pull data out with `>>` and it converts text to numbers automatically. File streams (`ifstream`/`ofstream`) are the same pipes, but connected to files instead of the console. String streams let you build a string piece by piece, or parse a string like it was typed. The `>>`/`<<` syntax means you can teach your own types to read and write themselves — `cout << myVec3` just works if you write the right function.

### Technical

C++ iostreams ([iostream.general]) use a streambuf layer for device-independent buffering. Each stream holds a pointer to a `std::streambuf` — `filebuf` for file I/O, `stringbuf` for in-memory I/O. The `operator<<` and `operator>>` are formatted I/O functions that use the stream's locale for numeric formatting. Stream state is tracked via `iostate` bitmask: `goodbit` (0), `eofbit` (1), `failbit` (2), `badbit` (4). When `failbit` is set, further operations are no-ops until `clear()` is called. The boolean conversion (`if (stream)`) is implemented via `operator bool()` (C++11+) or `operator void*()` (pre-C++11). `std::endl` calls `flush()` which calls `streambuf::pubsync()` — forcing the buffer to the OS. For binary I/O, `ios::binary` only disables text-mode newline conversion on Windows; on POSIX systems, text and binary modes are identical.

---

## Exercises

1. **Word counter:** Write a program that reads `input.txt` and prints: number of lines, number of words, and number of characters. Handle the file-not-found error gracefully.

2. **CSV parser:** Given a CSV string `"Name,Age,Score\nAlice,30,95\nBob,25,87"`, use `std::istringstream` + `std::getline` to parse it into a vector of structs. Handle quoted fields containing commas.

3. **Robust input loop:** Write a loop that repeatedly asks the user for an integer between 1 and 100. Handle: non-numeric input, numbers out of range, EOF. Loop until valid input received. No infinite loops on bad input.

4. **Binary vs text:** Write 1M ints to a file in text mode (`<<`) and binary mode (`write()`). Compare file sizes. Read them back — which is faster? Why?

5. **Design:** Your game's save system writes player state as text. The save file is 50 MB and takes 3 seconds to write. Would switching to binary I/O help? Would adding buffering help? What if you wrote to a stringstream first and then wrote the `.str()` to file in one call?

## See Also

- [[../09 — String Types & string_view|String Types]] — std::string and string_view used with streams
- [[../10 — std format (C++20)|std::format]] — Modern alternative to stringstream formatting
- [[../../01 — Primer/04 — Arrays, Vectors & Loops|Arrays & Loops]] — Basic iteration patterns for I/O
- [[../05 — Build & Debug Tools|Build & Debug Tools]] — Sanitizers that catch I/O bugs

01 \u2014 Stack vs Heap.content:
# Stack vs Heap

## The Two Memory Regions

> [!info] Systems Connection
> The stack and heap described here are the same regions shown in the **Memory Map diagram** in [[CPU Architecture]]. See [[../../Computer Systems/System Software/Function Calls/00 — Function Calls Overview|Function Calls]] for the CPU-level mechanics of how function calls create and destroy stack frames.

Every C++ program has two fundamental memory regions. Understanding which one your data lives in determines its speed, lifetime, and who cleans it up.

| | Stack | Heap |
|---|---|---|
| **Allocation** | Automatic, one CPU instruction (move stack pointer) | Manual via `new`/`malloc`, involves searching for free space |
| **Cleanup** | Automatic — popped when function returns | Manual — `delete` or smart pointer destructor |
| **Speed** | Very fast (L1/L2 cache hot) | Slower (cache-cold, fragmentation) |
| **Max size** | ~1-8 MB (platform-dependent) | Available RAM (gigabytes) |
| **Variable size** | Must be known at compile time[^1] | Can be determined at runtime |
| **Lifetime** | Tied to function scope (or block scope) | As long as you want — until `delete` |
| **Fragmentation** | None (LIFO) | Can fragment over time |
| **Thread safety** | Per-thread (each thread has its own stack) | Shared across all threads |

---

## The Stack

The stack is a contiguous block of memory. The CPU tracks the "top" with a register called the **stack pointer** (RSP on x86-64). Every function call pushes a new **stack frame** — the function's local variables, return address, and saved registers. When the function returns, the stack pointer snaps back — the entire frame is "gone" in one instruction.

```cpp
void Outer()
{
    int a = 1;          // Pushed to stack

    {
        int b = 2;      // Pushed to stack (nested scope)
        // b lives here
    }                   // b popped — stack pointer adjusted

    int c = 3;          // b's old space reused — this is free

    // a and c still alive
}                       // a and c popped — stack frame gone
```

**Why it's fast:** Stack allocation is just `sub rsp, N` (subtract from stack pointer). Deallocation is `add rsp, N` (add to stack pointer). One instruction each. The stack is always cache-hot because you're constantly using the top of it.

**The limit:** Stack size is fixed at thread creation — typically 1 MB on Windows, 8 MB on Linux. Large local arrays or deep recursion cause a **stack overflow** (program crash).

```cpp
void Overflow()
{
    int huge[1000000];  // ~4 MB — might overflow the stack!
    // Use std::vector<int> huge(1000000) instead — heap allocation
}
```

---

## The Heap

The heap is a large, flexible pool of memory. Think of it like a parking lot: cars (allocated memory) come and go in any order. Empty spots appear where cars left — but they might be too small for the next car that arrives. This is **fragmentation.**

```cpp
void Func()
{
    int* a = new int(1);  // Car A parks — allocator finds 4 bytes
    int* b = new int(2);  // Car B parks — allocator finds another 4 bytes

    delete a;             // Car A leaves — 4-byte gap appears
    int* c = new int[3];  // Car C needs 12 bytes — BUT the gap is only 4!
                          // Car C parks somewhere else. The 4-byte gap is wasted.

    delete b;             // Car B leaves — another 4-byte gap
    delete c;             // Car C leaves
    // Total free: 20 bytes. But in 4-byte fragments — can't fit a 12-byte car!
}
```

The allocator maintains a **free list** — a linked list of empty blocks, sorted by size or address. When you call `new`, the allocator walks this list looking for a block that fits. When you call `delete`, it adds the freed block back to the list (and may merge it with adjacent free blocks to reduce fragmentation).

Modern allocators (jemalloc, mimalloc, tcmalloc) use **thread-local caches** and **size classes** — small allocations (16, 32, 64 bytes) all come from the same pre-allocated pools, avoiding fragmentation entirely for the most common allocation sizes. This is what UE's `TSizedDefaultAllocator<32> does for `FString` — dedicates entire pages to 32-byte allocations so they never fragment each other.

**The advantage over stack:** Size and lifetime. Allocate a million integers — no problem. Allocate data once and pass it around for the entire program — it stays alive until you `delete` it. The stack can't do either of these.

---

## Placement New — Constructing Objects in Raw Memory

A `new` expression does TWO things: allocates memory AND constructs an object. Placement new separates these — it constructs an object in memory you already control.

```cpp
#include <new>  // Required for placement new — constructing an object at a specific memory address  // Required for placement new

// Pre-allocate raw memory however you want
alignas(Widget) std::byte buffer[sizeof(Widget) * 10];

// Construct a Widget in that memory — NO allocation
Widget* w = new (buffer) Widget(args);

// Use it normally
w->DoSomething();

// Destroy it manually — the memory (buffer) stays available
std::destroy_at(w);
// Or: w->~Widget(); — same thing
```

**This is what `emplace_back` does internally:**

```cpp
// Simplified emplace_back implementation
template<typename... Args>
T& emplace_back(Args&&... args)
{
    // 1. Check capacity, grow if needed (heap allocation, separate step)
    // 2. Construct element in the pre-allocated slot — placement new
    new (data + size) T(std::forward<Args>(args)...);
    ++size;
    return data[size - 1];
}
```

The storage-vs-object distinction: `buffer` is **storage** (raw bytes, no object). Placement new creates an **object** in that storage. `std::destroy_at` destroys the object but keeps the storage. You can reuse the storage for another object.

**When you need this:** Custom allocators, object pools, intrusive containers, serialization (reading objects from a network buffer), and any situation where you want to separate allocation from construction.

---

## "Heap Is Always Slower" Is Wrong

Stack allocation is always faster — one instruction. But for ACCESSING data after allocation, the difference blurs. A heap object that fits in L1 cache is just as fast to read as a stack object. The real enemy is **cache misses** — jumping to cold heap memory. Stack data is always hot because you just wrote it. Heap data might be cold.

For small, frequently-allocated objects, pool allocators bridge the gap: pre-allocate a big heap block, then hand out slots stack-style. This is what UE's `TSizedDefaultAllocator<32> does for `FString` — avoids general heap overhead for the most common allocation size.

---

## When to Use Which

```cpp
// ✅ STACK: known size, short lifetime, small
void ProcessData()
{
    int indices[100];           // Fixed small array
    float matrix[16];           // 4x4 matrix
    std::array<Widget, 10> ws;  // Fixed-size container
}

// ✅ HEAP: unknown/dynamic size, long lifetime, large
std::vector<int> LoadScores(const std::string& path)  // Returns heap data
{
    std::vector<int> scores;    // Internal storage on heap
    // Read from file, push_back as needed
    return scores;              // NRVO — no copy. Ownership transferred.
}

// ✅ HEAP: shared ownership
auto w = std::make_shared<Widget>();
RegisterWidget(w);     // Another reference
KeepAliveForever(w);   // Yet another — shared_ptr handles cleanup
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

The stack is a stack of sticky notes. Every function gets its own note — write variables on it, and when the function ends, the note is ripped up. Fast and automatic. The heap is a warehouse. You ask the warehouse manager for space, get a ticket with the address, and you're responsible for returning the ticket when you're done. Lose the ticket, and the space is occupied forever. Smart pointers are a service that returns the ticket for you.

### Technical

The stack is a thread-local contiguous LIFO allocation arena addressed via RSP/RBP registers. Allocation/deallocation is a single add/sub to RSP with zero fragmentation. Heap allocation involves a general-purpose allocator (typically ptmalloc, jemalloc, or mimalloc on modern systems) that maintains free lists and must handle fragmentation, thread safety, and variable-size requests. Placement new (`operator new(std::size_t, void*)`) constructs an object at a given memory address without allocation, enabling the separation of storage management from object lifetime — the foundation of custom allocators, container internals, and high-performance memory strategies.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a function that causes a stack overflow. What happens? Why does infinite recursion crash but a `while(true)` loop doesn't?
2. Why does `std::vector<int> v(10'000'000);` work but `int arr[10'000'000];` might crash? Where does each allocate?
3. Write a program that implements placement new — construct an object in a pre-allocated `char` buffer. Call the destructor manually.
4. What is the size (in bytes) of this struct? `struct X { char a; int b; char c; };` Now reorder to minimize size.
5. Explain why a pointer member in a class still leaks when the class goes out of scope. What's the difference between destroying the pointer and destroying what it points to?



## std::allocator — The Bridge Between Containers and Memory

Every STL container has a hidden template parameter: `std::allocator<T>`. It's the default for `std::vector<T>`, `std::map<K,V>`, etc. — but you can swap it for your own.

```cpp
template<typename T>
struct std::allocator {
    using value_type = T;

    T* allocate(std::size_t n);            // Get raw memory for n objects (calls ::operator new)
    void deallocate(T* p, std::size_t n);  // Return raw memory (calls ::operator delete)

    // Pre-C++17: construct/destroy objects in raw memory
    void construct(T* p, const T& val);    // Placement new
    void destroy(T* p);                    // Explicit destructor call

    // Post-C++17: construct/destroy removed — containers handle this themselves
};
```

The allocator is the hook between containers and the heap. `std::vector<int>` → `std::allocator<int>` → `::operator new` → `malloc`. If you want a vector that allocates from a pre-allocated arena, a memory-mapped file, or shared memory, you write a custom allocator and pass it as the second template argument:

```cpp
template<typename T>
struct ArenaAllocator {
    Arena* arena;
    T* allocate(std::size_t n) { return static_cast<T*>(arena->alloc(n * sizeof(T))); }
    void deallocate(T*, std::size_t) { /* Arena frees all at once */ }
};

std::vector<int, ArenaAllocator<int>> v(ArenaAllocator<int>{&frameArena});
```

This is what `std::pmr` does — it provides pre-built allocators (`monotonic_buffer_resource`, `unsynchronized_pool_resource`) that plug into `std::pmr::vector` via a type-erased `polymorphic_allocator`. The basic allocator model is the machinery underneath.
## See Also

- [[03 — Memory/03 — Smart Pointers & Ownership|Smart Pointers]] — `unique_ptr` and `shared_ptr` manage heap objects via RAII
- [[04 — RAII & The Rule of Five]] — Why destructors matter for heap cleanup
- [[03 — Memory/06 — std vector & Container Internals|std::vector]] — How `emplace_back` uses placement new
- [[03 — Memory/02 — Object Memory Layout|Object Memory Layout]] — Cache lines, SoA vs AoS, alignment

[^1]: Standard C++ does not support runtime-sized stack arrays (VLAs were rejected). GCC supports them as an extension and `alloca()` is available on most platforms, but both are discouraged in production code.

03 \u2014 Smart Pointers & Ownership.content:
# Smart Pointers & Ownership

## Why Raw Pointers Are Dangerous

>[!warning]
>In C, managing memory was simple and terrifying: you called `malloc`, and if you forgot `free`, the memory leaked forever. C++ gave us `new` and `delete`, which was slightly better — but still required you to remember to `delete` every `new`. Miss one, and you have a leak. Delete twice, and you have a crash.
>
>**Why raw pointers don't auto-clean:** When a pointer goes out of scope — whether it's a local variable or a class member — the pointer VARIABLE (the 8 bytes holding the address) is destroyed. But the memory it points to on the heap is NOT. The compiler has no idea whether that heap memory is still needed elsewhere. It only cleans up the address, not the house at that address.

```cpp
struct Owner {
    Widget* w;  // 8 bytes — cleaned when Owner dies. What about *w?

    Owner()  { w = new Widget(); }  // Widget allocated on heap
    // ~Owner() — pointer 'w' (8 bytes) freed ✅
    //           *w on the heap — STILL THERE ❌ LEAK
};

void Func() {
    Widget* w = new Widget();  // Widget allocated on heap
    // Func ends → pointer 'w' on stack freed ✅
    //             *w on heap — STILL THERE ❌ LEAK
    // SAME problem in both cases. Raw pointers never auto-delete.
};
```

> [!important] The Distinction That Makes This Click
> **A normal variable IS the data.** `int x = 5` — those 4 bytes on the stack hold the value 5. When `x` is destroyed, the 5 is gone with it. Nothing left behind.
>
> **A pointer is just a note saying where the data lives.** `int* p = new int(5)` — `p` is an address (8 bytes). The 5 lives separately on the heap. When `p` is destroyed, only the NOTE disappears. The 5 is still sitting on the heap — orphaned, unreachable, a memory leak.
>
> This is true whether the pointer is a local variable, a class member, or inside a container. Raw pointers never destroy what they point to. Smart pointers fix exactly this.

**Smart pointers solve this by tying object lifetime to scope.** When a smart pointer goes out of scope, it automatically deletes what it owns. The compiler enforces the rules. You can't forget.

> [!summary] The One-Liner
> `unique_ptr` = "I own this. Nobody else does." `shared_ptr` = "We share ownership. Last one out turns off the lights." `weak_ptr` = "I'm watching, but I don't keep it alive."

---

## std::unique_ptr — Exclusive Ownership

### What It Is

`unique_ptr` owns an object. Only one `unique_ptr` can point to a given object at a time. You can't copy it — only move it. When it goes out of scope, the object is deleted.

```cpp
#include <memory>  // std::unique_ptr, shared_ptr, weak_ptr, make_unique, make_shared — all smart pointer types

void Example()
{
    // Create a unique_ptr that owns an int
    std::unique_ptr<int> ptr = std::make_unique<int>(42);

    // Use it like a raw pointer
    *ptr = 100;
    std::cout << *ptr;  // 100

    // ptr goes out of scope here → the int is automatically deleted
}
```

**Why `make_unique` and not `new`?** Two reasons: exception safety (if an exception is thrown between `new` and the pointer assignment, `make_unique` prevents leaks) and clarity (`make_unique` is C++14's idiom, universally preferred).

### You Cannot Copy a unique_ptr

```cpp
std::unique_ptr<int> a = std::make_unique<int>(10);
std::unique_ptr<int> b = a;  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR — unique_ptr is not copyable
```

This is the whole point. If you could copy it, two `unique_ptr`s would both think they own the same object, and both would try to delete it. Double-delete = crash. The compiler prevents this at compile time.

### You CAN Move a unique_ptr

```cpp
std::unique_ptr<int> a = std::make_unique<int>(10);
std::unique_ptr<int> b = std::move(a);  // ✅ Ownership transferred

// a is now nullptr — it no longer owns anything
// b now owns the int
```

Moving transfers ownership. After the move, the source pointer is `nullptr`. This is how you pass ownership into functions or return ownership from factories.

### When To Use unique_ptr

| Scenario | Use unique_ptr? |
|---|---|
| A function creates an object and returns it | ✅ — `return std::make_unique<T>()` |
| A class owns a member that nothing else references | ✅ — `std::unique_ptr<Member> m_member` |
| A container owns its elements exclusively | ✅ — `std::vector<std::unique_ptr<T>>` |
| Multiple objects need to reference the same thing | ❌ — Use `shared_ptr` |
| PIMPL idiom (hide implementation details) | ✅ — Classic use case |

### Custom Deleters

`unique_ptr` can use a custom deleter for non-memory resources (file handles, sockets, etc.):

```cpp
// Close a file when the unique_ptr goes out of scope
auto FileDeleter = [](FILE* f) { if (f) fclose(f); };
std::unique_ptr<FILE, decltype(FileDeleter)> file(fopen("data.txt", "r"), FileDeleter);
```

---

## std::shared_ptr — Shared Ownership

### What It Is

`shared_ptr` uses **reference counting.** Every time you copy a `shared_ptr`, a counter increments. Every time a `shared_ptr` is destroyed, the counter decrements. When the counter reaches zero — nobody is referencing the object anymore — it's deleted.

```cpp
void Example()
{
    std::shared_ptr<int> a = std::make_shared<int>(42);

    {
        std::shared_ptr<int> b = a;  // Reference count: 2
        std::shared_ptr<int> c = a;  // Reference count: 3
    }
    // b and c destroyed → reference count: 1

    // a still owns the int — count is 1
}
// a destroyed → reference count: 0 → int deleted
```

### Reference Counting Has a Cost

| Aspect | unique_ptr | shared_ptr |
|---|---|---|
| **Size** | sizeof(raw pointer) — 8 bytes | 2× raw pointer — 16 bytes (pointer + control block pointer) |
| **Copy** | Not allowed | Atomic increment + pointer copy (~10-20 cycles) |
| **Destroy** | Direct delete | Atomic decrement + conditional delete |
| **Memory** | One allocation | Two allocations (object + control block) unless `make_shared` |

**Always use `make_shared`** — it allocates the object and control block together in one allocation, saving memory and improving cache locality.

### When To Use shared_ptr

| Scenario | Use shared_ptr? |
|---|---|
| Multiple objects share read-only data | ✅ |
| Asynchronous callbacks that might outlive the caller | ✅ — `shared_from_this()` |
| A cache where entries can be evicted | ✅ — combine with `weak_ptr` |
| A tree or graph with shared nodes | ✅ — but watch for cycles |
| Simple ownership with one owner | ❌ — `unique_ptr` is cheaper |

### The Reference Cycle Problem

```cpp
struct Node
{
    std::shared_ptr<Node> next;
    std::shared_ptr<Node> prev;
};

auto a = std::make_shared<Node>();
auto b = std::make_shared<Node>();
a->next = b;
b->prev = a;
// a and b go out of scope — but they reference EACH OTHER
// Reference count never reaches zero → MEMORY LEAK
```

**Fix:** Use `weak_ptr` for one direction of the cycle:

```cpp
struct Node
{
    std::shared_ptr<Node> next;   // Owns next
    std::weak_ptr<Node> prev;     // Observes prev — doesn't keep it alive
};
```

---

## std::weak_ptr — Non-Owning Observer

### What It Is

`weak_ptr` watches a `shared_ptr` without participating in ownership. It doesn't increment the reference count. If all `shared_ptr`s are destroyed, the `weak_ptr` becomes "expired" — it knows the object is gone.

```cpp
std::weak_ptr<int> weak;

{
    auto shared = std::make_shared<int>(42);
    weak = shared;  // weak observes shared — count still 1

    if (auto locked = weak.lock())  // Try to get a shared_ptr
    {
        std::cout << *locked;  // 42 — object is still alive
    }
}
// shared destroyed → count 0 → int deleted

if (auto locked = weak.lock())  // Returns nullptr
{
    // This block never executes — object is gone
}
```

### The Only Two Things You Do With weak_ptr

1. **`lock()`** — Try to create a `shared_ptr`. Returns `nullptr` if the object is gone.
2. **`expired()`** — Check if the object is still alive (less useful — there's a race between checking and using; prefer `lock()`).

---

## enable_shared_from_this — When 'this' Needs to be Shared

Sometimes an object needs to hand out `shared_ptr`s to itself. You can't just do `std::shared_ptr<T>(this)` — that creates a NEW control block, leading to double-delete.

```cpp
class Listener : public std::enable_shared_from_this<Listener>
{
public:
    void Register()
    {
        // ✅ Correct — uses the existing control block
        RegisterCallback(shared_from_this());
    }

    // ❌ Wrong — creates a second control block
    // void Register() { RegisterCallback(std::shared_ptr<Listener>(this)); }
};
```

**The rule:** If a class might need to share itself, inherit from `enable_shared_from_this`. Always use `make_shared` to create instances (it sets up the internal weak_ptr that `shared_from_this` needs).

---

## The Decision Flowchart

```
I have an object. Who owns it?
│
├─ Exactly ONE owner, nobody else references it
│  └─ std::unique_ptr
│
├─ Multiple owners with shared lifetime
│  │
│  ├─ Lifetime is simple (no cycles)
│  │  └─ std::shared_ptr (with make_shared)
│  │
│  └─ Lifetime has cycles (A→B and B→A)
│     └─ std::shared_ptr for owning directions
│        std::weak_ptr for back-references
│
├─ I want to observe, not own
│  └─ std::weak_ptr (from a shared_ptr)
│
└─ I just need to pass/use, not own
   └─ Raw pointer or reference (T* or T&)
```

---

## Raw Pointers — They Still Have a Place

With all these smart pointers, are raw pointers dead? No. They have a specific role: **non-owning observation.**

```cpp
void ProcessData(const std::vector<int>& Data);  // ✅ Reference — non-owning

void LogObject(MyClass* Obj);  // ✅ Raw pointer — non-owning
// Caller: LogObject(myUniquePtr.get());  // Explicitly: "I'm lending this, not giving it"
```

**The modern rule:** A raw pointer in C++ code means "I don't own this. Someone else manages its lifetime. I'm just borrowing it." If you see `new` or `delete`, that's a code smell — use `make_unique` or `make_shared` instead.

---

## C++23 Additions

| Feature | What It Does |
|---|---|
| `std::out_ptr` / `std::inout_ptr` | Safely pass smart pointers to C APIs that write through `T**` |
| `std::expected` integration | More patterns for returning smart pointers from fallible operations |

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

A raw pointer is like a sticky note with an address. You can lose the note, photocopy it, or throw it away — and the house at that address doesn't know. `unique_ptr` is a deed — there's exactly one, and when you tear it up, the house is demolished. `shared_ptr` is a guest list — as long as at least one person has their name on the list, the party continues. When the last person leaves, the venue closes. `weak_ptr` is a window — you can look through it to see if the party is still going, but you can't keep it alive just by watching.

### Technical

Smart pointers implement RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization) for heap-allocated objects. `unique_ptr<T> stores a raw `T*` and deletes it in its destructor; it's non-copyable (deleted copy constructor/assignment) but movable (transferring the raw pointer and nulling the source). `shared_ptr`<T>` stores a raw pointer plus a pointer to a control block containing a strong reference count (atomic), a weak count, and an optional deleter. `make_shared``<T>`` allocates the object and control block contiguously for cache efficiency. `weak_ptr`<T>` increments the weak count (not the strong count) and provides `lock()` which atomically checks the strong count and creates a `shared_ptr` or returns `nullptr`. C++17 guaranteed copy elision eliminates unnecessary moves when returning smart pointers from functions.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a minimal `unique_ptr`-like class that wraps a raw pointer and calls `delete` in its destructor.
2. Convert a class that currently uses raw `new`/`delete` to use `std::make_unique`. What fails to compile?
3. Create a circular reference between two `shared_ptr` objects. Does the memory leak? Fix it with `weak_ptr`.
4. When should you use `shared_ptr` vs `unique_ptr`? Give a concrete game development example for each.
5. Why does `std::make_shared` allocate the control block and object together? What's the performance advantage over `std::shared_ptr<T>(new T(...))`?

