04 \u2014 RAII & The Rule of Five.content:
# RAII, Lifetimes & The Rule of Five

## What Is RAII?

RAII — Resource Acquisition Is Initialization — is C++'s single most important idiom. It means: **tie the lifetime of a resource to the lifetime of an object.** When the object is created, it acquires the resource. When the object is destroyed, it releases the resource. Automatically. Deterministically. No `finally` blocks, no `defer` statements, no garbage collector.

```cpp
{
    std::ifstream file("data.txt");  // Resource acquired: file opened

    std::string line;
    std::getline(file, line);

}  // file destroyed here → file automatically closed
// Even if an exception was thrown between open and close!
```

**What resources can RAII manage?** Memory (`new`/`delete`), files (`open`/`close`), locks (`lock`/`unlock`), sockets, database connections, GPU buffers — anything with an acquire/release pair.

---

## How RAII Works — The Three Guarantees

C++ guarantees that destructors run in three cases:

1. **Normal scope exit:** The object goes out of scope — destructor runs
2. **Exception unwinding:** An exception is thrown — all local objects' destructors run in reverse order (stack unwinding)
3. **Early return / break / continue:** Any control flow leaving the scope runs destructors

```cpp
void ProcessFile(const std::string& path)
{
    std::ifstream file(path);     // 1. Open file
    if (!file.is_open())
        return;                    // file destructor runs — file closed

    std::string data = ReadData(file);
    if (data.empty())
        throw std::runtime_error("empty file");  // file destructor STILL runs

    ProcessData(data);

}  // file destructor runs — file closed
```

**No matter how you leave the function, the file is closed.** This is impossible to guarantee with manual `close()` calls unless you wrap every return/throw in error handling. RAII makes it automatic.

---

## The Rule of Five

If a class manages a resource directly (raw pointers, handles, file descriptors), it needs five special member functions:

```cpp
class Buffer
{
    char* data;
    size_t size;

public:
    // 1. Destructor — release the resource
    ~Buffer()
    {
        delete[] data;
    }

    // 2. Copy constructor — duplicate the resource
    Buffer(const Buffer& other)
        : data(new char[other.size])
        , size(other.size)
    {
        std::memcpy(data, other.data, size);
    }

    // 3. Copy assignment — duplicate, freeing old resource
    Buffer& operator=(const Buffer& other)
    {
        if (this != &other)
        {
            delete[] data;
            data = new char[other.size];
            size = other.size;
            std::memcpy(data, other.data, size);
        }
        return *this;
    }

    // 4. Move constructor — steal the resource
    Buffer(Buffer&& other) noexcept
        : data(other.data)
        , size(other.size)
    {
        other.data = nullptr;
        other.size = 0;
    }

    // 5. Move assignment — steal, freeing old resource
    Buffer& operator=(Buffer&& other) noexcept
    {
        if (this != &other)
        {
            delete[] data;
            data = other.data;
            size = other.size;
            other.data = nullptr;
            other.size = 0;
        }
        return *this;
    }
};
```

**Why all five?** If you write a destructor, the compiler knows you're managing a resource. It still auto-generates copy operations — but those default copies just copy the raw pointer, not the data. Both objects now point to the same memory. When both are destroyed, `delete[]` is called twice on the same pointer → crash. Writing the copy operations fixes this. Writing the move operations makes the class efficient.

> [!important] The Suppression Chain — Why Move Operations Disappear
> The compiler auto-generates all six special members **until you write one.** The moment you define ANY of the first three (destructor, copy constructor, copy assignment), the compiler **stops generating the move operations entirely.** This is the most surprising C++ rule for new developers:
>
> | You write... | Move constructor | Move assignment |
> |---|---|---|
> | Destructor | ❌ Suppressed | ❌ Suppressed |
> | Copy constructor | ❌ Suppressed | ❌ Suppressed |
> | Copy assignment | ❌ Suppressed | ❌ Suppressed |
>
> **Declaring a move constructor or move assignment has the opposite effect:** it causes the copy operations to be defined as **deleted** (since C++11). Any attempt to copy fails at compile time. This prevents accidentally copying a type that was designed to be moved.
>
> **The consequence:** If you write `~Buffer() { delete[] data; }` and nothing else, your class silently becomes **non-movable.** Code that tries to `std::move` a `Buffer` will still compile — it quietly falls back to the copy constructor! The fix: add `Buffer(Buffer&&) = default;` and `Buffer& operator=(Buffer&&) = default;` to bring the move operations back.
>
> ```cpp
> // ❌ After adding a destructor, moves are silently GONE
> struct Holder {
>     std::vector`<int>` data;
>     ~Holder() { /* custom cleanup */ }
>     // vector's move constructor still works internally, but Holder
>     // as a whole cannot be moved — it falls back to copying
> };
>
> // ✅ Bring moves back explicitly
> struct Holder {
>     std::vector`<int>` data;
>     ~Holder() { /* custom cleanup */ }
>     Holder(Holder&&) = default;            // Restore move
>     Holder& operator=(Holder&&) = default; // Restore move-assign
> };
> ``
>
> This is why `= default` exists on move operations — not because you forgot to write them, but because the compiler deleted them when you wrote the destructor.

---

## The Rule of Zero (Preferred)

If all your members are RAII types (`std::vector`, `std::string`, `std::unique_ptr`), the compiler-generated defaults are correct. **Write nothing:**

```cpp
class Good
{
    std::vector<int> data;      // RAII — owns its memory
    std::string name;           // RAII — owns its memory
    std::unique_ptr<Widget> w;  // RAII — owns the Widget

    // Compiler-generated:
    // ~Good() — calls each member's destructor in reverse order ✅
    // Good(const Good&) — copies each member ✅
    // Good& operator=(const Good&) — assigns each member ✅
    // Good(Good&&) — moves each member ✅
    // Good& operator=(Good&&) — move-assigns each member ✅
};
```

> [!tip] The Rule of Zero is the Goal
> If you're writing destructors, copy constructors, or assignment operators, ask: "Can I replace this raw resource with an RAII wrapper?" `std::unique_ptr<T>` replaces `T*` + manual `delete`. `std::vector<T>` replaces new `T[]` + `delete[]`. Every time you replace a raw resource with an RAII type, you remove one class from the Rule of Five.

---

## = default and = delete

You can explicitly request or reject compiler-generated functions:

```cpp
class NonCopyable
{
public:
    NonCopyable() = default;                      // Use compiler's default constructor
    NonCopyable(const NonCopyable&) = delete;     // No copying allowed
    NonCopyable& operator=(const NonCopyable&) = delete;

    NonCopyable(NonCopyable&&) = default;         // Moving is fine
    NonCopyable& operator=(NonCopyable&&) = default;
};

class AlwaysOnStack
{
public:
    void* operator new(size_t) = delete;  // Cannot be heap-allocated
};
```

`= delete` is how `std::unique_ptr` prevents copying — its copy constructor and copy assignment are deleted.

---

## Exception Safety Guarantees

C++ functions provide one of three exception safety levels:

| Level | Guarantee |
|---|---|
| **No-throw** (`noexcept`) | Will never throw. Destructors, move constructors, and `swap` should be here. |
| **Strong guarantee** | If it throws, the state is unchanged (as if the function was never called). Copy-and-swap idiom achieves this. |
| **Basic guarantee** | If it throws, no resources leak, and the object is in a valid (but possibly changed) state. |

**The copy-and-swap idiom** provides the strong guarantee:

```cpp
class Widget
{
    std::vector<int> data;
    std::string name;

public:
    Widget& operator=(const Widget& other)
    {
        Widget temp(other);   // Copy — might throw
        swap(temp);           // Swap — never throws
        return *this;
    }  // temp destroyed with old data

    void swap(Widget& other) noexcept
    {
        std::swap(data, other.data);
        std::swap(name, other.name);
    }
};
```

If the copy throws, `*this` is unchanged. The `swap` never throws. The strong guarantee is preserved.

---

## Object Lifetimes — Construction and Destruction Order

```cpp
class Outer
{
    MemberA a;    // 1. Constructed first
    MemberB b;    // 2. Constructed second
    MemberC c;    // 3. Constructed third

public:
    Outer()
        : a(...)   // Base classes and members are initialized HERE
        , b(...)   // in declaration order, NOT the order in the initializer list
        , c(...)
    {
        // Constructor body runs AFTER all members are constructed
    }

    ~Outer()
    {
        // Destructor body runs BEFORE members are destroyed
    }
    // 4. c destroyed  (reverse order)
    // 5. b destroyed
    // 6. a destroyed
};
```

**The rule:** Members are destroyed in reverse declaration order. Always. If `a` depends on `b`, declare `b` before `a`.

---

## RAII in Practice — Common Patterns

### Scoped Lock

```cpp
std::mutex m;

void ThreadSafeFunction()
{
    std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(m);  // RAII — acquires lock
    // ... critical section ...
}  // lock destroyed → mutex unlocked — even if exception thrown
```

### Scoped File

```cpp
void WriteToFile(const std::string& path, const std::string& data)
{
    std::ofstream file(path);  // RAII — opens file
    file << data;
}  // file destroyed → closed
```

### Scoped Timer (Custom RAII)

```cpp
class ScopedTimer
{
    std::chrono::steady_clock::time_point start;
    std::string name;
public:
    ScopedTimer(const std::string& n) : name(n), start(std::chrono::steady_clock::now()) {}

    ~ScopedTimer()
    {
        auto elapsed = std::chrono::steady_clock::now() - start;
        std::cout << name << ": " 
                  << std::chrono::duration_cast<std::chrono::microseconds>(elapsed).count() 
                  << "us\n";
    }
};

void ExpensiveFunction()
{
    ScopedTimer t("ExpensiveFunction");  // Timer starts
    // ... work ...
}  // Timer destroyed → prints elapsed time
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

RAII is the "you break it, you fix it" rule of C++. When you open a door (acquire a resource), you hang a key on the door frame that automatically closes it when you leave — even if you run out, get pushed out, or the building catches fire. The key is the destructor. It always runs.

### Technical

RAII leverages C++'s deterministic destruction semantics: stack-allocated objects have their destructors called in reverse declaration order at scope exit, including during stack unwinding from exceptions. The Rule of Five specifies that a class managing a resource should define (or delete) the destructor, copy constructor, copy assignment, move constructor, and move assignment. The Rule of Zero observes that composing RAII types (`std::vector`, `std::unique_ptr`, `std::string`) eliminates the need to write any of the five — the compiler-generated defaults correctly forward to member operations. `noexcept` on move operations and destructors enables optimizations (vector reallocation uses moves) and satisfies the no-throw guarantee. The copy-and-swap idiom provides the strong exception safety guarantee by performing all allocations before modifying `*this`.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a `ScopedTimer` class that prints elapsed time when it goes out of scope. Why does RAII make this trivial?
2. What happens if you forget to write a virtual destructor on a base class with virtual functions? Write a minimal example that demonstrates the leak.
3. Given a class that manages a file handle (`FILE*`), write the Rule of Five: destructor, copy constructor, copy assignment, move constructor, move assignment.
4. Why does adding a destructor silence move operations? What's the fix?
5. Convert a raw resource class to Rule of Zero by replacing raw pointers with `std::unique_ptr` or `std::vector`.

## See Also

