# std::map & std::unordered_map

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[01 — Stack vs Heap]], [[06 — std vector & Container Internals]]

---

## Why

Vectors give you O(1) access by index. But what if you need to look up by a string key — `scores["PlayerName"]` instead of `scores[3]`? Maps associate keys with values. `std::map` uses a balanced tree (O(log n)). `std::unordered_map` uses a hash table (O(1) average, O(n) worst). Choosing the wrong one can make your code 100x slower.

---

## std::map — The Balanced Tree

```cpp
#include <map>

std::map<std::string, int> scores;
scores["Alice"] = 95;
scores["Bob"] = 87;

int alice = scores["Alice"];    // 95
if (scores.count("Charlie")) {}  // 0 (Charlie not in map)
```

**Implementation:** Red-black tree. Keys are sorted. Iteration produces keys in order.

```
        "Bob" (87)
        /         \
  "Alice" (95)   "Charlie" (72)
```

| Operation | Complexity |
|---|---|
| Insert, erase, find | O(log n) — ~log2(n) comparisons |
| Iteration | O(n) — sorted order |
| Memory | ~3 pointers per node + key + value overhead |

---

## std::unordered_map — The Hash Table

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>

std::unordered_map<std::string, int> scores;
scores["Alice"] = 95;
scores["Bob"] = 87;
```

**Implementation:** Open addressing (typical). A hash function maps keys to bucket indices. Collisions resolved by chaining or probing.

| Operation | Average | Worst Case |
|---|---|---|
| Insert, erase, find | O(1) | O(n) — all keys collide |
| Iteration | O(n) | Unordered |

The hash function must be fast and distribute well. `std::hash<std::string>` uses MurmurHash or similar.

---

## Choosing Between Them

| Criterion | Use map | Use unordered_map |
|---|---|---|
| Need sorted iteration? | ✅ | ❌ |
| Need O(1) average? | ❌ | ✅ |
| Memory tight? | ❌ (node overhead) | ⚠️ (bucket overhead) |
| Keys are small ints? | Either | Either |
| Need stable iterators? | ✅ (never invalidated) | ❌ (invalidate on rehash) |

**Benchmark reality:** For 1M `std::string` keys, unordered_map is ~3-5x faster for insertion and ~2-3x faster for lookup vs map. But map gives sorted iteration for free.

---

## Custom Hashing

```cpp
struct Player {
    std::string name;
    int level;
};

struct PlayerHash {
    size_t operator()(const Player& p) const {
        return std::hash<std::string>{}(p.name) ^ (p.level << 1);
    }
};

struct PlayerEqual {
    bool operator()(const Player& a, const Player& b) const {
        return a.name == b.name && a.level == b.level;
    }
};

std::unordered_map<Player, int, PlayerHash, PlayerEqual> scores;
```

Hash and equality are separate — a hash collision isn't sufficient for equality (two different keys can hash to the same bucket).

---

## UE Equivalents — TMap

```cpp
// UE's TMap — always a hash table, always sorted
TMap<FString, int32> Scores;
Scores.Add(TEXT("Alice"), 95);

// TMultiMap — allows duplicate keys
TMultiMap<FName, AActor*> TaggedActors;
```

UE's `TMap` is always a hash table internally (no tree version). `TSet` is the unordered key-only equivalent. For sorted maps, UE uses `TMap` with `KeySort`.

---

## Exercises

1. **map vs unordered_map benchmark:** Insert 1M random strings into both. Measure time. Lookup all 1M. Measure. Which wins each test? Why?

2. **Custom key hash:** Write `PlayerHash` for a struct with 3 fields. Test with 100K insertions. What makes a bad hash function? (Hint: all hashing to bucket 0.)

3. **lower_bound:** `std::map` provides `lower_bound()`. Find all players with names >= "M". How many comparisons? What's the unordered_map equivalent? (Hint: none — it's unordered.)

4. **Rehash observation:** Insert 1M elements into unordered_map, tracking bucket_count() vs load_factor(). When does rehash occur? What's the default max_load_factor?

5. **UE TMap vs std::map:** UE's TMap is hashed, not tree-based. Why doesn't UE provide a sorted tree map? What would you use if you needed sorted keys in UE?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

A map is a phone book — names (keys) on the left, numbers (values) on the right. std::map keeps entries alphabetically sorted (tree). std::unordered_map throws entries into buckets by name length (hash) — finding "Alice" is instant if you know which bucket she's in, but the phone book has no alphabetical order. UE's TMap is always a hashed bucket system.

### Technical

`std::map<K,V> uses a red-black tree: O(log n) node-based operations, iterator stability, sorted order. `std::unordered_map`<K,V>` uses open addressing: hash→bucket, O(1) average, invalidates iterators on rehash when load_factor > max_load_factor (default 1.0, bucket_count doubles). Hash function quality determines collision rate and thus real-world O(1) performance. `TMap` in UE: hash-based with `KeyFuncs` for hashing and comparison, dynamically resizes like std::unordered_map, supports `FindOrAdd`, `FindRef`, and `RemoveAndCopyValue`.

## See Also

- [[06 — std vector & Container Internals]] — Sequential container
- [[05 — std array & C Arrays]] — Fixed-size container

08 \u2014 Iterators & Algorithms.content:
# Iterators & Algorithms

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[06 — std vector & Container Internals]], [[07 — std map & unordered_map]]

---

## Why

C++ has 100+ standard algorithms — `sort`, `find`, `transform`, `accumulate`, `copy`. They all work with ANY container through a common abstraction: the iterator. Write one `std::sort(begin, end)` and it works for vectors, arrays, deques, and even raw C arrays. The separation of containers (storage) from algorithms (operations) is C++'s most brilliant design.

---

## Iterator Categories

| Category | Capabilities | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Input** | Read once, forward only | `std::istream_iterator` |
| **Forward** | Read/write, forward only, multi-pass | `std::forward_list::iterator` |
| **Bidirectional** | Forward + backward | `std::list::iterator`, `std::map::iterator` |
| **Random Access** | Any offset in O(1) | `std::vector::iterator`, raw pointer |
| **Contiguous** (C++20) | Random Access + elements are adjacent | `std::vector::iterator` |

Each algorithm requires the minimum iterator category it needs. `std::sort` needs RandomAccess. `std::find` only needs Input.

---

## Common Iterator Operations

```cpp
std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};

auto it = v.begin();      // points to first element
*it = 10;                 // modify via iterator
++it;                     // advance to next
auto it2 = v.end();       // one-past-last (never dereference!)

// Iterator-based loop:
for (auto it = v.begin(); it != v.end(); ++it)
    std::cout << *it;     // 10 2 3 4 5

// Equivalent range-for (compiler generates iterator code):
for (int x : v) std::cout << x;

// Reverse iteration:
for (auto it = v.rbegin(); it != v.rend(); ++it)
    std::cout << *it;     // 5 4 3 2 10
```

---

## Algorithms — The STL Library

```cpp
#include <algorithm>
#include <numeric>

std::vector<int> data = {3, 1, 4, 1, 5, 9, 2, 6};

// Sorting
std::sort(data.begin(), data.end());                    // ascending
std::sort(data.begin(), data.end(), std::greater<int>{}); // descending

// Finding
auto it = std::find(data.begin(), data.end(), 5);       // O(n)
bool exists = std::binary_search(data.begin(), data.end(), 5); // O(log n) — sorted!

// Transforming
std::vector<int> doubled(data.size());
std::transform(data.begin(), data.end(), doubled.begin(),
               [](int x) { return x * 2; });

// Filtering (copy_if)
std::vector<int> evens;
std::copy_if(data.begin(), data.end(), std::back_inserter(evens),
             [](int x) { return x % 2 == 0; });

// Accumulating
int sum = std::accumulate(data.begin(), data.end(), 0);
int product = std::accumulate(data.begin(), data.end(), 1, std::multiplies<int>{});

// Removing
auto new_end = std::remove_if(data.begin(), data.end(),
                               [](int x) { return x % 2 == 0; });
data.erase(new_end, data.end());  // erase-remove idiom — actually deletes
```

---

## Functors and Lambdas as Algorithm Callbacks

```cpp
// Old style — functor struct:
struct IsEven {
    bool operator()(int x) const { return x % 2 == 0; }
};
auto it = std::find_if(data.begin(), data.end(), IsEven{});

// Modern — lambda:
auto it = std::find_if(data.begin(), data.end(),
                        [](int x) { return x % 2 == 0; });

// Lambda with capture:
int target = 5;
auto it = std::find_if(data.begin(), data.end(),
                        [target](int x) { return x > target; });
```

---

## Iterator Adapters

```cpp
// back_inserter — push_back for algorithms that write
std::vector<int> out;
std::copy(data.begin(), data.end(), std::back_inserter(out));

// ostream_iterator — write to stream
std::copy(data.begin(), data.end(),
          std::ostream_iterator<int>(std::cout, ", "));

// istream_iterator — read from stream
std::vector<int> from_cin;
std::copy(std::istream_iterator<int>(std::cin),
          std::istream_iterator<int>(),           // end sentinel
          std::back_inserter(from_cin));
```

---

## Ranges (C++20)

Ranges unify iterators into a single concept:

```cpp
#include <ranges>

auto evens = data | std::views::filter([](int x) { return x % 2 == 0; })
                  | std::views::transform([](int x) { return x * 2; });

for (int x : evens) std::cout << x;
// No intermediate vector allocation — lazy evaluation
```

Ranges are composable, lazy, and eliminate the verbosity of begin/end pairs.

---

## Iterators in UE

```cpp
// UE's TArray has iterators via Ranges:
for (AActor* Actor : TActorRange<AActor>(GetWorld()))

// Or CreateIterator:
for (auto It = Array.CreateIterator(); It; ++It)

// UE also provides TConstIterator and TSet/TMap iterators
```

---

## Exercises

1. **Sort and binary_search:** Sort a random vector. Time `std::find` (O(n)) vs `std::binary_search` (O(log n)). At what N does binary search overtake linear search?

2. **Transform pipeline:** Chain `filter` → `transform` → `accumulate` on a vector of 1M ints. Compare C++20 ranges vs raw loops. Which is clearer? Which compiles faster?

3. **Custom iterator:** Write a `range(start, end)` class with `begin()`/`end()` returning iterators. Make it work with range-for. Support `step` parameter.

4. **Erase-remove idiom:** Vector of ints. Remove all evens. Explain why `std::remove` alone doesn't change size(). Show the erase-remove idiom.

5. **UE iterator:** Write a UE-style `TActorIterator<APlayerController>` that iterates all PlayerControllers. What does the iterator's constructor do under the hood? (Hint: UWorld::GetActorIterator.)

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

An iterator is a book mark in a container. `begin()` puts the bookmark before the first page. `++it` advances one page. `*it` reads the current page. `end()` is the bookmark at the very end — past the last page, never to be read. Algorithms like `sort` and `find` work with ANY bookmarked container — they don't care if it's a vector-book or a map-book, as long as the bookmarks work the same way.

### Technical

Iterators generalize pointers. Each category adds capabilities: Input (read-once), Forward (multi-pass), Bidirectional (--it), RandomAccess (it+n), Contiguous (adjacent elements). Algorithms use tag dispatch: `std::advance(it, n)` uses O(1) for RandomAccess, O(n) for Forward. Range-for desugars: `for(auto& x : c)` → `auto __begin = begin(c); auto __end = end(c); for(; __begin != __end; ++__begin)`. C++20 ranges are lazy views — no allocation, evaluated on iteration. UE's `TArray::CreateIterator()` returns a thin wrapper with `operator++`/`operator*`.

## See Also

