# std::span (C++20)

> [!note] Why This Matters
> For 40 years, C and C++ passed arrays as `(T* ptr, size_t size)` pairs. The pointer and the size travel separately, get out of sync, and the compiler can't help you. Passing the wrong size, forgetting to update it after a resize, off-by-one errors — these are the root cause of buffer overruns, the #1 security vulnerability class. `std::span` binds a pointer and a size into a single object. The size travels with the data. The compiler can check bounds in debug builds. And it costs **zero bytes of overhead** beyond the pointer+size pair you were already passing. This note covers span's design, static vs dynamic extent, construction from containers, and how it eliminates entire categories of bugs.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[../../Primer/05 — Pointers & References|Pointers & References]] — understand pointers and references.
> [[../../Primer/01 — Variables, Types & Memory|Variables & Memory]] — memory addressing, `sizeof`.
> [[05 — std array & C Arrays|std::array]] — the container types span wraps.

---

## The Problem — (ptr, size) Pairs Are Brittle

```cpp
// THE TRAP: ptr and size travel separately — nothing enforces they're related
void ProcessParticles(Particle* particles, size_t count) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < count; ++i) {
        particles[i].Update();  // What if count is wrong? UB with zero diagnostics.
    }
}

Particle buffer[100];
ProcessParticles(buffer, 150);   // Oops — count exceeds buffer. BUFFER OVERRUN.
ProcessParticles(buffer + 50, 50); // Correct. But how do you know without auditing?

// THE FIX: span binds pointer and size together
void ProcessParticles(std::span<Particle> particles) {
    for (auto& p : particles) {  // Range-for works. No manual count variable.
        p.Update();
    }
}

Particle buffer[100];
ProcessParticles(buffer);          // Deduces extent=100 from array type
ProcessParticles(std::span(buffer).subspan(50, 30)); // 30 elements starting at 50
// ProcessParticles(std::span(buffer, 150)); // WOULD compile but is wrong — span can't catch this
```

---

## What span Actually Is

`std::span<T> is a **non-owning view** over a contiguous sequence of `T` objects. It stores exactly two things: a pointer and a size. Nothing else. No allocation. No ownership. No reference counting.

```cpp
template<typename T>
class span {
    T* data_;       // Pointer to first element
    size_t size_;   // Number of elements
    // That's it. sizeof(span<T>) = 16 on 64-bit.
};
```

`span` is to arrays what `string_view` is to strings — a borrowed reference that you can slice, dice, and pass around without copying the underlying data.

---

## Static vs Dynamic Extent

```cpp
// Dynamic extent: size stored at runtime (the common case)
std::span<int> s1 = /* ... */;         // extent = std::dynamic_extent
// sizeof(s1) = 16 bytes (pointer + size_t)

// Static extent: size known at compile time
std::span<int, 10> s2 = /* ... */;     // extent = 10
// sizeof(s2) = 8 bytes (pointer ONLY — size is compile-time constant!)
```

Static-extent spans don't store the size — it's part of the type. This saves 8 bytes and enables the compiler to optimize loops (known trip count). Use static extent when the size is a compile-time constant.

```cpp
int arr[10];
std::span<int, 10> s = arr;   // Static extent deduced from array type
// s.size() returns 10 — but the 10 is compiled into the code, not loaded from memory
```

---

## Construction — span Works With Everything

```cpp
#include <span>

// From C-style array (size deduced automatically)
int raw[5] = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
std::span s1(raw);          // span<int, 5>

// From std::array
std::array<float, 4> arr = {1.0f, 2.0f, 3.0f, 4.0f};
std::span s2(arr);           // span<float, 4>

// From std::vector
std::vector<int> vec = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
std::span s3(vec);           // span<int> (dynamic extent — vector can resize)

// From pointer + size (dynamic extent only)
int* buf = new int[100];
std::span s4(buf, 100);      // span<int> — YOU are responsible for the size being correct

// From another span
std::span s5 = s3.first(3);  // First 3 elements: {10, 20, 30}
std::span s6 = s3.last(2);   // Last 2 elements: {40, 50}
std::span s7 = s3.subspan(1, 3); // 3 elements starting at index 1: {20, 30, 40}
```

---

## Subspan — Zero-Cost Slicing

```cpp
std::span<int> data = /* 100 elements */;

// Split into chunks without copying
std::span chunk1 = data.first(25);           // Elements 0-24
std::span chunk2 = data.subspan(25, 25);     // Elements 25-49
std::span chunk3 = data.subspan(50, 25);     // Elements 50-74
std::span chunk4 = data.last(25);            // Elements 75-99

// All four spans point INTO the original data. Zero copies. Zero allocations.
// Modifying chunk1[0] modifies data[0].
```

This is a powerful pattern for parallel processing: split a buffer into N equally-sized spans, hand one to each thread. No heap allocation, no mutex, no data copying.

---

## span Eliminates Buffer Overrun Bugs

```cpp
// BEFORE span: nothing prevents reading past the buffer
void ProcessAudio(float* samples, size_t count) {
    for (size_t i = 0; i < count * 2; ++i) {  // BUG: count*2 reads past buffer
        samples[i] *= 0.5f;
    }
}

// AFTER span: bounds-checked in debug builds
void ProcessAudio(std::span<float> samples) {
    // Debug builds (with hardening): operator[] asserts i < size()
    // even Release builds: range-for can't overrun
    for (auto& s : samples) {
        s *= 0.5f;  // CANNOT overrun — loop bound is samples.size()
    }
}
```

C++26 is expected to add **bounds-safety** contracts to span, making out-of-bounds access ill-formed or contract-violated in all build modes. Tools like MSVC's `-fsanitize=address` and Clang's libc++ hardening mode already catch span overruns at test time.

---

## span vs Other Types

| Type | Owns Data? | Contiguous? | Knows Size? | sizeof (64-bit) |
|------|:---:|:---:|:---:|:---:|
| `T*` + `size_t` (pair) | ❌ | ✅ | ⚠️ Manually | 16 |
| `std::span<T>` | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | 16 |
| `std::span<T, N>` | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ (static) | **8** |
| `std::string_view` | ❌ | ✅ (chars) | ✅ | 16 |
| `std::vector<T>` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ | 24-32 |
| `std::array<T, N>` | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ (static) | N×sizeof(T) |
| `gsl::span<T>` (Guidelines) | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ | 16 (pre-standard) |

`span` is the universal function parameter for "I need to look at a sequence of T, and I don't care who owns it." Callers pass vector, array, C array, or another span — all work.

---

## The Subtle Trap — span Doesn't Own

```cpp
std::span<int> GetDanglingSpan() {
    std::vector<int> v = {1, 2, 3};
    return std::span(v);  // ❌ v is destroyed — span dangles!
}

// Fix: return the vector, not a span
std::vector<int> GetVector() {
    return {1, 2, 3};  // ✅ Ownership transfers to caller
}

// Or: pass span as parameter (caller owns the data)
void Process(std::span<const int> data) {
    for (int x : data) { /* ... */ }
}
```

`span` is a reference type. It must not outlive the data it points to. This is identical to `string_view`'s lifetime rules.

---

## span with Fixed-Size Small Buffers

```cpp
// Static-extent span enables stack-allocated buffer safety
template<size_t N>
void ReadFixedSize(std::span<char, N> buffer) {
    // buffer.size() is known at compile time — compiler can unroll loops
    read(fd, buffer.data(), N);
}

char buf[256];
ReadFixedSize(std::span<char, 256>(buf));  // Static extent = 256
// ReadFixedSize(std::span<char>(buf));    // Would NOT compile — extent must be 256
```

Static-extent spans prevent size mismatches at compile time. The caller can't accidentally pass a 128-byte buffer to a function expecting 256 bytes.

---

## UE Connection

Unreal Engine doesn't have `std::span` natively (UE5 uses C++17, span is C++20). However, UE has `TArrayView<T>` which is conceptually identical:

```cpp
// UE equivalent
void ProcessActors(TArrayView<AActor*> Actors) {
    for (AActor* Actor : Actors) {
        Actor->Tick(DeltaTime);
    }
}

// Called with TArray, C array, or initializer list
ProcessActors(MyActors);                     // TArray
ProcessActors(MakeArrayView(Ptr, Count));    // Pointer + count
```

`TArrayView` provides the same non-owning-view semantics as `std::span`. When UE eventually adopts C++20, `std::span` will be the standard replacement.

---

## Exercises

1. **Pointer+size vs span — bug count:** Rewrite a 20-line function that takes `(float* data, size_t count)` using `std::span<float>. Count how many lines change. Where was `count` previously used that span's `.size()` now provides? What bugs can you now eliminate by using range-for instead of index-based loops?

2. **Static vs dynamic extent sizeof:** Print `sizeof` for: `std::span<int>, `std::span<int, 10>, `std::span`<int, 100>. Also print for `int*` + `size_t` pair (as a struct). Verify that static-extent span is only 8 bytes. Disassemble a function using `span<int,10>` — confirm the size is an immediate constant, not a memory load.

3. **Subspan zero-copy proof:** Create a `std::vector<int> of 1,000,000 elements. Take multiple sub-spans: `first(250000)`, `subspan(250000, 250000)`, etc. Modify data through the sub-spans and verify the original vector reflects changes. Print the `.data()` pointers — show they're offsets into the original allocation, not new allocations.

4. **Buffer overrun — span detection:** Write a function that takes `std::span<int> and writes past the end using `operator[]` with an out-of-bounds index. Run with `-fsanitize=address` (GCC/Clang) or `/fsanitize=address` (MSVC). Does it detect the overrun? Now do the same with raw `int*` + `size_t` — does the sanitizer detect it? (Answer: it might not, because the size information is lost.)

5. **Design a binary buffer parser:** You receive network packets as `std::span<const uint8_t>. Design a parser that reads: 4-byte header (uint32_t), 2-byte payload length (uint16_t), variable-length payload. Each step returns a `std::span` of the remaining data (like a functional parser chain). Handle: insufficient data (span too short), and verify that the payload length doesn't exceed remaining span size. Why is span better than a `const uint8_t*` + `size_t` pair for this?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

`std::span` is a camera that looks at an array — it doesn't own the array, it just frames a view. You can zoom in on a subsection (`subspan`), split it into parts (`first`/`last`), and hand different views to different functions. The original array stays right where it is. Before span, you'd hand out a pointer and whisper the size separately — and someone would inevitably get the size wrong. Span staples the pointer and size together. Static-extent spans go further: they staple the size at compile time, so it's not even stored — the compiler just knows it.

### Technical

`std::span<T, Extent> (C++20, <span>)` is a non-owning contiguous view storing `T*` and (if Extent == `dynamic_extent`) `size_t`. Static-extent spans store only the pointer — `sizeof(span`<T,N>`) == sizeof(T*)`. Constructible from C arrays, `std::array`, `std::vector`, other spans, and pointer+size pairs. `subspan()`, `first()`, `last()` create sub-views in O(1) via pointer arithmetic — zero copies, zero allocations. Range-for, `operator[]`, `.data()`, `.size()`, `.size_bytes()` provide full container-like access. US government (NSA, NIST) and C++ Core Guidelines recommend span to eliminate spatial memory safety bugs; C++26 is expected to add bounds-safety contracts to span accessors. UE equivalent: `TArrayView<T>` (identical semantics, C++17 era).

