# std::filesystem — File I/O Without C APIs

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[01 — Stack vs Heap]], [[06 — std vector & Container Internals]]

---

## Why

For decades, C++ file I/O meant `<fstream> ` (awkward) or raw C `fopen`/`fread` (unsafe). C++17 `std::filesystem` provides a clean, type-safe API for: traversing directories, checking file types, manipulating paths (cross-platform!), reading/writing files, and querying file metadata. No more `#ifdef _WIN32` for path separators.

---

## Paths — Cross-Platform by Design

```cpp
#include <filesystem>
namespace fs = std::filesystem;

fs::path p = "assets/textures/hero.png";  // forward slash works on Windows too!
p = p / "normal" / "diffuse.png";         // operator/ joins paths
// Result: "assets/textures/hero/normal/diffuse.png"

p.extension();     // ".png"
p.stem();          // "diffuse"
p.filename();      // "diffuse.png"
p.parent_path();   // "assets/textures/hero/normal"
p.root_name();     // "C:" on Windows, "" on Linux
p.is_absolute();   // false

// Make absolute:
fs::path abs = fs::absolute(p);  // "C:/Users/.../assets/textures/hero/normal/diffuse.png"
```

**The operator/ trick:** `p / "subdir"` joins with the platform's separator. No manual `\` or `/` concatenation. Cross-platform by construction.

---

## Directory Traversal

```cpp
// Iterate directory entries:
for (const auto& entry : fs::directory_iterator("assets/textures")) {
    std::cout << entry.path() << " ";
    if (entry.is_directory()) {
        std::cout << "[DIR]";
    } else if (entry.is_regular_file()) {
        std::cout << "[" << entry.file_size() << " bytes]";
    }
}

// Recursive traversal (all subdirectories):
for (const auto& entry : fs::recursive_directory_iterator("assets")) {
    if (entry.path().extension() == ".png") {
        // Process all PNGs in all subdirectories
    }
}
```

---

## File Operations

```cpp
// Check existence:
if (fs::exists("config.json")) { /* ... */ }

// File size:
auto size = fs::file_size("data.bin");

// Copy file:
fs::copy("src.txt", "dst.txt", fs::copy_options::overwrite_existing);

// Rename/move:
fs::rename("old.txt", "new.txt");

// Create directory (with all parents):
fs::create_directories("assets/textures/characters");

// Remove file:
fs::remove("temp.txt");

// Remove directory and all contents:
fs::remove_all("build/");

// Last write time:
auto ftime = fs::last_write_time("config.json");
```

---

## Reading and Writing Entire Files

```cpp
// Read entire file as string:
std::string ReadFile(const fs::path& path) {
    std::ifstream f(path, std::ios::binary);
    if (!f) throw std::runtime_error("Cannot open: " + path.string());

    f.seekg(0, std::ios::end);
    auto size = f.tellg();
    f.seekg(0);

    std::string content(size, '\0');
    f.read(content.data(), size);
    return content;
}

// Write string to file:
void WriteFile(const fs::path& path, std::string_view content) {
    std::ofstream f(path, std::ios::binary);
    f.write(content.data(), content.size());
}
```

---

## Path Manipulation — Canonical and Relative

```cpp
fs::path p = "assets/../assets/textures/./hero.png";
fs::path clean = fs::canonical(p);  // resolves .. and .
// Result: "C:/project/assets/textures/hero.png"

fs::path base = "C:/project/assets";
fs::path target = "C:/project/assets/textures/hero.png";
fs::path rel = fs::relative(target, base);
// Result: "textures/hero.png"
```

---

## Temporary Files

```cpp
auto tmp = fs::temp_directory_path() / "myapp_XXXXXX";
// Use platform-specific temporary file creation...
```

---

## UE Equivalent — IFileManager

UE doesn't use std::filesystem (UE 5.8 = C++17, but engine predates it). Instead:

```cpp
IPlatformFile& PlatformFile = FPlatformFileManager::Get().GetPlatformFile();

// Iterate directory:
PlatformFile.IterateDirectory(TEXT("assets/textures"), Visitor);

// File size:
PlatformFile.FileSize(TEXT("data.bin"));

// Delete:
PlatformFile.DeleteFile(TEXT("temp.txt"));

// Read entire file:
TArray<uint8> Data;
FFileHelper::LoadFileToArray(Data, TEXT("data.bin"));
```

---

## Exercises

1. **Directory scanner:** Recursively scan a directory. Report: total file count, total size, largest file, file type distribution. Use recursive_directory_iterator.

2. **Path manipulation:** Given `"a/b/c/../../d/./e"`, compute canonical path. Given two absolute paths, compute relative. Test on Windows paths with drive letters.

3. **File watcher:** Poll a directory every second. Detect new files, modified files, deleted files. Compare last_write_time. Use it to implement a simple asset hot-reload system.

4. **Config file:** Write a JSON-like config to a file. Read it back. Handle: file doesn't exist (create default), corrupted (report error), permission denied (catch exception).

5. **UE comparison:** Port a directory scanner from std::filesystem to UE's IPlatformFile. What's missing? What's easier? What's UE-specific?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

std::filesystem is a universal remote for your hard drive. It speaks the same language on Windows (backslashes), Mac (forward slashes), and Linux. `exists()` checks if a file is there. `directory_iterator` walks through folders like a file explorer. `copy()` duplicates. `remove()` deletes. No more #ifdef for path separators.

### Technical

`fs::path` stores paths as `std::string` (or `std::wstring` on Windows). `operator/` appends with `preferred_separator`. `canonical()` resolves symlinks + `.` + `..` via OS syscalls (realpath on POSIX, GetFullPathName on Windows). Iterators use OS directory reading (readdir/FindFirstFile). File operations map to OS calls (CopyFile, rename, etc.). Throws `fs::filesystem_error` on failure.

