# std::pmr — Polymorphic Memory Resources (C++17)

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> `std::vector` and `std::string` allocate from the global heap. You can't give them a custom allocator without changing their TYPE — `std::vector<int, MyAllocator<int>>` is a DIFFERENT type than `std::vector<int>`. Code that takes `const std::vector<int>&` can't accept your custom-allocated vector. `std::pmr` (Polymorphic Memory Resources, C++17) fixes this: `std::pmr::vector<int>` is the SAME type regardless of where its memory comes from. You swap the allocator at runtime by swapping the `memory_resource*`. This is the allocator model that should have shipped in C++11. It enables arena allocation, per-frame scratch buffers, and memory tracking without template contamination.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[../03 — Memory/01 — Stack vs Heap|Stack vs Heap]] — understand heap allocation cost.
> [[../03 — Memory/11 — std deque, set & Container Adaptors|Container Internals]] — container memory models.

---

## The Problem — Allocators as Template Parameters

```cpp
// Traditional STL: allocator is part of the TYPE
std::vector<int, ArenaAlloc<int>> arenaVec;     // Different type!
std::vector<int, PoolAlloc<int>>   poolVec;     // Another different type!

// These can't be passed to the same function:'
void Process(const std::vector<int>& vec);       // Only accepts default allocator
Process(arenaVec);  // ❌ ERROR — different type
```

`std::pmr` decouples the allocator from the type:

```cpp
#include <memory_resource>

std::pmr::vector<int> vec;  // Type is always std::pmr::vector<int>
// The allocator is a runtime pointer, not a template parameter
```

---

## The Architecture — memory_resource + polymorphic_allocator

```
┌─────────────────────────────┐
│  std::pmr::vector<int>      │
│  ┌───────────────────────┐  │
│  │ polymorphic_allocator │──┼──→ memory_resource* (runtime dispatch)
│  └───────────────────────┘  │
└─────────────────────────────┘
                    │
                    ▼
    ┌───────────────────────────┐
    │  std::pmr::memory_resource│  (abstract base class)
    │  virtual void* allocate() │
    │  virtual void  deallocate()│
    └───────────────────────────┘
                    △
        ┌───────────┴───────────┐
        │                       │
┌───────┴──────────┐  ┌─────────┴────────────┐
│ new_delete_resource│  │ monotonic_buffer_resource│
│ (global heap)      │  │ (arena — bump allocator) │
└────────────────────┘  └──────────────────────────┘
```

---

## The Three Built-In Resources

### 1. `new_delete_resource()` — The Default (Global Heap)

```cpp
auto* heap = std::pmr::new_delete_resource();  // Wraps ::operator new/delete
std::pmr::vector<int> vec(heap);                // Behaves like regular std::vector
```

### 2. `monotonic_buffer_resource` — The Arena Allocator

Pre-allocate a buffer. Allocations bump a pointer forward. No individual deallocations — the entire buffer is freed at once by destroying the resource.

```cpp
// Pre-allocate a 1 MB buffer on the stack
std::array<std::byte, 1024 * 1024> buffer;

// Create the arena resource backed by our buffer
std::pmr::monotonic_buffer_resource arena(buffer.data(), buffer.size());

// Allocate from the arena
std::pmr::vector<int> vec(&arena);
for (int i = 0; i < 10000; i++) {
    vec.push_back(i);  // All allocations come from the stack buffer!
}
// When vec and arena go out of scope: buffer is reclaimed. No heap interaction.

// If the buffer is exhausted, monotonic_buffer_resource falls back to the
// upstream allocator (new_delete_resource by default, configurable).
```

### 3. `unsynchronized_pool_resource` — Pool Allocator

Maintains pools of same-sized blocks. Not thread-safe (hence "unsynchronized") — designed for single-threaded or externally-synchronized use.

```cpp
std::pmr::unsynchronized_pool_resource pool;
std::pmr::vector<int> vec(&pool);
// Allocations of similar sizes are served from pre-allocated pools.
// Reduces fragmentation compared to raw heap.
```

---

## Arena Benchmark — pmr vs Default Allocator

```cpp
#include <chrono>
#include <memory_resource>

// Default allocator: every push_back may hit the heap
auto t1 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
{
    std::vector<int> vec;
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) vec.push_back(i);
}
auto t2 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

// pmr monotonic: all allocations are bump-pointer within a pre-allocated buffer
char buffer[1024 * 1024];  // 1 MB stack buffer
std::pmr::monotonic_buffer_resource arena(buffer, sizeof(buffer));
auto t3 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();
{
    std::pmr::vector<int> vec(&arena);
    for (int i = 0; i < 100000; i++) vec.push_back(i);
}
auto t4 = std::chrono::high_resolution_clock::now();

// Typical result: pmr version is 3-10× faster, zero heap fragmentation
// Reallocations in pmr: move data within the same buffer (bump new region, memcpy old)
// Reallocations in default: new heap allocation + memcpy + free old
```

---

## Using pmr Without Changing Types — The Runtime Swap

```cpp
// Function takes pmr vector by const-ref — works with ANY underlying resource!
void ProcessFrame(const std::pmr::vector<Entity>& entities);

// Frame 1: use arena (fast, transient)
std::pmr::monotonic_buffer_resource frameArena(frameBuffer, sizeof(frameBuffer));
std::pmr::vector<Entity> frameEntities(&frameArena);
ProcessFrame(frameEntities);

// Frame 2: use pool (persistent)
std::pmr::unsynchronized_pool_resource pool;
std::pmr::vector<Entity> persistentEntities(&pool);
ProcessFrame(persistentEntities);

// Same type, same function — different allocator behavior at runtime.
// Zero template code duplication.
```

---

## Writing a Custom memory_resource

```cpp
class TrackingResource : public std::pmr::memory_resource {
    std::pmr::memory_resource* upstream;
    size_t totalAllocated = 0;
    size_t totalDeallocated = 0;

protected:
    void* do_allocate(size_t bytes, size_t alignment) override {
        totalAllocated += bytes;
        return upstream->allocate(bytes, alignment);
    }

    void do_deallocate(void* p, size_t bytes, size_t alignment) override {
        totalDeallocated += bytes;
        upstream->deallocate(p, bytes, alignment);
    }

    bool do_is_equal(const memory_resource& other) const noexcept override {
        return this == &other;
    }

public:
    TrackingResource(memory_resource* up = std::pmr::get_default_resource())
        : upstream(up) {}

    size_t GetLeakedBytes() const { return totalAllocated - totalDeallocated; }
};
// Drop-in memory leak detector — wraps any resource, zero code changes to containers
```

---

## UE Connection

UE doesn't use `std::pmr` (C++17 is not fully adopted), but the architecture mirrors UE's memory system:

| Concept | std::pmr | Unreal Engine |
|---------|----------|---------------|
| Polymorphic allocator | `polymorphic_allocator<T> | `FMemory::Malloc` (always global) |
| Arena | `monotonic_buffer_resource` | `FMemoryArena`, `FPageAllocator` |
| Pool | `unsynchronized_pool_resource` | `FMallocBinned` |
| Tracking | Custom `memory_resource` subclass | `LLM` (Low-Level Memory tracker) |
| Container integration | `std::pmr::vector<T> | `TArray` with `FMemory::Malloc` internally |

UE's `TArray` always allocates through `FMemory::Malloc`, which internally dispatches to binned allocators — similar to always using a pool resource. The plugin system provides `FMalloc` overrides for custom arena/tracking behavior.'

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

Regular `std::vector` bakes its allocator into its type — a vector with a custom arena is a DIFFERENT type than a normal vector. This means your functions that take `const vector<int>&` can't accept it. `std::pmr::vector<int>` is always the same type regardless of where its memory comes from. The allocator is a runtime pointer you can swap — use an arena for frame-temporary data, a pool for long-lived objects, and never change the type. The monotonic buffer resource is a pre-allocated block with a "next free spot" pointer — allocations just bump the pointer forward (extremely fast), and the whole block is freed at once when the resource is destroyed. It's like giving your container a private sandbox instead of making it compete for the public heap.

### Technical

`std::pmr` (C++17, <memory_resource>) decouples allocation from type identity via runtime polymorphism. `std::pmr::polymorphic_allocator<T> stores a `memory_resource*` and delegates `allocate`/`deallocate through virtual calls. `std::pmr::vector<T>` is `std::vector<T`, `polymorphic_allocator<T>>`. Built-in resources: `new_delete_resource` (global heap), `monotonic_buffer_resource` (arena — bump allocator with pre-allocated buffer, falls back to upstream on exhaustion), `unsynchronized_pool_resource` (size-classified pools, not thread-safe). Custom resources subclass `memory_resource` and override `do_allocate`, `do_deallocate`, `do_is_equal`. The type-erased design enables runtime allocator selection without template propagation — all `pmr::vector<int>` instances share the same type.

## See Also

- [[../03 — Memory/01 — Stack vs Heap|Stack vs Heap]] — Why arena allocation is faster than general heap
- [[../03 — Memory/06 — std vector & Container Internals|std::vector Internals]] — Growth semantics and reallocation cost that pmr mitigates
- [[../02 — Syntax & Types/06 — Explicit & Implicit Conversion|Custom Allocators]] — The manual approach that pmr standardizes

## Exercises

1. **Allocator comparison:** Benchmark `std::vector<int>` with `std::pmr::vector<int>` using a `std::pmr::monotonic_buffer_resource` backed by a 1 MB stack buffer. Push 100K integers. Measure allocations and time. Which is faster? Why?

2. **Arena switching:** Create two `monotonic_buffer_resource` arenas (one for frame data, one for level data). Allocate 10 vectors in frame arena, then switch the `std::pmr::polymorphic_allocator` to the level arena. Release the frame arena — what happens to the vectors? Why is this safer than manual `new`/`delete`?

3. **Pool fragmentation:** Create a `std::pmr::unsynchronized_pool_resource`. Allocate and free blocks of sizes 8, 16, 32, 64, 128, and 256 bytes in random order. Compare RSS (memory usage) after 10K iterations vs a monotonic resource. Which has less fragmentation? Which is faster?

4. **Default resource trap:** Write `std::pmr::vector<int> v;` without specifying an allocator. Where does it allocate? (Hint: `std::pmr::get_default_resource()` — which is `std::pmr::new_delete_resource()` by default.) What happens if someone upstream calls `std::pmr::set_default_resource()` to use a custom arena that's been destroyed?

5. **Design:** Your game has 3 allocation patterns: (a) per-frame scratch allocations (10K objects), (b) level-load allocations (50K objects, lives entire level), (c) persistent engine allocations. Which pmr resource type for each? Justify with allocation/deallocation patterns and fragmentation risk.

01 \u2014 Inheritance & Virtual Function.content:
# Inheritance & Virtual Functions

## Why Inheritance Exists

You have a game. Every enemy, player, and NPC shares common behavior — they all have health, a position, and can take damage. Instead of copying that code into every class, you write it ONCE in a base class and let specific types inherit from it.

```cpp
class Character {
public:
    int Health = 100;
    FVector Position;

    void TakeDamage(int Amount) {
        Health -= Amount;
        if (Health <= 0) Die();
    }
    virtual void Die() = 0;  // Each character dies differently
};
```

**Analogy:** Inheritance is like a family tree. A parent passes traits (member variables and functions) to children. Each child can override specific behaviors while keeping everything else the same.

---

## How Inheritance Works

### The Basic Syntax

```cpp
class Base {
public:
    int commonValue = 42;
    void CommonFunction() { /* ... */ }
};

class Derived : public Base {  // "Derived IS A Base"
    // commonValue and CommonFunction are inherited automatically
    int extraValue = 100;
};
```

**The three access levels for inheritance:**

| Inheritance Type | Public in Base becomes | Protected in Base becomes | Private in Base becomes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `public` | public | protected | inaccessible |
| `protected` | protected | protected | inaccessible |
| `private` | private | private | inaccessible |

> [!tip] Use `public` inheritance 99% of the time
> `public` inheritance means "Derived IS A Base" — this is what you want. `protected` and `private` inheritance are for niche cases where you want to reuse code but don't want the is-a relationship. UE uses `public` inheritance almost exclusively.

### What Gets Inherited

- ✅ All member variables
- ✅ All member functions
- ❌ Constructors (not inherited — but can be called from derived constructor)
- ❌ Destructor (not inherited — each class has its own)
- ❌ Assignment operators (not inherited)
- ❌ Friend declarations (not inherited)

```cpp
class Enemy : public Character {
public:
    int Damage = 10;

    Enemy() : Character() {}  // Must explicitly call base constructor if needed

    void Attack() { /* Enemy-specific */ }
};

Enemy goblin;
goblin.Health = 50;    // Inherited from Character
goblin.TakeDamage(10);  // Inherited from Character
goblin.Attack();        // Enemy's own function
```

---

## Virtual Functions — The Key to Polymorphism

Without `virtual`, the function called depends on the TYPE OF THE POINTER, not the actual object:

```cpp
Character* ptr = new Enemy();
ptr->Die();  // Without virtual: calls Character::Die() — WRONG!
             // With virtual: calls Enemy::Die() — CORRECT!
```

`virtual` tells the compiler: "Don't decide which function to call based on the pointer type. Look at the actual object at runtime and call the right version."

### How Virtual Functions Work — The VTable

Every class with virtual functions has a hidden pointer called the **vptr** (virtual pointer) at offset 0 in the object. This points to a **vtable** — a table of function pointers shared by all instances of that class.

```cpp
// What the compiler generates (simplified):
// sizeof(Character) = 8 (vptr) + 4 (Health) + alignment padding
// Character's vtable: [&Character::Die, ...]
// Enemy's vtable:     [&Enemy::Die, ...]
```

When you call `ptr->Die()`, the compiler generates:
```cpp
ptr->vptr[0]();  // Look up function at index 0 in vtable, call it
```

**This is the runtime cost of virtual functions:** one extra pointer dereference per call. For a game running at 60 FPS with thousands of actors, this cost is negligible. Use virtual functions freely when you need polymorphism.

---

## `override` — Your Safety Net

```cpp
class Base {
public:
    virtual void Update(float DeltaTime);
};

class Derived : public Base {
public:
    void Update(float DeltaTime) override;  // ✅ Compiler checks: does Base have Update(float)?
    // void Updaet(float DeltaTime) override;  // ❌ COMPILE ERROR — typo caught!
};
```

**Always use `override`** when overriding a virtual function. It catches:
- Typos in the function name
- Wrong parameter types
- Wrong const qualifiers
- Base function not actually virtual

```cpp
// Without override — silently creates NEW function instead of overriding:
class Bad : public Base {
    void Update(double DeltaTime);  // Different parameter type — NOT an override!
    // Base::Update(float) still exists, uncalled
};

// With override — compiler screams at you:
class Good : public Base {
    void Update(double DeltaTime) override;  // ❌ ERROR: no matching base function
};
```

---

## `final` — Stop the Chain

```cpp
class LastDerived final : public Base {  // No class can inherit from LastDerived
    void Die() override final;  // No derived class can override Die()
};
```

**Use `final` sparingly.** It's a promise that this is the final form. Good for critical functions where overriding would break invariants. Overused, it makes code inflexible.

---

## Pure Virtual Functions — Abstract Classes

```cpp
class Character {
public:
    virtual void Die() = 0;  // Pure virtual — NO implementation required
    // Character is now "abstract" — you cannot create Character objects
};

Character c;  // ❌ ERROR — Cannot instantiate abstract class
Enemy e;      // ✅ OK — Enemy implements Die()

class Enemy : public Character {
    void Die() override { /* death animation, drop loot, remove from world */ }
};
```

A class with at least one pure virtual function is **abstract**. You cannot create objects of it — it exists only to be inherited from. This is how UE defines interfaces and base classes.

> [!tip] Pure virtual CAN have a body
> `virtual void Die() = 0 { /* default impl */ }` — this has a default implementation. Derived classes can call it with `Character::Die()`. This is rare but useful for shared cleanup logic.

---

## Virtual Destructors — The #1 Pitfall

```cpp
class Base {
    // ❌ WRONG: non-virtual destructor
    ~Base() { /* cleanup */ }
};

Base* ptr = new Derived();
delete ptr;  // Only Base::~Base() is called — Derived's destructor NEVER RUNS!
             // Memory leak! Undefined behavior!

// ✅ CORRECT:
class Base {
public:
    virtual ~Base() = default;  // Virtual destructor
};
```

**The rule:** If a class has ANY virtual function, make its destructor virtual. This guarantees the correct destructor chain runs when you `delete` through a base pointer.

---

## Object Slicing — Copying Loses Type Information

```cpp
Enemy goblin;
goblin.Damage = 50;

Character c = goblin;  // SLICED! c is a Character — only Character's members are copied.
                        // goblin.Damage is lost. c is now just a plain Character.

// Fix: use pointers or references instead of copying
Character& ref = goblin;     // ref refers to the Enemy — no slicing
Character* ptr = &goblin;    // ptr points to the Enemy — no slicing
```

---

## C++23 — Deducing `this`

C++23 adds a new way to write member functions that simplifies `const` and value-category overloads:

```cpp
class Widget {
    int value;
public:
    // C++23: explicit object parameter — replaces const/non-const overloads
    template<typename Self>
    auto GetValue(this Self&& self) {
        return self.value;
    }
};

const Widget w;
w.GetValue();  // Self = const Widget& — returns const int&

Widget w2;
w2.GetValue();  // Self = Widget& — returns int&
```

This is advanced — you won't need it in UE for now, but know it exists when you see it in newer code.

---

## Quick Reference

| Keyword | What It Does |
|---|---|
| `virtual` | Function call resolved at runtime based on actual object type |
| `override` | Compiler verifies this function really overrides a base virtual function |
| `final` | No class can inherit / no derived class can override this function |
| `= 0` | Pure virtual — makes class abstract, must be overridden |
| `virtual ~Base()` | Virtual destructor — ensures correct cleanup through base pointer |

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

Inheritance is family. A child inherits traits from their parent but can have their own unique skills too. `virtual` means "ask the actual object what to do" — if you point at a dog and say "speak," a dog barks, but if you point at a cat, it meows. Without `virtual`, the pointer type decides — "speak" always means the generic animal noise, regardless of what animal it actually is. `override` is just double-checking that you spelled everything right.

### Technical

Virtual functions implement dynamic dispatch via a vtable — a per-class array of function pointers. Each object stores a vptr (8 bytes at offset 0) pointing to its class's vtable. Calling a virtual function loads the vptr, indexes the vtable, and calls through the function pointer. `override` is a compile-time annotation with no runtime cost. `final` enables devirtualization optimizations — the compiler can replace virtual calls with direct calls when it knows the exact type. Virtual destructors ensure the vtable includes the correct destructor pointer so `delete` through a base pointer calls the full destructor chain.

---

## Exercises

1. **vtable layout:** Class with 3 virtual functions. sizeof? Add member. Extra bytes = vptr. Debugger inspect.

2. **Virtual destructor:** `Base* p = new Derived; delete p;`. Non-virtual dtor — Derived's dtor runs? Add virtual.

3. **Pure virtual:** `class Character { virtual void Attack()=0; }`. `vector<unique_ptr<Character>`. Without virtual?

4. **Diamond:** A→B,C→D. One or two A copies? Virtual inheritance. Draw memory layout.

5. **final and override:** `override` on non-override — error? `final` class — derive? `final` method — override?


## See Also

- [[../02 — Lambdas & Function Objects|Lambdas]] — Polymorphism without inheritance (std::function)
- [[../03 — C++ Casting & RTTI|Casting & RTTI]] — dynamic_cast and virtual dispatch
- [[../05 — Templates & Concepts|Templates]] — Compile-time polymorphism (CRTP)
- [[../../03 — Memory/02 — Object Memory Layout|Object Memory Layout]] — vtable layout in memory
- [[../../../UE Core/UE Inheritance & UObject System|UE Inheritance]] — Unreal's UObject hierarchy

02 \u2014 Lambdas & Function Objects.content:
# Lambdas & Function Objects

## What Is a Lambda?

A lambda is an **anonymous function object** — a function you can define inline, capture variables from its surrounding scope, and pass around like any other object.

```cpp
// Traditional function
bool IsEven(int x) { return x % 2 == 0; }

// Lambda — same thing, defined where you need it
auto IsEven = [](int x) { return x % 2 == 0; };

// Usage: identical to a function
IsEven(4);  // true
```

Under the hood, the compiler generates a class with `operator()`. The lambda is just syntactic sugar for a function object.

---

## Lambda Syntax — The Full Breakdown

```cpp
[ captures ] ( parameters ) -> return_type { body }
   │           │            │              │
   │           │            │              └── The code
   │           │            └── Optional return type (usually auto-deduced)
   │           └── Like a normal function parameter list
   └── What variables from outside to capture, and how
```

```cpp
// Minimal — capture nothing, take nothing, return nothing
auto hello = [] { std::cout << "Hello"; };

// With parameters and return type
auto add = [](int a, int b) -> int { return a + b; };

// Return type auto-deduced (most common)
auto multiply = [](int a, int b) { return a * b; };
```

---

## Captures — The Heart of Lambdas

The capture list controls which variables from the enclosing scope the lambda can access:

| Capture | Syntax | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| Nothing | `[]` | Access no outside variables |
| Everything by value | `[=]` | Copy all variables used in the body |
| Everything by reference | `[&]` | Reference all variables used in the body |
| Specific by value | `[x, y]` | Copy x and y |
| Specific by reference | `[&x, &y]` | Reference x and y |
| Mixed | `[=, &z]` | Copy everything except z (by reference) |
| Mixed | `[&, z]` | Reference everything except z (by value) |
| Move | `[x = std::move(x)]` | Move x into the lambda (C++14 init capture) |

```cpp
int threshold = 10;
int count = 0;

// Capture threshold by value, count by reference
auto check = [threshold, &count](int x)
{
    if (x > threshold) count++;
    return x > threshold;
};

check(15);  // threshold = 10 (copy), count becomes 1
```

> [!danger] Capturing by Reference Is Dangerous
> The lambda holds a reference. If the referenced variable is destroyed before the lambda runs, you have a dangling reference — undefined behavior. This is the #1 crash with asynchronous lambdas:
> ```cpp
> std::function<void()> GetCallback() {
>     int local = 5;
>     return [&local] { std::cout << local; };  // ❌ local destroyed when function returns!
> }
> ``
> Use `[=]` or init capture `[local = local]` for asynchronous lambdas.

---

## Init Captures (C++14) — Moving Into Lambdas

```cpp
// Move a unique_ptr into a lambda
auto ptr = std::make_unique<int>(42);
auto lambda = [p = std::move(ptr)] { return *p; };
// ptr is now nullptr — p owns the int inside the lambda

// Calculate once, capture the result
auto lambda = [value = ComputeExpensive()] { return value * 2; };
```

Init captures let you move objects (which can't be copied via `[=]`) and pre-compute values at capture time.

---

## Mutable Lambdas

By default, a lambda's `operator()` is `const` — you cannot modify captured-by-value variables:

```cpp
int counter = 0;
// auto inc = [counter] { return ++counter; };  // ❌ ERROR — captured value is const

auto inc = [counter]() mutable { return ++counter; };  // ✅ mutable
inc();  // returns 1
inc();  // returns 2
// BUT: counter outside is still 0 — the lambda has its own COPY
```

**`mutable` only affects captured-by-value variables.** It does NOT affect captured-by-reference variables (those always reflect the original).

---

## Generic Lambdas (C++14) — auto Parameters

```cpp
// Lambda that works with any type
auto add = [](auto a, auto b) { return a + b; };

add(1, 2);         // int + int
add(1.5, 2.5);     // double + double
add(std::string("hello "), std::string("world"));  // string + string
```

Under the hood, this generates a template `operator()`. It's equivalent to writing:

```cpp
struct Anonymous {
    template<typename T, typename U>
    auto operator()(T a, U b) const { return a + b; }
};
```

Generic lambdas with `auto` parameters are the C++14 way. C++20 added explicit template parameters for lambdas (see below).

---

## Template Lambdas (C++20)

```cpp
// Explicit template parameters — clearer than auto
auto add = []<typename T>(T a, T b) { return a + b; };

// Useful when you need the type inside the body
auto printType = []<typename T>(const T& val) {
    std::cout << typeid(T).name();
};
```

Template lambdas let you name the type parameter, which `auto` doesn't. Useful when you need `T` inside the body or want to constrain with concepts.

---

## std::function — Type-Erased Callable

`std::function` can store any callable — function pointers, lambdas, function objects, member function pointers:

```cpp
#include <functional>

std::function<int(int, int)> op;

op = [](int a, int b) { return a + b; };  // Lambda
op = std::multiplies<int>{};               // Function object
op = &SomeFunction;                         // Function pointer

int result = op(3, 4);  // Calls whatever was stored
```

**The cost:** `std::function` uses type erasure, which means a virtual call (or similar) on every invocation. It also allocates on the heap for lambdas that capture too much state. For performance-critical code, use templates or `auto` instead.

```cpp
// ❌ std::function in a hot loop — virtual call every iteration
void ForEach(const std::vector<int>& v, std::function<void(int)> fn);

// ✅ Template — no virtual call, can inline
template<typename Fn>
void ForEach(const std::vector<int>& v, Fn fn);
```

---

## Lambdas vs Function Pointers

| | Lambda | Function Pointer |
|---|---|---|
| **Captures?** | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| **Inlineable?** | ✅ Yes (compiler sees definition) | ⚠️ Sometimes (LTO needed) |
| **Size** | Depends on captures | 8 bytes (pointer) |
| **Convertible to** | `std::function`, function pointer (if captureless) | — |

Captureless lambdas (with `[]`) are implicitly convertible to function pointers:

```cpp
auto lambda = [](int x) { return x * 2; };
int (*fnPtr)(int) = lambda;  // ✅ OK — no captures
```

---

## Common Lambda Patterns

### Sort with custom comparator

```cpp
std::vector<Person> people;
std::sort(people.begin(), people.end(),
    [](const Person& a, const Person& b) { return a.age < b.age; });
```

### Find with predicate

```cpp
auto it = std::find_if(v.begin(), v.end(),
    [threshold](int x) { return x > threshold; });
```

### Immediate invocation

```cpp
// Compute and assign in one expression
const auto result = [&] {
    if (condition) return ComputeA();
    else return ComputeB();
}();  // ← () invokes the lambda immediately
```

### Storing in a container

```cpp
std::vector<std::function<void()>> callbacks;
callbacks.push_back([&] { DoThing(); });
callbacks.push_back([=] { DoOtherThing(x, y); });
```

---

## Lambdas and `this` (C++17/20)

```cpp
class Widget
{
    int value;

    auto GetCallback()
    {
        // C++17: capture *this by value — copies the entire object
        return [*this] { return value; };

        // C++20: explicit this capture
        return [this] { return value; };      // By reference (old way)
        return [=, this] { return value; };   // Explicit this capture
    }
};
```

**The rule:** Prefer `[*this]` (C++17) for asynchronous callbacks. It copies the object, preventing lifetime issues. Use `[this]` only when the lambda's lifetime is guaranteed to be shorter than the object's.

---

## Common Mistakes

### 1. Dangling reference from `[&]` capture

```cpp
std::function<void()> MakePrinter(const std::string& msg) {
    return [&msg] { std::cout << msg; };  // ❌ msg is a reference to parameter — destroyed!
}

// Fix: capture by value
std::function<void()> MakePrinter(const std::string& msg) {
    return [msg] { std::cout << msg; };  // ✅ msg is copied into the lambda
}
```

### 2. Copying large objects via `[=]`

```cpp
std::vector<int> huge(1000000);
auto fn = [=] { return huge.size(); };  // ❌ Copies the ENTIRE vector!

// Fix: capture by reference if short-lived, or move
auto fn = [&huge] { return huge.size(); };     // Reference — safe if fn doesn't outlive huge
auto fn = [v = std::move(huge)] { return v.size(); }; // Move — transfers ownership
```

### 3. Forgetting `mutable` when modifying captured values

```cpp
int counter = 0;
auto fn = [counter] { return ++counter; };  // ❌ ERROR — captured value is const
auto fn = [counter]() mutable { return ++counter; };  // ✅
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

A lambda is a function you can write on the fly. Instead of declaring a named function somewhere else, you write it right where you need it. Captures are like a backpack — the lambda packs up variables from outside and carries them inside. `[=]` photocopies everything. `[&]` writes down the address. `std::function` is a universal remote that can call anything — lambda, regular function, or function object.

### Technical

A lambda expression generates an anonymous closure type with an `operator()` and storage for captured variables. Capture-by-value copies the variable into the closure; capture-by-reference stores a pointer/reference. Init captures (C++14) allow move-only types and expression evaluation at capture time. Generic lambdas (C++14) generate a templated `operator()` via `auto` parameters; explicit template lambdas (C++20) add named template parameters. `std::function` uses type erasure (typically a virtual call or small buffer optimization) to store any callable matching the signature, at the cost of heap allocation for large closures and indirect dispatch overhead. `std::move_only_function` (C++23) extends this to move-only callables.

---

## Exercises

1. **Lambda under the hood:** `auto f = [x](int y){return x+y;}`. Use C++ Insights. Generated functor class? Why zero-overhead?

2. **Capture by reference:** Lambda captures local by ref, stored in `function`. Call after local out of scope. What happens?

3. **Generic lambda:** `auto add = [](auto a, auto b){return a+b;}`. Call with int, double, string. Return type?

4. **std::function overhead:** Lambda vs function vs function pointer. Benchmark. Why does function allocate?

5. **UE's TFunction:** UE alternative to std::function. Differences? Raw lambda vs function vs TFunction vs delegate?


## See Also

- [[../01 — Inheritance & Virtual Functions|Inheritance]] — Runtime polymorphism vs lambda closures
- [[../03 — C++ Casting & RTTI|Casting & RTTI]] — Converting lambdas to function pointers
- [[../04 — Operator Overloading|Operator Overloading]] — Function objects via operator()
- [[../../05 — Modern C++/06 — std ranges (C++20)|std::ranges]] — Lambdas as range adaptors

03 \u2014 C++ Casting & RTTI.content:
# C++ Casting & RTTI

## The Four Named Casts

C++ has four casting operators. Each does something different. The compiler enforces which one you can use where — unlike the old C-style cast `(Type)expr`, which is a sledgehammer that tries everything until something compiles.

| Cast | Purpose | Runtime Cost | Safety |
|---|---|---|---|
| `static_cast` | Implicit conversions, upcasts, downcasts (unchecked) | Zero (usually) | Compile-time |
| `dynamic_cast` | Safe downcast with runtime type check | High — vtable walk | Runtime — returns `nullptr` or throws |
| `const_cast` | Add or remove `const`/`volatile` | Zero | Compile-time — but using it is dangerous |
| `reinterpret_cast` | Bit-level reinterpretation | Zero | None — "trust me" |

---

## static_cast — The Workhorse

**What it does:** Performs implicit conversions explicitly, or reverses them. It's what the compiler would do automatically, just made visible in the code.

```cpp
// Implicit conversions — static_cast makes them explicit
double d = 3.14;
int i = static_cast<int>(d);  // 3 (truncation — visible in code)

// Upcast — always safe, no runtime cost
Derived* derived = new Derived();
Base* base = static_cast<Base*>(derived);  // Pointer adjusted if needed

// Downcast — UNSAFE, no runtime check!
Base* base = GetSomeBase();
Derived* derived = static_cast<Derived*>(base);  // Compiles, but UB if wrong type

// Enum ↔ integer
enum class Color { Red, Green, Blue };
int val = static_cast<int>(Color::Red);  // 0
```

**When to use:** Upcasts, numeric conversions, enum ↔ int, void* ↔ T* (when you know the type). Never for downcasts — use `dynamic_cast` there.

> [!danger] static_cast Downcasts Are Dangerous
> `static_cast<Derived*>(base_ptr)` compiles silently. If `base_ptr` is actually a `Base`, not a `Derived`, the program has **undefined behavior**. The pointer is wrong. Accessing it could crash, corrupt memory, or (worst) silently produce wrong results that only fail in production. Always use `dynamic_cast` for downcasts.

---

## dynamic_cast — Safe, Runtime-Checked Downcasting

**What it does:** Checks at runtime whether the cast is valid by walking the class hierarchy. Requires at least one virtual function (a vtable).

```cpp
class Animal { public: virtual ~Animal() = default; };
class Dog : public Animal {};
class Cat : public Animal {};

Animal* animal = GetSomeAnimal();

// Pointer cast — returns nullptr on failure
Dog* dog = dynamic_cast<Dog*>(animal);
if (dog)
{
    dog->Bark();  // Safe — we verified it's a Dog
}

// Reference cast — throws std::bad_cast on failure
try
{
    Dog& dog_ref = dynamic_cast<Dog&>(*animal);
    dog_ref.Bark();
}
catch (const std::bad_cast& e)
{
    // animal wasn't a Dog
}
```

**Cost:** `dynamic_cast` walks the vtable and compares `type_info` objects. For deep hierarchies, this can be expensive (50-200+ cycles depending on depth). Don't use it in hot loops.

**When to use:** When you receive a base pointer from external code (event callback, message handler) and need to check the concrete type. It's the safe path — returns `nullptr` instead of corrupting memory.

---

## const_cast — "I Know What I'm Doing"

**What it does:** Removes or adds `const` or `volatile` qualifiers. This is the ONLY cast that can change cv-qualifiers.

```cpp
const int x = 42;

// ❌ Undefined behavior — modifying a const object
int& ref = const_cast<int&>(x);
ref = 100;  // x was declared const — this is UB

// ✅ Valid use — calling a legacy C API that takes non-const but doesn't modify
void LegacyPrint(char* str);  // Doesn't actually modify str
const char* msg = "Hello";
LegacyPrint(const_cast<char*>(msg));  // Safe because LegacyPrint doesn't write
```

**When to use:** Almost never. The only legitimate use is interop with legacy C APIs that take non-const pointers but don't actually modify the data. Even then, prefer wrapping the C API rather than spreading `const_cast` through your code.

> [!warning] const_cast Is A Code Smell
> If you're casting away `const` on an object that was declared `const`, and then modifying it, the behavior is **undefined.** The compiler may have placed the object in read-only memory. The optimizer may have cached its value. Anything can happen.

---

## reinterpret_cast — The Nuclear Option

**What it does:** Reinterprets the bits of one type as another type. No conversion. No checking. Just "treat these bytes as if they were a different type."

```cpp
// Cast pointer to integer (for hashing, debugging)
int* ptr = new int(42);
uintptr_t addr = reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(ptr);

// Cast integer back to pointer (DANGEROUS)
int* ptr2 = reinterpret_cast<int*>(addr);  // Only safe if addr came from a valid pointer

// Read raw bytes of a float
float f = 3.14f;
uint32_t bits = *reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(&f);  // OK — both are 32-bit trivially copyable
```

**When to use:** Extremely rarely. Legitimate cases: serialization (reading raw bytes), memory-mapped I/O, interop with C APIs that use opaque handles (`void*`), and pointer tagging for lock-free data structures. If you're using `reinterpret_cast` in everyday code, you're probably doing something wrong.

---

## C-Style Cast — The Legacy Sledgehammer

```cpp
double d = 3.14;
int i = (int)d;  // C-style cast
```

The C-style cast `(Type)expr` tries, in order: `const_cast`, `static_cast`, `static_cast` + `const_cast`, `reinterpret_cast`, `reinterpret_cast` + `const_cast`. It's a sledgehammer that tries everything until something works — including unsafe operations.

**Never use C-style casts in C++.** They hide dangerous operations. A `static_cast` that accidentally becomes a `reinterpret_cast` because of a missing `const` won't warn you. The named casts make intent explicit and let the compiler catch mistakes.

---

## RTTI — Runtime Type Information

RTTI is the machinery behind `dynamic_cast` and `typeid`. It's enabled by default but can be disabled with `-fno-rtti` (GCC/Clang) or `/GR-` (MSVC).

```cpp
#include <typeinfo>

Animal* a = GetSomeAnimal();
std::cout << typeid(*a).name();  // "Dog" or "Cat" — implementation-defined string

if (typeid(*a) == typeid(Dog))
{
    // a is exactly a Dog (not a subclass)
}
```

**`typeid` vs `dynamic_cast`:** `typeid` checks exact type equality. `dynamic_cast` checks "is this type, or a subclass?" Use `typeid` when you need to know the exact concrete class. Use `dynamic_cast` when you need to safely downcast.

**Cost of RTTI:** Each polymorphic class gets a `type_info` object stored in the vtable. `dynamic_cast` walks this. `typeid` does a single comparison. Disabling RTTI saves per-class overhead and can reduce binary size, but you lose `dynamic_cast` and `typeid` entirely.

---

## The Cast Decision Guide

| You want to... | Use |
|---|---|
| Convert `double` to `int` | `static_cast<int>(d)` |
| Convert enum to underlying integer | `static_cast<int>(MyEnum)` |
| Upcast `Derived*` to `Base*` | `static_cast` (or just assign — implicit) |
| Downcast `Base*` to `Derived*` safely | `dynamic_cast<Derived*>(base)` |
| Call a legacy C API with non-const pointer | `const_cast` (only if API doesn't write) |
| Read raw bytes of a trivially copyable type | `reinterpret_cast` or `std::bit_cast` (C++20) |
| Hash a pointer address | `reinterpret_cast<uintptr_t>(ptr)` |
| "I need this to compile and I don't care how" | ❌ — redesign your code |

---

## C++20: std::bit_cast — The Safe reinterpret_cast

C++20 introduced `std::bit_cast` as a safe alternative to `reinterpret_cast` for trivially copyable types:

```cpp
float f = 3.14f;
uint32_t bits = std::bit_cast<uint32_t>(f);  // ✅ Safe, defined behavior
// reinterpret_cast version — technically UB (strict aliasing violation)
// uint32_t bits = *reinterpret_cast<uint32_t*>(&f);
```

`std::bit_cast` guarantees the same size, copies the bits, and doesn't violate strict aliasing rules. Always prefer it over `reinterpret_cast` for type-punning.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

Casting is like verifying someone's identity. `static_cast` is checking their name badge — fast, but if they swapped badges, you're fooled. `dynamic_cast` is calling security — they verify against the database, slower but accurate. `const_cast` is convincing security to remove the "DO NOT TOUCH" sticker — dangerous and usually a bad idea. `reinterpret_cast` is looking at someone and saying "I declare you to be a different person" — almost never valid.

### Technical

`static_cast` performs compile-time conversions: implicit conversion sequences, upcasts (adjusting `this` pointer by base class offset), and user-defined conversions. `dynamic_cast` uses RTTI via the vtable — `__dynamic_cast` walks the class hierarchy comparing `type_info` objects. For pointer casts, it returns `nullptr` on failure; for reference casts, it throws `std::bad_cast`. `const_cast` is the only cast that modifies cv-qualifiers; it does nothing at runtime. `reinterpret_cast` performs no operation — the bits are unchanged, only the compiler's type interpretation changes. C++20's `std::bit_cast` provides defined behavior for trivially copyable type reinterpretation by copying through an intermediate byte array, avoiding strict aliasing violations.

---

## Exercises

1. **Four casts:** `static_cast`, `dynamic_cast`, `const_cast`, `reinterpret_cast`. When safe vs UB.

2. **dynamic_cast cost:** 1M dynamic_cast vs static_cast. Ratio? Why slow? (DAG walk.)

3. **typeid vs dynamic_cast:** Speed? Which works with -fno-rtti?

4. **Cross-cast:** Diamond. `B*` to `C*` via `D*`. static_cast work for cross-cast?

5. **UE's Cast vs dynamic_cast:** Implement simplified Cast using StaticClass() and bit flags. Benchmark.


## See Also

