02 \u2014 Slerp & Kinematics.content:
# Slerp & Kinematics

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Curves Overview|Curves]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[01 — Interpolation, Bezier & Splines]] — understand parametric curves first.


### Analogy: The Great Circle Flight

If you fly from New York to Tokyo, your plane doesn't follow a straight line on the flat map \u2014 it arcs over Alaska. That's the **great circle** path: the shortest route along the surface of a sphere. Quaternion rotations live on a 4D hypersphere. Lerping quaternions directly moves through the inside of the sphere (changing length \u2014 invalid rotation). Slerp travels along the surface, preserving the unit length and giving the rotationally shortest path.

### Why Not Just Lerp Quaternions?

```cpp
// \u274c WRONG: produces non-unit quaternion, rotation speeds up/slows down
Quat BadBlend = Quat::FastLerp(A, B, Alpha);  // use only when Alpha is very small

// \u2705 CORRECT: constant angular speed, stays on unit hypersphere
Quat GoodBlend = Quat::Slerp(A, B, Alpha);
```

Linear interpolation inside quaternion space means the intermediate quaternion has magnitude < 1.0 (it dips inside the hypersphere). Normalizing after lerp (\"nlerp\") fixes the magnitude but still gives non-constant angular velocity \u2014 the rotation speeds up in the middle.

### Mathematical Definition

For unit quaternions q\u2080 and q\u2081 with angle \u03a9 between them (where cos(\u03a9) = q\u2080\u00b7q\u2081):

$$\\text{slerp}(q_0, q_1, t) = \\frac{\\sin((1-t)\\Omega)}{\\sin(\\Omega)} q_0 + \\frac{\\sin(t\\Omega)}{\\sin(\\Omega)} q_1$$

```cpp
Quat Slerp(const Quat& A, const Quat& B, float t)
{
    // Compute the cosine of the angle between the two quaternions
    float cosOmega = A.X * B.X + A.Y * B.Y + A.Z * B.Z + A.W * B.W;

    // If very close, fall back to lerp to avoid division by ~0
    if (Math::Abs(cosOmega) > 0.9995f)
    {
        Quat Result = Quat::FastLerp(A, B, t);  // FastLerp (component blend + normalize) \u2014 NOT Math::Lerp which delegates to Slerp, defeating the fallback
        Result.Normalize();
        return Result;
    }

    // Take the shorter path
    float omega = Math::Acos(cosOmega);
    float sinOmega = Math::Sin(omega);
    float scaleA = Math::Sin((1.0f - t) * omega) / sinOmega;
    float scaleB = Math::Sin(t * omega) / sinOmega;

    return Quat(
        scaleA * A.X + scaleB * B.X,
        scaleA * A.Y + scaleB * B.Y,
        scaleA * A.Z + scaleB * B.Z,
        scaleA * A.W + scaleB * B.W
    );
}
```

> [!tip] The Double-Cover Problem
> Quaternions q and -q represent the same rotation. Before slerping, check the dot product: if it's negative, negate one quaternion to take the shorter arc. `Quat::Slerp()` in game engine handles this automatically.

### game engine Connection

```cpp
// Animation blueprint blending
Quat BlendedRot = Quat::Slerp(AnimA_Rotation, AnimB_Rotation, BlendWeight);

// Camera rotation smoothing
CurrentRotation = Quat::Slerp(CurrentRotation, TargetRotation, RotationSpeed * DeltaTime);

// Quat::Slerp is not a static \u2014 it's the non-static version
Quat Result = StartQuat.Slerp(EndQuat, Alpha);
```

---

### Analogy: The Puppet Strings

With **forward kinematics** (FK), you move the shoulder, then the elbow, then the wrist to place the hand somewhere. It's like controlling a puppet joint-by-joint \u2014 tedious and trial-and-error. **Inverse kinematics** (IK) flips the problem: you say \"put the hand HERE\" and the math figures out where the shoulder, elbow, and wrist should go. It's like pulling the puppet's hand to a location and letting the arm naturally follow.

### The IK Problem

Given:
- A chain of bones (shoulder \u2192 elbow \u2192 wrist \u2192 hand)
- Known bone lengths
- A target position for the end effector (hand)

Find: Joint angles that place the end effector at the target.

Two main algorithms dominate game IK:

### CCD (Cyclic Coordinate Descent)

**Analogy: The Hot-and-Cold Game**

You're trying to touch a target with your fingertip. Start at the fingertip and work backward: rotate the wrist to point the finger at the target. Then rotate the elbow to bring the wrist closer. Then rotate the shoulder. Then go back to the wrist (it moved when you rotated the elbow), then the elbow, then the shoulder... Repeat until the finger is close enough. Each joint does a simple \"point toward target\" rotation.

```cpp
void SolveCCD(TArray<Vec3>& JointPositions, const Vec3& Target, int MaxIterations = 10)
{
    int NumJoints = JointPositions.Num();
    if (NumJoints < 2) return;

    for (int Iter = 0; Iter < MaxIterations; ++Iter)
    {
        // Work backward from the end effector toward the root
        for (int i = NumJoints - 2; i >= 0; --i)
        {
            Vec3 JointPos = JointPositions[i];
            Vec3 EndEffector = JointPositions.Last();

            // Vector from joint to end effector
            Vec3 ToEnd = (EndEffector - JointPos).GetSafeNormal();
            // Vector from joint to target
            Vec3 ToTarget = (Target - JointPos).GetSafeNormal();

            // Angle between these vectors
            float Dot = Vec3::DotProduct(ToEnd, ToTarget);
            if (Dot > 0.9999f) continue;  // Already pointing at target

            Vec3 RotationAxis = Vec3::CrossProduct(ToEnd, ToTarget).GetSafeNormal();
            float Angle = Math::Acos(Math::Clamp(Dot, -1.0f, 1.0f));

            Quat DeltaRotation(RotationAxis, Angle);

            // Rotate all child joints around this joint
            for (int j = i + 1; j < NumJoints; ++j)
            {
                Vec3 Relative = JointPositions[j] - JointPos;
                JointPositions[j] = JointPos + DeltaRotation.RotateVector(Relative);
            }
        }

        // Check if we're close enough
        if (Vec3::Dist(JointPositions.Last(), Target) < 0.1f)
            break;
    }
}
```

**CCD Pros & Cons:**
- \u2705 Simple to implement (just rotate each joint toward the target)
- \u2705 Can handle joint limits easily
- \u274c Can produce unnatural-looking poses (elbow might bend backward)
- \u274c Tends to over-rotate joints near the end effector

### FABRIK (Forward And Backward Reaching Inverse Kinematics)

**Analogy: The Folding Ruler Trick**

Imagine a folding ruler (the kind carpenters use) that's been folded up. To make its tip touch a target, you:
1. **Forward pass:** Grab the tip and place it exactly on the target. Now the ruler segments are stretched \u2014 pull the next-to-last joint to maintain the segment length. Continue backward toward the base.
2. **Backward pass:** The base has moved from its anchor. Grab the base and put it back. Now pull each subsequent joint forward, maintaining segment lengths.
3. Repeat until the tip is close enough to the target.

FABRIK avoids angles entirely \u2014 it works purely with positions and segment lengths. This makes it fast and produces more natural poses than CCD.

```cpp
void SolveFABRIK(TArray<Vec3>& Joints, const TArray<float>& SegmentLengths,
                 const Vec3& Target, const Vec3& BasePosition, int MaxIterations = 10)
{
    int N = Joints.Num();
    if (N < 2) return;

    // Store base
    Vec3 Base = BasePosition;

    for (int Iter = 0; Iter < MaxIterations; ++Iter)
    {
        // --- FORWARD PASS: reach from end effector toward base ---
        Joints[N - 1] = Target;

        for (int i = N - 2; i >= 0; --i)
        {
            Vec3 Direction = (Joints[i + 1] - Joints[i]).GetSafeNormal();
            Joints[i] = Joints[i + 1] - Direction * SegmentLengths[i];
        }

        // --- BACKWARD PASS: reach from base toward end effector ---
        Joints[0] = Base;

        for (int i = 0; i < N - 1; ++i)
        {
            Vec3 Direction = (Joints[i + 1] - Joints[i]).GetSafeNormal();
            Joints[i + 1] = Joints[i] + Direction * SegmentLengths[i];
        }

        // Check convergence
        if (Vec3::Dist(Joints[N - 1], Target) < 0.01f)
            break;
    }
}
```

**FABRIK Pros & Cons:**
- \u2705 Produces more natural poses than CCD
- \u2705 Very fast \u2014 no trig functions
- \u2705 Angle constraints can be added (though trickier than CCD)
- \u2705 Handles multiple end effectors
- \u274c Slightly more complex to implement with joint limits

### How IK Drives Character Animation

**Foot IK:** When a character stands on uneven terrain, IK adjusts the legs so feet plant correctly on the ground. Without IK, feet would clip through slopes or float above them.

**Hand IK:** When a character reaches for a door handle, IK places the hand precisely on the handle. The animation just says \"reach toward handle area\" \u2014 IK does the fine positioning.

**Look-At IK:** The head and spine rotate so the character's eyes track a target (another character, an item, the camera).

**Full-Body IK (FBIK):** UE5's Full-Body IK solver handles complex multi-bone chains with constraints, used for climbing, vaulting, and environmental interactions.

```cpp
// UE5: Enabling IK on an animation blueprint
// In the AnimGraph, add an FABRIK node between the animation output and final pose.
// Set the Effector Transform to your target (e.g., hand socket on a weapon).

// Or programmatically:
// FABRIK node properties:
//   - EffectorTransform: where the end of the chain should be
//   - Precision: how close is \"close enough\" (default 1.0)
//   - MaxIterations: max FABRIK iterations (default 10)
//   - BoneChain: the chain of bones (e.g., \"clavicle_l\" \u2192 \"upperarm_l\" \u2192 \"lowerarm_l\" \u2192 \"hand_l\")
```

### game engine Connection: IK Rigs in game engines5

UE5's IK Rig system provides a non-destructive way to layer IK solvers:
- **IK Rig Asset:** Defines a skeleton's IK chain hierarchy, solvers, and goals
- **IK Retargeter:** Maps IK goals from one skeleton to another for animation retargeting
- **Solvers available:** FABRIK, CCD, Body Mover, Limb Solver, Polar Solver

The IK Rig can be applied at runtime (via Control Rig) or at authoring time (retargeting animations between skeletons).

---



> [!info] **Game Engine Connection**
> Every engine implements these concepts: Unity's Physics.Raycast, Godot's CollisionShape, Unreal's Box/Sphere/LineTrace. The math is identical — only the API wrapping changes. See [[../UE Math/Collision & Intersection Math]] and [[../UE Math/Curves, Ranges & Random]] for engine-specific implementations.
## Exercises

1. **Slerp degenerate case — the 180° flip:** Two quaternions q₀ and q₁ represent rotations 180° apart. Their dot product is -1. What happens to the slerp formula when cos(Ω) = -1? The `sin(Ω)` term in the denominator goes to zero — this is a genuine singularity. What is the correct behavior? (Hint: there are infinitely many shortest paths on the hypersphere when antipodal.) How does A game engine's `Quat::Slerp` handle this case?

2. **NLerp vs Slerp angular velocity:** Implement both nlerp (normalized lerp) and slerp for quaternions. For a 90° rotation between q₀ and q₁, measure the angular step per uniform Δt for both methods at t=0.1, t=0.5, and t=0.9. Which method has constant angular velocity? Explain why nlerp speeds up in the middle using the geometry of the chord vs the arc on the unit hypersphere.

3. **CCD convergence analysis:** In the CCD IK solver, each joint rotates to point the end effector toward the target. For a 3-joint chain (shoulder→elbow→wrist) with the target 100 units away, approximately how many iterations does CCD need to converge within 0.1 units? What factors affect convergence speed — joint count, target distance, initial pose? Why does CCD sometimes produce "corkscrew" poses where the elbow bends unnaturally?

4. **FABRIK constraint challenge:** The FABRIK implementation in the note does NOT include joint angle limits. Design a modification to enforce that the elbow cannot bend backward (angle between upper arm and forearm ≥ 0°). Your constraint should work within the position-based FABRIK framework without converting to angle space. Hint: after the forward pass, check if the elbow position is on the correct side of the shoulder-wrist line.

5. **IK solver selection for foot placement:** You're implementing foot IK for a character on uneven terrain. The hip is at (0, 80, 0), the foot target is at (30, 5, 20) on a sloped rock. The leg has upper leg = 40 units, lower leg = 38 units. Compare CCD and FABRIK for this scenario: (a) which converges faster to the target? (b) which produces a more natural-looking knee bend? (c) which is easier to constrain so the knee doesn't hyperextend? (d) if the character is running at 60 FPS, which algorithm's per-frame cost matters more — and why might you use a single iteration per frame instead of converging fully?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Slerp is the "fly the great circle route" of rotation blending. Regular lerp cuts through the inside of the rotation sphere — like digging a tunnel from New York to Tokyo instead of flying the arc. The tunnel is shorter in Euclidean distance but it exits the sphere's surface, producing invalid rotations with magnitude < 1. Nlerp (normalize after lerp) pushes the tunnel back to the surface but still doesn't follow the great circle — the motion speeds up in the middle like a car accelerating through a valley. Slerp stays on the surface at constant angular speed. IK is puppet math: CCD works joint-by-joint from the fingertip backward, each joint rotating to point at the target — simple but can produce weird elbow poses. FABRIK is the folding ruler trick — pull the tip to the target, pull the joints to maintain segment lengths, then pull the base back to its anchor, repeat. FABRIK feels more natural because it works with distances (not angles), like how you'd actually position a jointed arm.

### Technical
Slerp interpolates along the geodesic on S³ (the unit quaternion manifold): `slerp(q₀, q₁, t) = (sin((1-t)Ω)/sin(Ω))·q₀ + (sin(tΩ)/sin(Ω))·q₁` where cos(Ω) = q₀·q₁. When |cos(Ω)| > 0.9995, the denominator sin(Ω) → 0, so implementations fall back to nlerp. The double-cover issue (q and -q represent the same rotation) is resolved by negating one quaternion when the dot product is negative, ensuring the shorter arc. CCD (Cyclic Coordinate Descent) iteratively minimizes end-effector error by rotating each joint (from distal to proximal) using axis-angle rotation: axis = (ToEnd × ToTarget), angle = acos(ToEnd·ToTarget). CCD converges linearly; over-rotation of proximal joints produces unnatural poses. FABRIK (Forward And Backward Reaching IK) enforces distance constraints without computing angles: forward pass places the end effector at the target and adjusts proximal joints along the line to maintain segment lengths; backward pass anchors the base and readjusts distally. Convergence is typically faster than CCD, and the resulting poses are more natural because the algorithm distributes error across all joints rather than over-emphasizing distal ones. UE5's IK Rig system layers multiple solvers (FABRIK, CCD, Body Mover) with per-bone constraints for production-quality procedural animation.

## See Also

- [[Quaternions & 3D Rotations]] — Slerp uses quaternion math
- [[00 — Collision Detection Overview|Collision Detection]] — Kinematics feeds into collision response

01 \u2014 Skeletal Animation.content:
# Skeletal Animation

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> Every animated character in your game — the player, enemies, NPCs — is a skeleton driving a mesh. The skeleton is a hierarchy of bones (transforms). The mesh is a cloud of vertices. Skinning is the math that answers: given bone transforms, where does each vertex go? Linear Blend Skinning (LBS) is the industry default — fast, simple, GPU-friendly. But it has a notorious flaw: when a joint twists (like a wrist or shoulder), the mesh collapses inward — the "candy-wrapper effect." Dual quaternion skinning fixes this by treating each bone as a rigid transformation, eliminating volume collapse at the cost of ~2× the computation. This note covers the math behind both methods, the bone weight system, the bind pose, and what happens in the vertex shader every frame for every animated character.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[Matrices & Coordinate Systems]] — bone transforms are 4×4 matrices.
> [[Quaternions & 3D Rotations]] — quaternion interpolation and composition.
> [[../Rendering/02 — Barycentric Coordinates|Barycentric Coordinates]] — attribute interpolation across triangles.

---

## The Skeleton — A Hierarchy of Transforms

A skeleton is a tree of bones. Each bone is a 4×4 transform matrix relative to its parent. The root bone (pelvis/hips) is in model space.

```
Root (Pelvis)
 ├── Spine
 │    ├── Chest
 │    │    ├── Neck → Head
 │    │    ├── LeftShoulder → LeftArm → LeftForearm → LeftHand
 │    │    └── RightShoulder → RightArm → RightForearm → RightHand
 │    └── ...
 └── LeftHip → LeftLeg → LeftFoot
```

Each bone has:
- **Bind pose (rest pose):** the skeleton's default position — the pose the mesh was modeled in.
- **Current pose:** the animated pose — computed each frame from animation curves or physics.
- **Bone transform:** maps from bone-local space to model space in the current pose.
- **Inverse bind matrix:** maps from model space to bone-local space in the BIND pose.

---

## The Mesh — Vertices Tied to Bones

Each vertex is influenced by 1-4 bones (typically 4, controlled by `MAX_BONE_INFLUENCES`). For each influencing bone, the vertex stores:

```cpp
struct SkinnedVertex {
    float3 Position;   // In model space (bind pose)
    float3 Normal;
    float2 UV;

    uint8_t BoneIndices[4];   // Which bones influence this vertex
    float   BoneWeights[4];   // How much each bone influences (sum = 1.0)
};
```

Bone weights are painted by artists in tools like Maya/Blender. Red = strong influence, blue = weak, black = none.

---

## Linear Blend Skinning (LBS) — The Standard

For each vertex, compute the skinned position as a weighted blend of its position transformed by each bone:

```
v_skinned = Σ w_i · M_i · (IB_i · v_bind)
```

Where:
- v_bind: vertex position in model space (bind pose)
- IB_i: inverse bind matrix for bone i — transforms vertex from model space to bone-i-local space (in bind pose)
- M_i: current bone transform — transforms from bone-i-local space to model space (in current pose)
- w_i: bone weight for bone i (Σ w_i = 1)
- v_skinned: final vertex position in model space (current pose)

The combined matrix `M_i · IB_i` is the **skinning matrix** for bone i. It's pre-computed on the CPU, uploaded as a uniform array to the GPU.

### Vertex Shader Implementation

```hlsl
// GPU skinning in vertex shader (HLSL)
cbuffer BoneMatrices : register(b0) {
    float4x4 BoneTransforms[256];  // Pre-computed M_i · IB_i per bone
};

struct VSInput {
    float3 Position : POSITION;
    float3 Normal   : NORMAL;
    uint4  BoneIndices : BLENDINDICES;
    float4 BoneWeights : BLENDWEIGHT;
};

float4x4 SkinningMatrix(VSInput input) {
    float4x4 mat = 0;
    // Accumulate weighted bone transforms
    mat += input.BoneWeights.x * BoneTransforms[input.BoneIndices.x];
    mat += input.BoneWeights.y * BoneTransforms[input.BoneIndices.y];
    mat += input.BoneWeights.z * BoneTransforms[input.BoneIndices.z];
    mat += input.BoneWeights.w * BoneTransforms[input.BoneIndices.w];
    return mat;
}

VSOutput VSMain(VSInput input) {
    VSOutput output;
    float4x4 skinMat = SkinningMatrix(input);

    float4 skinnedPos = mul(float4(input.Position, 1.0), skinMat);
    output.Position = mul(skinnedPos, ViewProjection);

    // Transform normal (use inverse-transpose for correct normal under non-uniform scale)
    float3x3 skinMat3x3 = (float3x3)skinMat;
    output.Normal = normalize(mul(input.Normal, (float3x3)transpose(skinMat)));
    return output;
}
```

The GPU blends 4 weighted matrices per vertex. At 100,000 vertices × 60 FPS = 6 million matrix blends per second — trivially fast on modern hardware.

---

## The Candy-Wrapper Effect — Why LBS Fails

When a joint rotates around its axis (e.g., twisting a wrist), LBS interpolates the rotation linearly. Linear interpolation of rotation matrices does NOT preserve rigidity — intermediate points move INSIDE the joint, collapsing volume.

```
Bone A: rotated +45° around X
Bone B: rotated -45° around X (twist in opposite direction)

LBS: linearly blends the two rotation matrices
     → Result is a matrix with determinant < 1 (not a rigid rotation)
     → Vertices near the joint are SCALED DOWN → volume collapse

This is the candy-wrapper effect: the mesh pinches inward like a twisted candy wrapper.
Visual:     ||  becomes  )(  at the joint
```

The root cause: the space of rotation matrices (SO(3)) is NOT closed under addition. Adding two rotation matrices does not produce a rotation matrix. LBS adds weighted skinning matrices, and the result is not rigid.

---

## Dual Quaternion Skinning (DQS) — The Fix

A **dual quaternion** represents a rigid transformation (rotation + translation) as a single mathematical object. It is to rigid transforms what a quaternion is to rotations.

A dual quaternion is `Q = q_r + ε · q_d` where:
- q_r is a regular quaternion (the rotation)
- q_d is a dual quaternion (encoding translation: q_d = 0.5 · t · q_r, where t is the translation quaternion (0, x, y, z))
- ε² = 0 (dual unit — the algebraic trick)

### Converting a 4×4 Matrix to a Dual Quaternion

Given a rigid transform matrix (rotation R, translation t):

```cpp
struct DualQuaternion {
    Quat rotation;     // q_r — extract from rotation matrix
    Quat translation;  // q_d = 0.5 * (0, t.x, t.y, t.z) * q_r
};

DualQuaternion MatrixToDualQuat(const float4x4& M) {
    DualQuaternion dq;
    dq.rotation = Quat::FromMatrix(M);  // Standard matrix→quaternion extraction
    float3 t = M.GetTranslation();
    Quat tq(0, t.x, t.y, t.z);         // Translation as pure quaternion
    dq.translation = 0.5f * (tq * dq.rotation);
    return dq;
}
```

### Skin Blending with Dual Quaternions

Blend bone dual quaternions using the same weights as LBS, then normalize:

```cpp
DualQuaternion BlendDualQuats(const DualQuaternion* dqs, const float* weights, int count) {
    // Ensure consistent sign (quaternion double-cover issue)
    DualQuaternion base = dqs[0];
    if (dot(base.rotation, dqs[0].rotation) < 0) base = -base;

    DualQuaternion blended = weights[0] * base;
    for (int i = 1; i < count; i++) {
        DualQuaternion dq = dqs[i];
        // Flip sign if needed to take shortest path in quaternion space
        if (dot(base.rotation, dq.rotation) < 0) dq = -dq;
        blended.rotation += weights[i] * dq.rotation;
        blended.translation += weights[i] * dq.translation;
    }

    // Normalize: divide by length of the rotation quaternion
    float len = length(blended.rotation);
    blended.rotation /= len;
    blended.translation /= len;
    return blended;
}

float4x4 DualQuatToMatrix(const DualQuaternion& dq) {
    float4x4 M = dq.rotation.ToMatrix();  // Rotation part
    // Translation part
    Quat t = 2.0f * dq.translation * Conjugate(dq.rotation);
    M.SetTranslation(float3(t.x, t.y, t.z));
    return M;
}
```

### Why DQS Fixes the Candy-Wrapper Effect

Dual quaternions represent rigid transformations (rotation + translation). When you blend dual quaternions and normalize, the result is ALWAYS a rigid transformation (rotation + translation, no scale, no shear). The normalization step projects the blended result back onto the manifold of rigid transforms — the determinant is always 1, volume is always preserved.

**Cost:** DQS requires ~2× the computation of LBS (dual quaternion arithmetic vs matrix accumulation). For most game characters, the visual improvement at twisting joints (wrists, shoulders, ankles) justifies the cost.

---

## Comparison — LBS vs DQS

| Property | LBS (Linear Blend) | DQS (Dual Quaternion) |
|----------|-------------------|----------------------|
| Rigidity | ❌ Volume collapse at twists | ✅ Volume preserved |
| Computation | ~4 matrix blends per vertex | ~4 DQ blends + normalize |
| GPU cost | Low | ~2× LBS |
| Artifacts | Candy-wrapper, elbow collapse | Bulging near joint centers |
| UE default | Yes (standard skinning) | Optional (per-skeletal-mesh setting) |
| Support | All engines | UE5, Unity HDRP, custom engines |

UE5 supports both: choose per `USkeletalMesh` via the skinning method property. DQS is recommended for characters with significant joint twisting (realistic humanoids). LBS is fine for simple characters or when performance is critical.

---

## Bind Pose, Rest Pose, and Transforms

Understanding the coordinate spaces prevents 90% of skinning bugs:

- **Bind pose:** the skeleton pose at which the mesh was originally modeled and vertex weights were painted. This is the "reference" configuration.
- **Rest pose:** same as bind pose (some engines use different terms — UE uses "reference pose").
- **Inverse bind matrix (IB_i):** transforms a vertex FROM model space TO bone-local space, assuming the skeleton is in bind pose. This matrix is computed once at asset import and never changes.
- **Current bone transform (M_i):** the bone's current animated transform from bone-local to model space.

The skinning transform `M_i · IB_i` says: "take the vertex back to bone space (where it was modeled relative to bone i), then forward to where bone i is now."

---

## Engine Application — UE5 SkeletalMesh

```cpp
// UE5 skeletal mesh skinning (simplified pipeline):
// 1. Animation Blueprint evaluates animation curves → produces bone transforms (M_i)
// 2. USkeletalMeshComponent gathers bone transforms + inverse bind matrices
// 3. CPU computes skinning matrices: SkinMatrix[i] = M_i · IB_i
// 4. Uploads SkinMatrix[] array to GPU as a constant buffer (up to 256 bones)
// 5. Vertex shader (above) applies skinning per vertex

// UE5 supports both LBS and DQS:
// - LBS: default, fast, GPU-friendly
// - DQS: enabled via USkeletalMesh->SetSkinningMethod(ESkinningMethod::DualQuaternion)

// Bone influence limits:
// UE5 default: MAX_TOTAL_INFLUENCES = 8 (hardware), typically 4 per vertex
// Extra influences are dropped (lowest weights first) if > MAX_BONE_INFLUENCES
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Your game character is a puppet. The skeleton is the armature inside — a hierarchy of sticks (bones) connected by joints. The mesh is the rubber skin stretched over the armature. When you move the elbow joint, the skin near the elbow needs to stretch smoothly. The artist paints "this patch of skin belongs 70% to the upper arm bone and 30% to the forearm bone." At runtime, the GPU blends: "upper arm says go HERE, forearm says go THERE, so the skin goes 70% of the way." This is Linear Blend Skinning — simple but flawed. When the wrist twists, the blend of "rotate +45°" and "rotate -45°" mathematically produces a SHRUNKEN middle — the skin collapses inward like a twisted candy wrapper. Dual quaternion skinning fixes this by using a special kind of number (dual quaternion) that guarantees the blended result is always rigid — no shrinking, no collapsing. The tradeoff: ~2× more math per vertex, but wrists and shoulders look correct.

### Technical
Linear Blend Skinning computes the skinned vertex position as the weighted sum of skinning matrices: v' = Σ w_i · (M_i · IB_i) · v. The weighting is a linear combination in matrix space, but SO(3) (the rotation group) is not closed under addition — the blended matrix is not a rigid transform, causing volume collapse at twisting joints (candy-wrapper effect). Dual Quaternion Skinning converts each bone's rigid transform (rotation + translation) to a dual quaternion (q_r + ε·q_d, ε²=0), blends via weighted addition with sign-consistency handling, then normalizes (projects back onto the rigid transform manifold). The resulting transformation is always rigid — determinant 1, no volume loss. GPU cost is ~2× LBS due to dual quaternion arithmetic. UE5 supports both methods per-skeletal-mesh; DQS recommended for humanoid characters with significant joint rotation, LBS for performance-critical or rigid-mesh cases.

