01 \u2014 Frequency Domain & FFT.content:
# Frequency Domain & FFT

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> Audio in games is fundamentally about waves: a sound is a time-domain signal (air pressure over time → samples). But most audio processing — filtering, reverb, compression, pitch shifting, spectral analysis — happens in the **frequency domain**. The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) converts a time-domain signal into its frequency components. This is the algorithm behind: visualizing audio (spectrograms in Audacity/Wwise), convolution reverb (multiplying spectra), EQ filters (attenuating frequency bands), audio compression (MP3/AAC discard imperceptible frequencies), and voice chat noise suppression. Understanding the FFT means understanding what your audio middleware (Wwise, FMOD, MetaSounds) is doing under the hood.

---

## Complex Numbers — The Language of Frequency

Sound is real-valued (air pressure). But frequency analysis requires complex numbers:

```
z = a + bi, where i² = -1
```

A complex number can represent BOTH amplitude AND phase:
- **Euler's formula:** e^(iθ) = cos(θ) + i·sin(θ)
- A sinusoid of frequency f, amplitude A, phase φ: A · e^(i(2πft + φ))

Complex numbers make multiplication = rotation + scaling — ideal for representing sinusoidal components.

---

## The Discrete Fourier Transform (DFT)

The DFT converts N time-domain samples x[n] into N frequency-domain bins X[k]:

```
X[k] = Σ_{n=0}^{N-1} x[n] · e^(-i·2π·k·n / N)    for k = 0, 1, ..., N-1
```

- X[k]: complex number — magnitude = amplitude of frequency k, angle = phase
- k = 0: DC component (average value)
- k = 1 to N/2-1: positive frequencies
- k = N/2: Nyquist frequency (highest representable frequency = sample_rate/2)
- k > N/2: negative frequencies (mirror of positive, for real signals)

The inverse DFT reconstructs the original signal:
```
x[n] = (1/N) · Σ_{k=0}^{N-1} X[k] · e^(i·2π·k·n / N)
```

Direct DFT computation: O(N²) — 1,024 samples → 1,048,576 operations. Too slow for real-time audio.

---

## The Fast Fourier Transform (FFT) — Cooley-Tukey

The Cooley-Tukey FFT (1965, though known to Gauss in 1805) reduces DFT to O(N log N) by exploiting symmetry. The key insight: a DFT of size N can be expressed as two DFTs of size N/2 (even-indexed and odd-indexed samples):

```
X[k] = E[k] + W_N^k · O[k]
X[k+N/2] = E[k] - W_N^k · O[k]

where W_N = e^(-i·2π/N)  (the "twiddle factor")
E[k] = DFT of even-indexed samples
O[k] = DFT of odd-indexed samples
```

Apply recursively: divide each sub-DFT until reaching size 2 (butterfly operation). Depth = log₂(N).

```cpp
// Radix-2 DIT (Decimation In Time) FFT — simplified
void FFT(std::complex<float>* x, int N) {
    // Bit-reversal permutation
    for (int i = 0, j = 0; i < N; i++) {
        if (i < j) swap(x[i], x[j]);
        for (int bit = N >> 1; (j ^= bit) < bit; bit >>= 1);
    }

    // Butterfly stages
    for (int len = 2; len <= N; len <<= 1) {
        float angle = -2.0 * PI / len;
        std::complex<float> wlen(cos(angle), sin(angle));
        for (int i = 0; i < N; i += len) {
            std::complex<float> w(1, 0);
            for (int j = 0; j < len/2; j++) {
                std::complex<float> u = x[i + j];
                std::complex<float> v = x[i + j + len/2] * w;
                x[i + j] = u + v;
                x[i + j + len/2] = u - v;
                w *= wlen;  // Advance twiddle factor
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Performance: N=1024, DFT = 1,048,576 ops, FFT = 10,240 ops. **100× faster.** For N=4096 (common audio frame size): DFT = 16.7M ops, FFT = 98,304 ops. **170× faster.**

---

## From Waveform to Spectrogram

```cpp
// Spectrogram generation:
for (int frame = 0; frame < numFrames; frame++) {
    // Extract a window of samples
    float window[FFT_SIZE];
    for (int i = 0; i < FFT_SIZE; i++) {
        window[i] = audio[frame * HOP_SIZE + i] * HannWindow(i, FFT_SIZE);
    }

    // FFT
    std::complex<float> spectrum[FFT_SIZE];
    FFT(window, spectrum, FFT_SIZE);

    // Magnitude spectrum (discard phase for visualization)
    float magnitude[FFT_SIZE/2];
    for (int k = 0; k < FFT_SIZE/2; k++) {
        magnitude[k] = 20.0 * log10(abs(spectrum[k]) + 1e-10);  // dB scale
    }

    // magnitude[] is one vertical column of the spectrogram
    Spectrogram[frame] = magnitude;
}
```

- **Window function** (Hann, Hamming, Blackman): reduces spectral leakage from abrupt frame boundaries
- **Hop size:** frames overlap (typically 50-75%) for smooth temporal representation
- **Spectrogram:** 2D image — time on x-axis, frequency on y-axis, color = magnitude

---

## The Convolution Theorem — Why FFT Enables Fast Reverb

Convolution in the time domain equals multiplication in the frequency domain:

```
Time domain:   y[t] = x[t] ∗ h[t]                      (O(N²) — direct convolution)
Frequency:     Y[k] = X[k] · H[k]                       (O(N) — element-wise multiply)
               y[t] = IFFT(Y[k])                        (O(N log N) via FFT)
```

For reverb: `x[t]` = dry audio, `h[t]` = impulse response (recorded from a real space). Direct convolution of a 5-second reverb at 48 kHz = 240,000 × 240,000 operations per second. FFT convolution: FFT both (O(N log N)), multiply (O(N)), IFFT result (O(N log N)). **10,000× faster** — makes real-time convolution reverb possible.

```cpp
// Convolution reverb via FFT
void ApplyReverb(float* audio, int N, float* impulse, int M) {
    int fftSize = NextPowerOfTwo(N + M - 1);
    std::complex<float>* X = FFT(Pad(audio, fftSize));
    std::complex<float>* H = FFT(Pad(impulse, fftSize));
    for (int i = 0; i < fftSize; i++) X[i] *= H[i];
    IFFT(X, audio, N + M - 1);  // Result = dry signal convolved with room response
}
```

---

## Engine Application — UE MetaSounds and Wwise

```cpp
// UE5 MetaSounds: spectral analysis for real-time audio visualization
// FFT-based frequency analyzer (simplified):
void UMetaSoundFrequencyAnalyzer::ProcessAudio(const float* Samples, int NumSamples) {
    // Accumulate samples into FFT buffer
    // When buffer is full (e.g., 1024 samples):
    PerformFFT(FFTBuffer, Spectrum, FFT_SIZE);

    // Extract frequency bands (bass, mid, treble)
    float Bass = SumMagnitude(Spectrum, 20, 250);     // 20-250 Hz
    float Mid  = SumMagnitude(Spectrum, 250, 4000);   // 250-4000 Hz
    float High = SumMagnitude(Spectrum, 4000, 20000); // 4-20 kHz

    // Drive gameplay parameters from audio
    OnBassBeat.Broadcast(Bass > BassThreshold);
}
// This is how rhythm games sync gameplay to music, and visualizers pulse to the beat
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Sound is a squiggly line — air pressure over time. The Fourier Transform answers: "what pure tones make up this squiggle?" It takes your waveform and returns a bar chart — how much bass (low bars), how much midrange (middle bars), how much treble (high bars). The FFT is the fast version — it exploits mathematical symmetry to compute the same answer 100-1,000× faster. The convolution theorem is the magic that makes real-time reverb possible: applying a room's acoustic fingerprint to a sound normally requires millions of calculations per second. But in frequency-land, it's just one multiply per frequency bin. FFT → multiply → inverse FFT, and your dry sound is now in Carnegie Hall.

### Technical
The Discrete Fourier Transform converts N time samples x[n] to N frequency coefficients X[k] = Σ x[n]·e^(-i·2πkn/N), mapping to the complex plane where magnitude = amplitude and angle = phase. The Cooley-Tukey FFT reduces O(N²) to O(N log N) by recursive divide-and-conquer: even-indexed and odd-indexed DFTs are combined with twiddle factors in butterfly operations. Bit-reversal permutation reorders input for in-place computation. Real-time spectrograms apply a sliding window (Hann, 50-75% overlap) and FFT per frame. The convolution theorem (F{x∗h} = F{x}·F{h}) enables O(N log N) convolution via FFT→multiply→IFFT, making real-time convolution reverb computationally feasible. UE MetaSounds uses FFT-based frequency analysis for audio-driven gameplay events (rhythm games, visualizers).

