03 \u2014 Network Interpolation.content:
# Network Interpolation

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> In a multiplayer game, you receive player positions not every frame, but every 50-100 ms (tick rate 10-20 Hz). Rendering at 60 FPS means 3-6 frames where you have NO new data. Without interpolation, characters teleport — snapping from one received position to the next. With interpolation, you blend between the last two known positions, smoothing the motion. Without prediction, your own character feels laggy — input → send to server → server processes → response → render, 50-100 ms round trip. With client-side prediction, you simulate your own movement locally, then reconcile with the server's authoritative state. Without dead reckoning, disconnected players freeze instantly. This note covers the math that makes multiplayer feel responsive despite the fundamental latency of light-speed-limited networks.

---

## The Problem — Discrete Updates at Low Tick Rates

```
Server tick rate: 20 Hz → 50 ms between updates
Client render: 60 FPS → 16.7 ms per frame

Timeline (ms):  0    16   33   50   66   83   100
Server state:   P0 ═══════════ P1 ═══════════ P2
Client frames:  F0  F1  F2  F3  F4  F5  F6
                 ↑              ↑              ↑
                 Receives P0    Receives P1    Receives P2

Problem: What position does the client render at F1, F2, F3, F4, F5 when only P0 and P1 are known?
Solution: Interpolate between P0 and P1 based on elapsed time.
```

---

## Linear Interpolation — The Simplest Smoothing

```cpp
float3 InterpolatePosition(float3 prevPos, float3 nextPos, uint32_t prevTime, uint32_t nextTime, uint32_t renderTime) {
    float t = float(renderTime - prevTime) / float(nextTime - prevTime);
    t = clamp(t, 0.0f, 1.0f);
    return lerp(prevPos, nextPos, t);
}
```

The client renders the past — interpolation means the displayed position is always ~50-100 ms behind the server's "true" position. This is acceptable for other players (you can't perceive 50 ms delay in their movement), but NOT for your own character.

---

## Hermite Interpolation — Smoothing with Velocity

Linear interpolation produces constant velocity between updates — sudden direction changes at each received packet. Hermite (cubic) interpolation smooths the curve using the velocity at each endpoint:

```cpp
float3 HermiteInterpolate(float3 p0, float3 v0, float3 p1, float3 v1, float t) {
    float t2 = t * t;
    float t3 = t2 * t;

    // Hermite basis functions
    float h00 = 2*t3 - 3*t2 + 1;  // Position at p0
    float h10 = t3 - 2*t2 + t;     // Tangent at p0
    float h01 = -2*t3 + 3*t2;      // Position at p1
    float h11 = t3 - t2;            // Tangent at p1

    return h00 * p0 + h10 * v0 + h01 * p1 + h11 * v1;
}
```

The velocity at each point should be sent by the server (preferred) or estimated from adjacent position updates: v₁ = (p₁ - p₀) / Δt. Hermite interpolation produces C¹-continuous motion — no sudden direction changes — at the cost of slightly more computation and bandwidth for velocity data.

---

## Client-Side Prediction — Make Your Own Character Responsive

Your local input must feel instant. Send input to the server, but don't wait for the response — simulate the result locally:

```
1. Player presses W (move forward)
2. Client IMMEDIATELY moves character forward (local prediction)
3. Client sends input to server: "I pressed W at tick 1042"
4. Server processes, sends back: "At tick 1042, your position was (X, Y, Z)"
5. Client receives server state (50 ms later)
6. Client compares predicted position vs server-authoritative position
7. If mismatch: rewind, reapply inputs from the mismatch point, interpolate
```

```cpp
struct Move {
    uint32_t tick;
    float forward, right;  // Input axes
    float deltaTime;
};

// Client stores a ring buffer of recent inputs
std::deque<Move> InputBuffer;

void OnServerStateReceived(const ServerState& state) {
    // Find the input the server processed
    auto it = std::find_if(InputBuffer.begin(), InputBuffer.end(),
        [&](const Move& m) { return m.tick == state.LastProcessedTick; });

    if (it != InputBuffer.end()) {
        // Compare prediction vs server
        float3 error = PredictedPosition - state.Position;
        if (length(error) > RECONCILE_THRESHOLD) {
            // Rewind to the server state...
            CurrentPosition = state.Position;
            // Re-apply all inputs since that tick
            for (auto next = it + 1; next != InputBuffer.end(); ++next) {
                CurrentPosition += ComputeMovement(*next);
            }
        }
        // Clean up processed inputs
        InputBuffer.erase(InputBuffer.begin(), it + 1);
    }
}
```

This is how UE's `UCharacterMovementComponent` implements client prediction in `PerformMovement()` and `ClientUpdatePositionAfterServerUpdate()`.

---

## Dead Reckoning — When Packets Stop Arriving

If a player disconnects or packets are lost for an extended period, you can't just freeze them. Dead reckoning extrapolates their motion assuming constant velocity (or acceleration):

```cpp
float3 DeadReckon(float3 lastPos, float3 lastVel, float3 lastAccel, float dt) {
    // Constant velocity: pos + vel * dt
    // Constant acceleration: pos + vel*dt + 0.5*accel*dt²
    return lastPos + lastVel * dt + 0.5f * lastAccel * dt * dt;
}
```

After some timeout (typically 1-2 seconds of no updates), stop dead reckoning and either freeze or interpolate to a "disconnected" state. UE handles this through `UNetConnection` timeout and `APlayerController` cleanup.

---

## Jitter Buffering — Smoothing Network Irregularity

Network packets don't arrive at perfectly regular intervals. Jitter is the variance in inter-arrival time. A **jitter buffer** queues incoming packets and delays playback by a fixed amount, smoothing out the variance:

```
Packets arrive:    P0 (t=0)   P1 (t=47ms) P2 (t=55ms) P3 (t=98ms)
Jitter = |47-50|=3, |55-50|=5, |98-50|=48 (spike!)

Without buffer: render P0 at t=0, P1 at t=50 (3ms late→extrapolate), P3 at t=100 (2ms late)
With 30ms buffer: queue P0, render at t=30; queue P1, render at t=80; etc.
Result: smooth playback, +30ms constant added latency
```

The buffer size is a tradeoff: larger = smoother but more latency. Adaptive jitter buffers dynamically resize based on measured jitter. UE's networking layer (`UNetDriver`, `FNetworkPredictionData`) implements jitter management internally.

---

## Clock Synchronization — Agreeing on "Now"

For interpolation to work, client and server must agree on what time "tick 1042" refers to. Network Time Protocol (NTP) synchronizes clocks over the network:

```
Client → Server: local time t1
Server receives at: server time t2
Server responds at: server time t3
Client receives at: local time t4

Round-trip time: RTT = (t4 - t1) - (t3 - t2)
Clock offset:    offset = ((t2 - t1) + (t3 - t4)) / 2

Client adjusts: synchronized_time = local_time + offset
```

Simpler approach for games: use the server's tick counter as the authoritative timeline. All events are timestamped with the server tick. The client maps its render time to server ticks:

```cpp
uint32_t ServerTickForRenderTime(float renderTime) {
    return lastKnownServerTick + (renderTime - lastKnownTickRenderTime) * TickRate;
}
```

UE's `UNetDriver::ServerTime` and `UWorld::TimeSeconds` synchronization uses this approach.

---

## UE CharacterMovement Prediction

```cpp
// Simplified UE5 client prediction flow:
void UCharacterMovementComponent::TickComponent(float DeltaTime) {
    if (IsLocallyControlled()) {
        // 1. Build move from input
        FSavedMove_Character* Move = BuildMove(DeltaTime);

        // 2. Perform movement locally (prediction)
        PerformMovement(DeltaTime);

        // 3. Send to server
        ServerMove(Move->TimeStamp, Move->Acceleration, Move->SavedLocation, ...);

        // 4. Save in buffer for reconciliation
        SavedMoves.Push(Move);
    }
}

void UCharacterMovementComponent::ServerMove_Implementation(...) {
    // Server: authoritative movement
    PerformMovement(DeltaTime);

    // Send corrected position back
    ClientAdjustPosition(TimeStamp, NewLoc, NewVel, ...);
}

void UCharacterMovementComponent::ClientAdjustPosition_Implementation(...) {
    // Client: reconcile prediction with server state
    if (Mismatch) {
        // Rewind and replay
        ClientUpdatePositionAfterServerUpdate();
    }
}
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Multiplayer is a game of telephone with a 50 ms delay. The server is the only one who knows the "true" game state — it's the referee. Your client receives position updates for other players every 50 ms. Between updates (3-6 frames), you guess where they are by interpolating between their last two known positions — like connecting dots with a smooth line. For your own character, you can't wait 50 ms — you'd feel drunk. So you predict locally: "I pressed W, so I should be 2 meters forward." Later, the server says "actually, you tripped on a rock and you're 1.8 meters forward." You reconcile the 0.2m error smoothly. Dead reckoning is the "keep flying in a straight line" assumption when the telephone line goes dead. Jitter buffering is a waiting room that holds arriving messages for 30 ms so they come out at a steady pace instead of in bursts.

### Technical
Linear interpolation between received positions (lerp with t based on render time relative to packet timestamps) provides C⁰-continuous motion at the cost of a ~50-100 ms render-behind latency. Hermite interpolation uses endpoint velocities for C¹-continuous curves. Client-side prediction simulates local input immediately, stores input history, and reconciles against server-authoritative state on receipt by rewinding and replaying unacknowledged inputs. Dead reckoning extrapolates with constant velocity/acceleration during packet loss, with a timeout before freezing. Jitter buffers introduce fixed playback delay to absorb packet arrival variance; adaptive buffers resize dynamically. Clock synchronization via NTP round-trip measurement (RTT/2 symmetry assumption) or server tick timestamping. UE's `UCharacterMovementComponent` implements all of these in `PerformMovement()`, `ServerMove()`, and `ClientAdjustPosition()`.

## See Also

