01 \u2014 Multivectors, Products & Rotor.content:
### Analogy: The Two-Part Handshake

When two people meet, the handshake has two parts: the **squeeze** (symmetric \u2014 both hands apply the same pressure) and the **twist** (antisymmetric \u2014 one hand rotates the other). The geometric product is the mathematical handshake: it combines the symmetric dot product (the squeeze) with the antisymmetric wedge product (the twist) in one operation.

For vectors a and b:

$$ab = a \\cdot b + a \\wedge b$$

- **a \u00b7 b** (dot product) is the **symmetric** part: scalar, measures how parallel they are
- **a \u2227 b** (wedge product) is the **antisymmetric** part: bivector, measures how perpendicular they are and defines the plane they span

> [!note] This Is NOT Just Notation
> The geometric product of two vectors produces a **multivector**: a scalar PLUS a bivector. Just like a complex number has a real part and an imaginary part: z = a + bi. The scalar is the \"real\" part, the bivector is the \"imaginary\" part. This is why complex numbers ARE the even subalgebra of 2D GA.

### Recovering Dot and Wedge from the Geometric Product

```cpp
// Dot product: symmetric part
float dot = 0.5f * (a * b + b * a);  // grade-0 part of geometric product

// Wedge product: antisymmetric part
Bivector wedge = 0.5f * (a * b - b * a);  // grade-2 part of geometric product
```

In 3D, the wedge product of two vectors is a bivector with 3 components (e\u2081\u2082, e\u2081\u2083, e\u2082\u2083):

$$a \\wedge b = (a_1b_2 - a_2b_1)e_{12} + (a_1b_3 - a_3b_1)e_{13} + (a_2b_3 - a_3b_2)e_{23}$$

Notice: the coefficients look EXACTLY like the cross product components! The wedge product IS the cross product, but without the artificial restriction to 3D.

### Geometric Product Examples

```cpp
// Example GA multiplication in 3D
struct Vec3 { float e1, e2, e3; };
struct Bivec3 { float e12, e13, e23; };
struct Rotor3 { float s; float e12, e13, e23; }; // even subalgebra = quaternion!

void GeometricProduct(const Vec3& a, const Vec3& b,
                      float& out_scalar, Bivec3& out_bivector)
{
    // Dot product (grade 0)
    out_scalar = a.e1 * b.e1 + a.e2 * b.e2 + a.e3 * b.e3;

    // Wedge product (grade 2) \u2014 these ARE the cross product components!
    out_bivector.e12 = a.e1 * b.e2 - a.e2 * b.e1;  // \"z\" of cross product
    out_bivector.e13 = a.e1 * b.e3 - a.e3 * b.e1;  // \"y\" of cross product
    out_bivector.e23 = a.e2 * b.e3 - a.e3 * b.e2;  // \"x\" of cross product
}
```

---

### Analogy: The Expanding Broom

A single vector is a broomstick \u2014 it sweeps a line. Two vectors that aren't parallel sweep out a parallelogram area as one \"slides\" along the other \u2014 that's the wedge product. Three vectors sweep out a parallelepiped volume. The wedge product builds higher-dimensional \"oriented extents\" from lower-dimensional ones. It's like extruding a shape into a higher dimension.

### Formal Definition

The wedge product is:
- **Associative:** (a \u2227 b) \u2227 c = a \u2227 (b \u2227 c)
- **Anticommutative:** a \u2227 b = -(b \u2227 a)
- **Distributive:** a \u2227 (b + c) = a \u2227 b + a \u2227 c
- **Bilinear:** (\u03b1a) \u2227 b = \u03b1(a \u2227 b)

### Geometric Meaning

| Expression | Geometric Meaning | Magnitude |
|-----------|-------------------|-----------|
| a \u2227 b | Oriented parallelogram spanned by a and b | |a||b|sin(\u03b8) |
| a \u2227 b = 0 | a and b are parallel (collinear) | \u2014 |
| a \u2227 b \u2227 c | Oriented parallelepiped spanned by a, b, c | |det([a b c])| |
| a \u2227 b \u2227 c = 0 | a, b, c are coplanar | \u2014 |

### Why Wedge Is More Powerful Than Cross Product

```cpp
// Cross product: ONLY works in 3D, returns a vector
Vec3 Cross3D = Vec3::CrossProduct(A, B);

// Wedge product: works in ANY dimension, returns a bivector
// 2D: wedge product of two 2D vectors is a scalar (signed area)
// 3D: wedge product of two 3D vectors is a bivector (3 components)
// 4D: wedge product of two 4D vectors is a bivector (6 components)
```

The cross product is the **Hodge dual** of the wedge product in exactly 3 dimensions. GA makes this explicit: a \u00d7 b = (a \u2227 b)* = (a \u2227 b) \u00b7 I\u207b\u00b9, where I is the pseudoscalar. This is why the cross product doesn't generalize to higher dimensions while the wedge product does.

### Visual Description: Building Up Grades

```
Step 1: Vector a \u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2192

Step 2: a \u2227 b (b swept along a)
        b \u2191
          \u2502  \u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510
          \u2502  \u2502area\u2502  \u2190 oriented parallelogram
          \u2502  \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518
          \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2192 a

Step 3: (a \u2227 b) \u2227 c (parallelogram swept along c)
           \u250c\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2510
          /\u2502        /\u2502
         / \u2502 volume/ \u2502  \u2190 oriented parallelepiped
        /  \u2502      /  \u2502
        \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518  /
         \u2502  /     \u2502 /
         \u2502 /      \u2502/
         \u2514\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2500\u2518
```

