# PGA & Applications

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Geometric Algebra Overview|Geometric Algebra]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[01 — Multivectors, Products & Rotors]].


### Analogy: The Camera Projection

When you take a photo, the 3D world is projected onto a 2D image plane. Points become pixels, lines in space become lines on the photo, and parallel lines (like railroad tracks) appear to meet at a vanishing point. **Projective Geometric Algebra** formalizes this: it adds one extra dimension so that **everything** \u2014 points, lines, AND planes \u2014 are represented as algebraic elements in the same algebra. The \"meet\" (intersection) of a line and a plane is literally their wedge product. The \"join\" (connection) of two points to make a line is also a wedge product. Everything is unified.

### PGA in a Nutshell

PGA models 3D Euclidean geometry using a 4D algebra where the 4th basis vector e\u2080 satisfies e\u2080\u00b2 = 0 (it's a null vector, representing the origin/translation direction).

In PGA (specifically the \"plane-based\" or \"dual\" PGA):

| Geometric Entity | PGA Representation | Grade |
|-----------------|-------------------|-------|
| Plane | 1-vector (4 components) | 1 |
| Line | 2-vector / bivector (6 components) | 2 |
| Point | 3-vector / trivector (4 components) | 3 |

> [!note] Points as Trivectors
> In PGA, a point is NOT a vector \u2014 it's a trivector! This is one of the mind-bending things about GA. A point is the intersection of three planes, represented algebraically as the wedge product of those three planes. This makes sense: you define a point by the three orthogonal planes that intersect there (x=?, y=?, z=?).

### PGA Operations as Products

The beauty of PGA: every geometric operation is just one algebraic product.

| Geometric Operation | Algebraic Operation |
|-------------------|-------------------|
| Join two points to make a line | L = P\u2081 \u2227 P\u2082 (wedge / outer product) |
| Join three points to make a plane | \u03a0 = P\u2081 \u2227 P\u2082 \u2227 P\u2083 |
| Meet (intersect) a line and a plane | P = L \u2228 \u03a0 (vee / regressive product) |
| Reflect a point in a plane | P' = \u03a0 P \u03a0\u207b\u00b9 (sandwich product) |
| Rotate around a line | P' = R P R\u0303 (sandwich with rotor) |
| Translate along a direction | P' = T P T\u0303 (sandwich with translator) |
| Distance between points | d = \u2016P\u2081 \u2228 P\u2082\u2016 |
| Project point onto plane | P_proj = (P \u00b7 \u03a0) \u03a0\u207b\u00b9 |

### Ray Casting in PGA

Traditional ray-plane intersection requires solving the parametric ray equation against the plane equation. In PGA, it's literally one operation:

```
Ray-Plane Intersection in PGA:
Given: Ray as a line L (join of origin point and direction point)
Given: Plane \u03a0 (1-vector)
Intersection point P = L \u2228 \u03a0  (the \"meet\" / regressive product)
```

```cpp
// Hypothetical PGA C++ code for ray-plane intersection
PGA_Point RayPlaneIntersection(const PGA_Line& Ray, const PGA_Plane& Plane)
{
    return Meet(Ray, Plane);  // single operation!
    // Equivalent to: regressive_product(Ray, Plane)
}
```

### Collision Detection in PGA

The distance and containment tests become algebraic:

```cpp
// Is a point inside a sphere?
// Sphere in PGA: a 4-vector (grade-1 \"plane\" in 4D PGA)
// Actually, in conformal GA (CGA), spheres are vectors
// In PGA, distance between two points:
float Distance(const PGA_Point& A, const PGA_Point& B)
{
    return Math::Abs(Meet(A, B).norm());
}

// Point-plane distance (signed)
float SignedDistance(const PGA_Point& P, const PGA_Plane& Plane)
{
    return Dot(P, Plane);  // dot product of a trivector and a vector
}
```

### Translation as a Rotor (in PGA)

One of the most beautiful features of PGA: **translations are rotors**. Just as a standard rotor rotates around the origin, a \"translator\" rotates around the plane at infinity. This means you can interpolate translations smoothly with the same slerp you use for rotations:

```cpp
// Translator: rotates by \"distance\" in the plane at infinity
PGA_Motor Translate(const Vec3& Direction, float Distance)
{
    // In PGA, a translator has the form: 1 - (distance/2) * d \u2227 e\u2080
    // where d is the direction and e\u2080 is the origin basis vector
    return PGA_Motor::Translator(Direction, Distance);
}

// Compose rotation and translation into a single \"motor\"
PGA_Motor Transform = Translate(Pos) * Rotate(Axis, Angle);
// Apply with ONE sandwich product:
PGA_Point Transformed = Transform * Point * Transform.Reverse();
```

**Motors** are the PGA generalization of dual quaternions \u2014 they represent rigid body transforms (rotation + translation) in a single unified object.

### Visual Description: PGA in Action

```
Traditional 3D math:
  Point = (x, y, z)          \u2190 3 numbers
  Plane = (nx, ny, nz, d)    \u2190 4 numbers with constraint
  Line = 6 Pl\u00fccker coords    \u2190 6 numbers with constraint
  Ray cast = solve P = O + tD \u2192 messy algebra

PGA:
  Point = trivector (4 components)
  Plane = vector (4 components)
  Line = bivector (6 components)
  Ray cast = L \u2228 \u03a0  (one product!)

  Everything lives in the same 16-dimensional multivector space,
  and every operation is the geometric/regressive product.
```

---

### 1. Unified Transform Pipeline

Instead of managing separate translation vectors, rotation quaternions, and scale matrices, use motors:

```cpp
struct Motor
{
    // PGA motor: scalar + 6 bivectors = 8 components
    // (isomorphic to dual quaternion)
    float s, e01, e02, e03, e12, e13, e23, e0123;

    // Compose two motors (geometric product)
    Motor operator*(const Motor& Other) const;

    // Apply to a point
    PGAPoint Transform(const PGAPoint& P) const;

    // Interpolate smoothly
    static Motor Slerp(const Motor& A, const Motor& B, float t);
};
```

### 2. Ray Casting and Picking

```cpp
// Build a ray from mouse click
PGAPoint CameraPoint = CameraPosition();
PGAPoint FarPoint = ScreenToWorld(MouseX, MouseY, 1.0f);
PGALine Ray = Join(CameraPoint, FarPoint);  // Wedge product

// Intersect with scene geometry
for (auto& Plane : GeometryPlanes)
{
    PGAPoint Hit = Meet(Ray, Plane);
    if (IsValid(Hit))
        Hits.Add(Hit);
}
```

### 3. Collision Detection

PGA can express containment tests cleanly \u2014 especially useful for convex hulls and polyhedral collision:

```cpp
// Is point inside a convex polyhedron? (defined by its bounding planes)
bool PointInsidePolyhedron(const PGAPoint& P, const TArray<PGAPlane>& Planes)
{
    for (const auto& Plane : Planes)
    {
        if (Dot(P, Plane) > 0)  // Point is outside this plane
            return false;
    }
    return true;  // Inside all half-planes \u2192 inside polyhedron
}
```

### 4. Skeletal Animation

The motor (rotation + translation) is a perfect representation for bone transforms:

```cpp
struct BoneTransform
{
    Motor Transform;  // Rigid transform as a single GA object

    // Interpolate between two bone poses
    static BoneTransform Blend(const BoneTransform& A, const BoneTransform& B, float Alpha)
    {
        BoneTransform Result;
        Result.Transform = Motor::Slerp(A.Transform, B.Transform, Alpha);
        return Result;
    }
};
```

This is more elegant than decomposing into translation Slerp + rotation Lerp separately \u2014 one unified interpolation.

### 5. Reflection and Mirror Effects

```cpp
// Reflect a point across a plane in PGA (one line!)
PGAPoint Reflect(const PGAPoint& P, const PGAPlane& Mirror)
{
    // Sandwich product with plane: \u03a0 P \u03a0
    return Mirror * P * Mirror;
}
```

---



> [!info] **Game Engine Connection**
> Every engine implements these concepts: Unity's Physics.Raycast, Godot's CollisionShape, Unreal's Box/Sphere/LineTrace. The math is identical — only the API wrapping changes. See [[../UE Math/Collision & Intersection Math]] and [[../UE Math/Curves, Ranges & Random]] for engine-specific implementations.
## Exercises

1. **PGA ray-plane intersection verification:** In PGA, a ray L = P_camera ∧ P_far (join of two points) and a plane Π (1-vector). The intersection is P = L ∨ Π (meet/regressive product). For the traditional approach, you'd solve `(O + tD)·n = d` → `t = (d - O·n)/(D·n)`. For the specific case: camera at (0,0,0), looking toward (1,0,0), plane x=5 (normal pointing left, so n=(-1,0,0), d=-5). Compute the intersection point using BOTH methods. Verify they match. What PGA basis elements encode the plane x=5? (Hint: a plane is a 1-vector in PGA with components for e₀, e₁, e₂, e₃.)

2. **Motor interpolation vs separate lerp+slerp:** A rigid transform combines translation (3, 0, 0) and rotation (90° around Z). Encode this as a PGA motor. Now interpolate from identity to this transform at t=0.5 using motor slerp. Separately, interpolate using `Lerp(pos, (3,0,0), 0.5)` and `Slerp(identity_quat, q_90z, 0.5)`. Do the results match? Why might motor interpolation produce a more natural-looking halfway pose for a character's arm reaching toward a target?

3. **Point-in-polyhedron PGA test:** The note's `PointInsidePolyhedron` tests if `Dot(P, Plane) ≤ 0` for all bounding planes. For a unit cube centered at origin: write the 6 planes as PGA 1-vectors. For point P = (0.5, 0.5, 0.5) (inside) and Q = (2, 0, 0) (outside), compute the dot product with each plane. Verify the test. What does `Dot(P, Plane) > 0` mean geometrically — which side of the plane is the point on?

4. **PGA reflect in one line:** The note shows reflection across a plane: `P' = Π P Π`. How would you reflect a point across a LINE using PGA? (Hint: a line L is a bivector. The reflection across a line is a 180° rotation around that line — which in GA is the sandwich with the line itself.) What algebraic property of bivectors makes `L P L` a 180° rotation rather than a reflection?

5. **Implement PGA Join operation:** The join of two points to form a line is `L = P₁ ∧ P₂` (wedge/outer product). If points in PGA are trivectors, what grade is their wedge product? A line in PGA has 6 components (Plücker coordinates). Given two points in standard 3D coordinates — P₁=(1,0,0) and P₂=(0,2,0) — convert them to PGA trivectors, compute the join, and extract the 6 Plücker coordinates. Verify that the direction component is (P₂-P₁) = (-1, 2, 0) and the moment component is P₁ × P₂.

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
PGA (Projective Geometric Algebra) is the "everything is a sandwich" upgrade to traditional 3D math. In regular math, a point is 3 numbers, a line is 6 numbers with a weird constraint, a plane is 4 numbers, and every operation uses different formulas. In PGA, everything lives in the same 16-dimensional space. A point is the intersection of three planes (so it's a trivector — the volume they mutually carve out). A line is the join of two points (wedge them together — bam, a bivector line). A plane is a 1-vector. Ray-plane intersection? One operation: `L ∨ Π` (the "meet"). Point inside a box? `Dot(P, Plane) ≤ 0` for all six planes. Translation is a rotor, rotation is a rotor, and you can combine them into one "motor" that does both in a single sandwich. Need to smoothly move AND rotate? Slerp the motor — one interpolation instead of separate lerp and slerp. It's the grand unification of rigid body math.

### Technical
Projective Geometric Algebra (PGA) models 3D Euclidean geometry in a 4D degenerate Clifford algebra Cl(3,0,1) where the added basis vector e₀ satisfies e₀² = 0 (null vector representing the ideal point at the origin, encoding translation). Entities are grade-inverted relative to standard GA: planes are 1-vectors, lines are 2-vectors (bivectors), points are 3-vectors (trivectors — the intersection wedge of three planes). The join (∧/outer product) creates higher-grade entities from lower: P₁∧P₂ = line through two points, P₁∧P₂∧P₃ = plane through three points. The meet (∨/regressive product) computes intersections: L ∨ Π = point where line meets plane. A motor M (even-grade, 8 components) represents a rigid body motion (rotation + translation) and acts via the sandwich product: P' = M P M̃. Motor composition uses the geometric product; motor interpolation uses slerp — unifying what traditionally requires separate lerp (position) and slerp (orientation). PGA motors are isomorphic to dual quaternions. The PGA framework reduces dozens of special-case formulas to a handful of algebraic products, all operating on the same 16-component multivector type.

