01 \u2014 A Star & Pathfinding.content:
# A* & Pathfinding

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]]

---

## Why

An NPC needs to walk from A to B without walking through walls. Pathfinding solves this: given a graph of walkable areas, find the shortest path. A* (A-star) is the standard algorithm — used by every game engine for AI navigation. Understanding it means understanding how your NPCs find their way.

**Engine use:** UE Navigation System, Unity NavMesh, Godot Navigation.

---

## The Problem — Graph Search

Convert the world to a graph: nodes = walkable positions, edges = direct connections with cost (distance).

```
Grid (8-connected):
. . . . . .     . = walkable
. # # # . .     # = wall
. . S . # .     S = start
. # . . # .     G = goal
. # # . # G
```

Each walkable cell connects to its 8 neighbors (orthogonal + diagonal). Diagonal cost is √2 ≈ 1.414× orthogonal cost.

---

## Dijkstra's Algorithm — The Foundation

Dijkstra finds the shortest path to EVERY node from the start. A* finds the shortest path to ONE node (the goal) by using a heuristic to prioritize.

```cpp
// Dijkstra: expand cheapest unvisited node
struct Node {
    float gCost;  // cost from start to this node
    Vec2i parent;  // previous node on best path
    bool visited;
};

void Dijkstra(Grid& grid, Vec2i start, Vec2i goal) {
    PriorityQueue<Vec2i, float> open;  // min-heap by cost
    open.Push(start, 0);

    while (!open.Empty()) {
        Vec2i current = open.Pop();
        if (current == goal) break;  // found!

        for (Vec2i neighbor : GetNeighbors(grid, current)) {
            float newCost = nodes[current].gCost + Cost(current, neighbor);
            if (newCost < nodes[neighbor].gCost) {
                nodes[neighbor].gCost = newCost;
                nodes[neighbor].parent = current;
                open.Push(neighbor, newCost);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

Dijkstra explores in all directions equally — wastes time exploring AWAY from the goal.

---

## A* — The Game Changer

A* adds a **heuristic** h(n) — estimated cost from node n to goal. The priority is f(n) = g(n) + h(n):

```cpp
float Heuristic(Vec2i a, Vec2i b) {
    // Octile distance (for 8-direction grid):
    float dx = Abs(a.x - b.x);
    float dy = Abs(a.y - b.y);
    return Max(dx, dy) + (1.414f - 1.0f) * Min(dx, dy);
    // Or simply Euclidean: Sqrt(dx*dx + dy*dy)
}

void AStar(Grid& grid, Vec2i start, Vec2i goal) {
    PriorityQueue<Vec2i, float> open;
    open.Push(start, Heuristic(start, goal));
    nodes[start].gCost = 0;

    while (!open.Empty()) {
        Vec2i current = open.Pop();
        if (current == goal) break;

        for (Vec2i neighbor : GetNeighbors(grid, current)) {
            float newG = nodes[current].gCost + Cost(current, neighbor);
            if (newG < nodes[neighbor].gCost) {
                nodes[neighbor].gCost = newG;
                nodes[neighbor].parent = current;
                float f = newG + Heuristic(neighbor, goal);
                open.Push(neighbor, f);
            }
        }
    }

    // Reconstruct path: follow parent pointers from goal to start
    vector<Vec2i> path;
    for (Vec2i p = goal; p != start; p = nodes[p].parent)
        path.push_back(p);
    path.push_back(start);
    Reverse(path);
}
```

**Why A* is faster:** The heuristic pulls exploration toward the goal. If h(n) = 0, A* becomes Dijkstra. If h(n) is EXACT (no obstacles), A* goes straight to the goal without exploring anything else.

**Heuristic must be admissible:** h(n) ≤ actual cost to goal. Otherwise A* might miss the optimal path.

---

## Beyond Grids — Navigation Meshes

A grid is simple but wasteful — 99% of cells are empty air. Navmeshes represent walkable SURFACES as polygons:

```
Polygon graph (navmesh):
  ┌────┬────┐     Nodes = convex polygons (walkable)
  │ A  │ B  │     Edges = shared boundaries (neighbors)
  ├────┼────┤     Cost = distance between polygon centers
  │ C  │ D  │
  └────┴────┘
```

A* on a navmesh works identically — just the graph is polygon adjacency, not grid adjacency. Path smoothing (string pulling) straightens the A* output to avoid zigzagging.

---

## Path Smoothing — Funnel Algorithm

A* produces a path through polygon centers — jagged. The funnel algorithm finds the shortest path through the corridor of polygons:

```
A* path:    ●────●────●  (jagged)
Funnel:     ●──────────●  (straight line through corridor)
```

UE applies this automatically. The result is a natural-looking path hugging corners tightly.

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE Navigation:** `UNavigationSystemV1`, navmesh generation (Recast/Detour), `AIController::MoveTo()`, path smoothing built-in
- **Unity:** NavMeshAgent, NavMesh.SamplePosition, automatic pathfinding
- **Godot:** NavigationAgent3D, NavigationServer
- **Dynamic obstacles:** Navmeshes are static. For moving obstacles, use local avoidance (RVO/ORCA) on top of A*.

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
A* is Google Maps for NPCs. Dijkstra explores every road equally (wastes time on dead ends). A* uses a "birds-eye heuristic" — it guesses how close each junction is to the destination and prioritizes the promising ones. If the guess is perfect (straight-line distance), A* goes directly to the goal. If the guess is zero, A* becomes Dijkstra. The path is reconstructed by tracing "how did I get here?" pointers backward from the goal.

### Technical
A* = best-first search with f(n) = g(n) + h(n). g(n) = exact cost from start. h(n) = heuristic estimate to goal (must be admissible for optimality, consistent for optimal + efficient). With a consistent heuristic, A* expands each node at most once. Priority queue (binary heap) gives O(log V) per expansion. On a grid: 8-connected (octile) or 4-connected. Jump Point Search (JPS) optimizes A* on uniform-cost grids by skipping intermediate nodes. Navmeshes reduce node count by 100-1000x vs grids.

