02 \u2014 Steering Behaviors.content:
# Steering Behaviors

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[01 — A Star & Pathfinding]], [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]]

---

## Why

A* gives the PATH. Steering behaviors give the MOTION — how an NPC actually moves along that path, reacts to dynamic obstacles, and interacts with other NPCs. Without steering, path followers move like robots (instant turns, no avoidance). With it, you get natural flocking, pursuit, and evasion.

**Engine use:** UE MovementComponent, Unity NavMeshAgent steering, boid systems.

---

## Seek and Flee

**Seek:** Steer toward a target.

```cpp
Vec3 Seek(Vec3 currentPos, Vec3 currentVel, Vec3 target, float maxSpeed) {
    Vec3 desired = Normalize(target - currentPos) * maxSpeed;
    Vec3 steering = desired - currentVel;
    return ClampMagnitude(steering, maxForce);  // limit turn rate
}
```

**Flee:** Opposite of seek — steer away.

```cpp
Vec3 Flee(Vec3 pos, Vec3 vel, Vec3 threat, float maxSpeed) {
    Vec3 desired = Normalize(pos - threat) * maxSpeed;
    return ClampMagnitude(desired - vel, maxForce);
}
```

---

## Arrival — Slowing Down

Seek overshoots — it keeps going at max speed past the target. Arrival slows down as it approaches:

```cpp
Vec3 Arrive(Vec3 pos, Vec3 vel, Vec3 target, float maxSpeed, float slowRadius) {
    Vec3 toTarget = target - pos;
    float dist = Length(toTarget);

    if (dist < 0.1f) return -vel;  // stop

    float speed = maxSpeed;
    if (dist < slowRadius) {
        speed = maxSpeed * (dist / slowRadius);  // linear ramp-down
    }

    Vec3 desired = Normalize(toTarget) * speed;
    return ClampMagnitude(desired - vel, maxForce);
}
```

---

## Pursuit and Evasion — Predicting the Future

Seek chases the current position — Pursuit chases WHERE THE TARGET WILL BE:

```cpp
Vec3 Pursue(Vec3 pos, Vec3 vel, Vec3 targetPos, Vec3 targetVel, 
            float maxSpeed, float maxPrediction) {
    Vec3 toTarget = targetPos - pos;
    float dist = Length(toTarget);
    float speed = Length(vel);

    // Prediction time: how far ahead based on distance
    float prediction = dist / maxSpeed;
    if (speed > dist / prediction) prediction = dist / speed;
    prediction = Min(prediction, maxPrediction);

    // Seek the predicted position
    Vec3 predicted = targetPos + targetVel * prediction;
    return Seek(pos, vel, predicted, maxSpeed);
}
```

**Evasion** is the same as flee but targeting the predicted position.

---

## Wander — Random Natural Movement

```cpp
Vec3 Wander(Vec3 pos, Vec3 vel, float maxSpeed, float& wanderAngle) {
    // Circle in front of the agent
    Vec3 circleCenter = Normalize(vel) * wanderDistance;

    // Random displacement on the circle
    wanderAngle += RandomRange(-wanderRate, wanderRate);
    Vec3 displacement = Vec3(Cos(wanderAngle), Sin(wanderAngle), 0) * wanderRadius;

    Vec3 desired = Normalize(circleCenter + displacement) * maxSpeed;
    return ClampMagnitude(desired - vel, maxForce);
}
```

---

## Flocking — Boids

Three simple rules produce complex group behavior:

```cpp
Vec3 Flock(Vec3 pos, Vec3 vel, vector<Boid>& neighbors,
           float sepWeight, float aliWeight, float cohWeight) {
    Vec3 separation = {0,0,0}, alignment = {0,0,0}, cohesion = {0,0,0};
    int count = 0;

    for (Boid& other : neighbors) {
        Vec3 toOther = pos - other.pos;
        float dist = Length(toOther);
        if (dist < neighborRadius) {
            // Separation: steer away from nearby boids
            separation += Normalize(toOther) / dist;  // closer = stronger

            // Alignment: match average velocity
            alignment += other.vel;

            // Cohesion: steer toward center of mass
            cohesion += other.pos;

            count++;
        }
    }

    if (count == 0) return {0,0,0};

    // Weight and combine
    alignment = alignment / count - vel;
    cohesion = (cohesion / count - pos) - vel;

    return separation * sepWeight + alignment * aliWeight + cohesion * cohWeight;
}
```

---

## Combining Behaviors — Priority Blending

Real NPCs combine multiple behaviors with priority:

```cpp
Vec3 CombinedSteering(NPC& npc) {
    Vec3 steering = {0,0,0};

    // High priority: collision avoidance (can't die)
    Vec3 avoid = ObstacleAvoidance(npc);
    if (Length(avoid) > 0) return avoid;

    // Medium: follow path from A*
    steering += FollowPath(npc) * 1.0f;

    // Low: flocking (nice to have)
    steering += Flock(npc) * 0.5f;

    // Wander if nothing else to do
    if (Length(steering) < 0.01f)
        steering += Wander(npc) * 0.3f;

    return ClampMagnitude(steering, maxForce);
}
```

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE:** `UCharacterMovementComponent` — Seek/Arrive built into `MoveTo`, avoidance via RVO, separate `UFloatingPawnMovement`
- **Unity:** NavMeshAgent handles steering automatically — `SetDestination()` includes arrival + avoidance
- **Godot:** NavigationAgent3D with `set_velocity()` callbacks
- **RVO/ORCA:** Optimal Reciprocal Collision Avoidance — guarantees collision-free local navigation for multiple agents

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Steering is how an NPC turns a path into motion. Seek = "go toward that." Flee = "run away from that." Arrive = "slow down as you get close." Pursue = "chase where they'll BE, not where they ARE." Wander = "pick random direction, look natural." Flocking = three simple rules (stay close but not too close, go the same direction, head toward the group's center) that create complex bird/fish school behavior.

### Technical
Steering force = desired velocity - current velocity, clamped to maxForce. All behaviors output a force vector — combine by weighted sum with priority masking. Reynolds' original 1999 paper defined the framework. RVO (Reciprocal Velocity Obstacles) extends to guaranteed collision-free multi-agent navigation. ORCA (Optimal Reciprocal Collision Avoidance) is the modern standard used in UE5.

## See Also

- [[01 — A Star & Pathfinding]] — The path steering follows
- [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]] — Dot/cross products for angle calculations

03 \u2014 Navmesh Generation.content:
# Navmesh Generation

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[01 — A Star & Pathfinding]], [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]]

---

## Why

A* needs a graph. For 3D games, that graph is a navigation mesh (navmesh) — a polygon mesh representing all walkable surfaces. Generating a good navmesh automatically is a hard problem: it must handle ramps, stairs, ledges, and overhangs while respecting agent size (radius + height).

**Engine use:** UE's Recast/Detour integration, Unity NavMesh, Godot Navigation.

---

## The Recast Pipeline

Recast is THE open-source navmesh generator used by UE, Unity, and Godot. Its pipeline:

```
1. Voxelization     → 3D grid of "solid" vs "empty" cells
2. Filtering         → Erode walkable surface, remove noise
3. Region Partition  → Group contiguous walkable cells
4. Contour Extraction → Find boundaries of each region
5. Polygon Mesh      → Triangulate contours into navmesh
6. Detail Mesh       → Add height detail for accurate placement
```

---

## Step 1 — Voxelization

Convert the world geometry into a 3D grid:

```cpp
struct VoxelGrid {
    int width, height, depth;
    float cellSize;  // typically 10-30 cm
    vector<bool> solid;  // true = geometry here

    void Rasterize(const TriangleMesh& world) {
        for (Triangle t : world.triangles) {
            // Find bounding box of triangle in voxel space
            AABB bounds = t.GetBounds();
            for (int x = bounds.minX; x <= bounds.maxX; x++)
            for (int y = bounds.minY; y <= bounds.maxY; y++)
            for (int z = bounds.minZ; z <= bounds.maxZ; z++) {
                if (TriangleOverlapsVoxel(t, x, y, z))
                    solid[Index(x,y,z)] = true;
            }
        }
    }
};
```

---

## Step 2 — Walkable Surface Detection

A voxel column is walkable if the top surface is nearly horizontal and there's enough headroom:

```cpp
struct Heightfield {
    struct Span {
        float minY, maxY;  // bottom and top of this solid span
    };
    vector<vector<Span>> columns;  // per-column stack of spans

    bool IsWalkable(int x, int z) {
        // Find the top span
        Span top = columns[Index(x,z)].back();

        // Check slope: neighboring columns' top surfaces
        float slope = Max(Abs(top.maxY - NeighborY(x+1,z)),
                          Abs(top.maxY - NeighborY(x,z+1)));
        if (slope / cellSize > maxSlope) return false;  // too steep (>45deg)

        // Check headroom: is there enough space above?
        float clearance = SpaceAbove(x, z, top.maxY);
        if (clearance < agentHeight) return false;

        return true;
    }
};
```

---

## Step 3 — Region Partitioning (Watershed)

Group contiguous walkable cells into regions using a watershed algorithm:

```
Walkable cells:    After watershed:
. . . . # . .      A A A A # B B
. . # # # . .      A A # # # B B
. . . . . . .      A A A A C C C  
. . # # . . .      D D # # C C C
```

Distance from impassable edges creates ridges. Invert the height and flood-fill to get basins = regions. Each region becomes a separate navmesh polygon.

---

## Step 4 — Contour Extraction (Marching Squares)

For each region, trace its boundary:

```
Region:    Raw contour:    Simplified:
AAAAA      ┌──────┐        ┌────┐
AA AAB     │ AAAA │        │ AA │
AAAAAB  →  └──┐ ┌─┘    →   └─┐┌─┘
              │ B │           │B│
```

Simplify using Douglas-Peucker: remove vertices that don't significantly change the shape. Tolerance = cellSize / 2 works well.

---

## Step 5 — Polygon Triangulation

Triangulate the simplified contours. Constrained Delaunay triangulation ensures no triangle edges cross contour boundaries.

---

## Step 6 — Detail Mesh

The polygon mesh is flat at the voxel resolution. The detail mesh samples the actual geometry height at each vertex for accuracy:

```cpp
float SampleHeight(float x, float z, const TriangleMesh& world) {
    Ray ray = {Vec3(x, 1000, z), Vec3(0, -1, 0)};  // shoot down from above
    for (Triangle t : world) {
        float t_hit;
        if (RayTriangleIntersect(ray, t, t_hit))
            return 1000 - t_hit;  // world-space height
    }
    return 0;
}
```

---

## Agent Parameters

```cpp
struct NavMeshBuildSettings {
    float agentRadius;     // how wide the agent is (adds to obstacle padding)
    float agentHeight;     // minimum clearance height
    float maxSlope;        // maximum walkable angle (typically 45 degrees)
    float stepHeight;      // maximum step-up height (stairs)
    float cellSize;        // voxel resolution (smaller = more accurate = slower)
};
```

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE:** `ANavigationData`, `ARecastNavMesh` — automatic generation from collision geometry, configurable agent params, runtime navmesh modifiers
- **Unity:** `NavMeshSurface`, `NavMeshBuilder` — automatic from scene geometry, `NavMeshObstacle` for dynamic cuts
- **Godot:** `NavigationMesh` + `NavigationServer` — bake from scene, `NavigationObstacle3D` for runtime changes
- **Runtime navmesh:** Dynamic obstacles require local navmesh updates — UE's `NavModifierComponent` cuts holes

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Navmesh generation turns a 3D world into a flat map for pathfinding. First, voxelize everything into tiny cubes (solid or empty). Find flat surfaces with enough headroom — that's walkable. Group contiguous walkable areas into regions (rooms, corridors). Trace the boundaries of each region and simplify them into polygons. Finally, adjust heights to match the actual geometry exactly. The result is a polygon soup that A* traverses.

### Technical
Recast: rasterization → heightfield → compact heightfield → watershed region partition → contour simplification (Douglas-Peucker) → constrained Delaunay triangulation → detail mesh. Voxel size trades accuracy for speed: 10cm for detailed indoor, 30cm for open terrain. Agent radius dilates obstacles inward before region partitioning. The result is a convex polygon mesh — A* paths through polygon center-to-center connections, then the funnel algorithm straightens the path.

## See Also

- [[01 — A Star & Pathfinding]] — Runs on the navmesh
- [[02 — Steering Behaviors]] — Motion after navigation

01 \u2014 AABB and Sphere.content:
# AABB and Sphere Collision

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Collision Detection Overview|Collision Detection]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[Trigonometry & Vectors]] — dot products, vector math.


### Analogy: The Gift Box

Imagine wrapping every object in your game in the smallest possible cardboard box whose edges align perfectly with the world's XYZ axes. A character gets a tall box, a ball gets a cube, a wall gets a long flat box. To check if two objects might touch, you just check if their boxes overlap. If the boxes don't overlap, the objects definitely don't collide — no need for expensive pixel-perfect checks. If they do overlap, you've narrowed down which objects need closer inspection.

### Definition

An AABB is defined by two vectors: `Min` (the corner with smallest x, y, z) and `Max` (the corner with largest x, y, z).

```cpp
struct AABB
{
    Vec3 Min;  // Minimum corner (bottom-left-back)
    Vec3 Max;  // Maximum corner (top-right-front)

    // Convenient accessors
    Vec3 Center() const { return (Min + Max) * 0.5f; }
    Vec3 Extents() const { return (Max - Min) * 0.5f; }
    Vec3 Size() const { return Max - Min; }
};
```

### AABB-AABB Intersection Test

Two AABBs overlap if and only if they overlap on all three axes. This is the simplest and fastest collision test in existence:

```cpp
bool AABBOverlap(const AABB& A, const AABB& B)
{
    return (A.Min.X <= B.Max.X && A.Max.X >= B.Min.X) &&
           (A.Min.Y <= B.Max.Y && A.Max.Y >= B.Min.Y) &&
           (A.Min.Z <= B.Max.Z && A.Max.Z >= B.Min.Z);
}
```

> [!tip] The Logic
> For each axis: the maximum of one box's lower bound and the other's lower bound must be less than the minimum of their upper bounds. If on any axis they DON'T overlap, the boxes are separated. Think of it as: if I can slip a piece of paper between the boxes on any axis, they don't touch.

```cpp
bool AABBOverlap(const AABB& A, const AABB& B, float& OutOverlapX, float& OutOverlapY, float& OutOverlapZ)
{
    OutOverlapX = Math::Min(A.Max.X, B.Max.X) - Math::Max(A.Min.X, B.Min.X);
    OutOverlapY = Math::Min(A.Max.Y, B.Max.Y) - Math::Max(A.Min.Y, B.Min.Y);
    OutOverlapZ = Math::Min(A.Max.Z, B.Max.Z) - Math::Max(A.Min.Z, B.Min.Z);

    return OutOverlapX > 0.0f && OutOverlapY > 0.0f && OutOverlapZ > 0.0f;
}
```

### AABB from a Moving Object

A character moving from point A to point B needs its AABB to cover the entire swept path:

```cpp
AABB SweptAABB(const Vec3& PosA, const Vec3& PosB, const Vec3& HalfExtents)
{
    AABB Result;
    Result.Min.X = Math::Min(PosA.X, PosB.X) - HalfExtents.X;
    Result.Min.Y = Math::Min(PosA.Y, PosB.Y) - HalfExtents.Y;
    Result.Min.Z = Math::Min(PosA.Z, PosB.Z) - HalfExtents.Z;
    Result.Max.X = Math::Max(PosA.X, PosB.X) + HalfExtents.X;
    Result.Max.Y = Math::Max(PosA.Y, PosB.Y) + HalfExtents.Y;
    Result.Max.Z = Math::Max(PosA.Z, PosB.Z) + HalfExtents.Z;
    return Result;
}
```

### game engine Connection: Box

```cpp
// Creating boxes
Box Bounds(Vec3(-100, -100, 0), Vec3(100, 100, 200));
Box FromCenter(Vec3(0, 0, 100), Vec3(50, 50, 100));  // Center + Extent

// Intersection test
if (Bounds.Intersect(OtherBox))
{
    // Boxes overlap
}

// Getting overlap info
Box Overlap = Bounds.Overlap(OtherBox);

// Expanding
Bounds.ExpandBy(10.0f);  // Adds 10 units on all sides

// Point test
bool bInside = Bounds.IsInside(Vec3(0, 0, 50));
```

---

### Analogy: The Bubble Wrap

If AABBs are cardboard boxes, spheres are bubble wrap — they're round, so they don't care about orientation. A sphere is the simplest possible 3D collision shape: one center point and one radius. Testing two spheres is just checking if the distance between their centers is less than the sum of their radii.

### Point-to-Sphere

Is a point inside a sphere?

```cpp
bool PointInSphere(const Vec3& Point, const Vec3& SphereCenter, float Radius)
{
    return Vec3::DistSquared(Point, SphereCenter) <= Radius * Radius;
}
```

### Sphere-to-Sphere

Do two spheres overlap?

```cpp
bool SphereOverlap(const Vec3& CenterA, float RadiusA,
                   const Vec3& CenterB, float RadiusB,
                   Vec3* OutNormal = nullptr, float* OutPenetration = nullptr)
{
    Vec3 Delta = CenterB - CenterA;
    float DistSq = Delta.SizeSquared();
    float RadiusSum = RadiusA + RadiusB;

    if (DistSq > RadiusSum * RadiusSum)
        return false;

    if (OutNormal || OutPenetration)
    {
        float Dist = Math::Sqrt(DistSq);
        if (Dist > KINDA_SMALL_NUMBER)
        {
            if (OutNormal) *OutNormal = Delta / Dist;
            if (OutPenetration) *OutPenetration = RadiusSum - Dist;
        }
        else
        {
            // Spheres are concentric — pick an arbitrary normal
            if (OutNormal) *OutNormal = Vec3::UpVector;
            if (OutPenetration) *OutPenetration = Math::Min(RadiusA, RadiusB);
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```

### Sphere-to-AABB

Find the closest point on the AABB to the sphere center, then do a point-in-sphere test:

```cpp
Vec3 ClosestPointOnAABB(const Vec3& Point, const AABB& Box)
{
    return Vec3(
        Math::Clamp(Point.X, Box.Min.X, Box.Max.X),
        Math::Clamp(Point.Y, Box.Min.Y, Box.Max.Y),
        Math::Clamp(Point.Z, Box.Min.Z, Box.Max.Z)
    );
}

bool SphereAABBOverlap(const Vec3& SphereCenter, float Radius, const AABB& Box)
{
    Vec3 Closest = ClosestPointOnAABB(SphereCenter, Box);
    return Vec3::DistSquared(SphereCenter, Closest) <= Radius * Radius;
}
```

### game engine Connection: FCollisionShape

```cpp
FCollisionShape SphereShape = FCollisionShape::MakeSphere(50.0f);
FCollisionShape BoxShape = FCollisionShape::MakeBox(Vec3(50, 30, 100));
FCollisionShape CapsuleShape = FCollisionShape::MakeCapsule(30.0f, 80.0f);
```

