02 \u2014 Ray Casting.content:
# Ray Casting

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Collision Detection Overview|Collision Detection]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[01 — AABB and Sphere]] — understand AABB and sphere intersection first.


### Analogy: The Laser Pointer

A ray is like a laser pointer: it starts somewhere (origin), points in a direction, and goes infinitely far (or up to some max distance). Ray casting asks: "What does this laser hit first?" It's the most fundamental query in game development — used for shooting, visibility checks, mouse picking, AI line-of-sight, and a hundred other things.

### Ray Definition

$$\text{Ray: } P(t) = \text{Origin} + t \cdot \text{Direction}, \quad t \geq 0$$

```cpp
struct Ray
{
    Vec3 Origin;
    Vec3 Direction;  // Should be normalized

    Vec3 PointAt(float t) const { return Origin + Direction * t; }
};
```

### Ray-AABB Intersection: The Slab Method

**Analogy: The Three Sliding Doors**

Imagine three pairs of sliding doors along X, Y, and Z axes. The ray is a bullet flying through space. For each axis, compute when the bullet enters and exits that pair of doors. The bullet is inside the box only when it's inside all three pairs simultaneously. If the latest "enter" time is before the earliest "exit" time, the ray hits the box.

```cpp
bool RayAABB(const Ray& Ray, const AABB& Box, float& OutTMin, float MaxDistance = FLT_MAX)
{
    float tMin = 0.0f;
    float tMax = MaxDistance;

    // Test each axis independently
    for (int Axis = 0; Axis < 3; ++Axis)
    {
        float InvDir = 1.0f / Ray.Direction[Axis];
        float t0 = (Box.Min[Axis] - Ray.Origin[Axis]) * InvDir;
        float t1 = (Box.Max[Axis] - Ray.Origin[Axis]) * InvDir;

        if (InvDir < 0.0f) Swap(t0, t1);

        tMin = Math::Max(tMin, t0);
        tMax = Math::Min(tMax, t1);

        if (tMax < tMin)
            return false;
    }

    OutTMin = tMin;
    return true;
}
```

> [!warning] Avoid NaN Direction
> If `Ray.Direction[Axis]` is exactly zero (ray parallel to that axis), `InvDir` becomes infinity. Guard against this by checking `Math::Abs(Ray.Direction[Axis]) < SMALL_NUMBER` and treating that slab as always passing (or failing if the origin is entirely outside).

### Ray-Triangle Intersection: Möller-Trumbore Algorithm

**Analogy: The Barycentric Dartboard**

Imagine throwing a dart at a triangular dartboard. Instead of using X/Y coordinates, the dartboard uses **barycentric coordinates**: three weights (u, v, w) that sum to 1.0. If all three weights are positive, the dart hit inside the triangle. Möller-Trumbore finds u, v, and the distance t simultaneously with one elegant piece of linear algebra — no need to compute the plane equation first.

### The Math

A triangle with vertices V₀, V₁, V₂. The ray hits at:

$$O + tD = (1 - u - v)V_0 + uV_1 + vV_2$$

Rearranging to solve for t, u, v:

$$O - V_0 = -tD + u(V_1 - V_0) + v(V_2 - V_0)$$

This is a 3×3 linear system. Using Cramer's rule and some clever factoring (the "Möller-Trumbore trick"):

Let E₁ = V₁ - V₀, E₂ = V₂ - V₀, T = O - V₀
Let P = D × E₂, Q = T × E₁

Then:
```
det = P · E₁
u = (P · T) / det
v = (Q · D) / det
t = (Q · E₂) / det
```

Hit if: det ≠ 0, u ≥ 0, v ≥ 0, u + v ≤ 1, t ≥ 0

### Code Implementation

```cpp
bool RayTriangleIntersection(
    const Vec3& RayOrigin, const Vec3& RayDirection,
    const Vec3& V0, const Vec3& V1, const Vec3& V2,
    float& OutT, float& OutU, float& OutV, bool bCullBackface = false)
{
    const float EPSILON = 0.0000001f;

    Vec3 E1 = V1 - V0;
    Vec3 E2 = V2 - V0;

    Vec3 P = Vec3::CrossProduct(RayDirection, E2);
    float Det = Vec3::DotProduct(P, E1);

    // If determinant is near zero, ray is parallel to triangle plane
    if (Math::Abs(Det) < EPSILON)
        return false;

    // Culling: if det < 0, ray hits from behind
    if (bCullBackface && Det < 0.0f)
        return false;

    float InvDet = 1.0f / Det;

    Vec3 T = RayOrigin - V0;

    // Calculate u (barycentric coordinate for V1)
    OutU = Vec3::DotProduct(P, T) * InvDet;
    if (OutU < 0.0f || OutU > 1.0f)
        return false;

    // Calculate v (barycentric coordinate for V2)
    Vec3 Q = Vec3::CrossProduct(T, E1);
    OutV = Vec3::DotProduct(Q, RayDirection) * InvDet;
    if (OutV < 0.0f || OutU + OutV > 1.0f)
        return false;

    // Calculate t (distance along ray)
    OutT = Vec3::DotProduct(Q, E2) * InvDet;

    return OutT > EPSILON;  // Intersection is in front of ray origin
}
```

> [!tip] Barycentric Coordinates Are Useful
> The outputs u, v (and w = 1 - u - v) aren't just for validation — they let you interpolate any vertex attribute at the hit point:
> ```cpp
> Vec3 HitNormal = (1 - u - v) * N0 + u * N1 + v * N2;
> Vec32D HitUV = (1 - u - v) * UV0 + u * UV1 + v * UV2;
> ``

### game engine Connection: Line Traces

```cpp
// Single line trace (ray cast)
FHitResult Hit;
bool bHit = GetWorld()->LineTraceSingleByChannel(
    Hit,
    StartLocation,
    EndLocation,
    ECC_Visibility,
    FCollisionQueryParams::DefaultQueryParam
);

if (bHit)
{
    Vec3 HitPoint = Hit.Location;
    Vec3 HitNormal = Hit.Normal;
    AActor* HitActor = Hit.GetActor();
    float Distance = Hit.Distance;
}

// Multi trace (hit everything along the ray)
TArray<FHitResult> Hits;
GetWorld()->LineTraceMultiByChannel(Hits, Start, End, ECC_Visibility);

// Sweep trace (moving a shape along a line)
FCollisionShape Capsule = FCollisionShape::MakeCapsule(30, 80);
GetWorld()->SweepSingleByChannel(Hit, Start, End, Quat::Identity,
    ECC_Pawn, Capsule, QueryParams);
```

---



> [!info] **Game Engine Connection**
> Every engine implements these concepts: Unity's Physics.Raycast, Godot's CollisionShape, Unreal's Box/Sphere/LineTrace. The math is identical — only the API wrapping changes. See [[../UE Math/Collision & Intersection Math]] and [[../UE Math/Curves, Ranges & Random]] for engine-specific implementations.
## Exercises

1. **Ray-AABB intersection:** Implement the slab method (Kay and Kajiya). Compute tMin and tMax for each axis. A hit occurs when the maximum of all tMin values is less than the minimum of all tMax values. Test with a ray that hits, a ray that misses (direction away), and a ray that starts inside.

2. **Ray-sphere intersection:** Solve the quadratic `at^2 + bt + c = 0` where `a = D·D`, `b = 2(O-C)·D`, `c = (O-C)·(O-C) - r^2`. Compute the discriminant. If negative, no hit. If positive, return the smaller positive t. Handle the case where the ray starts inside the sphere (one negative t, one positive t).

3. **Ray-triangle intersection:** Implement Moller-Trumbore. Compute edge vectors, cross product with ray direction, solve the 2x2 linear system for barycentric coordinates u and v. Check: `u >= 0`, `v >= 0`, `u + v <= 1`. What does `u + v > 1` mean geometrically?

4. **A game engine's LineTraceSingle:** A game engine's `LineTraceSingleByChannel()` uses PhysX (or Chaos) for ray casts against the physics world. Trace the call chain: `LineTraceSingle` → `FPhysicsInterface::RayCast` → PhysX `PxScene::raycast()`. What does PhysX do internally — BVH traversal? kD-tree? Why is the broad phase necessary?

5. **Ray casting for selection:** You're building a level editor. The player clicks on the screen at pixel (x, y). Convert the 2D screen coordinate to a 3D world-space ray using the inverse view-projection matrix. Cast this ray against all selectable actors. How do you accelerate this without testing every actor? (Hint: spatial hashing or octree.)
## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Ray casting is throwing an invisible laser beam from a point in a direction and asking "what does it hit first?" The ray has an origin and a direction. For each object, we solve "at what distance along the ray does it intersect?" and pick the closest one. Ray-AABB uses the "slab method" — imagine the box as the intersection of three pairs of parallel planes (slabs). The ray enters each slab at tMin and exits at tMax. If it's inside all three slabs at some t, it hits.

### Technical
Ray: `P(t) = O + t*D` for `t >= 0`. Ray-AABB (slab method): compute `t1 = (min[i] - O[i]) / D[i]` and `t2 = (max[i] - O[i]) / D[i]` for each axis, swap if needed so t1 is the near intersection. `t_enter = max(t1_x, t1_y, t1_z)`, `t_exit = min(t2_x, t2_y, t2_z)`. Hit if `t_enter <= t_exit` and `t_exit >= 0`. Ray-sphere: solve quadratic, use discriminant. Ray-triangle (Moller-Trumbore): solve for barycentric coordinates (u, v) — the point is `(1-u-v)*V0 + u*V1 + v*V2`. A game engine's line traces use the physics engine's acceleration structure (BVH for static geometry, per-body shapes for dynamics).

