03 \u2014 Separating Axis Theorem.content:
# Separating Axis Theorem

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Collision Detection Overview|Collision Detection]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[02 — Ray Casting]] — understand ray intersection patterns first.


### Analogy: The Shadow Test

Stand two objects side by side and shine a flashlight from the side. If their shadows on the wall don't overlap, the objects don't collide. Now rotate the flashlight 90 degrees and try again. If you can find ANY angle where the shadows don't overlap, the objects are separated. SAT is the mathematical version: project both shapes onto a line (axis), check for overlap, repeat for several axes. If there's a **separating axis** where projections don't overlap, there's no collision.

### The Theorem

For two **convex** shapes, they do NOT intersect if and only if there exists an axis where their projections (intervals) do NOT overlap. This axis is the **separating axis**.

For convex polyhedra, the candidate separating axes are:
- Face normals of shape A
- Face normals of shape B
- Cross products of every edge from A with every edge from B

### 2D SAT Implementation

For two convex polygons, the candidate axes are just the edge normals.

```cpp
struct Polygon2D
{
    TArray<Vec32D> Vertices;

    // Get the perpendicular normal for each edge
    TArray<Vec32D> GetAxes() const
    {
        TArray<Vec32D> Axes;
        int N = Vertices.Num();
        for (int i = 0; i < N; ++i)
        {
            Vec32D Edge = Vertices[(i + 1) % N] - Vertices[i];
            // Perpendicular: (-y, x)
            Vec32D Normal(-Edge.Y, Edge.X);
            Normal.Normalize();
            Axes.Add(Normal);
        }
        return Axes;
    }
};

// Project polygon onto axis, returning [min, max]
void ProjectPolygon(const TArray<Vec32D>& Vertices, const Vec32D& Axis,
                    float& OutMin, float& OutMax)
{
    OutMin = OutMax = Vec32D::DotProduct(Vertices[0], Axis);
    for (int i = 1; i < Vertices.Num(); ++i)
    {
        float Proj = Vec32D::DotProduct(Vertices[i], Axis);
        OutMin = Math::Min(OutMin, Proj);
        OutMax = Math::Max(OutMax, Proj);
    }
}

bool SATIntersect(const Polygon2D& A, const Polygon2D& B,
                  Vec32D* OutMTV = nullptr)
{
    float MinOverlap = FLT_MAX;
    Vec32D SmallestAxis;

    // Combine axes from both polygons
    TArray<Vec32D> Axes = A.GetAxes();
    Axes.Append(B.GetAxes());

    for (const Vec32D& Axis : Axes)
    {
        float MinA, MaxA, MinB, MaxB;
        ProjectPolygon(A.Vertices, Axis, MinA, MaxA);
        ProjectPolygon(B.Vertices, Axis, MinB, MaxB);

        float Overlap = Math::Min(MaxA, MaxB) - Math::Max(MinA, MinB);

        if (Overlap <= 0.0f)
            return false;  // Separating axis found — no collision

        if (Overlap < MinOverlap)
        {
            MinOverlap = Overlap;
            SmallestAxis = Axis;
        }
    }

    if (OutMTV)
    {
        // Make sure MTV points from A toward B
        Vec32D CenterDiff = B.Center() - A.Center();
        if (Vec32D::DotProduct(SmallestAxis, CenterDiff) < 0.0f)
            SmallestAxis = -SmallestAxis;
        *OutMTV = SmallestAxis * MinOverlap;
    }

    return true;
}
```

### Visual Description: SAT in Action

```
      Shape A                Shape B
    +----+                  +----+
    |    |                  |    |
    |    |     ------>      |    |    axis
    |    |                  |    |
    +----+                  +----+

Projections on axis:
A:  [====]
B:          [====]
    ↑ no overlap → SEPARATED!
```

```
      Shape A              Shape B
    +----+                +----+
    |    |  +--+          |    |
    |    |  |  |          |    |
    +----+  +--+          +----+

Projections on axis:
A:  [======]
B:    [=======]
    ↑ overlap on this axis — try another axis
```

### SAT in 3D

The generalization to 3D tests: face normals of A (up to N faces), face normals of B (up to M faces), and cross products of all edge pairs (up to E_A × E_B axes). This makes 3D SAT expensive for complex shapes — which is why physics engines use GJK instead.

---



> [!info] **Game Engine Connection**
> Every engine implements these concepts: Unity's Physics.Raycast, Godot's CollisionShape, Unreal's Box/Sphere/LineTrace. The math is identical — only the API wrapping changes. See [[../UE Math/Collision & Intersection Math]] and [[../UE Math/Curves, Ranges & Random]] for engine-specific implementations.
## Exercises

1. **2D SAT:** Write `bool SATOverlap(const std::vector<Vec32D>& polyA, const` std::vector`<Vec32D>`& polyB)`. For each polygon, collect candidate axes: the normals of all edges. For each axis, project both polygons and check for overlap. If ANY axis shows separation, return false. Test with triangles and convex quads.

2. **OBB-OBB SAT:** Extend SAT to 3D for two oriented bounding boxes. How many axes do you need to test? (Hint: 15 — 3 faces of A, 3 faces of B, 9 cross products of edges.) Implement the projection step: for each axis, compute `min = dot(axis, corner)` for all 8 corners. Compare the intervals.

3. **SAT edge case:** Two boxes are separated by a very small gap (0.0001 units). Due to floating-point error, the projection intervals overlap. What epsilon should you use in the interval comparison? Write a robust SAT that handles this case. Test with nearly-separating boxes.

4. **SAT vs GJK:** When would you choose SAT over GJK for convex polyhedra? When is GJK faster? (Hint: SAT scales with number of features; GJK scales with number of iterations which is typically small.) For two 8-vertex convex polyhedra, estimate operations for each.

5. **A game engine's collision:** game engine uses PhysX (or Chaos) which implements SAT for convex mesh collision internally. Find `FKConvexElem` in game engine source. How does A game engine's pre-computed convex decomposition (V-HACD) interact with SAT? Why decompose a concave mesh into convex parts instead of running SAT directly?
## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
SAT says: two convex shapes don't overlap if you can find ANY line (axis) where their shadows don't overlap. Imagine shining a flashlight at two objects from every possible angle. If there's ANY angle where their shadows are separated, the objects are separated. You only need to test the angles perpendicular to each face and each edge pair — for two boxes, that's 15 angles total. If shadows overlap on ALL 15, the boxes intersect.

### Technical
SAT for convex polyhedra: candidate axes are face normals of both objects plus cross products of all edge pairs. For two OBBs: 3 A-face normals + 3 B-face normals + 3*3=9 edge cross products = 15 axes. Project each polyhedron onto each axis: `[min(dot(axis, vertex_i)), max(...)]`. If `max_A < min_B` or `max_B < min_A` on any axis → separated. All 15 show overlap → intersecting. SAT is O(F_A + F_B) for face count but the edge-edge cross products dominate. GJK outperforms SAT for objects where support functions are cheap vs explicit vertex enumeration.


---

## OBB-OBB — The Full 15-Axis Test

For two oriented bounding boxes (OBBs), SAT requires 15 candidate axes:

```
3 face normals of box A      (the box's own X, Y, Z axes in world space)
3 face normals of box B      (box B's X, Y, Z in world space)
9 edge cross products        (every edge of A crossed with every edge of B = 3×3)
```

**Why 15?** The separating axis must be perpendicular to both shapes. For boxes, this means either a face normal (separation is a face plane) or a cross product of edges (separation is an edge-edge pair).

```cpp
bool OBBOverlapSAT(const Mat4& transformA, const Vec3& halfExtentsA,
                   const Mat4& transformB, const Vec3& halfExtentsB) {
    // Extract rotation matrices (upper 3×3)
    Mat3 rotA = transformA.GetRotation();
    Mat3 rotB = transformB.GetRotation();
    Vec3 transA = transformA.GetTranslation();
    Vec3 transB = transformB.GetTranslation();

    // Translation between centers in world space
    Vec3 T = transB - transA;

    // 15 axes to test
    struct Axis { Vec3 dir; float ra, rb; };
    vector<Axis> axes;

    // Face normals of A (3 axes)
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        Vec3 axis = rotA.Column(i);
        axes.push_back({axis, 
            halfExtentsA[i],  // ra = half-extent of A on this axis
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(0))) * halfExtentsB[0] +
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(1))) * halfExtentsB[1] +
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(2))) * halfExtentsB[2]  // rb = projection of B
        });
    }

    // Face normals of B (3 axes)
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        Vec3 axis = rotB.Column(i);
        axes.push_back({axis,
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(0))) * halfExtentsA[0] +
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(1))) * halfExtentsA[1] +
            Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(2))) * halfExtentsA[2],
            halfExtentsB[i]
        });
    }

    // Edge cross products (9 axes)
    for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) {
        for (int j = 0; j < 3; j++) {
            Vec3 axis = Cross(rotA.Column(i), rotB.Column(j));
            float len = Length(axis);
            if (len < 1e-6f) continue;  // parallel edges — skip
            axis /= len;

            axes.push_back({axis,
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(0))) * halfExtentsA[0] +
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(1))) * halfExtentsA[1] +
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotA.Column(2))) * halfExtentsA[2],
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(0))) * halfExtentsB[0] +
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(1))) * halfExtentsB[1] +
                Abs(Dot(axis, rotB.Column(2))) * halfExtentsB[2]
            });
        }
    }

    // Test each axis
    for (const Axis& a : axes) {
        float separation = Abs(Dot(a.dir, T));
        float overlap = a.ra + a.rb;
        if (separation > overlap + 1e-6f) return false;  // separated!
    }
    return true;  // overlapping on all 15 axes
}
```

**Robustness:** Use epsilon = 1e-6 for near-parallel edges. For boxes that are touching (zero separation), the test correctly returns true due to the `>` comparison with epsilon.

---

## SAT vs GJK — When to Use Which

| Criterion | SAT | GJK |
|---|---|---|
| Best for | Polytopes with explicit vertices | Any convex shape |
| Axes to test | O(n_features²) | O(n_iterations) typically < 10 |
| Separating axis found | Yes — useful for contact normal | No — only distance |
| Penetration depth | No (separated only) | Yes (via EPA) |
| Non-polyhedral shapes | No | Yes (spheres, capsules, cylinders) |
| Engine use | Box-box (dominant case) | General convex-convex |

**Rule of thumb:** Use SAT for box-box (15 axes, cheap). Use GJK for everything else.


