04 \u2014 GJK Algorithm.content:
# GJK Algorithm

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Collision Detection Overview|Collision Detection]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[03 — Separating Axis Theorem]] — understand SAT before the general algorithm.


### Analogy: The Shrinking Triangle Hunt

You're hunting for the origin point (0,0) inside a strange shape. You start by picking a direction and finding the farthest point of the shape in that direction. You now have a single point. Pick a direction toward the origin, find the farthest point — now you have a line. Pick a perpendicular direction, find the farthest — now you have a triangle. Does this triangle contain the origin? If yes, the shapes collide. If no, throw away the farthest point of the triangle from the origin, and try again. You're sculpting a simplex (point → line → triangle → tetrahedron) that hopefully contains the origin, iteratively refining it.

### The Key Insight: Minkowski Difference

Instead of testing if two complex shapes A and B overlap, GJK tests if their **Minkowski Difference** contains the origin:

$$A \cap B 
eq \emptyset \iff \vec{0} \in (A \ominus B)$$

The Minkowski difference A ⊖ B is the set of all vectors {a - b | a ∈ A, b ∈ B}. If the shapes overlap, there's some point that's in both A and B, so a - b = 0 is in the difference.

```
Shape A:  [a]     Shape B:  [b]       A ⊖ B:  [a-b]
   +--+                +--+              +-----+
   |  | overlaps  +--+ |  |    →    +--+ |     | +--+
   +--+  with     |  | +--+         |  | |  0  | |  |
                  +--+              +--+ |     | +--+
                                         +-----+
```

### The Support Function

The magic of GJK: we never compute the full Minkowski difference. We query it with a **support function**: "given a direction d, what's the farthest point of A ⊖ B in that direction?"

$$S_{A \ominus B}(d) = S_A(d) - S_B(-d)$$

Where S_A(d) is the farthest point of shape A in direction d.

```cpp
// Support function for a convex polyhedron (list of vertices)
Vec3 Support_Polyhedron(const TArray<Vec3>& Vertices, const Vec3& Direction)
{
    float MaxDot = -FLT_MAX;
    int BestIdx = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < Vertices.Num(); ++i)
    {
        float Dot = Vec3::DotProduct(Vertices[i], Direction);
        if (Dot > MaxDot)
        {
            MaxDot = Dot;
            BestIdx = i;
        }
    }
    return Vertices[BestIdx];
}

// Support function for a sphere
Vec3 Support_Sphere(const Vec3& Center, float Radius, const Vec3& Direction)
{
    return Center + Direction.GetSafeNormal() * Radius;
}

// Combined Minkowski support for two shapes
Vec3 Support_Minkowski(const Vec3& Direction)
{
    return Support_ShapeA(Direction) - Support_ShapeB(-Direction);
}
```

### GJK Core Loop

```cpp
bool GJKIntersect(const Shape& A, const Shape& B)
{
    // Start with an arbitrary direction
    Vec3 Direction = Vec3(1, 0, 0);

    // Get first point on Minkowski difference
    Vec3 A_pt = Support(A, B, Direction);

    // Simplex is an array of up to 4 points (for 3D)
    TArray<Vec3> Simplex;
    Simplex.Add(A_pt);

    // Search in opposite direction (toward origin)
    Direction = -A_pt;

    while (true)
    {
        // Get new point in search direction
        Vec3 NewPt = Support(A, B, Direction);

        // If new point doesn't go past origin, origin can't be inside — no collision
        if (Vec3::DotProduct(NewPt, Direction) < 0.0f)
            return false;

        Simplex.Add(NewPt);

        // Update simplex and direction based on simplex size
        if (Simplex.Num() == 2)
        {
            // Line case: find closest point on line segment to origin
            // Update simplex to keep only contributing vertices
            if (!UpdateSimplex_Line(Simplex, Direction))
                return true;  // Origin on line → collision
        }
        else if (Simplex.Num() == 3)
        {
            // Triangle case: find closest point on triangle to origin
            if (!UpdateSimplex_Triangle(Simplex, Direction))
                return true;  // Origin in triangle → collision
        }
        else if (Simplex.Num() == 4)
        {
            // Tetrahedron case: if origin inside tetrahedron → collision
            if (!UpdateSimplex_Tetrahedron(Simplex, Direction))
                return true;  // Origin in tetrahedron → collision
        }
    }
}
```

```cpp
// Line simplex update: simplex = {A, B}, find closest point on AB to origin
bool UpdateSimplex_Line(TArray<Vec3>& Simplex, Vec3& Direction)
{
    Vec3 A = Simplex[1];  // Most recently added
    Vec3 B = Simplex[0];

    Vec3 AB = B - A;
    Vec3 AO = -A;

    // If AB points toward origin...
    if (Vec3::DotProduct(AB, AO) > 0.0f)
    {
        // Closest point is on line segment AB
        Direction = Vec3::CrossProduct(Vec3::CrossProduct(AB, AO), AB);
    }
    else
    {
        // Closest point is A — reduce simplex to just A
        Simplex = { A };
        Direction = AO;
        return false;  // Keep going
    }

    // Check if origin is on the line AB
    if (Direction.SizeSquared() < KINDA_SMALL_NUMBER)
        return false;  // origin on line → collision

    return true;  // Keep simplex as is, continue
}
```

> [!note] EPA: Getting Contact Information
> GJK only tells you IF two shapes collide. To find penetration depth and contact normal, you follow GJK with the **Expanding Polytope Algorithm (EPA)**. Once GJK produces a simplex containing the origin, EPA expands it to find the closest face to the origin — that face gives the contact normal and distance.

### Why GJK Is the Standard

- Works with ANY convex shape (as long as you can write a support function)
- No need to precompute edges/faces — support functions can be analytical (sphere, capsule, cylinder) or vertex-based (convex hull, box)
- Very fast in practice (usually converges in 3-6 iterations)
- Handles continuous motion via time-of-impact variants

---



> [!info] **Game Engine Connection**
> Every engine implements these concepts: Unity's Physics.Raycast, Godot's CollisionShape, Unreal's Box/Sphere/LineTrace. The math is identical — only the API wrapping changes. See [[../UE Math/Collision & Intersection Math]] and [[../UE Math/Curves, Ranges & Random]] for engine-specific implementations.
## Exercises

1. **Minkowski difference:** Given two convex shapes A and B, the Minkowski difference `A - B = {a - b | a in A, b in B}`. Prove: A and B intersect if and only if the origin is inside `A - B`. Draw the Minkowski difference of two triangles — what shape is it?

2. **Support function:** Write `Vec3 Support(const Box& box, Vec3 direction)` that returns the corner of the box furthest in the given direction. Now write `Vec3 Support(const Sphere& sphere, Vec3 direction)`. Combine them: `Vec3 SupportMinkowski(A, B, direction) = Support(A, direction) - Support(B, -direction)`. Test with known intersections.

3. **Simplex evolution:** Implement the 2D GJK loop. Start with an arbitrary support point as the simplex. Each iteration: find the point on the simplex closest to the origin. If it's the origin, intersecting. Otherwise, compute the search direction toward the origin, get a new support point, add to simplex. Keep at most 3 points (triangle in 2D). Implement the 3D case: keep at most 4 points (tetrahedron).

4. **GJK termination:** GJK doesn't converge — it terminates when it CAN'T get closer. Implement the termination conditions: if the new support point doesn't pass the origin (dot product check), no intersection. If the closest point to the origin IS the origin (within epsilon), intersection. What epsilon is reasonable?

5. **EPA for penetration:** GJK tells you IF objects intersect. EPA (Expanding Polytope Algorithm) tells you HOW DEEPLY. After GJK finds a simplex containing the origin, EPA expands the simplex to find the point on the Minkowski difference's surface closest to the origin. The distance is the penetration depth and the direction is the minimum translation vector. Sketch the EPA loop.
## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
GJK is the magic algorithm that detects if any two convex shapes intersect — boxes, spheres, capsules, convex meshes — using a single unified method. The trick: instead of testing the shapes directly, it tests their Minkowski difference (A minus B). If this difference shape contains the origin (0,0,0), the shapes overlap. GJK builds a simplex (a triangle in 2D, a tetrahedron in 3D) inside the Minkowski difference, iteratively refining it toward the origin. If the simplex reaches the origin: hit. If it can't get any closer: miss.

### Technical
Minkowski difference: `M = {a - b : a in A, b in B}`. A and B intersect iff `0 in M`. Support function `S_A(d)` returns the point in A furthest in direction d. For Minkowski difference: `S_M(d) = S_A(d) - S_B(-d)`. GJK loop: (1) start with arbitrary support point as simplex, (2) find closest point on simplex to origin (projection onto faces/edges), (3) if at origin → hit, (4) compute new direction toward origin, (5) get new support point, (6) if dot(new_point, direction) < 0 → miss (can't get closer), (7) add to simplex (keep max 4 points via Johnson's algorithm). EPA extends GJK: after hit, expand polytope to find MTD. game engine uses PhysX/Chaos GJK+EPA for all convex collision detection.


---

## EPA — Finding Penetration Depth

GJK tells you IF objects intersect. **EPA (Expanding Polytope Algorithm)** tells you HOW DEEPLY. After GJK finds a simplex containing the origin, EPA expands the simplex outward until it finds the point on the Minkowski difference's surface closest to the origin.

```
After GJK: simplex contains origin
    ● origin
   /│\
  / │ \     EPA expands this tetrahedron...
 /  │  \    ...until a face contains the closest point to origin
●───●───●
```

**EPA Loop:**

```cpp
struct EPA {
    vector<Vec3> vertices;  // Minkowski difference support points
    vector<Face> faces;     // triangular faces

    void Compute(const Shape& A, const Shape& B, Vec3& penetration, Vec3& normal) {
        // Start with GJK simplex (4 points containing origin)
        vector<Vec3> simplex = GJKSimplex(A, B);
        BuildInitialTetrahedron(simplex);

        while (true) {
            // Find closest face to origin
            Face closestFace = FindClosestFace();
            float dist = closestFace.DistanceToOrigin();
            Vec3 n = closestFace.Normal();

            // Get support point in direction n
            Vec3 support = SupportMinkowski(A, B, n);
            float d = Dot(support, n);

            // If support is on the face (within tolerance), we found the closest point
            if (Abs(d - dist) < 1e-6f) {
                penetration = dist;
                normal = n;
                break;
            }

            // Expand polytope: remove faces facing the support point, add new faces
            ExpandPolytope(support);
        }
    }
};
```

**The result:** normal = direction to push objects apart. penetration = distance to push. Apply impulse along normal to separate. This is what PhysX/Chaos calls internally after GJK+EPA.

## Minkowski Sum/Difference — Visual Intuition

GJK and EPA operate on the **Minkowski difference** M = A - B = {a - b : a∈A, b∈B}.

```
Square A:           Triangle B:         Minkowski Difference A-B:
┌───┐                   ▲                ┌──────┐
│   │                  / \               │      │
└───┘                 /   \              │      │
                     /_____\             └──────┘
```

The Minkowski difference of two convex shapes is convex. If the origin is INSIDE A-B, the shapes overlap. EPA finds the point on A-B's surface closest to the origin — that's the minimum translation vector.


