01 \u2014 Rigid Body Dynamics.content:
# Rigid Body Dynamics

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[../../Trigonometry & Vectors]], [[../../Matrices & Coordinate Systems]], [[../Collision Detection/01 — AABB and Sphere|Collision Detection]]

---

## Why This Matters

Collision detection tells you IF two objects touch. Rigid body dynamics tells you what happens NEXT — how they bounce, spin, slide, and settle. Without dynamics, your game is a static diorama. With it, crates tumble, characters ragdoll, and vehicles handle. Every physics engine (PhysX, Havok, Bullet, Jolt) is built on the equations in this note.

**Engine use:** PhysX (UE), Havok, Bullet, Jolt — all implement these equations.

---

## Linear Motion — The Basics

Newton's Second Law: `F = ma`. Force causes acceleration. Acceleration integrates to velocity. Velocity integrates to position.

```cpp
struct RigidBody {
    Vec3 position;     // center of mass (world space)
    Quat orientation;  // rotation
    Vec3 velocity;     // linear velocity (m/s)
    Vec3 angularVelocity; // angular velocity (rad/s around each axis)

    float mass;           // kg
    Mat3 inertiaTensor;   // how mass is distributed around center
    Mat3 invInertia;      // cached inverse for efficiency
};
```

**Integration (Euler — simplest, least stable):**

```cpp
void IntegrateEuler(RigidBody& body, Vec3 force, Vec3 torque, float dt) {
    // Linear: F = ma → a = F/m
    Vec3 acceleration = force * (1.0f / body.mass);
    body.velocity += acceleration * dt;
    body.position += body.velocity * dt;

    // Angular: τ = Iα → α = I^(-1)τ
    Vec3 angularAccel = body.invInertia * (torque - 
        Cross(body.angularVelocity, body.inertiaTensor * body.angularVelocity));
    body.angularVelocity += angularAccel * dt;

    // Update orientation quaternion
    Vec3 axis = body.angularVelocity;
    float angle = Length(axis) * dt;
    if (angle > 0.0001f) {
        axis = Normalize(axis);
        Quat delta = Quat::FromAxisAngle(axis, angle);
        body.orientation = delta * body.orientation;
        body.orientation = Normalize(body.orientation);
    }
}
```

**Why Euler explodes:** Euler assumes acceleration is constant over the timestep. With large forces or small timesteps, energy is ADDED each frame — the system gains energy and explodes. Use semi-implicit (Symplectic) Euler or Verlet instead.

---

## Angular Motion — The Inertia Tensor

Linear motion is intuitive: push an object, it accelerates in that direction. Angular motion is NOT: push an object off-center, and it spins in a direction that depends on how mass is distributed.

**The inertia tensor** is a 3x3 matrix describing resistance to rotation:

```cpp
// Box with dimensions (w, h, d) and mass m
Mat3 BoxInertia(float m, float w, float h, float d) {
    float ixx = (1.0f/12.0f) * m * (h*h + d*d);  // around X axis
    float iyy = (1.0f/12.0f) * m * (w*w + d*d);  // around Y axis
    float izz = (1.0f/12.0f) * m * (w*w + h*h);  // around Z axis
    return Mat3(ixx, 0, 0, 0, iyy, 0, 0, 0, izz);  // diagonal for symmetric shapes
}

// Sphere with radius r and mass m
float SphereInertia(float m, float r) {
    return (2.0f/5.0f) * m * r * r;  // same for all axes
}
```

**Key insight:** A long thin box has LOW inertia around its long axis (easy to spin) and HIGH inertia around its short axis (hard to spin). This is why a spinning pencil is unstable — small perturbations around the low-inertia axis grow rapidly (tennis racket theorem).

---

## World-Space vs Body-Space

The inertia tensor is defined in the body's LOCAL frame. To use it in world-space equations, rotate it each frame:

```cpp
Mat3 worldInertia = orientation.ToMatrix() * bodyInertia * orientation.ToMatrix().Transpose();
Mat3 worldInvInertia = orientation.ToMatrix() * invBodyInertia * orientation.ToMatrix().Transpose();
```

This rotation is why angular integration is more expensive than linear — 3x3 matrix multiply per frame per body.

---

## Forces and Torques

Forces cause linear acceleration. Torques cause angular acceleration.

```cpp
// Force applied at world-space point 'at' on the body
void ApplyForce(RigidBody& body, Vec3 force, Vec3 at) {
    body.accumForce += force;
    Vec3 r = at - body.position;  // lever arm from COM to application point
    body.accumTorque += Cross(r, force);
}

// Impulse (instantaneous change — collisions use this)
void ApplyImpulse(RigidBody& body, Vec3 impulse, Vec3 at) {
    body.velocity += impulse * (1.0f / body.mass);
    Vec3 r = at - body.position;
    body.angularVelocity += body.worldInvInertia * Cross(r, impulse);
}
```

---

## Damping — Why Things Stop

Real objects lose energy to air resistance and internal friction:

```cpp
// Linear damping: F_damp = -k_d * v
body.velocity *= (1.0f - linearDamping * dt);

// Angular damping: τ_damp = -k_a * ω
body.angularVelocity *= (1.0f - angularDamping * dt);
```

Without damping, a bouncing ball bounces forever. Game engines typically apply 0.1-0.5% damping per frame.

---

## Engine Connection

- **PhysX (UE):** `FBodyInstance` stores mass, inertia tensor, velocities. `AddForce()`, `AddImpulse()`, `AddTorque()` map directly to the equations above.
- **Unity:** `Rigidbody.mass`, `.velocity`, `.angularVelocity`, `.AddForce()`.
- **Godot:** `RigidBody3D.mass`, `.linear_velocity`, `.angular_velocity`, `.apply_force()`.
- All three use semi-implicit Euler or Verlet integration internally — never plain Euler.

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
A rigid body is a hockey puck with mass (how heavy), center of mass (where to push), and an inertia tensor (how hard it is to spin). Push it through its center (no spin), or push off-center (spin). The inertia tensor is like a gyroscope — it describes how the puck resists rotation around each axis. A long thin puck spins easily around its long axis and resists around its short axis. Gravity pulls down, forces push, torques spin — integration accumulates these over time to produce motion.

### Technical
Newton-Euler equations: `F = m * a_cm` (linear), `τ = I * α + ω × (I * ω)` (angular, with gyroscopic term). Inertia tensor I is a 3×3 positive-definite matrix. Principal axes diagonalize I — aligning the body with its natural rotation axes. `ω × (I * ω)` is the gyroscopic term — it accounts for the rotating reference frame. Integration: Euler is unstable (energy grows). Symplectic Euler integrates velocity with new acceleration but position with new velocity — much more stable. Verlet is time-reversible and energy-conserving for harmonic systems.

## See Also

- [[../Collision Detection/04 — GJK Algorithm]] — When dynamics begins (after collision)
- [[../../Matrices & Coordinate Systems]] — How the inertia tensor rotates
- [[../../Quaternions & 3D Rotations]] — How orientation is stored and updated

02 \u2014 Numerical Integration.content:
# Numerical Integration

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[01 — Rigid Body Dynamics]]

---

## Why This Matters

`position += velocity * dt` looks innocent. It is also wrong — it silently adds energy to your simulation, making objects jitter, bounce higher with each collision, and eventually explode. The choice of integration method is the difference between a stable 60fps physics sim and a mess of NaN positions. Every physics engine chooses its integrator carefully.

**Engine use:** PhysX uses semi-implicit Euler for most bodies, Verlet for cloth. Choose wrong and your game jitters.

---

## The Problem — Continuous vs Discrete

Real physics is continuous: `dv/dt = a(t)`. Computers are discrete: `v += a * dt`. The error between them is the integration error. Different methods have different error characteristics:

| Method | Error per step | Stability | Energy |
|---|---|---|---|
| Explicit Euler | O(dt²) | Poor | Gains energy |
| Semi-Implicit Euler | O(dt²) | Good | Preserves energy |
| Verlet | O(dt²) | Excellent | Oscillates around constant |
| RK4 | O(dt⁵) | Excellent | Slight drift |

---

## Explicit Euler — The Naive Approach

```cpp
// Explicit Euler: use current state for everything
void EulerExplicit(RigidBody& b, float dt) {
    Vec3 a = force / mass;
    b.position += b.velocity * dt;  // uses old velocity
    b.velocity += a * dt;           // uses old acceleration
}
```

**Problem:** Energy increases without bound. A pendulum simulated with Euler swings HIGHER over time, not lower. For a mass-spring system, Euler diverges within seconds. Never use for production physics.

**Why it gains energy:** Euler's approximation of a curve as a straight line always overshoots the actual curve. On a circular orbit, each step pushes the body slightly outward — adding orbital energy.

---

## Semi-Implicit Euler (Symplectic) — The Workhorse

```cpp
// Semi-Implicit Euler: update velocity FIRST, then position with NEW velocity
void EulerSemiImplicit(RigidBody& b, float dt) {
    Vec3 a = force / mass;
    b.velocity += a * dt;           // NEW velocity
    b.position += b.velocity * dt;  // uses NEW velocity — more stable!
}
```

**Why it's stable:** It's a symplectic integrator — it preserves the phase-space volume of Hamiltonian systems. This means energy oscillates around a constant value instead of growing. PhysX uses this for rigid bodies.

**Benchmark:** Simulate a mass-spring for 1000 steps. Explicit Euler: amplitude grows 10x. Semi-implicit: amplitude oscillates within 1% of original.

---

## Verlet Integration — Cloth and Particles

```cpp
// Velocity Verlet (most common form):
void Verlet(RigidBody& b, float dt) {
    // Step 1: half-step velocity
    Vec3 a = force / mass;
    b.velocity += a * (0.5f * dt);

    // Step 2: full-step position
    b.position += b.velocity * dt;

    // Step 3: recompute forces at new position
    Vec3 a_new = ComputeForces(b.position) / mass;

    // Step 4: half-step velocity with new acceleration
    b.velocity += a_new * (0.5f * dt);
}
```

**Advantages over Euler:**
- Time-reversible: running backward brings you to the start
- Energy-conserving for harmonic systems
- Naturally handles constraints (project position, not velocity)

**Engine use:** Cloth simulation (PhysX NvCloth), hair (TressFX), particle systems. Verlet is the dominant method for connected systems.

---

## Runge-Kutta 4 (RK4) — When You Need Precision

RK4 evaluates acceleration at 4 points per timestep and weights them. 4x the cost, 1000x the accuracy.

```cpp
void RK4(RigidBody& b, float dt) {
    // k1: derivative at start
    Vec3 v1 = b.velocity;
    Vec3 a1 = ComputeAccel(b.position, v1);

    // k2: derivative at midpoint (using k1)
    Vec3 v2 = b.velocity + a1 * (0.5f * dt);
    Vec3 a2 = ComputeAccel(b.position + v1 * (0.5f * dt), v2);

    // k3: derivative at midpoint (using k2)
    Vec3 v3 = b.velocity + a2 * (0.5f * dt);
    Vec3 a3 = ComputeAccel(b.position + v2 * (0.5f * dt), v3);

    // k4: derivative at endpoint (using k3)
    Vec3 v4 = b.velocity + a3 * dt;
    Vec3 a4 = ComputeAccel(b.position + v3 * dt, v4);

    // Weighted sum
    b.position += (v1 + v2*2 + v3*2 + v4) * (dt / 6.0f);
    b.velocity += (a1 + a2*2 + a3*2 + a4) * (dt / 6.0f);
}
```

**Engine use:** Projectile prediction (UE `PredictProjectilePath`), spacecraft dynamics (Kerbal Space Program), offline baking. Not used for real-time rigid bodies — too expensive for hundreds of objects.

---

## Fixed vs Variable Timestep

Physics should ALWAYS use a fixed timestep. Variable timestep (tied to framerate) produces different physics at 30fps vs 144fps.

```cpp
const float PHYSICS_DT = 1.0f / 60.0f;  // 16.67ms
float accumulator = 0;

void Update(float frameDt) {
    accumulator += frameDt;
    while (accumulator >= PHYSICS_DT) {
        Step(PHYSICS_DT);
        accumulator -= PHYSICS_DT;
    }
}
```

UE does this: physics at 60Hz regardless of rendering framerate. The `Substep` system in UE5 allows finer sub-stepping for fast-moving objects.

---

## Engine Connection

- **PhysX:** Semi-implicit Euler for rigid bodies, Verlet for cloth, RK4 for vehicle suspension
- **UE Chaos:** PhysX successor — customizable integrator per-body
- **Unity:** PhysX integration, same fixed-timestep loop
- **Stability rule:** If your physics jitters, increase substeps. If it explodes, check your integration method.

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Integration is guessing where a moving car will be in the future. Euler says "keep going at your current speed" — you overshoot the curve. Semi-implicit says "adjust your speed first, THEN see where you end up" — much closer to reality. Verlet says "check halfway, adjust, then finish" — like looking at a map mid-journey. RK4 is a super-computer predicting your path from 4 different checkpoints — perfect but expensive. Game physics uses semi-implicit for most things and Verlet for wobbly things like cloth.

### Technical
Integration schemes approximate solutions to ODEs. Local truncation error: Euler O(dt²), RK4 O(dt⁵). Global error accumulates: Euler O(dt), RK4 O(dt⁴). Symplectic integrators preserve the symplectic 2-form of Hamiltonian systems — the area in phase space is conserved, meaning energy oscillates around a constant rather than drifting. Verlet is second-order and symplectic. Implicit methods (backward Euler) are unconditionally stable but require solving nonlinear equations each step — used for stiff systems like cloth with high spring constants.

## See Also

- [[01 — Rigid Body Dynamics]] — The equations being integrated
- [[../Collision Detection/04 — GJK Algorithm]] — Collision response uses impulses (instantaneous velocity changes)

04 \u2014 Continuous Collision Detection.content:
# Continuous Collision Detection (CCD)

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[../Collision Detection/04 — GJK Algorithm]], [[01 — Rigid Body Dynamics]]

---

## Why

Discrete collision detection checks if objects overlap THIS frame. If a bullet moves 10 meters per frame and the target is 0.1 meters thick, the discrete check sees the bullet before and after the target — never inside it. The bullet passes through (tunneling). CCD sweeps the object's motion over the timestep, finding the exact time of impact (TOI). Without CCD, fast objects tunnel through walls, players fall through floors, and bullets pass through enemies.

**Engine use:** UE `CCD` flag on collision, PhysX continuous collision, Hit-scan replacement.

---

## The Tunneling Problem

```
Frame N:    Bullet  ●                           █Target█
Frame N+1:  Bullet                                      ●  (already past!)
```

Discrete check: no overlap at N or N+1 → no collision detected → bullet phases through.

**Solutions:**
1. Smaller timesteps (sub-stepping) — reduces but doesn't eliminate
2. CCD — mathematically finds the exact TOI
3. Ray casts — discrete approximation (what UE hit-scan weapons use)

---

## Swept Shapes — The Core Idea

Instead of checking two shapes, check the SHAPE formed by sweeping one shape over its motion:

```cpp
// Sphere cast: sweep a sphere from A to B, check collision
bool SphereCast(Vec3 start, Vec3 end, float radius, 
                const World& world, float& hitTime, Vec3& hitNormal) {
    // The swept shape is a capsule (sphere extruded along the path)
    // Check capsule vs all world geometry
    float closestHit = 1.0f;
    for (const auto& obj : world.objects) {
        float t = CapsuleVsShape(Capsule{start, end, radius}, obj.shape);
        if (t < closestHit) {
            closestHit = t;
            // hitPoint = start + (end - start) * t
            // hitNormal = normal of surface at hitPoint
        }
    }
    return closestHit < 1.0f;
}
```

---

## Time of Impact (TOI) — The Math

For two moving convex shapes, the TOI is the earliest time t ∈ [0, 1] where the distance between them becomes zero:

```
d(t) = distance(A(t), B(t))
d(0) > 0  (starts separate)
d(t*) = 0 (first contact)
TOI = min{t : d(t) = 0}
```

**Conservative Advancement (CA):** The most common TOI algorithm:

```cpp
float ConservativeAdvancement(Shape A, Shape B, float maxTime) {
    float t = 0;
    while (t < maxTime) {
        // Compute closest distance between A(t) and B(t)
        float dist = Distance(A, B);
        if (dist < EPSILON) return t;  // contact!

        // Compute maximum relative speed (conservative bound)
        float maxSpeed = MaxRelativeSpeed(A, B);

        // Advance by safe step (can't miss contact)
        float dt = dist / maxSpeed;
        t += dt;

        // Move shapes to new time
        A = A.AtTime(t);
        B = B.AtTime(t);
    }
    return maxTime;  // no contact
}
```

**Why "conservative":** `maxSpeed` is an upper bound — the actual speed may be lower. This guarantees we don't step PAST the contact, but it can be slow if maxSpeed is much larger than actual speed.

---

## CCD in Practice — Per-Body Flags

Not every body needs CCD — it's expensive. Flag only fast-moving or small objects:

```cpp
// UE: Set CCD on the collision component
BodyInstance.SetUseCCD(true);

// Unity: Rigidbody.collisionDetectionMode = ContinuousDynamic;

// When to enable:
// - Bullets/projectiles (very fast, very small)
// - Player character (must never fall through floor)
// - Fast vehicles
// - Key gameplay objects
```

**Cost:** CCD is ~5-20x more expensive than discrete. Use sparingly. UE's Chaos physics offers `CCD` (swept), `CCDSwept` (tighter bound), and `CCDFast` (approximate).

---

## Speculative Contacts — The Halfway Solution

A cheaper alternative: expand contact points by the object's velocity:

```
expandedRadius = radius + |velocity| * dt
```

This catches MOST contacts without full swept collision. Used in Unity's `ContinuousSpeculative` mode. False positives are possible (objects that WOULD miss but get caught by the expanded radius) but typically harmless — they get resolved out by the constraint solver.

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE Chaos:** `FBodyInstance::SetUseCCD()`, per-body CCD cost, speculative contacts for intermediate speed
- **Unity:** `Rigidbody.collisionDetectionMode` — Discrete, Continuous, ContinuousDynamic, ContinuousSpeculative
- **PhysX:** PCM (Persistent Contact Manifold) with CCD — maintains contact points across frames, uses CCD for fast movers
- **Hit-scan vs projectile:** Most FPS games use hit-scan (instant ray cast) for bullets — avoids CCD cost entirely at the cost of realism

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Discrete collision is a strobe light — you see snapshots, not the motion between them. A fast bullet between two flashes is invisible. CCD is a video camera — it sees the entire path and catches the bullet mid-flight. Conservative advancement is the camera inching forward: "am I touching yet? No? Step forward by the safe distance." It's slow but guaranteed to catch the first touch. Speculative contacts are a floodlight — you make objects "bigger" by their speed, so anything nearby gets caught.

### Technical
TOI computation via Conservative Advancement: given shapes A(t) and B(t) with bounded motion, compute lower bound on distance d(t) and upper bound on relative velocity v_max. Safe step Δt = d / v_max. Repeat until d < ε. The bounding spheres/boxes accelerate the distance computation. GJK with motion — the support function includes the velocity: support(d, t) = support_at_rest + velocity * t. For rotational motion, the conservative bound is the maximum linear velocity of any point on the rotating shape. CCD pairs: specify which bodies can CCD against which — typically fast-movers vs static world only.

## See Also

- [[../Collision Detection/04 — GJK Algorithm]] — Distance computation for TOI
