01 \u2014 Noise Generation.content:
# Noise Generation

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> Hand-authoring every pebble, cloud, and terrain ripple is impossible. Noise functions generate infinite, deterministic, controllable randomness — the foundation of procedural content. Perlin noise (1983, Academy Award 1997) creates smooth, natural-looking variation. Simplex noise (2001) fixes Perlin's directional artifacts. Fractal octaves layer noise at different scales to create terrain, clouds, and marble. Worley/Voronoi noise produces cellular patterns for stone, skin, and organic surfaces. Domain warping distorts noise coordinates to create flowing, organic shapes. Every procedural terrain generator, texture variation system, and landscape tool in game engines builds on these primitives.

---

## White Noise — The Baseline

White noise is independent random values at each sample point — no correlation between neighbors:

```cpp
float WhiteNoise(float x, float y) {
    return RandomFloat();  // Uncorrelated, looks like TV static
}
```

White noise has equal energy at ALL frequencies. Visually chaotic. Not useful for natural phenomena — nature has structure across scales.

---

## Value Noise — Interpolated Random Values

Place random values on a grid, interpolate between them:

```cpp
float ValueNoise(float x, float y) {
    int ix = floor(x), iy = floor(y);
    float fx = x - ix, fy = y - iy;

    // Hash grid points to random values
    float v00 = Hash(ix,     iy);
    float v10 = Hash(ix + 1, iy);
    float v01 = Hash(ix,     iy + 1);
    float v11 = Hash(ix + 1, iy + 1);

    // Smooth interpolation
    fx = Smoothstep(fx);
    fy = Smoothstep(fy);

    return lerp(lerp(v00, v10, fx), lerp(v01, v11, fx), fy);
}

float Smoothstep(float t) {
    return t * t * (3.0 - 2.0 * t);  // C² smooth at boundaries
}
```

Value noise has blocky artifacts — the grid is visible. Perlin noise fixes this.

---

## Perlin Noise — Gradient-Based Smooth Noise

Instead of random values at grid points, Perlin noise places **random gradient vectors** at each grid point and interpolates dot products:

```cpp
float PerlinNoise(float x, float y) {
    int ix = floor(x), iy = floor(y);
    float fx = x - ix, fy = y - iy;

    // Random gradients at each corner
    float2 g00 = RandomGradient(ix,     iy);
    float2 g10 = RandomGradient(ix + 1, iy);
    float2 g01 = RandomGradient(ix,     iy + 1);
    float2 g11 = RandomGradient(ix + 1, iy + 1);

    // Dot products with offset vectors
    float n00 = dot(g00, float2(fx,     fy));
    float n10 = dot(g10, float2(fx - 1, fy));
    float n01 = dot(g01, float2(fx,     fy - 1));
    float n11 = dot(g11, float2(fx - 1, fy - 1));

    // Smoothstep interpolation (same as value noise)
    fx = Smoothstep(fx);
    fy = Smoothstep(fy);

    return lerp(lerp(n00, n10, fx), lerp(n01, n11, fx), fy);
}
```

The result is smooth, organic, with zero value at integer grid points (all offset vectors are zero there). Range: approximately [-1, 1].

---

## Simplex Noise — Fixing Perlin's Directional Artifacts

Perlin noise uses a square grid — diagonal directions align with the grid, creating visible 45° artifacts. Simplex noise (Ken Perlin, 2001) uses a **simplex grid** (triangles in 2D, tetrahedra in 3D), which has fewer directional biases and scales better to higher dimensions.

Key differences:
- Simplex shape instead of hypercube for the grid
- Radial attenuation function instead of simple dot products
- O(n²) complexity vs Perlin's O(2^n) — dramatic improvement in 3D+

```cpp
// 2D Simplex noise (simplified)
float SimplexNoise(float x, float y) {
    // Skew input space to simplex grid
    float s = (x + y) * 0.366025403f;  // (√3 - 1)/2
    float xs = x + s, ys = y + s;
    int i = floor(xs), j = floor(ys);

    // Unskew back
    float t = (i + j) * 0.211324865f;  // (3 - √3)/6
    float x0 = x - (i - t), y0 = y - (j - t);

    // Determine which simplex we're in, evaluate contributions
    // ... (3-4 corner contributions per simplex vs 4 for Perlin)
}
```

OpenSimplex noise (unpatented alternative) is widely used in game engines for the same purpose.

---

## Fractal Noise — Octaves of Detail

Natural phenomena have detail at multiple scales: mountains shape continents (large scale), ridges shape mountains (medium), rocks shape ridges (small). Fractal noise layers multiple octaves:

```cpp
float FractalNoise(float x, float y, int octaves, float lacunarity, float gain) {
    float value = 0.0;
    float amplitude = 1.0;
    float frequency = 1.0;
    float maxValue = 0.0;

    for (int i = 0; i < octaves; i++) {
        value += amplitude * PerlinNoise(x * frequency, y * frequency);
        maxValue += amplitude;
        amplitude *= gain;          // Each octave contributes less (typically 0.5)
        frequency *= lacunarity;    // Each octave has higher frequency (typically 2.0)
    }
    return value / maxValue;
}
```

- **Octaves:** number of detail layers (4-8 for terrain)
- **Lacunarity:** frequency multiplier between octaves (2.0 = each octave is twice as detailed)
- **Gain / persistence:** amplitude multiplier (0.5 = each octave has half the influence)
- **Fractal dimension:** controls roughness; low persistence = smooth terrain, high persistence = jagged

---

## Worley / Voronoi Noise — Cellular Patterns

Worley noise (1996) computes the distance to the nearest random feature point. It produces cell-like patterns — useful for stone, skin pores, water caustics, organic tissue.

```cpp
float WorleyNoise(float x, float y) {
    int ix = floor(x), iy = floor(y);
    float fx = x - ix, fy = y - iy;
    float minDist = 1e10;

    // Check 3×3 neighborhood of cells
    for (int dx = -1; dx <= 1; dx++) {
        for (int dy = -1; dy <= 1; dy++) {
            // Random feature point within cell
            float2 feature = Hash2D(ix + dx, iy + dy);  // Returns 2D point in [0,1]²
            float2 delta = float2(dx + feature.x - fx, dy + feature.y - fy);
            float dist = length(delta);
            minDist = min(minDist, dist);
        }
    }
    return minDist;  // F1 — distance to nearest point
    // F2 = second-nearest, F2-F1 = edge intensity
}
```

Voronoi variants: F1 (nearest), F2 (second nearest), F2-F1 (edge/crack pattern), F1+F2 (bubbly), distance to edge.

---

## Domain Warping — Distorting the Input

Apply noise to the INPUT coordinates of another noise function to create flowing, organic shapes:

```cpp
float DomainWarp(float x, float y) {
    // Warp the input coordinates
    float wx = x + PerlinNoise(x + 5.2, y + 1.3) * 4.0;
    float wy = y + PerlinNoise(x + 2.8, y + 9.7) * 4.0;

    // Feed warped coordinates to the main noise
    return FractalNoise(wx, wy, 6, 2.0, 0.5);
}
```

This produces swirling, marble-like, or fluid patterns — used for smoke, clouds, lava, and alien terrain. The "5.2", "1.3" offsets are arbitrary seeds — changing them produces different warp patterns.

---

## Engine Application — UE Landmass and Landscape

```cpp
// UE5 Landmass plugin: procedural landscape generation
// Uses fractal Perlin + Simplex noise for heightmap generation:

float Height = FractalNoise(WorldX, WorldY, Octaves=8, Lacunarity=2.0, Gain=0.5);

// Domain warp for mountain ridges:
float WarpX = WorldX + FractalNoise(WorldX + 5.0, WorldY, 3, 3.0, 0.3) * RidgeScale;
float WarpY = WorldY + FractalNoise(WorldX, WorldY + 5.0, 3, 3.0, 0.3) * RidgeScale;
float RidgeHeight = abs(FractalNoise(WarpX, WarpY, 4, 2.0, 0.6)) * RidgeIntensity;

// Voronoi for rock outcrops:
float Voronoi = 1.0 - WorleyNoise(WorldX * RockDensity, WorldY * RockDensity);
float RockMask = smoothstep(0.3, 0.7, Voronoi);

float FinalHeight = Height + RidgeHeight * RockMask;
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Noise is controlled randomness. White noise is TV static — every pixel independent, pure chaos. Value noise smooths randomness across a grid — like blurry static. Perlin noise is smarter: it places little arrows (gradients) at grid points and blends their influence, creating smooth, flowing hills and valleys with no visible grid. Simplex noise does the same on a triangular grid instead of square, removing directional bias. Fractal noise layers noise at different zoom levels — broad strokes (continents) plus medium strokes (mountain ranges) plus fine strokes (boulders) — like an artist working from large brushes to small. Worley noise creates cell patterns — distance to the nearest random dot, producing stone-like or skin-like textures. Domain warping is the "funhouse mirror" trick: feed distorted coordinates into noise to create flowing, organic swirls.

### Technical
Perlin noise places pseudo-random gradient vectors on an integer lattice and interpolates dot products with offset vectors via a smoothstep polynomial (3t²-2t³). Simplex noise uses a simplicial grid and radial attenuation, reducing directional artifacts and computational complexity to O(n²). Fractal noise (fBm — fractional Brownian motion) sums octaves: Σ amplitude · noise(frequency · x) where amplitude = gain^i, frequency = lacunarity^i. Worley noise computes min distance to randomly placed feature points in neighboring cells, producing cellular patterns (F1, F2, F2-F1 variants). Domain warping applies a displacement field to noise input coordinates, creating flowing, non-stationary textures. Engine applications: UE Landmass (landscape), Houdini (terrain), Substance Designer (textures), all build on these primitives.

## See Also

