- [[03 — L-Systems & Marching Cubes]] — Using noise as input to rule-based generation

02 \u2014 Sampling & Placement.content:
# Sampling & Placement

> [!note] Why This Matters (Engine Context)
> Scatter 10,000 trees on a landscape. Pure random: some trees clump, some areas are bare. A uniform grid: looks artificial, no variation. Poisson disc sampling: every tree is at least X meters from every other tree, and the distribution is maximally dense — natural-looking coverage with no overlap. Blue noise sampling: the frequency spectrum has minimal low-frequency energy, reducing visible clumping. These sampling patterns are used everywhere in rendering — scattering foliage with `FoliageTool`, placing SSR ray directions without banding artifacts, generating shadow map sample points, and distributing sound emitters. Good sampling is the difference between "procedural" looking fake and looking like an artist placed every object by hand.

---

## The Problem — Random vs Uniform vs Optimal

```
Random:    ·  ··   ·   ··    ·     — Clumps and gaps. High variance.
Uniform:   ·  ·  ·  ·  ·  ·  ·  ·  — No clumps, but grid-aligned. Visually harsh.
Jittered:  · ·  · ·  ·  ·  ·   ·   — Grid + random offset. Better but still grid-structured.
Poisson:   · ·  ·  · · · ·  · ·    — Maximal packing, min distance enforced, natural.
Blue noise:· · ·  ·· ·  · ·· ·     — No low-frequency clumping, even in frequency domain.
```

---

## Poisson Disc Sampling — The Classic

Goal: place N points in a region such that every pair is at least distance `r` apart, and the packing is maximal (no point can be added without violating the distance constraint).

The **dart-throwing algorithm** (simplest, O(N²) worst case):

```cpp
std::vector<float2> PoissonDisc2D(float width, float height, float r, int maxAttempts = 30) {
    std::vector<float2> points;
    std::vector<float2> active;  // "Active list" — points to generate candidates from

    // Seed with a random point
    float2 first = float2(Random() * width, Random() * height);
    points.push_back(first);
    active.push_back(first);

    while (!active.empty()) {
        // Pick random active point
        int idx = RandomInt(0, active.size() - 1);
        float2 center = active[idx];
        bool found = false;

        // Try k random candidates in annulus [r, 2r]
        for (int k = 0; k < maxAttempts; k++) {
            float angle = Random() * 2.0 * PI;
            float dist = r + Random() * r;  // Annulus: [r, 2r]
            float2 candidate = center + float2(cos(angle), sin(angle)) * dist;

            if (candidate.x < 0 || candidate.x > width) continue;
            if (candidate.y < 0 || candidate.y > height) continue;

            // Check distance to ALL existing points (can optimize with spatial grid)
            bool valid = true;
            for (auto& p : points) {
                if (distance(candidate, p) < r) { valid = false; break; }
            }

            if (valid) {
                points.push_back(candidate);
                active.push_back(candidate);
                found = true;
                break;
            }
        }

        if (!found) {
            active.erase(active.begin() + idx);  // Remove exhausted point
        }
    }
    return points;
}
```

The annulus [r, 2r] is the sweet spot: closer than r is invalid, further than 2r wastes effort.

**Spatial grid optimization:** Divide space into cells of size r/√2. Each cell can contain at most 1 point. Distance check only needs to examine neighboring cells — O(1) per check instead of O(N).

---

## Blue Noise — The Frequency Domain Approach

Poisson disc produces good spatial distribution. Blue noise goes further: it optimizes the **frequency spectrum** of the point set.

A point set's power spectrum is its Fourier transform. Blue noise has:
- Low energy at low frequencies → no large-scale clumping (the "blue" in blue noise)
- A sharp peak at the mean sampling frequency
- Low energy beyond the peak → minimal aliasing

This makes blue noise ideal for:
- **Rendering:** blue noise sample patterns for SSR, SSAO, and shadow maps produce less visible banding than white noise
- **Dithering:** blue noise dither hides quantization in HDR→LDR tone mapping
- **Foliage:** blue noise distribution looks natural — no clumps, no grids

```cpp
// Blue noise generation (simplified void-and-cluster algorithm)
// 1. Start with random white noise
// 2. Find "voids" — largest gaps between points → place new points there
// 3. Find "clusters" — tightest groups → remove points from there
// 4. Repeat until convergence
// Modern: pre-computed blue noise textures (64×64, 128×128) tiled at runtime
```

Most game engines use **pre-computed blue noise textures** — a 128×128 RGBA texture where each pixel's RG channels encode a 2D blue noise sample. Tile it across the screen, sample per-pixel for cheap, high-quality random numbers.

---

## Stratified / Jittered Sampling

Divide the domain into N equal strata (grid cells), place one random sample per stratum:

```cpp
for (int x = 0; x < gridW; x++) {
    for (int y = 0; y < gridH; y++) {
        float sx = (x + Random()) / gridW;
        float sy = (y + Random()) / gridH;
        samples.push_back(float2(sx, sy));
    }
}
```

Guarantees one sample per grid cell — no large gaps. Variance is lower than pure random (stratification reduces variance by removing inter-stratum variation). Used in:
- Shadow map sampling (stratified Poisson disc)
- SSAO sample directions
- Temporal anti-aliasing jitter offsets

---

## Importance Sampling for Placement

When the density should vary (more trees near water, fewer on rocks), use importance sampling:

```cpp
// Rejection sampling: sample uniformly, accept with probability = density(x,y)
float2 SampleWithDensity(Texture2D densityMap) {
    while (true) {
        float2 candidate = float2(Random(), Random());
        float density = densityMap.Sample(candidate);
        if (Random() < density) return candidate;  // Accept
    }
    // Higher density → more likely to accept → more points placed there
}
```

For large density variations, rejection sampling wastes many attempts. Better: inverse CDF sampling or Metropolis-Hastings for arbitrary density functions.

---

## Foliage Scattering in UE

```cpp
// UE FoliageTool: Poisson disc with density map
FFoliageInstance PlaceFoliage(UStaticMesh* Mesh, ULandscape* Landscape) {
    // 1. Generate Poisson disc samples on landscape surface
    TArray<FVector2D> Samples = PoissonDisc(Landscape->GetSize(), MinDistance);

    // 2. Filter by density map
    Samples = Samples.FilterByPredicate([&](FVector2D p) {
        float density = Landscape->GetDensityAtLocation(p);
        return Random() < density;
    });

    // 3. Align to surface normal, apply random rotation/scale
    for (FVector2D p : Samples) {
        FVector WorldPos = Landscape->GetWorldPosition(p);
        FVector Normal = Landscape->GetSurfaceNormal(p);

        FFoliageInstance Instance;
        Instance.Location = WorldPos;
        Instance.Rotation = FRotator::MakeFromX(Normal) + RandomYaw();
        Instance.Scale = Lerp(0.8f, 1.2f, Random());
        AddInstance(Instance);
    }
}
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Randomly scattering 10,000 trees gives you clumps and bare patches — nature isn't purely random, trees compete for space. A grid is too perfect — nature isn't a chessboard either. Poisson disc is the Goldilocks solution: every tree is at least X meters from every other tree (no overlap), and the placement is as dense as possible (no wasted space). The result looks hand-placed. Blue noise goes further: it mathematically eliminates visible clumping patterns across all scales. Think of it as the difference between a poorly-shuffled deck (clumps of same suit) and perfectly-shuffled (evenly mixed). Pre-computed blue noise textures give you this perfect randomness for free — just sample the texture.

### Technical
Poisson disc sampling enforces a minimum distance r between all points while maximizing density. The dart-throwing algorithm generates candidates in annuli [r, 2r] around active points; spatial grid acceleration (cell size r/√2) achieves O(N) performance. Blue noise optimizes the Fourier power spectrum: minimal low-frequency energy (no clumping), peak at the mean sampling frequency, and low energy beyond the peak (anti-aliasing). The void-and-cluster algorithm iteratively fills gaps and breaks clusters. Pre-computed blue noise textures (e.g., 128×128 RGBA) are tiled for runtime use. Stratified sampling divides the domain into equal strata for guaranteed coverage. Importance sampling (rejection, inverse CDF, Metropolis-Hastings) varies density according to an input map. UE FoliageTool uses Poisson disc + density maps for natural-looking object scattering.

## See Also

- [[01 — Noise Generation]] — Noise functions provide the density maps that drive sampling
- [[../Rendering/05 — Monte Carlo & Path Tracing|Monte Carlo & Path Tracing]] — Importance sampling for rendering integrals
- [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]] — Distance calculations for the Poisson disc constraint check

04 \u2014 Probability & Randomness.content:
# Probability & Randomness

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[../Trigonometry & Vectors]]

---

## Why

Random numbers are everywhere in games: loot drops (10% chance of legendary), critical hits (15% crit rate), procedural generation (trees randomly placed but not clumped), particle systems (random velocity within a cone), AI decision-making (patrol path selection). Getting probability right means your game feels fair. Getting it wrong means players rage-quit.

**Engine use:** Every game engine's random system — UE's FRandomStream, Unity's Random, Godot's RandomNumberGenerator.

---

## Uniform Distribution — The Foundation

```cpp
float Random() {     // [0, 1)
    return (float)rand() / (float)RAND_MAX;
}

float RandomRange(float min, float max) {
    return min + Random() * (max - min);
}

int RandomInt(int min, int max) {
    return min + (int)(Random() * (max - min + 1));
}
```

**True randomness vs pseudorandom:** `rand()` is deterministic — same seed = same sequence. This is actually DESIRABLE for games: replay a level with the same seed, get the same procedural generation. True randomness (hardware entropy) is used for cryptography, not gameplay.

---

## Weighted Random — Loot Tables

Not everything is equally likely. A loot table with weighted probabilities:

```cpp
struct LootEntry {
    string item;
    float weight;  // relative probability
};

string WeightedRandom(vector<LootEntry>& table) {
    // Compute total weight
    float total = 0;
    for (auto& e : table) total += e.weight;

    // Pick random value in [0, total)
    float roll = Random() * total;

    // Find which entry the roll landed on
    float cumulative = 0;
    for (auto& e : table) {
        cumulative += e.weight;
        if (roll < cumulative) return e.item;
    }
    return table.back().item;  // fallback (floating point edge case)
}

// Usage:
LootTable chest = {{"Common Sword", 70}, {"Rare Shield", 25}, {"Legendary Bow", 5}};
// 70% Common, 25% Rare, 5% Legendary
```

---

## Normal (Gaussian) Distribution — Bell Curve

Most natural phenomena follow a bell curve — most values near the mean, few at extremes. Height of NPCs, damage variance, aim spread:

```cpp
// Box-Muller transform: two uniform randoms → two normal randoms
float RandomGaussian(float mean, float stddev) {
    float u1 = Random();  // [0,1)
    float u2 = Random();
    float z = sqrt(-2.0f * log(u1)) * cos(2.0f * PI * u2);
    return mean + z * stddev;
}

// 68% of values within ±1 stddev, 95% within ±2, 99.7% within ±3
// Damage = 100 ± 15 means: 68% hits do 85-115, 95% do 70-130
```

**Why not uniform for damage:** Uniform 85-115 damage feels "spiky" — the player sees 85 and 115 equally often. Gaussian around 100 with stddev 5 makes most hits cluster near 100, with occasional high/low outliers — feels more natural.

---

## Binomial and Bernoulli — Success/Failure

```cpp
// Bernoulli: one trial with probability p
bool Bernoulli(float p) { return Random() < p; }

// Binomial: n trials, count successes
int Binomial(int n, float p) {
    int successes = 0;
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++)
        if (Bernoulli(p)) successes++;
    return successes;
}
```

**Engine use:** Critical hits (Bernoulli per attack), multishot attacks (Binomial), crafting (Binomial for quality tiers).

---

## Poisson Distribution — Events Over Time

How many raindrops fall in a second? How many enemies spawn per wave?

```cpp
// Poisson: expected number of events = lambda
// Probability of exactly k events: (lambda^k * e^-lambda) / k!
int Poisson(float lambda) {
    float L = exp(-lambda);
    int k = 0;
    float p = 1.0f;
    do {
        k++;
        p *= Random();
    } while (p > L);
    return k - 1;
}
```

**Engine use:** Enemy spawn timing (average 3 per wave), network packet arrivals, particle emission rates.

---

## Markov Chains — State Transitions

AI behavior: idle → patrol → chase → attack. Each state has probabilities of transitioning to others:

```cpp
enum AIState { Idle, Patrol, Chase, Attack };

// Transition matrix: row = from, col = to, value = probability
float transitions[4][4] = {
    // IDLE  PATROL  CHASE  ATTACK
    {  0.3f,   0.6f,   0.1f,   0.0f },  // from IDLE
    {  0.1f,   0.4f,   0.4f,   0.1f },  // from PATROL
    {  0.0f,   0.0f,   0.3f,   0.7f },  // from CHASE
    {  0.1f,   0.0f,   0.1f,   0.8f },  // from ATTACK
};

AIState NextState(AIState current) {
    float roll = Random();
    float cumulative = 0;
    for (int next = 0; next < 4; next++) {
        cumulative += transitions[current][next];
        if (roll < cumulative) return (AIState)next;
    }
    return current;
}
```

Each row sums to 1.0. An idle NPC has 30% chance to stay idle, 60% to patrol, 10% to chase (hearing a noise). The AI naturally cycles through behaviors.

---

## Shuffle — Fisher-Yates

Shuffling a deck of cards or a playlist:

```cpp
void Shuffle(vector<int>& deck) {
    for (int i = deck.size() - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        int j = RandomInt(0, i);  // pick random index ≤ i
        swap(deck[i], deck[j]);
    }
}
```

**Why not `sort()` with random comparator:** `sort()` requires strict weak ordering. A random comparator violates transitivity (A < B and B < C doesn't guarantee A < C) — causes undefined behavior and biased shuffles. Fisher-Yates is O(n) and produces every permutation with equal probability.

---

## Expected Value — Is This Fair?

```cpp
// Expected value E[X] = sum of (value × probability) over all outcomes
// Loot chest: (10g × 70%) + (100g × 25%) + (1000g × 5%) = 7 + 25 + 50 = 82g
// On average, opening one chest gives 82 gold

float ExpectedValue(vector<pair<float, float>>& outcomes) {
    float ev = 0;
    for (auto [value, probability] : outcomes)
        ev += value * probability;
    return ev;
}
```

**Game design use:** A weapon with 10% chance to deal 500 bonus damage has expected bonus of 50 per hit. Compare to a flat +40 damage weapon — risk/reward analysis.

---

## Engine Connection

- **UE:** `FMath::FRand()`, `FRandomStream`, `FMath::RandRange()`, `FMath::RandPointInBox()` — all seedable
- **Unity:** `Random.value`, `Random.Range()`, `Random.insideUnitSphere`
- **Godot:** `randf()`, `randi()`, `rand_range()`
- **Seeding:** Set seed for reproducible results — critical for networked games (same seed = same random events on all clients)

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Randomness is like spinning a wheel. Uniform = every slice is the same width (fair). Weighted = some slices are wider (rare loot has a tiny slice). Gaussian = the wheel is magnetized toward the center — most results cluster near average. Poisson = how many raindrops hit your window per minute (average 3 = sometimes 0, sometimes 7). Markov = a flowchart of behavior — at each step, roll the dice to see which arrow to follow. Expected value = "on average, how much gold per chest?"

### Technical
Pseudorandom number generators: LCG (Linear Congruential Generator) — fast, low quality. Mersenne Twister — high quality, larger state. Xoshiro — modern, fast, high quality. Fisher-Yates shuffle: O(n), unbiased when RandomInt is uniform. Box-Muller: trigonometric form generates two normals from two uniforms using polar coordinates. Poisson generation via Knuth's algorithm. Markov chain: transition matrix must be stochastic (rows sum to 1.0). Expected value: linearity of expectation — E[X+Y] = E[X]+E[Y] even if X and Y are dependent.

## See Also

