TArray Internals.content:
# TArray Internals

## The Core Idea
> [!info] C++ Connection
> `TArray<T>  is UE's equivalent of `std::vector`<T>`. Unlike `std::vector`, TArray uses UE's allocators (`FMemory::Realloc`) and integrates with the GC via `UPROPERTY`. See [[03 — Memory/06 — std vector & Container Internals|std::vector]] for the standard C++ version.


`TArray<T>` is Unreal Engine's dynamically-resizable array. It stores elements contiguously in heap memory and manages three things:

| Member | Meaning | Source |
|---|---|---|
| `AllocatorInstance` | Manages the heap allocation (malloc/realloc/free) | `Array.h:3810` |
| `ArrayNum` | Number of **live** elements in the array | `Array.h:3811` |
| `ArrayMax` | Number of elements the allocation can hold **before realloc** | `Array.h:3812` |

`ArrayNum ≤ ArrayMax` always — the invariant is checked by `CheckInvariants()` (`Array.h:1322`).

> [!tip] Key intuition
> `ArrayNum` is \"how many things are in the array right now.\" `ArrayMax` is \"how many things we have room for.\" The difference (`ArrayMax - ArrayNum`) is the **slack** — pre-allocated but unused space that avoids a realloc on the next `Add`.

---

## Memory Layout

```
TArray<FThing> arr;
// arr.ArrayNum     = 5     (live elements)
// arr.ArrayMax     = 14    (capacity)
// arr.GetSlack()   = 9     (spare slots before realloc)
//
// Heap:
// [elem0][elem1][elem2][elem3][elem4].....................................[uninitialized slack]
//  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^                                   ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
//         ArrayNum = 5                                                  GetSlack() = 9
//  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^
//         ArrayMax = 14 = allocation in elements
```

The actual pointer to heap memory is retrieved via `AllocatorInstance.GetAllocation()` — `GetData()` (`Array.h:1271`) simply casts it:

```cpp
// Array.h:1271
[[nodiscard]] ElementType* GetData() UE_LIFETIMEBOUND
{
    return (ElementType*)AllocatorInstance.GetAllocation();
}
```

The allocator instance is `ElementAllocatorType` (`Array.h:3810`), which resolves to the allocator's `ForElementType<T> (or `ForAnyElementType` if the allocator doesn't need element type info).

> [!info] Default allocator
> `FDefaultAllocator` = `TSizedDefaultAllocator<32> (`ContainersFwd.h:16`), which wraps `FHeapAllocator`. On the heap allocator, `GetInitialCapacity()` returns 0 — so a default-constructed `TArray` has `ArrayNum = 0`, `ArrayMax = 0`, and no heap allocation.

---

## Allocation & Growth Strategy (Slack)

When `ArrayNum == ArrayMax` and you add another element, the array must grow. UE uses a slack-based growth strategy defined in `DefaultCalculateSlackGrow()`:

```cpp
// ContainerAllocationPolicies.h:170
template <typename SizeType>
SizeType DefaultCalculateSlackGrow(SizeType NewMax, SizeType CurrentMax, SIZE_T BytesPerElement, ...)
```

### Growth Factors

| Parameter | Default (shipping) | AGGRESSIVE_MEMORY_SAVING |
|---|---|---|
| `UE_CONTAINER_SLACK_GROWTH_FACTOR_NUMERATOR` | 3 | 1 |
| `UE_CONTAINER_SLACK_GROWTH_FACTOR_DENOMINATOR` | 8 | 4 |
| `FirstGrow` | 4 | 1 |
| `ConstantGrow` | 16 | 0 |

Source: `ContainerAllocationPolicies.h:121-134` (defines), `ContainerAllocationPolicies.h:175-181` (uses)

### The Growth Formula

**First allocation** (when `CurrentMax == 0`):
- If `NewMax > FirstGrow`: `Grow = NewMax` (exact fit)
- Otherwise: `Grow = FirstGrow` (4 in shipping, 1 in memory-saving)

**Subsequent allocations** (when `CurrentMax > 0`):
```
Grow = NewMax + (NUMERATOR / DENOMINATOR) × NewMax + ConstantGrow
     = NewMax + (3/8) × NewMax + 16
     ≈ 1.375 × NewMax + 16
```

Then `Grow` is quantized via `FMemory::QuantizeSize()` to match the allocator's bucket sizes.

> [!warning] ZERO_SLACK initial allocation
> `CONTAINER_INITIAL_ALLOC_ZERO_SLACK = 1` (`ContainerAllocationPolicies.h:109-110`) means the **first ever allocation** for an array gets **exact size, no slack**. Slack is only added on the **second and subsequent** growths. This saves memory at almost no performance cost, since many arrays never grow beyond a few elements.

### Example Growth Trace (shipping build)

| Add # | Before (Num/Max) | NewNum | Grow calculation | NewMax |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| 1st | 0/0 | 1 | `1 > 4`? No → `Grow=4` | 4 |
| 2nd | 1/4 | 2 | no realloc | — |
| 3rd | 2/4 | 3 | no realloc | — |
| 4th | 3/4 | 4 | no realloc | — |
| 5th | 4/4 | 5 | `5 + 3×5/8 + 16 = 5 + 1 + 16 = 22` | 22 |

### Shrinking

`DefaultCalculateSlackShrink()` (`ContainerAllocationPolicies.h:140`) triggers shrink when:
- Slack bytes ≥ 16384, **OR**
- `3 × ArrayNum < 2 × ArrayMax` (more than ~33% slack)
- Slack elements > 64 (unless array is empty)

When triggered, the allocation shrinks to exactly `ArrayNum` (no slack).

---

## `Add` vs `Emplace`

Both add an element to the end. The difference is **how the element gets constructed**.

### `Add` — copy or move an existing object

```cpp
// Array.h:2961 — const ref overload
SizeType Add(const ElementType& Item)
{
    CheckAddress(&Item);
    return Emplace(Item);  // copy-constructs from Item
}

// Array.h:2948 — rvalue ref overload
SizeType Add(ElementType&& Item)
{
    CheckAddress(&Item);
    return Emplace(MoveTempIfPossible(Item));  // move-constructs from Item
}
```

Both call `Emplace` under the hood. The const-ref version copy-constructs. The rvalue-ref version move-constructs.

### `Emplace` — construct in-place from arguments

```cpp
// Array.h:2813
template <typename... ArgsType>
SizeType Emplace(ArgsType&&... Args)
{
    // ... grow if needed ...
    SizeType OldArrayNum = ArrayNum;
    ArrayNum++;
    void* Ptr = (char*)AllocatorInstance.GetAllocation() + sizeof(ElementType) * OldArrayNum;
    (void)new (Ptr) ElementType(Forward<ArgsType>(Args)...);  // placement new — single construction
    return OldArrayNum;
}
```

> [!important] Performance difference
> `Add(MyObj)` does **copy-construct** then potentially moves the copy. `Emplace(arg1, arg2)` constructs the object **directly** in the array's memory — zero extra copies or moves. For types with expensive constructors (like `FString`, `FName`, or large structs), `Emplace` is always preferred.

| Operation | What happens | When to use |
|---|---|---|
| `Add(const T& item)` | Copy-constructs item into array | You already have the object |
| `Add(T&& item)` | Move-constructs item into array | You have a temporary/rvalue |
| `Emplace(args...)` | Constructs in-place from args | You have constructor arguments |
| `AddDefaulted()` | Calls default constructor | You want a default-initialized element |
| `AddZeroed()` | Zeros the memory (no ctor!) | POD/trivial types only |

---

## `AddUninitialized`

```cpp
// Array.h:1903
SizeType AddUninitialized()
{
    if (ArrayNum == ArrayMax)
    {
        // ... realloc grow ...
    }
    SizeType OldArrayNum = ArrayNum;
    ArrayNum++;
    return OldArrayNum;  // returns index BEFORE increment
}
```

Allocates space but does **NOT** call any constructor. The memory is left as raw bytes.

> [!danger] Only for trivial/POD types
> `AddUninitialized` bypasses constructors entirely. Using it on types like `FString` or `TArray` will leave the new element in an undefined state — reading it is UB and will crash. It's safe for `int32`, `float`, `FVector`, and other trivially-constructible types.

**When to use:** You're about to fill the element yourself (e.g., reading from a buffer, deserializing, or `memcpy`-ing data in).

---

## `Reserve` vs `SetNum`

| | `Reserve(N)` | `SetNum(N)` |
|---|---|---|
| Changes `ArrayNum`? | ❌ No | ✅ Yes |
| Changes `ArrayMax`? | ✅ If N > ArrayMax | ✅ If N > ArrayMax |
| Constructs new elements? | ❌ No | ✅ Default-constructs |
| Destructs elements when shrinking? | ❌ N/A | ✅ Yes |

### `Reserve` — grow capacity without adding elements

```cpp
// Array.h:3268
void Reserve(SizeType Number)
{
    // ...
    if (Number > ArrayMax)
    {
        ReallocTo<...>(..., Number, AllocatorInstance, ArrayNum, ArrayMax);
    }
}
```

`Reserve` calls `CalculateSlackReserve` which can add **extra** slack beyond `Number` due to quantizing. Use `Reserve` before a loop of `Add`s to prevent repeated reallocs.

### `SetNum` — resize the array, constructing or destructing as needed

```cpp
// Array.h:2531
void SetNum(SizeType NewNum, EAllowShrinking AllowShrinking = ...)
{
    if (NewNum > Num())
    {
        const SizeType Diff = NewNum - ArrayNum;
        const SizeType Index = AddUninitialized(Diff);
        DefaultConstructItems<ElementType>((void*)(...), Diff);  // constructs new elements
    }
    else if (NewNum < Num())
    {
        RemoveAt(NewNum, Num() - NewNum, AllowShrinking);  // destructs and removes
    }
}
```

> [!summary] Variants
> - `SetNum(N)` — default-constructs new elements, destructs when shrinking
> - `SetNumZeroed(N)` — zeros new elements (no constructor), destructs when shrinking
> - `SetNumUninitialized(N)` — no construction of new elements, destructs when shrinking
> - `SetNumUnsafeInternal(N)` — just sets `ArrayNum = N`. No construction, no destruction. Requires `N ≤ current Num()`. Use only when you know what you're doing.

---

## `Remove` vs `RemoveAt` vs `RemoveSwap`

### `RemoveAt` — O(N), preserves order

```cpp
// Array.h:2280
void RemoveAtImpl(SizeType Index)
{
    ElementType* Dest = GetData() + Index;
    DestructItem(Dest);                                          // destroy at hole
    SizeType NumToMove = (ArrayNum - Index) - 1;
    if (NumToMove)
        RelocateConstructItems<ElementType>((void*)Dest, Dest + 1, NumToMove);  // shift left
    --ArrayNum;
}
```

Destructs the element at `Index`, then **shifts all subsequent elements left** by one. O(N) because every element after `Index` must be moved.

### `RemoveAtSwap` — O(1), destroys order

```cpp
// Array.h:2367
void RemoveAtSwapImpl(SizeType Index)
{
    ElementType* Data = GetData();
    ElementType* Dest = Data + Index;
    DestructItem(Dest);                                          // destroy at hole
    const SizeType NumElementsAfterHole = (ArrayNum - Index) - 1;
    const SizeType NumElementsToMoveIntoHole = FPlatformMath::Min(1, NumElementsAfterHole);
    if (NumElementsToMoveIntoHole)
        RelocateConstructItems<ElementType>((void*)Dest, Data + (ArrayNum - NumElementsToMoveIntoHole), ...);
    --ArrayNum;
}
```

Destructs the element at `Index`, then **moves the last element** into the hole and decrements `ArrayNum`. O(1). The array's order is no longer preserved.

> [!tip] When to use `RemoveSwap`
> `RemoveSwap` is for cases where element order **doesn't matter** — e.g., a list of active particle emitters, a pool of pooled objects, or a set of dirty components to tick. If you're iterating in any deterministic order or showing elements as a UI list, use `RemoveAt`.

### Comparison

| | `RemoveAt` | `RemoveAtSwap` |
|---|---|---|
| Complexity | O(N) | O(1) |
| Preserves order | ✅ Yes | ❌ No |
| Invalidates indices | ✅ After removed index | ✅ Last element index changes |
| Use case | Ordered lists, UI | Pools, unordered collections |

### `Remove` — by value, calls `RemoveAll` with predicate

```cpp
// Array.h:3343
SizeType Remove(const ElementType& Item)
{
    CheckAddress(&Item);
    return RemoveAll([&Item](ElementType& Element) { return Element == Item; });
}
```

`RemoveAll` (`Array.h:3360`) uses a run-length optimization — it groups matching and non-matching runs, only shifting non-matching elements, and destructing matching runs in bulk. Still O(N) but faster than calling `RemoveAt` in a loop.

---

## Iterator Implementation

TArray provides **two** iterator systems.

### STL-Style Iterators: `TIndexedContainerIterator`

```cpp
// Array.h:64
template <typename ContainerType, typename ElementType, typename SizeType>
class TIndexedContainerIterator
{
    ContainerType& Container;
    SizeType       Index;
    // ...
};
```

Created via `CreateIterator()` / `CreateConstIterator()` (`Array.h:3591`). Stores a **reference to the array** and a **numeric index**.

Key methods:
- `operator*()` → `Container[Index]` (`Array.h:126-129`)
- `operator++()` → `++Index` (`Array.h:77-81`)
- `operator bool()` → `Container.IsValidIndex(Index)` (`Array.h:137-140`) — uses `ArrayNum`, so it reflects **current** array size
- `RemoveCurrent()` → `Container.RemoveAt(Index); Index--` (`Array.h:161-165`) — decrements so the next `++` lands on the right element
- `RemoveCurrentSwap()` → `Container.RemoveAtSwap(Index); Index--` (`Array.h:172-176`)

> [!important] Safe iteration with removal
> When using `CreateIterator()`, you **must** use the iterator's `RemoveCurrent()` — it handles the index decrement. If you call `RemoveAt` directly on the array while using an index-based iterator, your index will skip elements.

### Ranged-For Iterators: `TCheckedPointerIterator`

```cpp
// Array.h:208 (only in non-shipping builds)
template <typename ElementType, typename SizeType, bool bReverse = false>
struct TCheckedPointerIterator
{
    ElementType*    Ptr;
    const SizeType* CurrentNum;   // pointer to ArrayNum
    SizeType        InitialNum;   // snapshot of ArrayNum at loop start
};
```

`begin()` returns `TCheckedPointerIterator(ArrayNum, GetData())` — it stores a **pointer to `ArrayNum`** and its **initial value** (`Array.h:3625`).

Every comparison (`==`, `<`) checks:
```cpp
// Array.h:375
ensureMsgf(!CurrentNum || CurrentNum[0] == InitialNum,
    TEXT(\"Array has changed during ranged-for iteration!\"));
```

> [!bug] Shipping builds = raw pointers
> When `TARRAY_RANGED_FOR_CHECKS == 0` (shipping/test builds, `Array.h:39-42`), `begin()`/`end()` return raw `ElementType*` — **no safety checks at all**. Adding to a TArray during ranged-for in a shipping build silently causes undefined behavior.

---

## Iterator Invalidation Rules

> [!danger] Critical
> Iterators (both `TIndexedContainerIterator` and raw pointers) are invalidated when the underlying heap allocation moves. Any operation that causes `ReallocGrow` or `ReallocTo` invalidates **all** iterators.

### Invalidation Table

| Operation | Invalidates? | What happens |
|---|---|---|
| `Add` / `Emplace` (no realloc) | ❌ No | Existing element addresses are stable |
| `Add` / `Emplace` (triggers realloc) | ✅ ALL iterators | Allocation moved, all pointers dangling |
| `AddUninitialized` (no realloc) | ❌ No | Same as above |
| `AddUninitialized` (triggers realloc) | ✅ ALL iterators | Same as above |
| `Reserve(N)` where N > ArrayMax | ✅ ALL iterators | Reallocation |
| `Reserve(N)` where N ≤ ArrayMax | ❌ No | No-op |
| `SetNum(N)` where N > ArrayMax | ✅ ALL iterators | Reallocation |
| `SetNum(N)` where N < ArrayNum | ✅ From removed index onward | Elements shift left |
| `RemoveAt(Index)` | ✅ Iterators at/after Index | Elements shift left |
| `RemoveAtSwap(Index)` | ✅ Iterator at Index; possibly last-element iterator | Last element swapped into hole |
| `Insert` | ✅ Iterators at/after insertion point | Elements shift right (and possible realloc) |
| `Empty` / `Reset` | ✅ ALL iterators | All elements destructed, ArrayNum=0 |
| `Sort` | ✅ ALL index-based iterators | Elements reordered, raw pointers still valid |
| Assigning/overwriting element via `[]` | ❌ No | Element address unchanged |

### The Classic Crash: Adding Inside Ranged-For

```cpp
// ❌ CRASH in non-shipping, UB in shipping
for (AActor* Actor : MyArray)
{
    if (SomeCondition(Actor))
    {
        MyArray.Add(OtherActor);  // may realloc → ALL pointers invalid!
    }
}
```

In non-shipping builds this triggers `ensureMsgf(\"Array has changed during ranged-for iteration!\")` (`Array.h:375`). In shipping, `begin()`/`end()` are raw pointers — the loop continues reading from freed memory.

**Fix: collect first, add later**
```cpp
TArray<AActor*> ToAdd;
for (AActor* Actor : MyArray)
{
    if (SomeCondition(Actor))
        ToAdd.Add(OtherActor);
}
MyArray.Append(ToAdd);
```

---

## Real UE 5.8 Source Examples

### Default construction — zero-initialized members

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h, line 800
```cpp
constexpr TArray()
    : ArrayNum(0)
    , ArrayMax(AllocatorInstance.GetInitialCapacity())
{
}
// For FDefaultAllocator, GetInitialCapacity() returns 0 → ArrayMax = 0, no heap allocation
```

### GetData — returns raw pointer to heap

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h, line 1271
```cpp
ElementType* GetData() UE_LIFETIMEBOUND
{
    return (ElementType*)AllocatorInstance.GetAllocation();
}
```

### Slack calculation — default growth

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/ContainerAllocationPolicies.h, line 170
```cpp
template <typename SizeType>
SizeType DefaultCalculateSlackGrow(SizeType NewMax, SizeType CurrentMax, SIZE_T BytesPerElement, ...)
{
    const SIZE_T FirstGrow = 4;    // shipping: 4; AGGRESSIVE_MEMORY_SAVING: 1
    const SIZE_T ConstantGrow = 16; // shipping: 16; AGGRESSIVE_MEMORY_SAVING: 0
    SIZE_T Grow = FirstGrow;

    if (CurrentMax)  // CONTAINER_INITIAL_ALLOC_ZERO_SLACK skips first alloc
    {
        Grow = SIZE_T(NewMax) + 3 * SIZE_T(NewMax) / 8 + ConstantGrow;
    }
    else if (SIZE_T(NewMax) > Grow)
    {
        Grow = SIZE_T(NewMax); // exact fit for large first allocations
    }
    // ... quantize ...
}
```

### Emplace — placement new in array memory

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h, line 2813
```cpp
template <typename... ArgsType>
SizeType Emplace(ArgsType&&... Args)
{
    if (ArrayNum == ArrayMax)
    {
        // ReallocGrow1 path — grows by slack formula
        ArrayNum = ReallocGrow1_DoAlloc<Tiny>(...);
    }
    SizeType OldArrayNum = ArrayNum;
    ArrayNum++;
    void* Ptr = (char*)AllocatorInstance.GetAllocation() + sizeof(ElementType) * OldArrayNum;
    (void)new (Ptr) ElementType(Forward<ArgsType>(Args)...);
    return OldArrayNum;
}
```

### TCheckedPointerIterator — safety check on comparison

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h, line 375
```cpp
bool UEOpEquals(const TCheckedPointerIterator& Rhs) const
{
    ensureMsgf(!CurrentNum || CurrentNum[0] == InitialNum,
        TEXT(\"Array has changed during ranged-for iteration!\"));
    return Ptr == Rhs.Ptr;
}
```

### RemoveAtImpl — shift-left after destruction

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h, line 2280
```cpp
void RemoveAtImpl(SizeType Index)
{
    ElementType* Dest = GetData() + Index;
    DestructItem(Dest);
    SizeType NumToMove = (ArrayNum - Index) - 1;
    if (NumToMove)
        RelocateConstructItems<ElementType>((void*)Dest, Dest + 1, NumToMove);
    --ArrayNum;
    SlackTrackerNumChanged();
}
```

---

## Practical Rules

```
Q: Should I use Add or Emplace?
   ├─ I already have the object → Add (by value or move)
   └─ I have constructor arguments → Emplace (avoids temp object)

Q: Should I use Reserve or SetNum?
   ├─ I know how many I'll add but don't need default values yet → Reserve
   └─ I need N default-initialized elements right now → SetNum

Q: Should I use RemoveAt or RemoveAtSwap?
   ├─ Order matters → RemoveAt (O(N))
   └─ Order doesn't matter → RemoveAtSwap (O(1))

Q: Can I modify a TArray during ranged-for?
   ├─ Only read/modify element values (no adding/removing) → ✅ OK
   └─ Add/Remove/Insert → ❌ Will crash or UB (collect changes first)
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### For someone new to C++

Think of a TArray like a row of lockers on a wall. `ArrayNum` is how many lockers are actually in use. `ArrayMax` is how many lockers the wall can physically hold. When you `Add` something and all lockers are full, the janitor installs a **bigger wall** (realloc) and moves all your stuff — but he also leaves extra empty lockers for next time (that's the **slack**).

`Emplace` is like building the item **inside** the locker directly from raw materials, instead of building it elsewhere and then carrying it over. `Add` is carrying a finished item to the locker.

`RemoveAtSwap` is like taking something out of locker #3, noticing locker #10 is occupied, and moving #10's contents into locker #3. It's fast, but now the items are in a different order.

### For someone who knows C++

TArray is a contiguous heap-allocated buffer with a growth strategy of `NewMax = NewNum + (3/8)×NewNum + 16` (shipping), quantized to malloc bucket sizes. Elements are assumed **trivially relocatable** — `RelocateConstructItems` uses `memcpy` when the type trait allows it.

`Emplace` uses placement-new with perfect forwarding, eliminating the move-constructor call that `Add(T&&)` incurs. In practice, for trivially-relocatable types with trivial constructors, `Add`, `Emplace`, and `AddDefaulted` all compile to identical code — the difference matters for types with non-trivial constructors.

The ranged-for safety check is a debug-only feature (`TARRAY_RANGED_FOR_CHECKS`) that snapshots `ArrayNum` and compares on every iterator comparison. In shipping builds, `begin()`/`end()` are raw pointers — iterator invalidation is silent UB, exactly like `std::vector`.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Why is RemoveAtSwap faster than RemoveAt? When is it unsafe?
2. What's the growth factor of TArray? How much slack is typical?
3. Why does AddUninitialized exist? When should you use it?
4. Write a function that takes TArrayView```<FItem>`. Why use a view over const TArray`<FItem>`&?

## See Also

- [[03 — Memory/06 — std vector & Container Internals|std::vector]] (C++) — std::vector comparison
- [[UE Templates & T-Containers]] — All UE container types
- [[03 — Memory/02 — Object Memory Layout|Object Memory Layout]] (C++) — Memory layout and cache effects on TArray

- `TArray` source: `Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/Array.h`
- Growth/slack logic: `Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/ContainerAllocationPolicies.h`
- `TArrayView`: `Engine/Source/Runtime/Core/Public/Containers/ArrayView.h`
- `TMap` internals: [[TMap Internals]]
- `TSet` internals: [[TSet Internals]]

