# TMap Internals

## Why This Note Exists

TMap is UE's hash map — used everywhere for fast key-value lookups. Understanding its internals means understanding when it's fast, when it rehashes, and why iteration order is unpredictable.

> [!info] Source
> `Containers/Map.h`, `Containers/SparseArray.h`, `Containers/HashTable.h`

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[TArray Internals]] — TMap is built on TSparseArray and THashTable, which build on TArray concepts.

---

## TMap's Internal Structure

TMap is NOT a simple array of buckets. It's built on three layers:

```cpp
// Source: Map.h

template<typename KeyType, typename ValueType>
class TMap {
    TSparseArray<TPair<KeyType, ValueType>> Pairs;  // The actual key-value data
    THashTable Hash;                                  // Maps hash → sparse array index
};
```

**The three components:**
1. **TSparseArray** — stores the actual key-value pairs. Sparse means indices can be non-contiguous (holes from removals).
2. **THashTable** — maps a hash value to an index in the sparse array. This is the O(1) lookup.
3. **TPair```<Key, Value>`** — a simple struct with `Key` and `Value` members.

```
TMap<int, FString> Scores:
  HashTable:  [ 0 → 2,  1 → empty,  2 → 1,  3 → 0,  4 → empty ]
                  │              │          │
                  ▼              ▼          ▼
  SparseArray: [ {3, \"Alice\"}, {7, \"Bob\"}, {1, \"Charlie\"}, empty ]
                  idx=0          idx=1       idx=2          idx=3
```

**Key hash 0** → HashTable slot 0 → Pairs index 2 → \"Charlie\" (key=1)
**Key hash 1** → HashTable slot 1 → empty → key not found
**Key hash 3** → HashTable slot 3 → Pairs index 0 → \"Alice\" (key=3)

---

## Hashing and Collisions

### GetTypeHash

Every key type used in a TMap must have a `GetTypeHash()` overload:

```cpp
// Built-in types work automatically:
uint32 Hash = GetTypeHash(42);        // Fast int hash
uint32 Hash = GetTypeHash(FName(\"Fire\")); // FName index (O(1) — it's already an index!)
uint32 Hash = GetTypeHash(FString(\"Hello\")); // CRC of string contents (O(n))

// Custom structs need an overload:
struct FMyKey {
    int32 ID;
    FName Name;

    friend uint32 GetTypeHash(const FMyKey& Key) {
        return HashCombine(GetTypeHash(Key.ID), GetTypeHash(Key.Name));
    }
};
```

### Collision Resolution

When two different keys produce the same hash, UE uses **open addressing with linear probing.** The HashTable stores the sparse array index directly. If slot H is occupied, probe H+1, H+2, etc. until an empty slot is found.

The lookup cost degrades as the HashTable fills up. TMap monitors the load factor and **rehashes** (allocates a larger HashTable) when it exceeds a threshold.

---

## Rehashing

```cpp
// Source: Map.h, HashTable.h

// TMap rehashes when HashTable load factor exceeds threshold.
// Like TArray, the HashTable grows by a factor (~1.5x).

TMap<int, FString> Map;
Map.Reserve(1000);  // Pre-allocate — avoids multiple rehashes during population
```

**Rehash cost:** Every existing key-value pair must be re-inserted into the new HashTable. This is O(n) and invalidates all iterators.

**When rehash happens:**
- Adding an element when the load factor exceeds threshold
- Calling `Compact()` or `Shrink()`
- Explicit `Rehash()`

---

## Iteration and Iterator Invalidation

```cpp
for (auto& Pair : Map) {
    // Pair.Key, Pair.Value
}

for (auto It = Map.CreateIterator(); It; ++It) {
    It->Key;
    It->Value;
}
```

**Iteration order is UNDEFINED.** TMap iterates in HashTable order, which depends on hash values and collision resolution — not insertion order. Two identical maps may iterate in different orders.

**Iterator invalidation:**
- `Add()` / `Emplace()`: MAY invalidate if rehash occurs
- `Remove()`: invalidates iterator to that element, others remain
- `Compact()` / `Shrink()`: invalidates all iterators

> [!tip] Use TMap::CreateIterator() for safe removal during iteration
> ```cpp
> for (auto It = Map.CreateIterator(); It; ++It) {
>     if (It->Value <= 0)
>         It.RemoveCurrent();  // Safe — iterator handles removal
> }
> ``

---

## Memory Layout

```
TMap<K,V> = sizeof(TSparseArray<TPair<K,V>>) + sizeof(THashTable)
           = ~40 bytes (pointer + size + capacity + allocator metadata)
             + ~40 bytes (HashTable metadata)

TPair<K,V> for TMap<int32, FString>:
  Key (int32):   4 bytes
  padding:       4 bytes (alignment to 8)
  Value (FString): 16 bytes (pointer + size + capacity)
  Total: 24 bytes per pair
```

---

## Performance Profile

| Operation | Average | Worst | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| Find(key) | O(1) | O(n) | O(n) with high collision rate |
| Add(key, value) | O(1) amortized | O(n) | O(n) on rehash |
| Remove(key) | O(1) | O(n) | Leaves a hole in SparseArray |
| Contains(key) | O(1) | O(n) | Same as Find |
| Iteration (full) | O(n + capacity) | O(n + capacity) | Iterates HashTable + SparseArray |
| Compact | O(n) | O(n) | Defragments SparseArray |

> [!warning] RemoveAt is NOT O(1) on TMap
> Unlike TArray, which has RemoveAtSwap, TMap removal leaves holes in the sparse array. These holes accumulate. Use `Compact()` periodically if you remove many elements.

---

## Common Patterns

### FindOrAdd — The most common pattern
```cpp
// ❌ Double lookup:
if (!Map.Contains(Key))
    Map.Add(Key, DefaultValue);
ValueType& Val = Map[Key];

// ✅ Single lookup:
ValueType& Val = Map.FindOrAdd(Key, DefaultValue);
```

### Emplace — avoid temporary Pair
```cpp
// ❌ Creates temporary TPair:
Map.Add(Key, FSomeStruct(A, B, C));

// ✅ Constructs directly:
Map.Emplace(Key, A, B, C);
```

### Custom Key with GetTypeHash
```cpp
struct FItemKey {
    int32 Type;
    FName Subtype;
    bool operator==(const FItemKey& Other) const {
        return Type == Other.Type && Subtype == Other.Subtype;
    }
};

// REQUIRED for TMap:
uint32 GetTypeHash(const FItemKey& Key) {
    return HashCombine(GetTypeHash(Key.Type), GetTypeHash(Key.Subtype));
}

// Now works:
TMap<FItemKey, int32> Inventory;
```

---


## TMultiMap — Multiple Values Per Key

`TMultiMap<K, V>` allows multiple values per key. Internally it stores values as a linked chain for each hash entry:

```cpp
TMultiMap<FName, AActor*> TargetsPerPlayer;
TargetsPerPlayer.Add(FName(\"PlayerA\"), Enemy1);
TargetsPerPlayer.Add(FName(\"PlayerA\"), Enemy2);  // Same key, different value
TargetsPerPlayer.Add(FName(\"PlayerA\"), Enemy3);

// Find all values for a key:
TArray<AActor*> Enemies;
TargetsPerPlayer.MultiFind(FName(\"PlayerA\"), Enemies);
// Enemies = { Enemy1, Enemy2, Enemy3 }
```

**Use TMultiMap when:** one key naturally maps to many values (matchmaking queues, inventory slots, faction membership). **Use TMap`<K, TArray<V>`> when:** you need to modify the value array independently of the key lookup.


## See Also

- [[TArray Internals]] — TMap is built on TSparseArray
- [[TSet Internals]] — TSet uses the same hash structure without values
- [[UE Templates & T-Containers]] — All UE containers at a glance
- [[03 — Memory/06 — std vector & Container Internals|std::vector]] (C++) — std::unordered_map comparison

