# TSet Internals

## Why This Note Exists

TSet is UE's hash set — a collection of unique elements with O(1) add/remove/contains. It shares the same internal architecture as TMap, just without the value half of the key-value pair.

> [!info] Source
> `Containers/Set.h`, `Containers/SparseArray.h`

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[TMap Internals]] — TSet and TMap share the same internal structure.

---

## TSet's Internal Structure

TSet is essentially TMap`<ElementType, void>` — a TMap where the value doesn't exist:

```cpp
// Source: Set.h

template<typename ElementType>
class TSet {
    TSparseArray<ElementType> Elements;  // The actual elements
    THashTable Hash;                      // Maps hash → sparse array index
};
```

**Compared to TMap:**
- TMap: `TSparseArray<TPair<Key, Value>>` — stores key AND value
- TSet: `TSparseArray<ElementType>` — stores only the element (it IS the key)

---

## Core Operations

```cpp
TSet<FName> ActiveTags;

// Add — returns whether element was new
bool bWasNew = ActiveTags.Add(FName(\"Burning\"));  // true
bool bWasDuplicate = ActiveTags.Add(FName(\"Burning\"));  // false — already present

// Emplace — construct in-place
ActiveTags.Emplace(\"Frozen\");

// Containment check
if (ActiveTags.Contains(FName(\"Burning\"))) { }

// Find — returns pointer or nullptr
if (const FName* Found = ActiveTags.Find(FName(\"Burning\"))) {
    UseTag(*Found);
}

// Remove
ActiveTags.Remove(FName(\"Burning\"));

// Set operations
TSet<int32> A{1, 2, 3};
TSet<int32> B{2, 3, 4};
TSet<int32> Union = A.Union(B);            // {1, 2, 3, 4}
TSet<int32> Intersection = A.Intersect(B);  // {2, 3}
TSet<int32> Difference = A.Difference(B);   // {1}
```

---

## Memory Layout

TSet has no value type — it stores elements directly:

```
TSet<int32>:
  sizeof(TSet<int32>) = sizeof(TSparseArray<int32>) + sizeof(THashTable)
                      = ~80 bytes (container metadata)

  Each element: 4 bytes (int32)
  HashTable entry: 4 bytes (sparse array index)
```

**Space efficiency:** TSet uses significantly less memory than TMap```<K, bool>` for flag sets because there's no dummy `bool` value stored.

---

## When to Use TSet vs TMap`<K, bool>`

| Scenario | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Set of tags/IDs (presence only) | TSet | Cleaner, less memory, no dummy bool |
| Count occurrences | TMap`<K, int32>` | You need the count |
| Cached lookup results | TMap`<K, bool>` | You need to distinguish \"false\" from \"not checked\" |

```cpp
// ❌ TMap as a set — wasteful:
TMap<FName, bool> ActiveEffects;
ActiveEffects.Add(FName(\"Burning\"), true);

// ✅ TSet — cleaner:
TSet<FName> ActiveEffects;
ActiveEffects.Add(FName(\"Burning\"));
```

---

## Iteration and Invalidation

Same rules as TMap — iteration order is undefined (HashTable order), and rehashing invalidates iterators.

```cpp
for (const FName& Tag : ActiveTags) { }

// Safe removal during iteration:
for (auto It = ActiveTags.CreateIterator(); It; ++It) {
    if (ShouldExpire(*It))
        It.RemoveCurrent();
}
```

---

## Performance Profile

| Operation | Average | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Add(Element) | O(1) amortized | O(n) on rehash |
| Remove(Element) | O(1) | Leaves hole in SparseArray |
| Contains(Element) | O(1) | |
| Find(Element) | O(1) | Returns pointer or nullptr |
| Union / Intersect / Diff | O(n + m) | Allocates new TSet |
| Iteration | O(n + capacity) | Includes hash table overhead |

---

## See Also

- [[TMap Internals]] — The key-value version built on the same internals
- [[TArray Internals]] — TSet is built on TSparseArray
- [[UE Templates & T-Containers]] — All UE containers at a glance

UE Enums & Flags.content:
# UE Enums & Flags

## UENUM() — Making Enums Visible to UE

Standard C++ `enum class` is invisible to Unreal's reflection system. Add `UENUM()` and UHT generates the metadata that makes it work with Blueprints, serialization, and the editor:

```cpp
UENUM(BlueprintType)
enum class ECharacterState : uint8
{
    Idle,
    Running,
    Jumping,
    Dead
};

// Now usable in Blueprints, can be UPROPERTY, serializes automatically
UPROPERTY(EditAnywhere, BlueprintReadWrite)
ECharacterState CurrentState = ECharacterState::Idle;
```

> [!info] Source
> `ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS`: `Core/Public/Misc/EnumClassFlags.h:8`

---

## ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS() — Bitmask Enums

When each enum value is a power of 2, you can combine them with bitwise OR. `ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS()` enables this for `enum class`:

```cpp
UENUM(BlueprintType, Meta = (Bitflags))
enum class EPermission : uint8
{
    None    = 0,
    Read    = 1 << 0,  // 1
    Write   = 1 << 1,  // 2
    Execute = 1 << 2   // 4
};
ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS(EPermission)  // Enables | & ~ operators

// Now bitwise operations work directly:
EPermission permissions = EPermission::Read | EPermission::Write;
bool canRead = (permissions & EPermission::Read) == EPermission::Read;
permissions |= EPermission::Execute;  // Add a flag
permissions &= ~EPermission::Write;   // Remove a flag
```

> [!tip] Without ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS, you need static_cast for every bitwise operation
> `EPermission p = static_cast<EPermission>(static_cast<uint8> `(Read) | static_cast<uint8>(Write));` — ugly and error-prone. `ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS` makes it clean.

### Where UE Uses Bitmask Enums

| Enum | What It Represents |
|---|---|
| `EClassCastFlags` | Which cast path to use (`Cast<T>()` uses a single bitwise AND) |
| `EObjectFlags` (`RF_*`) | Object state: `RF_Transient`, `RF_Public`, `RF_Standalone`, etc. |
| `EFunctionFlags` (`FUNC_*`) | Function metadata: `FUNC_BlueprintCallable`, `FUNC_Net`, etc. |
| `EPropertyFlags` (`CPF_*`) | Property metadata: `CPF_Edit`, `CPF_BlueprintVisible`, etc. |

---

## UENUM Specifiers

| Specifier | Effect |
|---|---|
| `BlueprintType` | Usable as Blueprint variable type |
| `Meta = (Bitflags)` | Tells the editor to show as checkboxes (used with `ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS`) |
| `Meta = (DisplayName = \"Friendly Name\")` | Rename the enum in Blueprint menus |

---

## Enum-to-String and String-to-Enum

```cpp
// Enum to display name:
FString stateName = UEnum::GetValueAsString(CurrentState);
// Returns \"ECharacterState::Running\" or just \"Running\" depending on use

// Display name to enum:
ECharacterState state;
if (UEnum::TryParse(\"Running\", state)) { /* found */ }

// Iterate all values:
for (int32 i = 0; i < StaticEnum<ECharacterState>()->NumEnums() - 1; ++i)
{
    ECharacterState value = static_cast<ECharacterState>(
        StaticEnum<ECharacterState>()->GetValueByIndex(i));
}
```

---

## Enum Naming Convention

UE follows strict enum naming:

| Rule | Example |
|---|---|
| Prefix with `E` (enums) | `ECharacterState` |
| Prefix with `EM` (enum used in many places) | `EMouseCursor` |
| Values use `PascalCase` | `Running`, `TakingDamage` |
| Flag enums use plural names | `EPermission` (not `EPermissionFlag`) |
| Flag values use singular | `Read`, `Write` (not `ReadFlag`) |

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a UENUM with the meta = (Bitflags) specifier and ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS. How does it appear in Blueprints?
2. How do you iterate all values of a UENUM at runtime?
3. Convert an enum value to its display string using UEnum::GetValueAsString.


## Blueprint-Friendly Bitmask Enums

When you mark an enum with `meta = (Bitflags)`, the Blueprint editor shows checkboxes instead of a dropdown:

```cpp
// Source: EnumClassFlags.h:8

UENUM(BlueprintType, meta = (Bitflags))
enum class EAbilityTags : uint8
{
    None      = 0,
    Fire      = 1 << 0,   // 1
    Ice       = 1 << 1,   // 2
    Lightning = 1 << 2,   // 4
    Heal      = 1 << 3    // 8
};
ENUM_CLASS_FLAGS(EAbilityTags)

// In Blueprints: shows as checkboxes to combine tags.
// In C++: bitwise operations work directly.
EAbilityTags Tags = EAbilityTags::Fire | EAbilityTags::Ice;
if ((Tags & EAbilityTags::Fire) != EAbilityTags::None) { }
```

## UEnum Utilities

```cpp
// Get enum display name (for UI / debug)
FString Name = UEnum::GetValueAsString(MyEnumValue);
// Returns \"ECharacterState::Running\"

// Parse string back to enum
ECharacterState State;
if (UEnum::TryParse(\"Running\", State)) { /* found */ }

// Get enum value by index (for iteration)
const UEnum* EnumPtr = StaticEnum<ECharacterState>();
for (int32 i = 0; i < EnumPtr->NumEnums() - 1; ++i) {
    ECharacterState Val = static_cast<ECharacterState>(EnumPtr->GetValueByIndex(i));
}
```


## See Also

- [[02 — Syntax & Types/01 — Enums & enum class|Enums]] (C++) — Standard C++ enums
- [[UHT, Macros & Reflection]] — How UENUM generates reflection data

01 \u2014 Cast Internals & Variants.content:
UE has its own type-identification system, completely independent of `dynamic_cast`. Instead of walking a vtable, UE stores a `uint64` bitfield called `ClassCastFlags` on every `UClass`:

> [!note] RTTI in UE vs Standard C++
> **Standard C++ RTTI:** Every polymorphic class stores a `type_info` object in its vtable. `dynamic_cast` walks the inheritance chain comparing `type_info` pointers — O(depth) cost, varies by compiler, and throws `std::bad_cast` on reference failure.
>
> **UE's replacement:** Every `UClass` stores a `uint64` bitfield. `Cast<T>()` does one bitwise AND — O(1) cost, identical on all platforms, returns `nullptr` on failure (no exceptions). The `UClass` that stores cast flags also powers the Blueprint editor, property system, and serialization — one reflection system for everything.

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/ObjectMacros.h` — Lines 343–415


```cpp
enum EClassCastFlags : uint64
{
    CASTCLASS_None                  = 0x0000000000000000,
    CASTCLASS_UField                = 0x0000000000000001,
    CASTCLASS_FInt8Property         = 0x0000000000000002,
    CASTCLASS_UEnum                 = 0x0000000000000004,
    CASTCLASS_UStruct               = 0x0000000000000008,
    CASTCLASS_UScriptStruct         = 0x0000000000000010,
    CASTCLASS_UClass                = 0x0000000000000020,
    // ...
    CASTCLASS_AActor                = 0x0000001000000000,
    CASTCLASS_APlayerController     = 0x0000002000000000,
    CASTCLASS_APawn                 = 0x0000004000000000,
    CASTCLASS_USceneComponent       = 0x0000008000000000,
    CASTCLASS_UPrimitiveComponent   = 0x0000010000000000,
    // ... (52 total flags, with room for ~12 more)
};
```

### How Classes Get Their Flags

`UHT` (Unreal Header Tool) generates the cast flags. Each class's `DECLARE_CLASS` / `GENERATED_BODY` macro produces:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/ObjectMacros.h` — Lines 1895–1945


```cpp
#define DECLARE_CLASS( TClass, TSuperClass, TStaticFlags, TStaticCastFlags, ... )
    // ...
    /** Returns the unique cast flag for this class if any */
    constexpr static EClassCastFlags StaticClassCastFlags()
    {
        return TStaticCastFlags;
    }
    /** Returns all cast flags for this class, including those inherited */
    consteval static EClassCastFlags StaticAllClassCastFlags()
    {
        if constexpr (std::is_same_v<ThisClass, Super>) 
        { 
            return StaticClassCastFlags(); 
        }
        return StaticClassCastFlags() | Super::StaticAllClassCastFlags();
    }
```

So `UPrimitiveComponent::StaticAllClassCastFlags()` returns `CASTCLASS_UPrimitiveComponent | CASTCLASS_USceneComponent | CASTCLASS_UActorComponent | ...` — the full hierarchy OR'd together.

### The Cast Flag Check

The actual runtime check:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Private/UObject/Class.cpp` — Lines 586–589


```cpp
bool UField::HasAnyCastFlags(const uint64 InCastFlags) const
{
    return !!(GetClass()->ClassCastFlags & InCastFlags);
}
```

This is a **single bitwise AND**. No function calls, no vtable walks. That's why this path is called the "fast path" in `Cast<T>()`.

> [!tip] What Is a Bit-Flag Check?
> Imagine an apartment building with 64 apartments. Each apartment has a mailbox flag. AActor is apartment #1, APawn is #2, ACharacter is #3. When the UHT generates code for `ACharacter`, it raises flags #1, #2, AND #3 — because ACharacter IS an AActor and IS an APawn.
>
> When `Cast<APawn>(Obj)` runs, it checks: "Is flag #2 raised in Obj's mailbox?" One bitwise AND: `flags & PawnFlag`. If non-zero, flag #2 was raised → Obj IS an APawn.
>
> Standard C++ `dynamic_cast` would walk the building floor by floor: "Are you a Pawn? Are you an Actor?" — multiple steps. UE does it in one CPU instruction. That's the entire trick.

### CastFlags Declarations in Casts.h

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/Templates/Casts.h` — Lines 468–531


```cpp
#define DECLARE_CAST_BY_FLAG(ClassName)     class ClassName;     template <>     constexpr inline EClassCastFlags UE::CoreUObject::Private::TCastFlags_V<ClassName> = CASTCLASS_##ClassName;

DECLARE_CAST_BY_FLAG(UField)
DECLARE_CAST_BY_FLAG(UEnum)
DECLARE_CAST_BY_FLAG(AActor)
DECLARE_CAST_BY_FLAG(APawn)
// ... etc
```

The `TCastFlags_V<To> specialization maps a C++ type to its `EClassCastFlags` bit at compile time. If `TCastFlags_V`<To>` == `CASTCLASS_None`, the template falls through to the `IsA<T>()` slow path.

### What Controls the Fast vs Slow Path

The decision between fast path (bit-flag) and slow path (`IsA`) is made **at compile time** via `if constexpr`:

```cpp
if constexpr (UE_USE_CAST_FLAGS && TCastFlags_V<To> != CASTCLASS_None)
{
    // FAST PATH — this branch compiles ONLY when the type has a cast flag
    // The `if constexpr` is evaluated by the compiler, not at runtime
}
else
{
    // SLOW PATH — this branch compiles ONLY when the type lacks a cast flag
    // The other branch doesn't even exist in the compiled binary
}
```

> [!tip] Why `if constexpr` Matters Here
> Without `if constexpr`, BOTH branches would need to compile for every `Cast<T>()` call — including the fast path for types that don't have cast flags, which would fail. `if constexpr` discards the unused branch entirely. The compiled binary contains only ONE path per `Cast<T>()` instantiation. Zero runtime branching overhead — the decision was made when you hit "Build."

```cpp
// Casts.h line 17
#define UE_USE_CAST_FLAGS (USTRUCT_FAST_ISCHILDOF_IMPL != USTRUCT_ISCHILDOF_STRUCTARRAY)
```

The fast bit-flag path is used in **shipping/cooked builds** (where `OuterWalk` is used for `IsChildOf`). In editor/debug configurations that use `StructArray` for `IsChildOf`, cast flags may be disabled — but the fast path is the default for packaged games.

---

When cast flags aren't available for a type, `Cast<T> delegates to `IsA`<T>`()`:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/UObjectBaseUtility.h` — Lines 632–657


```cpp
template <typename OtherClassType>
inline bool IsA( OtherClassType SomeBase ) const
{
    const UClass* SomeBaseClass = SomeBase;
    checkfSlow(SomeBaseClass, TEXT("IsA(NULL) cannot yield meaningful results"));
    const UClass* ThisClass = GetClass();
    UE_ASSUME(SomeBaseClass);
    UE_ASSUME(ThisClass);
    return IsChildOfWorkaround(ThisClass, SomeBaseClass);
}

template<class T>
bool IsA() const
{
    return IsA(T::StaticClass());
}
```

`IsChildOfWorkaround` delegates to `UStruct::IsChildOf()`:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/Class.h` — Lines 807–834


```cpp
template<class T>
bool IsChildOf() const
{
    if constexpr (TModels_V<CStaticClassProvider, T>)
        return IsChildOf(T::StaticClass());
    // ...
}

// The underlying check:
bool IsChildOfUsingStructArray(const FStructBaseChain& Parent) const
{
    int32 NumParentStructBasesInChainMinusOne = Parent.NumStructBasesInChainMinusOne;
    return NumParentStructBasesInChainMinusOne <= NumStructBasesInChainMinusOne 
        && StructBaseChainArray[NumParentStructBasesInChainMinusOne] == &Parent;
}
```

This is an **O(1) array lookup** — the hierarchy is pre-flattened into `StructBaseChainArray`, and the "is this a child?" check is just verifying the parent sits at its known depth in the child's chain.

---


# Cast Variants

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Casting Overview|Casting]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[01 — Cast Internals & Variants]] — understand how Cast works first.




> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/Templates/Casts.h` — Lines 534–594


UE **hijacks** `dynamic_cast` for UObject types:

```cpp
namespace UE::CoreUObject::Private
{
    template <typename To, typename From>
    inline To DynamicCast(From* Arg)
    {
        if constexpr (!std::is_pointer_v<To> || 
                      !TIsCastable<From>::Value || 
                      !TIsCastable<ToValueType>::Value)
        {
            return dynamic_cast<To>(Arg);  // fall through to standard
        }
        else
        {
            return Cast<ToValueType>(Arg);  // use UE's Cast<T> instead
        }
    }
}

#define dynamic_cast UE::CoreUObject::Private::DynamicCast
```

> [!warning] UE Redefines `dynamic_cast`
> The **last line** of `Casts.h` is `#define dynamic_cast UE::CoreUObject::Private::DynamicCast`. If you `#include` any UE header that pulls in `Casts.h` (which is almost all of them), any `dynamic_cast<AActor*>(ptr)` in your code is **preprocessed into** `UE::CoreUObject::Private::DynamicCast<AActor*>(ptr)`, which internally calls `Cast<T>(ptr)` for UObject types and falls through to real `dynamic_cast` for non-UE types. This means `dynamic_cast` on UObjects **still works** but uses UE's faster mechanism. You should **not** rely on this — always use `Cast<T>()` explicitly, since the redefinition only applies when `Casts.h` is included.

---

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/Templates/Casts.h` — Lines 169–173


```cpp
template <typename To, typename From>
UE_FORCEINLINE_HINT TCopyQualifiersFromTo_T<From, To>* ExactCast(From* Src)
{
    return Src && (Src->GetClass() == To::StaticClass()) ? (To*)Src : nullptr;
}
```

`ExactCast<AActor>(Obj)` only succeeds if `Obj->GetClass()` is **exactly** `AActor` — not a child class. This is used when you need the precise class, e.g., comparing archetypes.

---

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/Templates/Casts.h` — Lines 196–238


```cpp
template <typename To, typename From>
FUNCTION_NON_NULL_RETURN_START
    TCopyQualifiersFromTo_T<From, To>* CastChecked(From* Src)
FUNCTION_NON_NULL_RETURN_END
{
    if (!Src)
        CastLogError(TEXT("nullptr"), *GetTypeName<To>());

    auto* Result = Cast<To>(Src);
    if (!Result)
        CastLogError(*GetFullNameForCastLogError(Src), *GetTypeName<To>());

    return Result;
}
```

In **shipping** builds (`!DO_CHECK`), `CastChecked` becomes a zero-overhead static cast:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/Templates/Casts.h` — Lines 243–277 (shipping version)


```cpp
// In shipping: no checks, just return (To*)Src
template <typename To, typename From>
inline TCopyQualifiersFromTo_T<From, To>* CastChecked(From* Src)
{
    if constexpr (TIsIInterface<From>::Value)
    {
        UObject* Obj = Src->_getUObject();
        if constexpr (TIsIInterface<To>::Value)
            return (To*)Obj->GetInterfaceAddress(To::UClassType::StaticClass());
        else
            return (To*)Obj;
    }
    else
    {
        if constexpr (TIsIInterface<To>::Value)
            return (To*)((UObject*)Src)->GetInterfaceAddress(To::UClassType::StaticClass());
        else
            return (To*)Src;
    }
}
```

> [!tip] CastChecked in Shipping
> `CastChecked` **strips all checks in shipping**. It compiles to a raw pointer cast. This means a wrong `CastChecked` in shipping is **undefined behavior** — the same danger as an unchecked `static_cast`. Only use it when you're **100% certain** the object is the right type (checked in development), or the cast is already guarded.

The two-parameter form:

```cpp
CastChecked<To>(Src, ECastCheckedType::NullAllowed)
```

Allows `nullptr` to pass through without error (in debug). Default is `NullChecked` — null source will log an error.

---


## Exercises

1. **Cast`<T>` trace:** Write a function that calls . Trace the internal path:  →  →  → bit flag check. What is each step doing? Why is this faster than ?

2. **CastChecked vs Cast:** Create a scenario where  returns null (actor is not a PlayerController). Now use  — what happens? When would you use CastChecked in engine startup code vs runtime gameplay?

3. **ExactCast vs Cast:** Write a test where you have  inheriting from .  succeeds. Does ? What about ? When would ExactCast prevent bugs?

4. **Interface casting:** Create an  interface. Have  implement it. Cast a generic  to . What does the generated  do? Compare to standard C++ .

5. **Benchmark Cast vs IsA:** Time 1 million  calls vs 1 million  checks. Which is faster? Why? What tradeoff does  make that  doesn't?

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Cast`<T>` is Unreal Engine's type-check security guard. When you hand it an actor and say 'is this a PlayerController?', the guard checks the actor's ID badge (its UClass) against the PlayerController's authorized list (ClassCastFlags). If the badge matches, the guard lets you through and hands you a properly-typed pointer. If not, you get null back — no crash, no undefined behavior. CastChecked is the impatient guard who tackles you if the badge doesn't match (asserts/crashes). ExactCast is the strict guard who demands an EXACT match — a child class pretending to be its parent won't fool them.

### Technical
 calls  — a bitwise AND on . The UHT generates  at compile time, mapping each UCLASS to a unique bit flag.  adds  with the failed type name.  uses  — no inheritance allowed. Interface casting via  uses  which walks the class's  array (populated by UHT from  macro).  is 1-2 cycles (bitwise AND + branch);  is 50-200+ cycles (RTTI DAG walk).

