02 \u2014 Interface Casting & References.content:
# Interface Casting and References

> [!info] Part of the [[00 — Casting Overview|Casting]] learning path.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[01 — Cast Internals & Variants]] — understand the Cast variants first.


Casting to/from `UINTERFACE` types uses a completely different mechanism:

> [!info] Source
> `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/UObjectBaseUtility.h` — Lines 666–675


```cpp
/**
 * Returns a pointer to this object safely converted to a pointer of the 
 * specified interface class.
 */
COREUOBJECT_API void* GetInterfaceAddress( UClass* InterfaceClass );
```

When you write `Cast<UMyInterface>(MyObject)`, the `TIsIInterface` trait detects that `To` is an interface. Cast then calls `MyObject->GetInterfaceAddress(UMyInterface::StaticClass())` which looks up the interface offset in the `UClass`'s internal map of implemented interfaces. This is **more expensive** than a bit-flag check (~20–40 cycles) but still faster than `dynamic_cast`'s vtable walk.

> [!note] How `TIsIInterface` Detects Interfaces
> `TIsIInterface<T> is a template that answers: "Is `T` a `UInterface`?" It uses **SFINAE** (Substitution Failure Is Not An Error) — the compiler tries to match a specialization that checks for `_getUObject()` (a method all `UINTERFACE` types have). If the type has that method, the specialization succeeds → `Value = true`. If not, the specialization silently fails → the default kicks in → `Value = false`.
>
> This happens entirely at compile time. `if constexpr (TIsIInterface<To>::Value)` is resolved before the binary is generated. The interface path only exists in compiled code when `To` IS an interface. The class path only exists when `To` is a class. Zero runtime branching to decide which mechanism to use.

```cpp
// How TIsIInterface works:
template <typename T, bool bIsAUObject = std::is_convertible_v<T*, const volatile UObject*>>
struct TIsIInterface { enum { Value = false }; };

// For non-UObject types, it checks if UClassType::StaticClassFlags has CLASS_Interface
template <typename T>
struct TIsIInterface<T, false>
{
    template <typename U> 
    static char (&Resolve(typename U::UClassType*))[(U::UClassType::StaticClassFlags & CLASS_Interface) ? 2 : 1];
    template <typename U> static char (&Resolve(...))[1];
    enum { Value = sizeof(Resolve<T>(0)) - 1 };
};
```

---

### Hard References (UPROPERTY pointers)

```cpp
UPROPERTY()
TObjectPtr<AActor> MyActor;

// Direct Cast (uses TObjectPtr overload — Casts.h lines 315–370)
AActorDerived* Derived = Cast<AActorDerived>(MyActor);
```

The `TObjectPtr` overload of `Cast<T>()` resolves the handle, then does the same bit-flag or `IsA` check.

### Soft References (TSoftObjectPtr / FSoftObjectPath)

```cpp
UPROPERTY()
TSoftObjectPtr<AActor> SoftActor;

// ❌ DOES NOT WORK — Cast operates on live UObject pointers
AActorDerived* Derived = Cast<AActorDerived>(SoftActor); // Compile error

// ✅ Must load first:
if (SoftActor.IsValid() || SoftActor.LoadSynchronous())
{
    AActorDerived* Derived = Cast<AActorDerived>(SoftActor.Get());
}
```

`Cast<T>()` works on **live in-memory UObject pointers**, not asset paths. You cannot cast across a soft reference without loading the object first.

### TSubclassOf Casting

```cpp
// Casts.h lines 428–441
template <typename To, typename From>
UE_FORCEINLINE_HINT TCopyQualifiersFromTo_T<From, To>* Cast(const TSubclassOf<From>& Src)
{
    return Cast<To>(*Src);  // dereferences TSubclassOf → UClass*
}
```

Casting a `TSubclassOf<AActor> checks whether the stored `UClass` is a child of the target type — conceptually: "is this class a subclass of that class?"

---



