PushModel & Dirty Marking.content:
# PushModel & Dirty Marking

## Why This Exists
> [!note] Why This Matters
> The old replication system checked every replicated property of every actor every frame. PushModel flips this: the game code tells the system exactly what changed. The result: 40x less work for idle objects. This note explains the macros and the architecture.

> [!info] Prerequisites
> [[Network Roles]] and basic replication concepts. [[UHT, Macros & Reflection]] (UE Core) — how UPROPERTY generates replication code.


In the old replication system, the engine had a fundamental problem: **it didn't know what changed.** Every network tick, it compared every replicated property on every actor against its last sent value — just to figure out what to actually send.

For a game with 200 replicated actors, each with 30 properties, that's 6,000 comparisons per tick. Most found nothing. The engine was burning CPU asking \"did anything change?\" over and over, 60 times per second.

**PushModel solves this by inverting the question.** Instead of the engine asking you what changed, you tell the engine what changed. You raise a flag. The engine checks the flag. If no flag is raised, zero CPU is spent on that object.

> [!summary] The Mental Model
> Old way: \"Engine, go figure out what changed.\" (engine does all the work)
> PushModel: \"Engine, Health changed. Stamina changed. That's it.\" (you do the work of flagging, engine does zero polling)

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Net/Core/Public/Net/Core/PushModel/PushModel.h
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Net/Core/Public/Net/Core/PushModel/PushModelMacros.h
```

---

## How It Works — Step by Step

Let's trace what happens when you change `Health` on a replicated actor:

```
1. YOUR CODE
   void AMyActor::SetHealth(float NewHealth)
   {
       Health = NewHealth;
       MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyActor, Health, this);
   }

2. THE MACRO EXPANDS (at compile time)
   The macro looks up Health's RepIndex in AMyActor's UHT-generated enum.
   Health has RepIndex 3.
   It calls: MarkPropertyDirty(this, NetPushId, 3)

3. PUSH MODEL LAYER (at runtime)
   Sets bit #3 in this object's dirty bitfield to 1.
   That's it. One integer bit-set operation.

4. NEXT NETWORK TICK
   Iris checks: \"Does object 0x7F3A have any dirty bits?\"
   Bitfield is non-zero → yes.
   Iris reads the bitfield: bits 3 and 7 are set → Health and Stamina changed.
   Iris serializes ONLY Health and Stamina. The other 28 properties are skipped.

5. AFTER REPLICATION
   Iris clears the bitfield. All bits back to 0.
   Next frame: if nothing changed, bitfield stays 0 → object skipped entirely.
```

**The key insight:** When nothing changes, the entire object costs ONE integer comparison (is bitfield == 0?). That's ~3 CPU cycles. In the old system, the same object cost ~120 cycles (30 property comparisons). That's a 40x difference for idle objects — which is most objects, most frames.

---

## The Macros — What To Use When

```
Source: PushModel.h — Lines 440-470
```

There are six macros. Here's when to use each, with examples.

### 1. MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME — Your Daily Driver

```cpp
// PushModel.h:454
#define MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(ClassName, PropertyName, Object)
```

**What it does:** Marks a single property dirty. Compile-time validated — if you typo the class name or property name, the build fails. This is the one you'll use 95% of the time.

```cpp
void AMyCharacter::SetHealth(float NewValue)
{
    Health = NewValue;
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Health, this);
}
```

**Why the class name?** The macro uses `ClassName::ENetFields_Private::PropertyName` to get the RepIndex at compile time. This means no runtime lookup, no string comparison, no hash table. It resolves to a literal integer constant in the compiled code. That's why it's fast.

### 2. COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY — The Optimized Setter
> [!tip] What Constitutes \"Large\"?
> A struct with 3 floats (12 bytes) is fine. 10 floats (40 bytes) is fine. 100 floats (400 bytes) is not — the `!=` comparison costs more than just marking dirty unconditionally. Rule of thumb: if your struct exceeds 64 bytes (a cache line), benchmark whether comparing or always-marking-dirty is faster.


```cpp
// PushModel.h:466-470
#define COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY(ClassName, PropertyName, NewValue, Object)
```

**What it does:** Checks `NewValue != PropertyName` BEFORE assigning. Only marks dirty if the value actually changed. This avoids wasting bandwidth when a setter is called with the same value.

```cpp
void AMyCharacter::SetHealth(float NewValue)
{
    // If health is already 100 and caller passes 100, nothing happens.
    // No assignment. No dirty mark. No network traffic.
    COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY(AMyCharacter, Health, NewValue, this);
}
```

> [!warning] When NOT to use this
> Don't use `COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY` with large structs. The `!=` comparison does a full struct comparison (memcmp), which costs more than just marking dirty and letting Iris handle the comparison during serialization. Reserve this macro for simple types: ints, floats, bools, pointers, FNames.

### 3. The Array Macros

Static arrays (fixed-size arrays declared in UPROPERTY) get individual RepIndices per element. You can mark one index, or the whole array:

```cpp
// Mark a single element of a static array
// PushModel.h:457
MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME_STATIC_ARRAY_INDEX(AMyActor, MyStaticArray, 2, this);

// Mark the entire static array (all elements)
// PushModel.h:460
MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME_STATIC_ARRAY(AMyActor, MyStaticArray, this);
```

**Dynamic arrays (TArray) are different** — see the Structs and Arrays section below.

### 4. MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_UNSAFE — When You Have a Raw RepIndex

```cpp
// PushModel.h:440
#define MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_UNSAFE(Object, RepIndex)
```

**What it does:** Marks dirty by raw integer RepIndex. No compile-time type checking. You're responsible for the index being correct.

**When to use:** Almost never in gameplay code. This is for internal engine systems that don't have compile-time access to the class type. If you find yourself reaching for this, reconsider — you probably want `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME` instead.

---

## How To Enable PushModel — The Complete Recipe

### Step 1: Mark Properties as Push-Based

In your `GetLifetimeReplicatedProps`:

```cpp
void AMyCharacter::GetLifetimeReplicatedProps(TArray<FLifetimeProperty>& OutLifetimeProps) const
{
    Super::GetLifetimeReplicatedProps(OutLifetimeProps);

    FDoRepLifetimeParams Params;
    Params.bIsPushBased = true;  // ← This is the switch

    DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyCharacter, Health, Params);
    DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyCharacter, Stamina, Params);
    DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyCharacter, bIsAlive, Params);

    // Non-push-model properties use the default
    Params.bIsPushBased = false;
    DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyCharacter, NonPushProperty, Params);
}
```

**Why `bIsPushBased = true` matters:** It tells Iris \"don't poll this property.\" Iris stops comparing it automatically. If you forget to call `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY` after changing it, the change **never replicates**. This is both the power and the danger of PushModel.

### Step 2: Mark Dirty On Every Change

Every code path that writes to a push-based property MUST call the macro:

```cpp
void AMyCharacter::TakeDamage(float Amount)
{
    // ❌ WRONG — Health changes but never replicates
    // Health -= Amount;

    // ✅ CORRECT
    Health -= Amount;
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Health, this);
}
```

**The rule:** If a push-based property is on the left side of an `=`, a `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY` must be nearby. Every single assignment. No exceptions.

### Step 3: Nothing Else

That's it. PushModel registration is automatic. When `bIsPushBased = true`, Iris sets up the necessary bookkeeping when the actor begins replicating. You never call any registration function.

---

## Blueprint Support — What's Automatic, What's Not

**Automatic:** Properties marked `Replicated` + `BlueprintReadWrite` get automatic dirty marking when set via Blueprint. The UHT generates setter nodes that include the dirty mark.

**NOT Automatic:** Properties with custom `BlueprintSetter` functions. You must call the macro in your setter:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(Replicated, BlueprintSetter=SetMyProperty)
FString MyProperty;

UFUNCTION(BlueprintSetter)
void SetMyProperty(const FString& NewValue)
{
    MyProperty = NewValue;
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyActor, MyProperty, this);  // ← Required
}
```

**NOT Automatic:** Properties set from C++ that happen to be BlueprintReadWrite. If you write to `MyBlueprintProperty` from C++, you must mark it dirty — the automatic marking only triggers from Blueprint graph execution.

---

## Structs and Arrays — The Tricky Part

> [!important] PushModel Only Tracks Top-Level Properties
> If you have a replicated struct `FMyStruct MyData` and you change `MyData.SomeField`, PushModel doesn't know `SomeField` exists. It only knows about `MyData`. You must mark the **owning struct** dirty. Iris will then compare the entire struct during serialization to discover which fields changed.
>
> This is stated explicitly in the source (PushModel.h:107-111):
> *\"If changes are made to Structs, Containers, or nested properties therein, the owning Struct or Container property must be marked dirty.\"*

### Struct Example

```cpp
// Your struct
USTRUCT()
struct FCombatState
{
    GENERATED_BODY()

    UPROPERTY()
    float AttackDamage;

    UPROPERTY()
    bool bIsBlocking;
};

// Your actor
UPROPERTY(Replicated)
FCombatState CombatState;

// ✅ CORRECT — mark the struct when any field changes
void AMyCharacter::SetBlocking(bool bBlocking)
{
    CombatState.bIsBlocking = bBlocking;
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, CombatState, this);
}

// ❌ WRONG — this won't compile (SomeField has no RepIndex)
// MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, CombatState.bIsBlocking, this);
```

### Dynamic Array Example

```cpp
UPROPERTY(Replicated)
TArray<FInventoryItem> Inventory;

// ✅ CORRECT — mark the array
void AMyCharacter::AddItem(const FInventoryItem& Item)
{
    Inventory.Add(Item);
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Inventory, this);
}

void AMyCharacter::RemoveItem(int32 Index)
{
    Inventory.RemoveAt(Index);
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Inventory, this);
}
```

Iris will use `IrisFastArraySerializer` to only send the elements that actually changed (added, removed, modified) — you don't need to mark a specific index. You just mark the array, and Iris figures out the delta.

### Static Array (Fixed-Size) — The Exception

Static arrays CAN be individually indexed because the UHT generates a RepIndex per element:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(Replicated)
float DamageMultipliers[4];  // Fixed-size array

void AMyActor::SetMultiplier(int32 Index, float Value)
{
    DamageMultipliers[Index] = Value;
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME_STATIC_ARRAY_INDEX(AMyActor, DamageMultipliers, Index, this);
}
```

---

## The REPLICATED_BASE_CLASS Macro

```
Source: PushModelMacros.h:16-22
```cpp
#define REPLICATED_BASE_CLASS(ClassName)
// Expands to:
//   private: uint64 NetPushId_Internal = INDEX_NONE;
//   public:  uint64 GetNetPushId() const;
//   virtual overrides for SetNetPushIdDynamic / GetNetPushIdDynamic
```

**When do you need this?** Almost never. `AActor` already inherits from a base class that includes this. You only need `REPLICATED_BASE_CLASS` if you're creating a completely new base class that inherits directly from `UObject` (not `AActor`, not `UActorComponent`) and you want PushModel support.

---

## Internal Mechanics — For Understanding, Not Memorization

```
Source: PushModel.h:275-419
```

Behind the macros, the system lives in `UEPushModelPrivate`:

```cpp
// PushModel.h:283-285
using FNetLegacyPushObjectId = int32;
using FNetIrisPushObjectId = uint64;

// PushModel.h:288-294 — unified ID for both systems
struct FNetPushObjectId
{
    FNetPushObjectId() : Value(0xFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFFULL) {}
    explicit FNetPushObjectId(FNetLegacyPushObjectId Id) { ... }
    explicit FNetPushObjectId(FNetIrisPushObjectId Id) { Value = Id; }
};
```

**Why a dual ID system?** When Iris was introduced, it needed a larger ID space (uint64 vs int32). The `FNetPushObjectId` union lets the same macros work with both legacy and Iris replication without any code changes. Your `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME` call works identically regardless of which backend is active.

There are also Iris-specific delegates that get invoked when Iris is the active backend:

```cpp
// PushModel.h:414-418
DECLARE_DELEGATE_ThreeParams(FIrisMarkPropertyDirty, const UObject*, 
    UEPushModelPrivate::FNetIrisPushObjectId, const int32);

NETCORE_API void SetIrisMarkPropertyDirtyDelegate(const FIrisMarkPropertyDirty& Delegate);
```

When Iris is active, `MarkPropertyDirty` forwards to the Iris delegate instead of the legacy path. Your code doesn't change — the macro handles the routing internally.

---

## Common Mistakes — And How To Avoid Them

### 1. Forgetting To Mark Dirty (The Silent Killer)

```cpp
// ❌ Health changes on the server but NEVER replicates to clients
void AMyCharacter::TakeDamage(float Amount)
{
    Health -= Amount;
    // Missing: MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Health, this);
}
```

**Symptom:** The server's Health decreases. Clients still see full Health. No error, no warning, no crash — just silently wrong behavior.

**Prevention:** Wrap all push-based properties behind setters. Make the setter the ONLY place the property changes, and put the dirty mark inside the setter. Never assign directly to `Health` from other functions.

```cpp
// ✅ The setter pattern
void AMyCharacter::SetHealth(float NewValue)
{
    COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY(AMyCharacter, Health, NewValue, this);
}

// Now TakeDamage calls the setter
void AMyCharacter::TakeDamage(float Amount)
{
    SetHealth(Health - Amount);  // Dirty marking happens inside SetHealth
}
```

### 2. Returning Mutable References

```cpp
// ❌ Caller modifies the struct without marking dirty
FCombatState& GetCombatState_Mutable() { return CombatState; }

// Some other file:
auto& State = Character->GetCombatState_Mutable();
State.bIsBlocking = true;  // Changed! Not marked dirty!
```

**Fix:** Mark dirty before returning the reference, so any modification by the caller is covered:

```cpp
// ✅ Mark dirty preemptively
FCombatState& GetCombatState_Mutable()
{
    MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, CombatState, this);
    return CombatState;
}
```

The source file explicitly warns about this (PushModel.h:199-218).

### 3. Holding References Beyond Scope

```cpp
// ❌ Reference captured, modified later in a different scope
void UMyManager::Register(AMyCharacter* Char)
{
    // Storing a reference to a push-model property
    CachedCombatState = &Char->GetCombatState();
}

void UMyManager::Tick(float DeltaTime)
{
    CachedCombatState->bIsBlocking = true;  // Modified! No dirty mark!
}
```

**Prevention:** Never store references to push-model properties. Always go through the owning object's API so dirty marking happens correctly.

### 4. Marking Individual Struct Fields

```cpp
// ❌ Won't compile — only top-level properties have RepIndices
MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, CombatState.bIsBlocking, this);

// ✅ Mark the owning struct
MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, CombatState, this);
```

---

## Performance — Before and After

| Scenario | Without PushModel | With PushModel |
|---|---|---|
| Actor with 0 changed properties | Compare all 30 (~120 cycles) | Bitfield check (~3 cycles) |
| Actor with 1 changed property | Compare all 30 (~120 cycles) | Bitfield + 1 compare (~15 cycles) |
| Actor with 5 changed properties | Compare all 30 (~120 cycles) | Bitfield + 5 compares (~60 cycles) |
| 200 actors, average 2 changes each | 24,000 comparisons | 400 bitfield checks + 400 comparisons |
| Server with 2000 actors at 60fps | ~7.2M comparisons/sec | ~120K comparisons/sec |

**The real win is idle objects.** In most games, 80-90% of replicated actors don't change in a given frame (static props, distant enemies, completed objectives). PushModel makes these cost nearly zero.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple (The Window Alarm Analogy)

Old system: Every night, check every window in the building to see if any are broken. 500 windows. Every night.

PushModel: Give every window an alarm sensor. When a window breaks, its sensor triggers. You only visit windows whose alarm went off. On nights when nothing breaks, you do zero work.

### Technical

PushModel replaces O(n) per-object property polling with O(d) where d is the count of actually-dirty properties. Each push-based property resolves to a compile-time `RepIndex` via the UHT-generated `ENetFields_Private` enum (`GET_PROPERTY_REP_INDEX` macro, PushModel.h:426). The per-object dirty bitfield is stored alongside the `NetPushId` and checked via `DoesHaveDirtyPropertiesOrRecentlyCollectedGarbage()` (PushModel.h:407) before any serialization begins. The `FNetPushObjectId` dual-representation (lines 288-294) unifies Iris (uint64) and legacy (int32) push IDs into one struct, with Iris-specific dirty marking routed through `FIrisMarkPropertyDirty` delegates set at initialization (lines 414-418). The macros expand to calls through `CONDITIONAL_ON_OBJECT_NET_ID` (line 433) which checks that the push ID is valid before forwarding — meaning on non-replicated objects, the macros become no-ops with zero runtime cost.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Mark a property `bIsPushBased = true`. What if you forget `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME`?
2. Write a struct with 5 fields. Mark dirty when any field changes.
3. When use `COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY` vs `MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME`?
4. What's the performance difference for an idle object with 50 replicated properties?

## See Also

- [[Iris Replication System Overview]] — The pipeline this feeds into
- [[Network Roles]] — How ownership connects to replication
- `Engine/Source/Runtime/Net/Core/Public/Net/Core/PushModel/PushModel.h` — All macros (lines 440-470) and implementation
- `Engine/Source/Runtime/Net/Core/Public/Net/Core/PushModel/PushModelMacros.h` — `REPLICATED_BASE_CLASS`, `WITH_PUSH_MODEL`

