# RPCs in Unreal Engine

## What Is an RPC?
> [!info] C++ Connection
> RPC dispatch is UHT-generated. `UFUNCTION(Server)` causes UHT to generate `_Validate` and `_Implementation`. `GetFunctionCallspace` (Actor.cpp:5540) determines execution location. See [[UHT, Macros & Reflection]].

> [!info] Math Connection
> RPCs serialize FVector/FRotator with quantization. See [[Trigonometry & Vectors]] and [[Quaternions & 3D Rotations]] for the math being compressed.


An RPC (Remote Procedure Call) is a function that executes on a **different machine** than the one that called it. You write a function in C++, mark it with a specifier, and the engine handles the network transport automatically.

> [!summary] The Three Types
> | Specifier | Who Calls It | Where It Executes | Who Can Call It |
> |---|---|---|---|
> | `Server` | Owning client | Server | Only `ROLE_AutonomousProxy` |
> | `Client` | Server | Owning client | Only `ROLE_Authority` |
> | `NetMulticast` | Server | Server + all clients | Only `ROLE_Authority` |

**Concrete example:** When a player presses the \"jump\" button on their client, the client calls a `Server` RPC. The function body executes on the server, which validates the jump and applies the physics. The server then calls a `NetMulticast` RPC so every client sees the character jump.

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Engine/Private/Actor.cpp — GetFunctionCallspace (lines 5540-5666)
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/Engine/Private/Actor.cpp — CallRemoteFunction (lines 5668-5688)
```

---

## How RPCs Are Declared

### Server RPC — Client Calls, Server Executes

```cpp
// In your header (.h)
UFUNCTION(Server, Reliable)
void ServerRequestJump();

// In your .cpp — the implementation runs ONLY on the server
void AMyCharacter::ServerRequestJump_Implementation()
{
    // This code executes on the server
    if (CanJump())
    {
        Jump();
    }
}
```

**Naming convention:** The engine automatically generates `_Implementation` and `_Validate` suffixes. You write `ServerRequestJump_Implementation`. The generated thunk function `ServerRequestJump` handles the network dispatch.

### Client RPC — Server Calls, Owning Client Executes

```cpp
UFUNCTION(Client, Reliable)
void ClientNotifyDamage(float DamageAmount, const FVector& HitLocation);

void AMyCharacter::ClientNotifyDamage_Implementation(float DamageAmount, const FVector& HitLocation)
{
    // This code executes on the owning client
    // Play hit effects, screen shake, damage numbers — things only the hit player needs to see
    PlayHitEffects(HitLocation);
    ShowDamageNumber(DamageAmount);
}
```

### NetMulticast RPC — Server Calls, Everyone Executes

```cpp
UFUNCTION(NetMulticast, Reliable)
void MulticastPlayExplosion(const FVector& Location);

void AMyActor::MulticastPlayExplosion_Implementation(const FVector& Location)
{
    // This code executes on the server AND every client
    // Use for visual effects that everyone needs to see
    SpawnExplosionVFX(Location);
    PlayExplosionSound(Location);
}
```

> [!warning] NetMulticast Executes On The Server Too
> Unlike `Client` RPCs (server-only → client-only), `NetMulticast` executes on the server **and** all clients. The server also plays the effect. If you only want clients to see something, filter inside the implementation with `if (!HasAuthority())`.

---

## Reliable vs Unreliable

| | Reliable | Unreliable |
|---|---|---|
| **Guaranteed delivery?** | Yes — will arrive eventually | No — may be dropped |
| **Ordering** | In order | May arrive out of order |
| **Use for** | Gameplay state changes (damage, death, ability activation) | Frequent cosmetic updates (footstep sounds, muzzle flashes) |
| **Cost** | Higher — ACKs, retransmission, head-of-line blocking | Lower — fire and forget |
| **Specifier** | `UFUNCTION(Server, Reliable)` | `UFUNCTION(Server, Unreliable)` |

**The default is Unreliable.** If you don't specify `Reliable`, your RPC is Unreliable. Always be explicit.

**When to use Unreliable:** Anything where missing one call doesn't matter — footstep sounds, weapon trail effects, animation stutters. If the packet drops, the next call arrives 16ms later and the player doesn't notice.

**When to use Reliable:** Anything where missing one call breaks the game — damage application, ability activation, inventory changes, death. Use it for state transitions, not continuous updates.

---

## Validation — Preventing Cheaters

Server RPCs travel from a client (which the player controls) to the server (which you control). A cheater can modify their client to send any data they want. **Validation functions** are your firewall.

```cpp
UFUNCTION(Server, Reliable, WithValidation)
void ServerDealDamage(AActor* Target, float Amount);

// Validation runs first — rejects invalid calls BEFORE the implementation executes
bool AMyCharacter::ServerDealDamage_Validate(AActor* Target, float Amount)
{
    // Reject if the target is too far away (speed hack)
    if (FVector::Dist(GetActorLocation(), Target->GetActorLocation()) > AttackRange * 1.5f)
    {
        return false;  // RPC is dropped silently
    }

    // Reject if the damage amount is suspicious (damage hack)
    if (Amount > MaxPossibleDamage)
    {
        return false;
    }

    return true;  // RPC proceeds to _Implementation
}

void AMyCharacter::ServerDealDamage_Implementation(AActor* Target, float Amount)
{
    // Validation passed — safe to apply damage
    Target->TakeDamage(Amount, FDamageEvent(), GetController(), this);
}
```

> [!tip] Validate What The Client Shouldn't Control
> Validate cooldowns (did they wait long enough?), distances (are they close enough?), resource costs (do they have enough mana?), and state (are they alive? not stunned?). The client tells you what they WANT to do. Validation checks if they're ALLOWED to do it.

**Without `WithValidation`:** The function compiles without a validate function. The server executes whatever the client sends. This is only safe for RPCs where the client can't abuse the parameters (e.g., `ServerAcknowledgeReceipt` where there's nothing to cheat).

---

## How RPC Dispatch Works — Under The Hood

When you call `ServerRequestJump()` on a client, here's what actually happens:

```
1. YOUR CODE (on owning client)
   ServerRequestJump();

2. UHT-GENERATED THUNK
   The UHT generates a wrapper that calls:
   AActor::GetFunctionCallspace(Function, ...)

3. GetFunctionCallspace (Actor.cpp:5540-5666)
   Checks FUNC_NetServer flag:
   - Are we on the server? → Execute locally (don't send to server)
   - Are we on a client? → Return FunctionCallspace::Remote

4. CallRemoteFunction (Actor.cpp:5668-5688)
   If callspace is Remote:
   - Finds the active NetDriver
   - NetDriver->ProcessRemoteFunction(this, Function, Parameters, ...)
   - Sends the function name + serialized parameters over the network

5. ON THE SERVER
   NetDriver receives the RPC packet
   - Deserializes parameters
   - Calls ProcessEvent → runs ServerRequestJump_Implementation
   - If WithValidation: runs _Validate first, skips if it returns false
```

**Key source lines:**

```cpp
// Actor.cpp:5555 — NetMulticast dispatch
if ((Function->FunctionFlags & FUNC_NetMulticast))
{
    if (bIsServer)
    {
        return (FunctionCallspace::Local | FunctionCallspace::Remote);
        // Execute locally AND send to all clients
    }
}

// Actor.cpp:5577-5594 — Server/Client dispatch
if (bIsServer && !(Function->FunctionFlags & FUNC_NetClient))
{
    return Callspace;  // Server calling a Server function → run locally
}
if (!bIsServer && !(Function->FunctionFlags & FUNC_NetServer))
{
    return Callspace;  // Client calling a Client function → run locally
}
```

**The absorption check** (Actor.cpp:5652):
```cpp
// If the actor isn't replicated, absorb the RPC (silently drop it)
if (RemoteRole == ROLE_None)
{
    return FunctionCallspace::Absorbed;
}
```

---

## Who Can Call Which RPC

| Caller Location | Server RPC | Client RPC | NetMulticast RPC |
|---|---|---|---|
| **Server** (`HasAuthority()`) | Executes locally (doesn't network) | ✅ Sent to owning client | ✅ Executes locally + sent to all clients |
| **Owning Client** (`ROLE_AutonomousProxy`) | ✅ Sent to server | Executes locally (doesn't network) | ❌ Dropped silently |
| **Other Client** (`ROLE_SimulatedProxy`) | ❌ Dropped silently | ❌ Dropped silently | ❌ Dropped silently |

**The rule:** RPCs only travel in the direction they're designed for. A `Server` RPC from a SimulatedProxy is absorbed — it never reaches the network. A `Client` RPC from a client is absorbed — there's no \"server above the server\" to send it to.

---

## RPC vs Replicated Property — When To Use Which

| | RPC | Replicated Property |
|---|---|---|
| **Best for** | One-time events (\"jump now\", \"fire weapon\") | Ongoing state (\"health = 50\", \"is alive = true\") |
| **Timing** | Immediate — sent when called | On next replication tick (variable) |
| **Guaranteed** | Reliable RPCs are guaranteed | Property changes are guaranteed (eventually) |
| **Late joiners** | Missed — they weren't connected when the RPC fired | Received — the current value is sent on join |
| **Cost** | Per-call overhead (function name, serialization) | Per-tick overhead (only if dirty, with PushModel) |

> [!tip] The Late-Joiner Problem
> If a player joins mid-game, they missed every RPC that fired before they connected. The server doesn't replay RPCs. That's why critical state (health, inventory, team) should be in replicated properties — late joiners get the current value. Use RPCs for transient events (explosions, sounds, animations) that don't need to be \"caught up.\"

---

## Common Mistakes

### 1. Calling a Server RPC From a SimulatedProxy

```cpp
// ❌ On a non-owning client, this call is silently absorbed
ServerRequestJump();  // Never reaches the server

// ✅ Guard the call
if (GetLocalRole() == ROLE_AutonomousProxy)
{
    ServerRequestJump();
}
```

### 2. Forgetting The _Implementation Suffix

```cpp
// ❌ Linker error — the UHT generates the thunk, you must provide the impl
void AMyActor::ServerRequestJump() { }  // Wrong name

// ✅ Correct
void AMyActor::ServerRequestJump_Implementation() { }
```

### 3. Expensive Parameters on Frequent RPCs

```cpp
// ❌ Sending full actor references every tick
UFUNCTION(Server, Unreliable)
void ServerUpdateTarget(AActor* Target);  // Expensive — serializes actor reference

// ✅ Send minimal data
UFUNCTION(Server, Unreliable)
void ServerUpdateTarget(FVector AimLocation);  // Cheap — float quantization
```

### 4. Using NetMulticast For Owner-Only Effects

```cpp
// ❌ Everyone sees your damage screen shake
UFUNCTION(NetMulticast, Reliable)
void MulticastDamageEffect();

// ✅ Use Client RPC for owner-only effects
UFUNCTION(Client, Reliable)
void ClientDamageEffect();
```

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

RPCs are like walkie-talkies with different channels:

- **Server RPC:** You (client) talk to headquarters (server) on Channel 1. \"I want to jump.\" Headquarters decides if you're allowed to and makes it happen.
- **Client RPC:** Headquarters talks to you on Channel 2. \"You took 10 damage.\" Only you hear it — nobody else needs to know your health bar flashed.
- **NetMulticast:** Headquarters broadcasts on Channel 3. \"Explosion at coordinates X,Y!\" Everyone hears it.

Validation is the security guard at headquarters who checks your ID before letting your message through. \"You say you want to jump? Let me check if you're not stunned first.\"

### Technical

RPCs use UE's reflection system (`UFunction` with `FUNC_NetServer`/`FUNC_NetClient`/`FUNC_NetMulticast` flags) to route function calls across the network. The UHT generates thunk functions that call `AActor::GetFunctionCallspace()` (Actor.cpp:5540) to determine the call's destination — `Local`, `Remote`, or `Absorbed`. `CallRemoteFunction()` (Actor.cpp:5668) iterates active `UNetDriver` instances, calling `ProcessRemoteFunction()` to serialize the function name (via `FName`) and parameters (via `FNetSerializer` per parameter type) into a network packet. On the receiving end, the NetDriver deserializes and calls `UObject::ProcessEvent()`. For Iris, RPCs travel through the `NetBlob` system (`NetRPC.h`, `NetRPCHandler.h`) as reliable/unreliable blobs, bypassing the property replication pipeline.

---

## What ProcessRemoteFunction Does

When you call an RPC, `CallRemoteFunction` (Actor.cpp:5668) passes it to `UNetDriver::ProcessRemoteFunction`:

1. **Serializes** the function name (FName) and parameters using `FNetSerializer`
2. If **Reliable**, adds to the reliable queue (guaranteed delivery, ACK tracking)
3. If **Unreliable**, adds to the unreliable queue (fire and forget)
4. If **NetMulticast**, sends to server + all clients
5. If **Client**, sends only to the owning connection

The serialized RPC is packed into the outbound UDP packet and sent on the next network tick.

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a Server RPC that changes a replicated property. Why must the SERVER change it?
2. Write a NetMulticast RPC that plays a particle effect. Why does the effect also play on the server?
3. What happens if you call a Server RPC from a pawn with `ROLE_SimulatedProxy`? Write a guard.
4. Write an RPC with `WithValidation`. What should `_Validate` check?
5. Why use an Unreliable RPC over a Reliable one? Give a game example.



## See Also

- [[Network Roles]] — `ROLE_AutonomousProxy` determines who can call Server RPCs
- [[RepNotifies & OnRep]] — The property-based alternative to RPCs
- [[GAS Networking & Prediction]] — How GAS uses RPCs for ability activation
- `Engine/Source/Runtime/Engine/Private/Actor.cpp` — Lines 5540-5688 for RPC dispatch

RepNotifies & OnRep.content:
# RepNotifies & OnRep

## What Is a RepNotify?

A RepNotify is a callback function that fires when a replicated property's value arrives from the server. Instead of polling \"did this change?\", the engine calls your function automatically whenever new data arrives.

> [!summary] RPC vs RepNotify
> RPC = \"do this thing now\" (event). RepNotify = \"this value changed, react to it\" (state change). RPCs are one-shot. RepNotifies fire every time the value changes. Use RepNotifies for visual/audio reactions to replicated state. Use RPCs for one-time commands.

```
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/ObjectMacros.h — CPF_RepNotify (line 466)
Source: Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/CoreNetTypes.h — ELifetimeRepNotifyCondition (lines 39-42)
```

---

## How RepNotifies Work — Step by Step

Let's trace what happens when the server changes `Health` and it replicates to a client:

```
1. SERVER — You change the value
   Health = 50;
   MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY_FROM_NAME(AMyCharacter, Health, this);

2. SERVER — Replication tick
   Iris detects Health is dirty (bitfield check)
   Serializes Health = 50 into a packet
   Sends to client

3. CLIENT — Receives the packet
   Deserializes Health = 50
   Compares with client's current Health (was 100)
   Health changed! Updates client's Health to 50

4. CLIENT — RepNotify fires
   Because Health is declared with ReplicatedUsing=OnRep_Health:
   OnRep_Health() is called
   Inside OnRep_Health, you play damage effects, update UI, etc.
```

**The critical detail:** RepNotify fires AFTER the value is already updated on the client. When `OnRep_Health()` runs, `Health` is already 50. You don't need to set it — you just need to react to it.

---

## Declaring a RepNotify

```cpp
// In your header (.h)
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_Health)
float Health;

UFUNCTION()
void OnRep_Health();

// In your .cpp
void AMyCharacter::GetLifetimeReplicatedProps(TArray<FLifetimeProperty>& OutLifetimeProps) const
{
    Super::GetLifetimeReplicatedProps(OutLifetimeProps);
    DOREPLIFETIME(AMyCharacter, Health);
}

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Health()
{
    // Health is already updated to the new value
    // React to the change here
    UpdateHealthBar(Health);

    if (Health <= 0)
    {
        PlayDeathAnimation();
    }
}
```

**Naming convention:** `OnRep_PropertyName`. The engine doesn't enforce this, but it's universal UE convention. The UHT uses the function name you provide in `ReplicatedUsing=` — it doesn't care what you call it, but every UE developer expects `OnRep_`.

---

## The Old Value — RepNotifies With Previous State

Sometimes you need to know what the value WAS, not just what it IS. For example, to calculate how much damage was taken:

```cpp
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_Health)
float Health;

UFUNCTION()
void OnRep_Health(float PreviousHealth)
{
    float DamageTaken = PreviousHealth - Health;
    ShowDamageNumber(DamageTaken);

    if (Health <= 0 && PreviousHealth > 0)
    {
        PlayDeathAnimation();  // Only on the transition to death
    }
}
```

The engine passes the previous value as a parameter. You don't need to store it yourself — the replication system remembers it.

> [!tip] Previous Value Parameter Pattern
> The parameter type must match the property type. For `float Health`, use `float PreviousHealth`. The parameter name can be anything, but `Previous` + PropertyName is the convention.

---

## RepNotify Conditions — OnChanged vs Always

```
Source: CoreUObject/Public/UObject/CoreNetTypes.h — Lines 39-42
```cpp
enum ELifetimeRepNotifyCondition
{
    REPNOTIFY_OnChanged = 0,  // Only call RepNotify if the value actually changed
    REPNOTIFY_Always = 1,     // Always call RepNotify, even if the value is the same
};
```

**`REPNOTIFY_OnChanged` (default):** The RepNotify only fires if the new value differs from the current client value. If the server sends `Health = 100` and the client already has `Health = 100`, nothing happens. This is what you want 95% of the time.

**`REPNOTIFY_Always`:** The RepNotify fires on EVERY replication, even if the value didn't change. Use this when the arrival itself is significant — for example, when the server re-sends state to resynchronize, and you want to re-trigger effects.

```cpp
FDoRepLifetimeParams Params;
Params.RepNotifyCondition = REPNOTIFY_Always;
DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyActor, SomeProperty, Params);
```

**When to use Always:** Rarely. One valid case: the server sends a \"sync complete\" signal by re-setting a replicated bool. The client's RepNotify fires even though the bool didn't change, and the client knows to refresh its UI.

---

## Common RepNotify Patterns

### Pattern 1: Health/Stat Changes (Most Common)

```cpp
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_Health)
float Health;

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Health(float PreviousHealth)
{
    UpdateHealthBar(Health);

    float DamageTaken = PreviousHealth - Health;
    if (DamageTaken > 0)
    {
        PlayHitReaction(DamageTaken);
    }
}
```

### Pattern 2: State Machine Transitions

```cpp
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_CharacterState)
ECharacterState CharacterState;

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_CharacterState(ECharacterState PreviousState)
{
    switch (CharacterState)
    {
    case ECharacterState::Dead:
        PlayDeathAnimation();
        DisableCollision();
        break;
    case ECharacterState::Stunned:
        PlayStunAnimation();
        break;
    }
}
```

### Pattern 3: Inventory/Array Changes

```cpp
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_Inventory)
TArray`<FInventoryItem>` Inventory;

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Inventory()
{
    // The entire array was replaced or modified on the server
    // Refresh the UI
    RefreshInventoryUI();
}
```

> [!warning] Arrays and RepNotify
> For dynamic arrays (`TArray`), the RepNotify fires when the array reference changes OR when elements are added/removed (via Fast Array Serialization). You don't get told which element changed — you get told \"the array changed.\" Use the array data to figure out what to update.

### Pattern 4: Replicated Object References

```cpp
UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_TargetActor)
AActor* TargetActor;

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_TargetActor(AActor* PreviousTarget)
{
    // Previous target — remove highlight
    if (PreviousTarget)
    {
        PreviousTarget->SetHighlight(false);
    }

    // New target — add highlight
    if (TargetActor)
    {
        TargetActor->SetHighlight(true);
    }

    UpdateTargetUI(TargetActor);
}
```

---

## RepNotify vs RPC — Decision Guide

| Scenario | Use | Why |
|---|---|---|
| Health changed from 100 to 50 | **RepNotify** | State change. Late joiners need current value. OnRep handles the transition. |
| \"Fire weapon now!\" | **RPC** | One-time event. No state to remember. Late joiners don't need to see past shots. |
| Player joined the game | **RepNotify** (bool bIsConnected) | State change. Late joiners need to see everyone who's already connected. |
| Explosion at location X | **NetMulticast RPC** | Visual event. Late joiners don't need to see past explosions. |
| Score changed from 10 to 15 | **RepNotify** | State change. UI updates. Late joiners need the current score. |
| \"You've been targeted by an enemy\" | **Client RPC** | Player-specific event. Only the targeted player needs the warning. |

**The rule of thumb:** If you'd save it in a variable, use a RepNotify. If you'd put it in a function call, use an RPC.

---

## RepNotify and PushModel

When you use PushModel (`bIsPushBased = true`), RepNotifies still work exactly the same:

```cpp
FDoRepLifetimeParams Params;
Params.bIsPushBased = true;  // PushModel
DOREPLIFETIME_WITH_PARAMS_FAST(AMyCharacter, Health, Params);

// The setter marks dirty
void AMyCharacter::SetHealth(float NewValue)
{
    COMPARE_ASSIGN_AND_MARK_PROPERTY_DIRTY(AMyCharacter, Health, NewValue, this);
}

// OnRep fires when the client receives the updated value
void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Health(float PreviousHealth)
{
    // Same as before — no changes needed for PushModel
}
```

PushModel only changes HOW the server detects changes (dirty marking instead of polling). The client-side RepNotify mechanism is unchanged.

---

## Common Mistakes

### 1. Modifying The Property Inside OnRep

```cpp
// ❌ DON'T — OnRep fires because the value already changed FROM the server
void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Health()
{
    Health = FMath::Clamp(Health, 0, MaxHealth);  // Changes Health AGAIN
    // This doesn't re-trigger OnRep (no infinite loop) but it's confusing
    // The server's value is the source of truth — don't override it
}
```

### 2. Assuming OnRep Fires In A Specific Order

```cpp
// ❌ DON'T rely on Health's OnRep firing before MaxHealth's OnRep
// The engine doesn't guarantee property replication order
void AMyCharacter::OnRep_Health()
{
    // MaxHealth might not be updated yet!
    float Ratio = Health / MaxHealth;  // Could use old MaxHealth
}
```

**Fix:** If properties depend on each other, use a single struct with one RepNotify:

```cpp
USTRUCT()
struct FHealthData
{
    GENERATED_BODY()
    UPROPERTY()
    float Current;
    UPROPERTY()
    float Max;
};

UPROPERTY(ReplicatedUsing = OnRep_HealthData)
FHealthData HealthData;

void AMyCharacter::OnRep_HealthData()
{
    // Both Current and Max are updated atomically
    float Ratio = HealthData.Current / HealthData.Max;  // Safe
}
```

### 3. Using RepNotify Where The Previous Value Doesn't Matter

If you don't need the previous value parameter, that's fine — the parameter is optional. But if you DO need it and forget to add it, the OnRep still compiles, it just won't receive the old value.

---

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple

A RepNotify is like a doorbell. When the server changes a value (someone arrives at your door), the RepNotify rings (the doorbell sounds). You don't have to stand at the door waiting — you go about your business, and when the doorbell rings, you react.

Without RepNotify, you'd have to keep checking the door every few seconds: \"Is anyone here yet? How about now?\" That's polling. RepNotify is interrupt-driven.

### Technical

RepNotifies are implemented via the `CPF_RepNotify` property flag (ObjectMacros.h:466). UHT generates code that stores the pre-replication value and compares it after deserialization. The `ELifetimeRepNotifyCondition` (CoreNetTypes.h:39-42) controls whether the callback fires on every replication (`REPNOTIFY_Always`) or only on value change (`REPNOTIFY_OnChanged`, default). The `FRepLayout` (legacy) or `FReplicationStateDescriptor` (Iris) tracks the previous value per-property and calls the registered `RepNotifyFunc` via `UObject::ProcessEvent()` after updating the property. The previous value is passed as a function parameter through the reflection system, matching the property's type.

---

## Exercises — Test Your Understanding

1. Write a RepNotify for Health. How do you detect the transition from alive to dead?
2. When use `REPNOTIFY_Always` over `REPNOTIFY_OnChanged`?
3. Mark a property `ReplicatedUsing=OnRep_Score`. Write `OnRep_Score`. What arguments?
4. When an actor first spawns and replicates, does OnRep fire for every property?

## See Also

- [[RPCs in Unreal Engine]] — The function-call alternative to RepNotify
- [[PushModel & Dirty Marking]] — How the server detects changes that trigger RepNotifies
- [[GAS Networking & Prediction]] — How GAS uses RepNotifies for ability state
- `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/ObjectMacros.h` — CPF_RepNotify (line 466)
- `Engine/Source/Runtime/CoreUObject/Public/UObject/CoreNetTypes.h` — RepNotify condition enum (lines 39-42)
```

04 \u2014 Sorting Algorithms.content:
# Sorting Algorithms

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[The Big O Complexity Spectrum]]

---

## Why

`std::sort` is a single function call. But it hides the single most studied family of algorithms in CS. Understanding WHY std::sort uses Introsort (a hybrid of Quick, Heap, and Insertion sort) means understanding the tradeoffs every engine makes: cache-friendly vs branch-predictable vs worst-case-safe.

---

## Comparison of Core Sorts

| Algorithm | Best | Average | Worst | Space | Stable | Cache |
|---|---|---|---|---|---|---|
| Quick Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n²) | O(log n) | No | Good |
| Merge Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) | Yes | Poor |
| Heap Sort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(1) | No | Poor |
| Insertion | O(n) | O(n²) | O(n²) | O(1) | Yes | Excellent |
| Timsort | O(n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n) | Yes | Good |
| Introsort | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(n log n) | O(log n) | No | Good |

---

## Quick Sort — The Workhorse

```cpp
int Partition(int arr[], int low, int high) {
    int pivot = arr[high];  // Lomuto partition (simple)
    int i = low - 1;
    for (int j = low; j < high; j++) {
        if (arr[j] <= pivot) {
            i++;
            swap(arr[i], arr[j]);
        }
    }
    swap(arr[i + 1], arr[high]);
    return i + 1;
}

void QuickSort(int arr[], int low, int high) {
    if (low < high) {
        int pi = Partition(arr, low, high);
        QuickSort(arr, low, pi - 1);
        QuickSort(arr, pi + 1, high);
    }
}
```

**Why O(n²) worst case:** If the pivot is always the smallest/largest element, one partition is empty. On sorted data with Lomuto partition, this happens every time — QuickSort degenerates to O(n²). Fix: median-of-three pivot selection, or random pivot.

**Why Introsort:** Start with QuickSort. Count recursion depth. If depth exceeds 2·log₂(n), switch to HeapSort (guaranteed O(n log n)). For small subarrays (<16 elements), switch to Insertion Sort (O(n²) but very fast for tiny n due to cache and low overhead). This is what `std::sort` does.

---

## Heap Sort — The In-Place Guarantee

```cpp
void Heapify(int arr[], int n, int i) {
    int largest = i;
    int left = 2 * i + 1;
    int right = 2 * i + 2;

    if (left < n && arr[left] > arr[largest]) largest = left;
    if (right < n && arr[right] > arr[largest]) largest = right;

    if (largest != i) {
        swap(arr[i], arr[largest]);
        Heapify(arr, n, largest);
    }
}

void HeapSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int i = n/2 - 1; i >= 0; i--) Heapify(arr, n, i);  // build max-heap
    for (int i = n - 1; i > 0; i--) {
        swap(arr[0], arr[i]);   // move max to end
        Heapify(arr, i, 0);     // restore heap property
    }
}
```

**Why cache-poor:** Heap access pattern is random — parent-children relationships jump across memory. Modern CPUs hate this (cache misses every access). QuickSort's sequential partition scan is much more cache-friendly.

---

## Timsort — Python's Choice, Used in std::stable_sort

Timsort exploits real-world data: most arrays are partially sorted. It finds natural "runs" of consecutive ascending elements, merges them using a merge strategy inspired by binary merging.

**Key insight:** Identify runs of length ≥ minrun (typically 32-64). Use Insertion Sort to extend short runs. Merge runs using a stack-based strategy that ensures balanced merge tree (similar to Huffman coding). Stable. Adaptive to existing order.

---

## Counting and Radix Sort — Beyond Comparisons

When keys are integers in a known range, you can beat O(n log n):

```cpp
// Counting Sort — O(n + k) where k = range
void CountingSort(int arr[], int n, int maxVal) {
    vector<int> count(maxVal + 1);
    for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) count[arr[i]]++;

    int idx = 0;
    for (int val = 0; val <= maxVal; val++)
        for (int j = 0; j < count[val]; j++)
            arr[idx++] = val;
}

// Radix Sort — O(d * (n + b)) where d = digits, b = base
void RadixSort(int arr[], int n) {
    for (int digit = 0; digit < 10; digit++) {  // 32-bit int = 10 decimal digits
        // Stable sort by current digit using Counting Sort with base 10
        CountingSortByDigit(arr, n, digit);
    }
}
```

---

## Engine Use

- **UE:** `TArray::Sort()` uses Introsort. `TArray::StableSort()` uses Timsort. FName sorting uses Radix Sort (FName is an interned index — perfect for integer sorting)
- **Rendering:** Depth sorting for transparent objects (O(n log n) must run every frame), painter's algorithm
- **Physics:** Broad phase sorts objects along axis for sweep-and-prune

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
Sorting is arranging books on a shelf. QuickSort picks a pivot book, puts smaller books left and larger right, then sorts each side. Introsort starts with QuickSort but counts how deep it goes — if it gets too deep (bad pivot choices), it switches to HeapSort as a safety net. For tiny shelves (under 16 books), it switches to Insertion Sort (like arranging a hand of cards — fast for small sets). Timsort looks for already-sorted runs (like finding books already in order) and merges them smartly.

### Technical
QuickSort: average 1.39 n log n comparisons. Introsort = QuickSort + HeapSort fallback at 2 log n depth + Insertion for n < 16. HeapSort: build max-heap O(n), extract-max n times O(log n) = O(n log n). Timsort: identify natural runs, merge using galloping (exponential search when one run dominates). Counting/Radix break Ω(n log n) by not comparing — they exploit integer key structure.

## See Also

- [[The Big O Complexity Spectrum]] — The complexity classes these algorithms inhabit
- [[../C++/03 — Memory/08 — Iterators & Algorithms]] — The STL algorithms wrapping these sorts

05 \u2014 Graph Algorithms.content:
# Graph Algorithms

> [!info] Prerequisites: [[The Big O Complexity Spectrum]], [[04 — Sorting Algorithms]]

---

## Why

Graphs model everything: AI pathfinding (nodes = positions, edges = walkable connections), skill trees (nodes = skills, edges = prerequisites), dependency resolution (nodes = build steps, edges = dependencies), social networks. Understanding DFS, BFS, and Dijkstra means understanding how every navigation and dependency system works.

---

## Graph Representation

```cpp
// Adjacency list (most common for sparse graphs):
struct Graph {
    int V;  // vertices
    vector<vector<int>> adj;  // adj[v] = list of neighbors

    void AddEdge(int u, int v, bool directed = false) {
        adj[u].push_back(v);
        if (!directed) adj[v].push_back(u);
    }
};

// Adjacency matrix (dense graphs, O(V²) space):
struct DenseGraph {
    vector<vector<float>> matrix;  // matrix[u][v] = weight (0 = no edge)
};
```

---

## BFS — Shortest Path in Unweighted Graphs

```cpp
vector<int> BFS(Graph& g, int start) {
    vector<int> dist(g.V, -1);
    queue<int> q;

    dist[start] = 0;
    q.push(start);

    while (!q.empty()) {
        int u = q.front(); q.pop();
        for (int v : g.adj[u]) {
            if (dist[v] == -1) {  // unvisited
                dist[v] = dist[u] + 1;
                q.push(v);
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;  // dist[v] = shortest path from start to v (unweighted)
}
```

BFS visits nodes in order of increasing distance — like ripples in a pond. O(V + E). Uses a queue (FIFO).

---

## DFS — Exhaustive Exploration

```cpp
void DFS(Graph& g, int u, vector<bool>& visited, vector<int>& order) {
    visited[u] = true;
    order.push_back(u);  // pre-order

    for (int v : g.adj[u]) {
        if (!visited[v]) {
            DFS(g, v, visited, order);
        }
    }
    // Post-order: process after children
}
```

Uses recursion (implicit stack). O(V + E). DFS is the foundation for: topological sort, cycle detection, strongly connected components, maze generation.

**Topological Sort (DAGs only):** Run DFS, record vertices in reverse post-order. Used for build systems (A depends on B → B before A).

```cpp
vector<int> TopoSort(Graph& g) {
    vector<int> order;
    vector<bool> visited(g.V);

    function<void(int)> dfs = [&](int u) {
        visited[u] = true;
        for (int v : g.adj[u])
            if (!visited[v]) dfs(v);
        order.push_back(u);  // post-order
    };

    for (int i = 0; i < g.V; i++)
        if (!visited[i]) dfs(i);

    reverse(order.begin(), order.end());
    return order;
}
```

---

## Dijkstra — Shortest Path in Weighted Graphs

```cpp
vector<float> Dijkstra(Graph& g, int start) {
    vector<float> dist(g.V, INFINITY);
    // Min-heap: (distance, vertex)
    priority_queue<pair<float,int>, vector<pair<float,int>>, greater<>> pq;

    dist[start] = 0;
    pq.push({0, start});

    while (!pq.empty()) {
        auto [d, u] = pq.top(); pq.pop();
        if (d > dist[u]) continue;  // stale entry

        for (int v : g.adj[u]) {
            float w = g.weight(u, v);
            if (dist[u] + w < dist[v]) {
                dist[v] = dist[u] + w;
                pq.push({dist[v], v});
            }
        }
    }
    return dist;
}
```

O((V + E) log V). Requires non-negative edge weights. For negative edges, use Bellman-Ford O(V·E). For all-pairs, use Floyd-Warshall O(V³).

---

## Minimum Spanning Tree — Kruskal

Connect all nodes with minimum total edge weight:

```cpp
float Kruskal(Graph& g) {
    sort(g.edges.begin(), g.edges.end());  // by weight
    UnionFind uf(g.V);
    float total = 0;

    for (auto [w, u, v] : g.edges) {
        if (uf.Find(u) != uf.Find(v)) {
            uf.Union(u, v);
            total += w;
        }
    }
    return total;
}
```

Union-Find data structure: O(α(V)) per operation (inverse Ackermann — effectively O(1)).

---

## Engine Use

- **UE:** Navigation system = A* (graph search). Skill tree = DAG traversal. Asset dependency graph = topological sort.
- **Build systems:** CMake/UBT dependency resolution = topological sort on DAG of targets
- **Networking:** Dijkstra for QoS routing, BFS for network topology discovery

## Two-Way Explanation

### Simple
BFS explores like ripples in a pond — visit all neighbors at distance 1, then all at distance 2. DFS explores like a maze runner who always goes as deep as possible before backtracking. Dijkstra is BFS with a priority pass — closer nodes are explored first based on actual travel cost, not just hop count. Topological sort is a recipe: you can't frost the cake before baking it, so bake comes before frost in the ordering.

### Technical
BFS: queue, O(V+E), finds shortest path in unweighted graphs. DFS: recursion/stack, O(V+E), basis for topological order, cycle detection, connectivity. Dijkstra: priority queue (min-heap), O((V+E)log V), non-negative weights. Bellman-Ford: O(V·E), handles negative edges. Floyd-Warshall: O(V³), all-pairs. Union-Find: path compression + union by rank → nearly O(1). Kruskal's MST: sort edges + Union-Find = O(E log E).

